<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-SYSTEMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING RESUMES IN COYOTE NETWORK SYSTEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Trading of Coyote Network Systems' shares resumed
Friday after Nasdaq imposed a one-day halt due to a controversy
involving one of its business partners.
</P>
<P>
   The telecom equipment and network services company ran into
trouble after TheStreet.Com reported earlier this week that it
couldn't find Coyote's partner Crescent Communications, which
Coyote described as an international telecom company. Crescent
indirectly accounted for the majority of Coyote's second quarter
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote's stock dropped by 45 percent to $7.8125 on Wednesday,
and Nasdaq halted trading on Thursday to let the market absorb
material news about the firm. When trading resumed Friday, Coyote
took another hit, dropping by 19 percent to $6.5625 on volume of
2.3 million shares _ 18 times its six-month daily average.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq spokesman would not say whether the organization is
investigating Coyote. However, he explained that it's customary to
halt trading if there's news about a company that might materially
affect its stock price. Trading resumes once Nasdaq deems that the
market has had enough time to absorb the news.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote has defended itself against the allegations, and an
analyst dismissed TheStreet.Com's report. Coyote officials could
not be reached for comment Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Coyote issued two statements explaining its
relationship with Crescent. Coyote said it sold equipment to
Comdisco, an established Illinois telecom leasing firm, which in
turn leased it to Crescent.
</P>
<P>
   Comdisco officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, editor-in-chief of TheStreet.Com, said his
reporters started to search for Crescent before Thanksgiving. A
reporter even drove to the company's Long Beach address, but there
was no company.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote analyst Vik Grover said that although he has never talked
to anyone at Crescent, he believes it is based in Long Beach but
operates out of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered the phone of Gene Curcio, president of Crescent,
in Long Beach, and he did not respond to a Daily News e-mail
request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
