<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6371 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-POSSIBLEDEAL-HNS &LR;      12-12 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-POSSIBLEDEAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Secret talks put a deal in sight
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stern, Hunter take NBA bull by the horns
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NBA commissioner David Stern and union executive director Billy
Hunter have been holding secret meetings and are close to reaching
a deal that could end the 164-day-old NBA lockout before Christmas,
sources close to the negotiations told the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said the framework for a new collective bargaining
agreement could be hammered out as early as next week, putting NBA
players back on the court by the end of January and salvaging what
had been getting precariously close to a lost season.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are still in a ``delicate'' stage, but Stern and Hunter
are close to resolving several points of contention in the
often-acrimonious labor negotiations between the owners and the
National Basketball Players' Association. And the only way they
felt it could get done was away from the media spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy as well as David understands the fact that if we get
this (a new agreement) done, they're going to have to do it,'' said
one source of the secret meetings. ``They weren't going to get it
done (with the negotiating committees) because there was just too
much finger-pointing going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking each individual issue and coming to an
agreement so each side understands what the other has agreed to.
When they finally come in there (to the full negotiating
committees), they're going to have it down so neither side can say,
`No, that's not what I meant.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way it's going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Hunter brought in scaled-down negotiating teams for a
secret five-hour meeting in New York on Thursday. Stern and deputy
commissioner Russ Granik represented the owners, and Hunter and
union president Patrick Ewing represented the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed not to discuss any of the details, and I don't want
to break that pledge,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   More discussions are planned for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key issues reportedly hammered out is the percentage
of basketball-related income (BRI) to be divided between players
and owners. The owners began negotiations requesting a 50-50 split,
while players had a 60-40 split as their starting point.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that the final agreement will have players
receiving an average of 54 percent of BRI over the life of a
seven-year agreement, even though the union was still asking for a
bit more than that as of Friday. The owners will respond by
relaxing their proposal for a timing-rule change, which would have
forced teams that sign another team's free agent to forfeit the
right to go over the salary cap to re-sign their own Larry Bird
exception free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The timing-rule change reportedly will be phased in after two or
three years, with possible exemptions involved to make it less
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be unhappy people on both sides when this
(agreement) is announced,'' said one source. ``But that's
understandable when you look at the hard-line stance both sides
took during the course of this lockout. Something had to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some things the players are going to get
that the owners won't be happy with, and there are some things the
owners are going to get that aren't going to make the players
happy. But that's part of the negotiating process.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some grumbling over concessions, approval of the new
collective bargaining agreement by the union rank and file is not
expected to be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that will not be a problem,'' said one union source of
approval. ``These guys have so much faith in Billy that when he
brings something to him, they're going to feel that it's the best
deal they could get. They trust him that much. As soon as the
negotiating committee gets through reviewing it, I'm confident it
will be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   That possibility seemed remote at best just one week ago, when
it appeared the cancellation of the season was imminent. But such a
move would cost the league an estimated $2 billion in revenues and
the players just over $1 billion in salaries and would do untold
damage to an image that has been embraced by corporate sponsors
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say both Stern and Hunter were unhappy with the
contentious nature of the negotiating meetings, preferring instead
to meet one-on-one, or in small groups, minus all the distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meetings had gone beyond negotiating,'' said one source.
``We had real serious negotiating problems. We'd start negotiating
on a point, but for whatever reason, things would break down into
shouting matches. It gets to the point where everyone is (angry) at
each other, and nothing gets accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can get more accomplished in a smaller group. They've
been over this territory so many times that it's not like they're
starting from scratch. It's just Billy and David saying, `Can you
sell this to your people?' and, `Can you sell this to yours?'
That's what's allowing this (stalemate) to break.''
</P>
<P>
   The next hurdle will be getting players in camp while the
agreement is drawn up and ratified, a process that could take two
weeks, even though some think the process could be condensed to 10
days. Stern has indicated in the past that a handshake deal would
not be enough to lift the lockout, since that occurred after the
brief 1995 lockout, when misunderstandings and disagreements over
``unresolved issues'' caused further tensions between players and
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, one management source said, ``The lockout will
continue until the ink is dry on the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, at least three weeks would be necessary to sign free
agents, make trades, hold an abbreviated training camp and squeeze
in either an exhibition game or a scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The league will reportedly organize a schedule that will have
teams playing exclusively in their respective conferences, which is
what hockey did after the lockout of 1994-95, when the NHL, after a
six-day camp, wound up playing 48 games in a 102-day regular
season. Every NHL game that season was played in-conference, with
more weight given to divisional games.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA will go with a schedule that is all in-conference,
meaning the only time East will meet West will be in the NBA
Finals. But the NBA will go with a balanced, completely redrawn
52-game schedule, which means the Rockets would play each of the
other 13 Western Conference teams four times. Because each Eastern
Conference team would have 14 opponents, a slight adjustment will
be necessary for those clubs to play 52 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the traditional thing to do,'' said one NBA source,
``but it's not going to be a traditional season.''
</P>
<P>
   Is 52 games enough to make a meaningful season? Consider that at
the halfway point of last season, the top eight teams in each
conference were the same eight that made the playoffs _ Chicago,
Indiana, Miami, New Jersey, New York, Charlotte, Atlanta and
Cleveland in the East, and Utah, Seattle, San Antonio, Houston,
Phoenix, Portland, Minnesota and the Lakers in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Should the season begin Feb. 1, which is the date many are
pointing to right now, the Rockets would have 40 games left on
their old schedule, which ends April 21.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the extra 12 games necessary to reach 52, the NBA
would play through what would have been the All-Star break (Feb.
10-16) and tack on an additional two weeks to the end of the
regular season, perhaps going until May 10. As a result, the
playoffs would be pushed back toward the end of June, with Game 7
of the Finals scheduled for no later than July 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it makes any sense to us or to them (TV
networks) to put the Finals on into July,'' Granik said.
``Households using television drops so dramatically as you approach
July 4th weekend, that I don't think that is a realistic
possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
