<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WINTERMEETINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rumors run ahead of action at baseball meetings
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The baseball winter meetings, which resumed
Friday after a six-year absence, are famous for big deals and
bigger rumors.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of that reputation stood up on Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slow day when the sight of Steve Avery walking into the
interview room qualifies as big news, but that was the highlight of
Friday's dealings. The veteran lefthander signed a one-year deal
with Cincinnati, officially kicking off the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a few rumors were making the rounds, including one
involving the Astros, and the agent for Kevin Brown hinted that his
client is close _ perhaps within hours _ of announcing who will
employ that talented right arm for the next five, six or seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash brushed off speculation the
Astros and Toronto had reached an agreement on a trade that would
send outfielder Derek Bell and righthanded reliever Jay Powell to
Toronto for five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' Ash said sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are believed to be pushing for a package anchored
by Bell and righthander Scott Elarton. Outfielder Carl Everett's
name also has been mentioned in recent speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Ash said five teams remain in the running for Clemens, with two
teams farther along in the process than the other three. The Astros
are believed to be one of the two front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that we'll leave here (Nashville) without
getting this done,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our winter-meetings practice. In the past, clubs
always have shown a willingness to do deals in this setting. This
isn't Rocket science; excuse the pun. This is a matter of trying to
get the best deal possible.''
</P>
<P>
   All eyes will continue to focus on Clemens and Astro-killer
Brown, who reportedly has narrowed his choice of teams to Los
Angeles and Baltimore _ the only two willing to meet agent Scott
Boras' demand for a six-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Once the two marquee pitchers have landed with new teams, it
could have a domino effect on other dealings and create the kind of
excitement that gave this annual session its reputation in the late
1980s and early '90s _ before team owners got fed up with the kind
of money being paid out and canceled the gathering of baseball's
general managers.
</P>
<P>
   In signing Avery, the Reds reunited the lefthander with the man
who replaced him in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, 10-7 for Boston last season, was the Braves' No. 4
starter in 1996 until Atlanta acquired Denny Neagle from
Pittsburgh. Avery was bumped to the bullpen, became a free agent
after the 1996 World Series, and spent the last two seasons with
the Red Sox, where he was a combined 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle was traded to the Reds last month in a four-player deal
also involving Bret Boone and Michael Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, 28, the Red Sox's No. 4 starter most of 1998, said: ``I
like hitting, and I like the NL cities. That's not a knock on the
AL. But I think if you're a pitcher, you like the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a hitter, you like the AL. And I'm no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's only other deal involved outfielder Tony Phillips
agreeing to terms with Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is said to be interested in Astros righthander
Sean Bergman, and the Astros would seem to have an excess of
starting pitching _ if there is such a thing _ assuming Chris Holt
makes a full recovery from rotator-cuff surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker is expected to arrive
here on Sunday, and he would love to return home with a deal for
Clemens. But he probably would settle for addressing a couple of
the Astros' other needs _ a righthanded reliever and a righthanded
bat off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   In other major-league rumblings, Reds shortstop Barry Larkin has
asked to be traded, listing five teams as possible destinations _
including the Dodgers, Cardinals, Cubs and Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Reds general manager Jim Bowden has said he doesn't intend to
trade Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have explored trade possibilities involving All-Star
outfielder Greg Vaughn, and Boston appears to have an interest.
Also, all-time steals leader Rickey Henderson is expected to sign
with either the Mets or Mariners by the time the winter meetings
end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
