</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Reconnecting with the past gives Drexler's Cougars direction
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
RALEIGH, N.C. _ Never mind the flecks of gray in the hair, the age
lines that sprint away from the corners of the eyes or the extra
pound or so around the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how you know you're getting old:
</P>
<P>
   At a recent practice, University of Houston assistant basketball
coach Reid Gettys was asked a question by one of his players.
``Coach,'' the kid wanted to know, ``have we ever played North
Carolina State before?''
</P>
<P>
   Have the Dodgers played the Yankees? Have the Colts played the
Jets? Has Poland ever played Germany?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy,'' said Gettys, smiling and then swinging his arm to
deliver a mock backhand. ``I just wanted to smack him.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgive them their naivet, these millennium-straddling
dribblers. The oldest, Gee Gervin, was only 6{ years old on April
4, 1983, the gloomiest night in Cougars basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Anders just misses the steal. Dereck Whittenburg launches
the fateful airball. Lorenzo Charles stuffs in the dunk for the
NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State 54, Houston 52.
</P>
<P>
   It was the night when Jimmy Valvano seemed to sprint all over
downtown Albuquerque, N.M., searching for somebody to hug and the
Cougars left the floor with a vacant look in their eyes that hasn't
gone completely away, even 15 year later.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings them all to tonight's encounter at Reynolds
Coliseum, just another game on the schedule for the rookie head
coach's 4-3 team, but full of tainted memories for Clyde Drexler
and his staff. For Drexler, a junior, it was his last collegiate
game before leaving for the NBA. Michael Young was a junior, Gettys
a sophomore and George Walker a graduate assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde, as you might expect, tries to glide over any show of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I would have liked to have won that game,'' he said.
``But look at it this way. If we had won like everybody expected,
the world might never have heard of Jim Valvano. That was his claim
to fame, and now he's gone. Maybe you have to say that every event
does have a purpose from some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you, there are February games against the
Clippers that I can remember every detail of the loss. The key is
to learn and then let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Without a doubt. No different than a loss to the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   So consider this tale told by Gettys, who is in charge of
putting together the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Saturday morning last May, just a couple of hours
before the Rockets were going to play the Jazz in Game 5 of the
playoffs, and I called Clyde in his hotel room in Salt Lake City.
He was going out the door to the game when I got him. He was in a
hurry. But I said, `Just one question. I've got a chance to line up
a game with N.C. State. Do you want it?' And he didn't hesitate for
a second. `Absolutely!' he said. `Get them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was last Saturday night after the Cougars survived a
63-61 win at Sacramento State. Drexler had just finished addressing
the media when Tom Abatemarco, the losing coach and a former N.C.
State reserve, entered the room. He walked right up to Drexler,
shoved his hand with the NCAA championship ring in Clyde's face and
said, ``Yeah, but I got you in '83.''
</P>
<P>
   What is often forgotten is N.C. State got UH twice in '83,
winning 76-64 behind Spud Webb in the Hall of Fame Classic at
Springfield, Mass., to open the next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack will finally pay a visit to Hofheinz Pavilion next
year. A four-game set with Georgetown is on tap, and the Coogs are
trying to get a series with North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Gettys jokes that he seeks revenge on all of UH's conquerors in
the Final Four in '82, '83 and '84. But it's actually part of the
big picture, which is to upgrade the schedule considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be happy to have every game against a Top 25 team,''
Drexler said. ``That's the only way we're going to get where we
want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Gettys works the phones. He has managed to get the Cougars a
spot in the high-profile Top of the World Classic next year in
Nome, Alaska. They will likely play in the Puerto Rico Shootout in
2000, Rainbow Classic (Hawaii) in 2001 and Great Alaska Shootout in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA, Stanford, Kentucky, Duke, Temple _ we'll play any of
them,'' he said. ``We want to get this back to where we were. I
remember how that excitement and emotion felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they have to spoon-feed it to the next generation. So
the other day at practice, in the middle of three-on-two drills,
Gettys called out to Treva Crosby, a sophomore, who was 5 years old
in 1983:
</P>
<P>
   ``Treva, how do we feel about N.C. State?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate 'em!''
</P>
<P>
   Even Clyde smiled. It's all part of the teaching process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
