<SLUG> BC-BURNED-TEEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNED STUDENT OFF CRITICAL LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICIA FARRELL AIDEM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hart High School senior Christopher James was
taken off the critical list Friday, days after he exercised his
burned vocal cords for the first time in two weeks to tell his
mother, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors upgraded James' condition from critical to serious after
performing the latest in a series of skin-grafting surgeries, said
Larry Weinberg, spokesman for the Grossman Burn Center at Sherman
Oaks Hospital. The 17-year-old was severely burned Nov. 25 in a
physics class experiment on the football field of the Newhall
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's past the critical shock stage,'' Weinberg said. ``He now
has a tracheotomy tube that allows him to speak somewhat. I don't
think they want him to talk too much, but the first thing was to
his mom. He said, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   James and two classmates were burned the day before Thanksgiving
while participating in a physics experiment that involved homemade
cannons ignited by burning methanol.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel flashed, severely burning James and classmate Nolan
LeMar.
</P>
<P>
   James inhaled the superheated fuel, burning his vocal cords, and
35 percent of his body was severely burned. LeMar suffered burns
over 12 percent of his body and was released from the Sherman Oaks
hospital Sunday. Classmate Jesse Honea was treated at Henry Mayo
Newhall Memorial Hospital and released the day of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly happened during the physics class is being
investigated by Sheriff's Department arson specialists and school
officials, but the William S. Hart Union High School District has
halted such experiments until their questions are answered. The
experiment is not uncommon, and is used to teach students to
measure velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's surgery was expected to be one of the final skin
graftings for James. Doctors took healthy skin from the teen's back
and used it to cover the last of the burned areas to prevent
life-threatening infection caused by bacteria from decaying skin.
</P>
<P>
   Infection is still the greatest threat to the varsity soccer
player, but doctors are ``always more comfortable when they've
covered the damaged skin,'' Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the grafting is done,'' he said. ``Everybody can feel
a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also viewed James' lungs and vocal cords with a scope
and were pleased with his progress.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements have raised James' spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten a lift from being able to talk with his folks,''
Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   According to his parents, he is visited constantly by relatives
and school friends.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
