<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SABERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK AGAIN SHUTS OUT THE RANGERS, AND THEY GET TESTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Goalie Dominik Hasek of the Sabres gets lots of
shutouts. Some are spectacular, the kind that have prompted voters
to award him the Vezina and Hart trophies for the last two seasons
as the best goalie and the most valuable player in the National
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Others are just routine. That was the case Friday night, when
Hasek made only 16 saves in a 2-0 victory over the Rangers. It was
so routine that he was not even the most interesting Sabre. That
distinction went to Mike Peca, who scored the winning goal, and his
linemate Vaclav Varada, who scored the other one and had many
Rangers angry at him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hasek's second shutout against the Rangers this season
and his fifth over all, to lead the league. Mike Richter, the
Ranger goalie, was the man of the match, making 30 saves, many of
them spectacular. The only shot that beat him was a backhander by
Peca, the Sabres' captain, with 2 minutes 1 second remaining in
what was then a scoreless game, a rebound that was the third shot
of a high-pressure volley.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a minute remaining and Richter out of his net for
an extra attacker, Varada scored for Buffalo into the empty net. He
took his time about it, tantalizing Todd Harvey, who chased him
down the ice, before depositing the puck over the line as if it
were a Christmas card in a mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   After the red light flashed, Harvey continued his pursuit,
following the celebrating Varada to the sideboards. From behind,
Harvey hit him on the head, triggering an angry scrum of players
immediately and another one after the next face-off.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were angry not only for the empty-net goal, but for
something Varada said two weeks ago after Buffalo beat the Rangers
by 4-2. When asked how hard it was for his line to check Wayne
Gretzky's line, Varada said it was easy, that he did not have much
to do because Gretzky spent much of that game, two weeks ago, in
the middle of the ice without the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to talk about that kind of stuff in the papers,
that is up to him,'' Harvey said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's deed could be reviewed for suspension by Colin
Campbell, the National Hockey's Leagues chief disciplinarian.
However, Campbell is the former Rangers coach and he has chosen
twice this season not to suspend New York players for flagrant
fouls. One was a ``slew-foot'' trip by Jeff Beukeboom; the other
was a flagrant elbow by Ulf Samuelsson.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought the league should investigate Harvey's
deed, Varada said: ``They should do something. It's not my
decision. I got fined last game for a cross-check.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone suggested that the Rangers remained angry about his
words regarding Gretzky, Varada said: ``I said what was the truth.
I didn't lie and I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's attack was similar to that by Washington's Dale Hunter
against Pierre Turgeon, then with the Islanders, in the 1993
playoffs. Hunter was suspended for 21 games, but Turgeon suffered a
severe shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Varada said he was not hurt except for a headache. But earlier
this season, Matt Johnson of Los Angeles was suspended for 12 games
after knocking Beukeboom unconscious with a sucker punch.
Beukeboom, who returned for a few games, has missed the last two
with post-concussion syndrome. The league has said it is cracking
down on blows to the head.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the Rangers coach, said he did not see Harvey's
hit. But Lindy Ruff, the Buffalo coach, said: ``I didn't like the
fact that Harvey came from all the way from across the ice to jump
him from behind. That wasn't really called for. If you're going to
get a guy and you're upset with him, get him at the right time.
After he scores a goal, he's not looking. I guess it was a cheap
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 0-2-1 against Buffalo this season, including a
0-0 tie, and are 0-6-3 against them in their last nine meetings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers' second consecutive defeat. Their last best
chance to tie was hurt in the final minute when defenseman Mathieu
Schneider was sent off for elbowing Jay McKee after the Rangers had
pulled Richter for an extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game, several Rangers bumped Varada hard, but
that didn't give them an edge in the first period. After 20
minutes, the Sabres had a 14-2 advantage in shots, and one of the
Rangers' two shots came in the final seconds, from near the New
York blue line, by Brian Leetch, near the end of an ineffective
power play. During two power plays in the first half of the second
period, the Rangers had no shots on goal, although a couple
whistled inches wide of Hasek's posts.
</P>
<P>
   As play ground on toward the second intermission, the top lines
for both teams got good chances, grinding and cycling deep. Petr
Nedved's line and Gretzky's line threatened, as did Peca's. But,
after 40 minutes, the score was 0-0 with Buffalo holding a 22-9
edge in shots
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
