<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARMIJO-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZANARDI PREDICTED HIS RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only did Alex Zanardi seal his future by capturing the
Championship Auto Racing Teams title, he also predicted it.
</P>
<P>
   A second straight championship nudged Zanardi into seeking
Formula One employment, which he secured by signing a lucrative
contract to drive next season and beyond for Frank Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But before Zanardi departed for Italy, where he lives, he proved
prophetic by announcing he would return to Indianapolis Motor
Speedway before any of his CART peers.
</P>
<P>
   As it eventually turned out, Zanardi was right.
</P>
<P>
   A rumor became a reality last week when IMS owner Tony George
and F-1 czar Bernie Ecclestone said the series will return to the
United States in 2000 for the first time since 1991, when it waved
bye-bye to Phoenix after three financially dismal performances.
</P>
<P>
   While some purists believe the additions of NASCAR's Brickyard
400 and now the U.S. Grand Prix at Indianapolis will further dilute
the prestige and glamour of the track, which for 82 years was the
site of only the Indy 500 and nothing else, there's no question
that F-1 needs to be in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Although the defunct Iceberg Grand Prix through the streets of
downtown Phoenix attracted ridiculously sparse crowds, those fans
who did pony up the cost of outrageously priced tickets ($50 for
standing room only) watched some of the all-time greatest drivers.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to judge the immense talents of such drivers as
Alain Prost and the late Ayrton Senna on a temporary downtown road
course lacking technological genius, but there should be no
question regarding Senna's abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Senna could have negotiated a one-hour commute home during rush
hour into a 20-minute breeze. And he would have done so without so
much as a scratch on the fender.
</P>
<P>
   F-1's recent version of Senna is Germany's Michael Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Finland's Mika Hakkinen captured this year's crown,
Schumacher remains the sport's heralded star.
</P>
<P>
   A chance to see Schumacher in person should be on any fan's
holiday wish list. And if F-1 racing continues to put on decent
shows, unlike some years when there were more passes at a shy
people's convention than there were on the racetrack, whatever
George charges will be money well-spent.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is Ecclestone. I don't trust him.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, city officials share some of the blame for entering into a
contract in which it would pay $8 million over five years to stage
a race and not even share in gate receipts, advertising or
concession revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But Ecclestone is the same flighty bird who left the Valley the
day before the first race in 1989, undoubtedly embarrassed by poor
ticket sales, and the same guy who didn't even show up for the 1990
race.
</P>
<P>
   Ecclestone stuck around for the third race, assuring at least
one member of the media that the series would return for the
contract's final two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will exhaust all possibilities before we even think'' of
moving to another state, Ecclestone said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during the course of two telephone calls seven months
later, Ecclestone informed city officials that the circuit would
not return.
</P>
<P>
   Ecclestone cited low attendance, among other reasons, for
pulling the plug on the financial nightmare, leaving the city with
an approximate $1.2 million bill for garages, barricades and other
race-related capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, I don't think it looked like a good deal for
Phoenix,'' said Jim Haynes, who was Chamber of Commerce president
at the time. ``It was a very expensive lesson in humility for the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ticket prices ($50 to $100) were astronomical, and there
were very little resources committed to marketing the event by
Formula One,'' Greater Phoenix Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau
President David Radcliffe said. ``It was always up to the city (to
do the promoting), but (Ecclestone) was the one always making
money. His net (profit) was pretty much guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the city fallout, the on-track performance, while not
always spectacular over the Phoenix layout, still provided a
glimpse into F-1 racing and its stars.
</P>
<P>
   If the racing is as good as it was this past season, it will
have been worth the wait. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 0240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
