<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR &UR; TV-AZR &LR;      12-12 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR SEEKS DRIVER'S SEAT  
 CIRCUIT WANTS TO NEGOTIATE OWN TV DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  TV-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its never-ending search to further fatten the piggy bank,
NASCAR may start doing what other professional sports already do,
which is negotiate its television contracts.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's surging popularity has transformed the sport into a
financial cash cow on four wheels. Yearly souvenir and licensed
merchandise sales should reach $1 billion by 2000, and attendance
is at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings also have increased, up 20.8 percent between
1993 and 1997. During the same period on cable, the increase was 40
percent, according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, NASCAR television ratings (5.8) in 1997 were second
only to the NFL (12.2).
</P>
<P>
   So like any business, NASCAR is attempting to take advantage of
its product. And one way it might succeed is studying whether it
would be economically prudent to auction off its TV rights.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, racetrack owners do their negotiating, a major
reason 33 races this past season were shown on two broadcast (CBS,
ABC) and three cable (ESPN, TNN, TBS) networks. NBC also will join
the mix in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NFL recently signed an eight year, $18 billion
contract for its TV rights, NASCAR rights fees are sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   TNN President David Hall, whose cable network televised nine
Winston Cup races last season, including the Dura-Lube/Kmart 500 at
Phoenix International Raceway, estimated the average rights fee
worth of each race is about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race is not worth the same amount of money,'' Hall said.
``I read where (CBS paid) $12.5 million for the Daytona 500, but
the rest of the races average in the $3 million range, and some are
in the $600,000 range.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if NASCAR's study concludes all parties would be
financially better off by allowing it sole authority to sell the
entire TV rights package, the sanctioning body still will have to
convince racetrack owners to go along with it. And that might be
difficult considering much of a racetrack's annual revenue stems
from rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, between International Speedway Corp., Speedway
Motorsports Inc., and Penske Motorsports Inc., those companies own
nearly half of the racetracks comprising the Winston Cup schedule.
And many of their races are sold as a package.
</P>
<P>
   ISC owns six racetracks, including PIR and Daytona International
Speedway, and SMI also owns six.
</P>
<P>
   ISC spokesman David Talley declined to speculate what NASCAR
might or might not do.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Hall isn't overly worried of losing his place
on the NASCAR map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we would be part of (the future),'' Hall said.
``There's no way we would wake up one day standing on the
sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   PIR Executive Vice President and General Manager Robin Braig
said he hopes Hall is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with TNN,'' Braig said. ``TNN gives us
great coverage and a great lineup of broadcasters.''
</P>
<P>
   TNN recently extended its contract with PIR by three years,
which now expires in 2001. Although neither Hall nor PIR officials
would reveal the financial terms of the deal, it is believed to be
worth between $15 million and $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the agreement, however, is the Copper World Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, what NASCAR is studying probably will (become a
reality),'' Hall said. ``But I think (NASCAR) has a long, long ways
to go in getting it done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
