<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON HAS BEEN EARLY DISAPPOINTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The early returns from Pac-10 precincts are in, and there aren't
a lot of surprises so far. Stanford, despite losses to North
Carolina and Maryland and some injuries that have thinned its
bench, is still probably the league's best team, although ``Sports
Illustrated's'' preseason No. 1 ranking was ludicrous.
Freshman-intensive Arizona and UCLA are formidable now and will
only get better. California looks like an NCAA Tournament team.
Southern California is exceeding expectations, Oregon and Arizona
State are under construction and Washington State and Oregon State
are laying the groundwork for potential coaching changes.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves Washington as the biggest, and most disappointing,
story to date.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off its first NCAA Tournament appearance since 1986,
where they advanced to the Sweet 16, and the fourth straight year
of improvement under Coach Bob Bender, the Huskies were supposed to
break through this year. They made everyone's preseason Top 25, and
SI had them eighth. (What's with this infatuation with the Pac-10?)
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Washington has turned the predictions to mush,
making it seem as if last year's hot streak during the tournament
was more like a hot flash. The Huskies are 4-3, losers of three
straight for the first time since the 1994-95 season. After losing
by 20 to Connecticut in the Great Eight, the next two defeats came
at the hands of Boise State and Gonzaga. Both were on the road and
both happened without starting guard Donald Watts, who injured his
ankle in the Boise State game, but this is not how a quality team
is supposed to play.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows this better than Bender, who yelled at his players
after the Gonzaga game, which ended with the Spokane Arena crowd
yelling ``overrated'' at the Huskies. The primary topic on Bender's
agenda was toughness _ the Huskies' apparent lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all new for our guys, being an important (opponent)
for people,'' Bender said. ``Obviously, we haven't learned our
lessons yet. That's what needs to sink in. We're not pushing all
the right buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior center Todd MacCulloch scored 28 points against Gonzaga,
trying to fill the void left by Watts, who averaged 16.9 points
last year. Junior forward Chris Walcott added 18. But junior guard
Deon Luton made just 1 of 9 shots. Luton was one of three Huskies,
along with MacCulloch and Watts, who averaged more than 15 points
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Luton will have better days, but the overriding problem
continues to be at point guard. That should have been a red flag
for anyone who fell in love with the Huskies before the season.
Sophomore Dan Dickau and freshman Senque Carey are showing their
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Counting three games at the Hilo Classic in Hawaii, which the
Huskies won against a so-so field, Washington played six straight
games away from home in 11 days because Bender wanted to toughen
his troops. It's far too early to write anyone off, and the Huskies
probably are better than what they have shown lately. The question
is whether they're as good as they were supposed to be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Temple doomed? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An even more mystifying tailspin is Temple's. The Owls, who
appeared to be a bona fide Top 10 team, have lost four straight for
the first time since 1992-93 and for only the third time in head
coach John Chaney's 17 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the skid should be five, because Temple was admittedly
lucky in coming back to beat Michigan State in their last victory.
The Owls trailed by 10 points with 3:36 to go, but took advantage
of the new held-ball rule to overtake the Spartans on two free
throws by Pepe Sanchez with half a second remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney remarked before that game that it wouldn't be bad if his
team lost, just to humble his players a little bit. Now it seems
they're getting a bit carried away with that. Like Bender, Chaney
addressed his team at great length and decibel level after the
latest loss, 63-56, at home to Wisconsin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost our way,'' Chaney said. ``The guards beat us
tonight. Not the other guards, our guards. We got beat through our
own lack of effort. They were absolutely horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin is pretty good at 8-1, and its coach, Dick Bennett, is
excellent. But Chaney is genuinely concerned. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fast breaks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temple has plenty of company in the Atlantic-10 in the letdown
department. Two other teams with high expectations, Massachusetts
and Xavier (Ohio), are off to slow starts. UMass played well in its
59-54 loss to No. 1 Connecticut, but the Minutemen have dropped
four straight since beating Niagara to start the season. Xavier is
missing injured forward Darnell Williams but still has a deep,
veteran team. But the Musketeers have lost four of their past six.
After losing to Toledo on Wednesday, Coach Skip Prosser turned
around en route to his post-game radio show to offer some more
thoughts to his team. He never did the show.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't often that a ranked team derives a moral victory from a
loss, but that's how Stanford looked at the Maryland game. Playing
perhaps the best team in the country in a near-road environment
(the MCI Center in Washington, D.C.), the Cardinal shot 40 percent
and had 19 turnovers, yet lost by just two. Forward Peter Sauer
said, ``I think it's a confidence builder. We're not hitting on all
cylinders and we're right there. We know that when we play well, we
can beat any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California outscored Loyola Marymount by 37 points
Wednesday _ in the second half. The Trojans shot 29 percent in the
first half and trailed by one point before steamrolling the Lions
after halftime. USC (6-0), off to its best start since 1974-75,
will play at Kansas tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State's next game is Dec. 19 at Texas A&AMP;M. The 7-1
Aggies are led by point guard Clifton Cook, a transfer from Howard.
Cook's nickname is ``Fats.'' Why is that? His dad said, ``He was so
overweight when he was a baby that he could barely walk. He just
kind of wobbled. So, one day I called him a `big old fatso.'
Everybody laughed and the nickname stuck. His friends later
shortened it to Fats.'' Let's hear it for positive reinforcement. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
