<HEADLINE>
MOTEN ACTIVATED, LIKELY TO KEEP PLANE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rumors persist that the loser in the Los Angeles-Houston NFL
expan sion sweepstakes will try to bring an existing franchise to
that city, but the Cardinals may not be that team.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Robert McNair has said he would go after
another franchise if Los Angeles is picked over Houston for the
NFL's 32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to McNair said he would have little interest in
the Cardinals because the team is not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   McNair owns the rights to the Houston franchise and wants to run
the team. The Cardinals have been owned by the Bidwill family since
the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials reiterated Friday that they have had no
contact with officials from either city and are spending their time
trying to get a new multipurpose domed stadium in the East Valley. &QL; 
Mike Moten has followed a circu itous path to reclaiming a roster
spot for the Cardinals' stretch drive to the playoffs. He was
activated on Friday when Eric Swann was placed on injured reserve,
officially ending the Pro Bowl defensive tackle's season.
</P>
<P>
   Moten was yanked off the team's charter jet moments before
takeoff for the season opener to Dallas and told he'd been waived
because hold out first-round draft pick Andre Wadsworth had come to
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Moten was re-signed to the practice squad midway through the
season. He was activated for Sunday's game at Philadelphia in the
wake of widespread injuries along the defen sive line, including
Swann's seventh knee surgery on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a backup almost my whole career at Florida, so I know
how important it is to stay ready,'' Moten said.
</P>
<P>
   He will be insurance against further injuries. Backups Rashod
Swinger and Bernard Wilson will start at the tackles for Swann and
Mark Smith (ankle). First-team ends Simeon Rice (ribs) and
Wadsworth (calf) are expected to start. Wadsworth prac ticed most
of the week. Rice did not practice at all. Carl Simpson and Jomo
Cousins also are available for backup duty ahead of Moten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who are playing are maybe not as good as the guys
they are replacing, but they've got to execute and do their
responsibilities, and I think they will do that,'' Coach Vince
Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles no doubt have noted the Cardinals have had difficulty
stop ping the run recently. Eagles back Duce Staley is averaging
3.9 yards per carry and is on pace for a 1,000-yard season. &QL; 
Take a seat &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tobin on Friday announced that offensive lineman Matt Joyce (bro
ken hand), Smith, running back Michael Pittman (broken hand) and
cornerback Tom Knight (hamstring strain) will be inactive.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the status of starting middle linebacker Ron
McKinnon a game-day decision. McKinnon has not practiced and has
been expected to miss his second straight game (knee strain). He
would be replaced again by Mark Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   Three more players will be declared inactive on Sunday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Move unlikely &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rumors persist that the loser in the Los Angeles-Houston NFL expan
sion sweepstakes will try to bring an existing franchise to that
city, but the Cardinals may not be that team.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Robert McNair has said he would go after
another franchise if Los Angeles is picked over Houston for the
NFL's 32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to McNair said he would have little interest in
the Cardinals because the team is not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   McNair owns the rights to the Houston franchise and wants to run
the team. The Cardinals have been owned by the Bidwill family since
the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials reiterated Friday that they have had no
contact with officials from either city and are spending their time
trying to get a new multipurpose domed stadium in the East Valley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
