<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-JACKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKE GETS COLD RECEPTION  
 KICKER HAPPY ABOUT 2ND SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it one of life's ironies.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals kicker Chris Jacke spent eight years on the frozen
tundra of Green Bay, often dreaming of performing his art on a soft
green field under a warm sun.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a place that sounds, looks and smells exactly like
the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   So Jacke arrives in town as the emergency replacement for
injured kicker Joe Nedney last week, and on the day he debuts, it
snows in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable, it snows and now I've got a cold,'' said Jacke,
who upon arrival last week suggested he might carry around a bag of
ice to remind him of Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will be perfectly happy if he merely kicks as he
did in Green Bay, where he posted very impressive numbers en route
to winning a Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   During his eight seasons there, Jacke attempted 22 field goals
in the fourth quarter when the score was within three points of
being tied. He made 19.
</P>
<P>
   Not once did he miss from inside the 30 in the fourth quarter or
overtime. He's one of only three players in Packers history to
score 700 points, and he made 15 game-winning kicks.
</P>
<P>
   He made good on 40 of his 51 field-goal attempts in the fourth
quarter or in overtime, and 17 of the 26 field goals he tried from
50-plus yards.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was 31 of 39 on grass fields when the temperature
was 32 degrees or lower, which makes one only hope that whoever
kept that statistic has found a life.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke's one-game Arizona career is perfect and now consists two
successful extra-point conversions and a 21-yard field goal after
sitting out for what basically has been a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The butterflies were gone after the first kick,'' Jacke said
of last Sunday's action. ``After that, you don't have time to think
about it because you are into the flow of the game. Once you are
out there, it's like you have done it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was this man so unceremoniously bumped into the night by the
Packers after Green Bay's Super Bowl victory on Jan. 26, 1997?
Because the Pack didn't show him the money.
</P>
<P>
   Dealings between his agent, Steve Weinberg, and the team grew so
acrimonious that the team wasn't going to take Jacke along when it
visited the White House after the Super Bowl victory. It yielded
only after public reaction to the slight.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day, Weinberg thought he was close to reaching a deal,
but the Packers refused to give an extra $150,000 to $200,000
signing bonus and drafted kicker Brett Conway, who is no longer
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice of the fans to rally around me, but everything
that happened there is now in the past,'' Jacke said. ``I don't
even think about it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he didn't have time to think of it. He went to
Pittsburgh's training camp last year but suffered a thigh injury
and was released.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play again until the final game of the season, when he
was 5 for 5 on extra points and was promptly released. He spent
this season working in the finance department for American Express
in Green Bay, until Nedney suffered his injury two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough sitting at home knowing or feeling that I could
still be kicking in this league,'' Jacke said. ``It was real tough.
It's why I've got to use this opportunity to take full advantage of
it. I don't know what the outcome will be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they (Cardinals) are quite happy with Joe, and he's
done an outstanding job for them. I can possibly use this as a
steppingstone to go elsewhere or, if they want me, to just come
back here. We can discuss it after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Cardinals called about replacing Nedney, Jacke's phone
wasn't ringing off the hook. He might have thought he could still
kick in the league, but even he had some doubts about whether
another opportunity would surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there were times when I thought it (career) was over,''
said Jacke, whose wife, Tracey, and two young sons are remaining in
Green Bay until his future is solidified. ``But you have to keep
out. I've been out of the game for a year and a half, but I kept
plugging and kicking, hoping for another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unhappy it happened this way, but it has and I have to
take advantage of it. I kicked 25 to 30 balls, twice a week. I did
it because I thought I'd get one more chance, and I wanted to stay
in shape. If not this year, then when expansion comes. There will
probably be a lot of movement among players and kickers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 0243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
