<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ACTION AT WINTER MEETINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ There was a time when the winter meetings took place
in the lobby of whatever hotel major league officials converged on
each December.
</P>
<P>
   The wheeling and dealing were intense as general managers
basically set up shop in some lounge chair, usually one where they
had a bird's-eye view of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I used to do,'' said Cincinnati Manager Jack
McKeon, who was nicknamed ``Trader Jack'' during his days as a
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd find the best seat in the lobby and plant myself there for
days. If I saw someone I wanted to talk to, I'd send someone over
to them and we'd talk. We'd end up making a deal in no time. Those
were different times, though. It's not the same anymore, at least I
don't see it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   No one sees it that way anymore, because general managers no
longer troll through the hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the winter meetings are back in earnest, just the way major
league baseball wanted them to be. After six years of baseball
dissuading big league clubs from attending the traditional winter
meetings, it has brought them back.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the national press has come back to the meetings,
once the zenith of all off-season baseball talk. But with free
agency taking center stage, the meetings don't measure up to their
former status. Trades aren't as big a part of baseball as they once
were. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No lobby strolling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These winter meetings really don't resemble the ones we
remember. General managers, who used to discuss (and sometimes
consummate) trades at the lobby, the hotel bar, the dining room and
even the registration line, no longer linger in plain sight.
</P>
<P>
   The days of strolling through the lobby looking for fellow GMs
appear to be over. After spending most of Friday waiting to watch
the migration of GMs _ any general managers _ the realization
finally set in that these are not the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   New-age general managers tend to spend their time holed up
inside their hotel rooms, making phone calls to each other and
poring over statistical breakdowns from computers (none of the
old-school GMs ever had a computer on hand) of any and all players
they might be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they think they can outsmart everyone by studying inside
their rooms,'' McKeon said. ``But that's not what these meetings
were for. They were for everyone to see each other and discuss
trades. You can't see anyone from inside your room.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason computer breakdowns are necessary seems to be the
general distrust among today's GMs. There was a time when GMs would
see each other and one would simply say, ``I need a catcher for my
Triple A club.''
</P>
<P>
   Another would say, ``I got one. I need an outfielder at Double
A.'' Within minutes, a deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, you knew you were getting equal value for the
player,'' former GM Dick Balderson said. ``You didn't want to screw
anyone over because word would spread that you didn't deal fairly.
There was a lot more trust in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's basically a free-for-all, with each club responsible
for knowing every player's ability in every system at every level.
That's sad. It's also sad how the winter meetings now include
little action. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lasorda does Lasorda &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights (if that's an appropriate word) from the
first day was watching Tommy Lasorda be Tommy Lasorda in the lobby
of the expansive Opryland Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as though Lasorda, who barely moved from one spot,
was in the lobby simply to be seen by anyone who cared to walk up
and ask him a question. Lasorda even stopped to take pictures with
Japanese tourists.
</P>
<P>
   There was nary a GM in the lobby Friday, and the odds seem small
that they will congregate there in the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   If the ensuing days resemble Friday, the winter meetings may
indeed be a thing of the past, at least in the traditional sense.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball needs to seize the moment instead of boring us to
death. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 0243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
