<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SEEK REVENGE FOR `EMBARRASSING' LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sits there, like a huge black mark on the NHL's best record.
The only blot on an otherwise unbeaten home record: Ottawa Senators
4, Phoenix Coyotes 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes can't erase the opening night setback, or its
memory. But they can gain some peace of mind tonight at 5 (Arizona
time) when they get their second and last chance of the regular
season at the Senators, who will play host at the Corel Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object is always to win, but, yeah, it means a little more
to us,'' Coyotes forward Keith Tkachuk said. ``It was embarrassing,
and we would like to get a little revenge, sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still the most important thing is to win to keep us going in
the right direction. It's always important to win the first game of
a road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game opens a four-game trip that also sees the Coyotes
play Monday night at Montreal, which Phoenix beat, 4-2, at home on
Wednesday night, and then take on Northeast Division-leading
Toronto on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The trip ends Thursday in St. Louis against the Blues, who are
second in the Central Division. The Coyotes return home Dec. 20 to
play the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has only one question mark in the injury department.
Defenseman Gerald Diduck missed the Montreal game because of a
thigh bruise and is listed day-to-day, but he was with the the team
when it departed Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to win every game you play, but obviously we will be
happy with anything over .500 on the trip,'' Tkachuk said. ``I'd
just like to see us start playing complete 60-minute games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been finding ways to win, but we haven't played a
complete 60 minutes of solid and hard hockey yet. We have been
getting up 2-0 and 3-0, but we haven't been putting teams away like
we should. Our record (16-3-3) is great, but we haven't played our
best yet. It's not even close.''
</P>
<P>
   After going unbeaten in 11 games in November, the Coyotes are
2-1-1 in December, a month in which they play 10 of their 14 games
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators, 13-9-3 and fourth in the tough Northeast Division,
are unbeaten in their past three outings against the Coyotes. But
at least the Coyotes won't see goalie Damian Rhodes, who was in net
in the opener and has stuffed Phoenix in two straight games by a
4-1 count.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes rotates in net with Ron Tugnutt, who will get the start
tonight. Tugnutt was in goal last season when the Coyotes tied the
Senators 4-4 at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ottawa is a hard-working and fast team,'' Tkachuk said. ``They
get a lot of goals on rushes that they create defensively with
their speed. We'll have to play a solid defensive game to beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in the opener. The Coyotes were a study in
still life. The Senators jumped off to a 1-0 first-period lead and
added two goals in 3{ minutes in the second period. Their play was
so disappointing that fans booed them as they left the ice at the
end of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense the poor effort served as a catalyst for the league's
fastest start. The Coyotes had four days off before they played
again, and returned to the ice against Colorado as a different team
that had bought into Coach Jim Schoenfeld's forechecking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a couple of games under their belt and it was opening
night for us,'' Tkachuk said. ``Like I said, it was embarrassing.
Opening nights are tough, but we expected a lot from ourselves and
so did the fans and we ended up standing around a lot.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
