<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ_SUPERFAN-     12-12 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ_SUPERFAN-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A WORKOUT FOR POTATOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's face facts: Some of your biggest sports fans are . . .
``big'' sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   As in, fat. Something about lying on a couch balancing a beer on
your belly while shoveling tortilla chips into your mouth as fast
as you can tends to lead to weight gain. I've known people who kept
coolers next to their recliners; if they knew how to
self-catheterize themselves, they'd never get up.
</P>
<P>
   If the only exercise you get during ``Monday Night Football'' is
lifting cylindrical weights that start out at 12 ounces and
decrease every time you lift them, well, welcome to the club,
fatso.
</P>
<P>
   But don't despair. Stewart Smith is offering hope.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a former Navy SEAL, has written ``The TV Watcher's
Workout'' ($14.95, Five Star Fitness). While it's aimed at tube
hounds of all types, it works fine for TV sports fans, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ideal for them,'' Smith said, from outside Annapolis,
Md., where he lives. ``You can probably get a good hour and a half
worth of exercise during a football game. There's a lot of
commercials in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't say is that many of those commercials advertise
beer and food. So maybe we're better off skipping them anyway. But
really, exercise?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Smith is, as you might guess, something of a fitness
nut. He's no longer in the Navy, but he owns a fitness center. He
got the idea for the book from his parents. Not from their minds _
from their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are the type of people who work all day, eat
dinner, watch a couple of hours of TV and go to bed,'' he said. ``I
was concerned for their health. They weren't tremendously
overweight, (but) I want my child to know grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew that starting them on a regular exercise program
wouldn't work, so he searched for an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dissected my parents' day to the minute,'' he said. ``I
said, `Where can we squeeze in exercise here without interrupting
their day too much?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The only place he could find was during their television time.
One problem: They didn't want to interrupt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let's do it during the commercials,' '' he said. ``I
started timing the commercials, and I said, `Wow!' I couldn't
believe there was 20 minutes of commercials in an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is laid out, as you might expect from a military man,
with precision. It tells you how to budget your time, how to
stretch, explains the exercises, offers schedules and includes a
section on nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   The exercises are your garden-variety basics, with television
names thrown in. For instance, the standard push-up is the ``Regis
Regular Push-up.'' One in which you put your knees on the ground is
the ``Kathy Lee Knee Push-up.'' Others include ``Letterman
Lunges,'' ``Brady Bunch Crunches'' and ``Primetime Pelvic Lifts,''
which sound rather adult in nature but aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Smith acknowledges that these are just a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a beginning exercise, for people who haven't done
anything in a long time or who never have before,'' he said. ``They
get a good foundation. Now they're ready to start a good exercise
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith works out regularly, but says he takes his own advice,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say I missed my workout because I was too busy all day,'' he
said. ``I drop down and try to do push-ups the entire commercial
series. You go to exhaustion, till you can't do them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't have to _ I'm exhausted just hearing him talk about it.
The next set of commercials he'll do squats, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has written a follow-up book of more advanced exercises,
called the ``Five Star Fitness Boot Camp Workout'' that he hopes
will be in stores early next year. Meanwhile, he's promoting ``The
TV Watcher's Workout'' and keeping his sense of humor. He knows his
book isn't for every couch potato, but that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``At worst,'' he said, laughing, ``it makes a great gift.'' &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
