   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Making his first appearance in public since
his arrest two months ago, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former
Chilean dictator, sternly told a London court Friday that he did
not acknowledge the right of any court outside his own country to
consider charges against him. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-U.S. (Washington) _ While Israel has frozen its
compliance with the Wye accords, the Palestinian Authority is not
fully complying with its own commitments at Wye, senior U.S. and
Israeli officials said Friday. By Steven Erlanger. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BOMB (Undated) _ A German official said Friday that his
government has received indications from U.S. officials that they
will not seek the death penalty for a suspected aide to Osama bin
Laden, which could clear a major hurdle to win the man's
extradition from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCHROEDER (Berlin) _ After assuring its allies that it
represents continuity, the new government of Gerhard Schroeder is
using a bold, often challenging directness that marks a radical
departure from other post-war German administrations. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-SUMMIT (Vienna) _ The European Union summit conference
opened with a squabble over how much expansion will cost and who
will pay what. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL-GODDESS (Katmandu) _ The little girl became Nepal's
official living goddess the day before she turned 4, a grandly
ceremonial event that made her parents enormously proud. But now,
seven years later, her parents are sorry they allowed their girl to
be plucked from obscurity and turned into the ornately costumed and
fussily pampered goddess, the Royal Kumari. By Barry Bearak. (With
photo and map.)
</P>
