   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ After a passionate debate that was by
turns solemn with history, fiercely partisan and at times
sorrowful, the House Judiciary Committee voted along party lines
Friday to impeach President Clinton and remove him from office for
perjury and obstruction of justice. By Alison Mitchell. (With
photos and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOOD (Washington) _ This is how it was to be Bill
Clinton this week: Holding a round of cheery Christmas parties
where your guests gobble your baby lamb chops and speculate, out of
your earshot, whether you will keep your job. Attending a private
viewing of ``Enemy of the State,'' even as you are accused of being
just that. By James Bennet and Melinda Henneberger. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ A careworn President Clinton on
Friday once more expressed regret for the actions that have brought
him to the brink of impeachment and, for the first time in public,
invited Congress to censure him. By John M. Broder. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Why, when the people have made
limpidly clear their view that Clinton should not be impeached _
polls, election _ do the Republicans press on? A news analysis by
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-NETWORKS (Undated) _ Faced with a daylong debate on a
proposed article of impeachment against the president of the United
States, only the third such debate in the nation's history, the
three big broadcast networks responded Friday with a collective
shrug, and the message: Wake us when they're voting. By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BOUCHER (Washington) _ A look at a significant Democrat
on the Judiciary Committee, Rick Boucher of Virginia. By Julian E.
Barnes. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GRAHAM (Washington) _ A look at a significant
Republican, Lindsey O. Graham of South Carolina. By Lizette
Alvarez. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-AMBITION (Washington) _ Rep. Rick Lazio of New York is
just one of the moderate Republicans who is calculating how to vote
based on complicated home-state political mathematics, that go far
beyond one district. For Lazio and others with larger ambitions
this vote is one that will be part of their biography for a long
time. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ As the impeachment vote neared,
oddly bipartisan tinges of sadness glimmered at times along the
House Judiciary Committee. A hurriedly jotted note of consolation _
``Don't worry, this is a strong country.'' _ was quietly dispatched
in mid-debate by a sympathetic Republican to a Democrat agonizing
across the aisle. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
