<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6412 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLEMENS-T     12-12 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLEMENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BID FOR CLEMENS FALLING SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Rangers lack the resources to acquire
right-hander Roger Clemens, unless their best proposal _ likely
right-hander Esteban Loaiza and designated hitter Lee Stevens among
others _ emerges as the most attractive the Toronto Blue Jays
receive.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' proposal for Toronto's five-time Cy Young Award
recipient encompasses only a ``framework or grouping'' of eight or
nine players for the Blue Jays' consideration, general manager Doug
Melvin acknowledged yesterday from Major League Baseball's winter
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we haven't offered the best package that suits
their needs,'' Melvin said. ``They have a couple of needs we might
not be able to fill. Sometimes you're not compatible.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the Rangers are giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking to improve their offense, and that's why I
still think we have a chance in this,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin foresees a scenario in which the Blue Jays might not
receive what could be expected for a pitcher of Clemens' stature
and perhaps slide to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's always that possibility,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization that acquires Clemens not only will be required
to part with players in the trade, but it likely will be forced to
renegotiate the 36-year-old pitcher's existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who informed the Blue Jays on Dec. 2 of his desire to
be traded to an organization closer to his Houston home or a
playoff contender, can veto any trade. That empowers Clemens to
force potential suitors to renegotiate his existing contract _ in
length and/or value _ before granting consent to any trade made by
Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash. Clemens will earn $8 and $8.1
million the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' representatives, Randy and Alan Hendricks, likely will
seek ``Randy Johnson money'' from that organization during
negotiations. Johnson, whom the Rangers also pursued, signed a
four-year contract worth $52.4 million with the Arizona
Diamondbacks on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza and Stevens appear to represent the best the Rangers can
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin recently called it ``very unlikely'' that catcher Ivan
Rodriguez or left fielder Rusty Greer would be involved in the
Rangers' proposal for Clemens, and the Blue Jays' insistence on
receiving major-league talent likely rules out minor-league center
fielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez's contract contains a limited
no-trade clause that prevents him from being traded to the Blue
Jays, and first baseman Rafael Palmeiro's contract also includes a
no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton cannot be traded after being signed
earlier this month as a free agent, and the Blue Jays likely
possess little interest in second baseman Mark McLemore or third
baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore underwent his fourth knee operation after the season,
and the Blue Jays plan to utilize a platoon of Tony Fernandez and
Tom Evans at third base this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not want to part with center fielder Tom Goodwin
or right-hander Rick Helling, and right-hander Aaron Sele's ability
to become a free agent after the 1999 season makes him unattractive
to the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Loaiza and Stevens as the best proposal the Rangers
can assemble, with the Blue Jays interested in major-league talent
with little service time and reasonable salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one guy clubs have asked about more than any of our
pitchers,'' Melvin said of Loaiza, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league officials respect Loaiza's arm, and the
right-hander will earn just $1.4 million this season. The Blue Jays
also seek a power hitter to replace designated hitter Jose Canseco,
who signed Thursday with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who earned $1.2 million this past season, remains
eligible for salary arbitration and cannot become a free agent
until after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lack the second baseman the Blue Jays seek, but Ash
yesterday acknowledged a potential trade for one _ likely
Pittsburgh's Tony Womack, Colorado's Mike Lansing or Los Angeles'
Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on the table, and we're waiting to hear for a call back
now,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   Ash also wants Clemens' suitors to make firm proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to use this pun, but this isn't rocket science,'' Ash
said. ``I'm just trying to get clubs to put their best packages
together so we can make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash also does not foresee departing Nashville without a trade
for Clemens being consummated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see going home,'' Ash said, ``without making a deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
