<SLUG> BC-FBO-GRAPEVINE </SLUG>
 FOOTBALL-TEX 
GRAPEVINE MUSTANGS HAVE THEIR EYES ON CLASS 4A DIVISION I TITLE
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD TIJERINA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE _ The ring rests on a wooden shelf in Jordan Wilson's
bedroom, tossed to the side next to some old medals like an
unwanted knick-knack. The shelf is dusty, the ring case is dusty
and part of Wilson _ who will try to quarterback Grapevine High
School today to a state championship _ doesn't even want it.
</P>
<P>
   The ring is from Grapevine's 1996 state championship. Wilson got
it the easy way, as a junior-varsity call-up at the end of the
regular season, seeing action mostly on kickoffs the day the
Mustangs dispatched Hays Consolidated on a December afternoon at
Floyd Casey Stadium in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he wants another ring to replace the one on his shelf. He
wants a ring he can call his own.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, he'll wear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got that ring as a keepsake. I wasn't expecting to get
the opportunity to get my own,'' Wilson said. Years ago, his family
considered moving to Southlake so he could someday lead Carroll's
state-title rich Dragons to glory. Now, Wilson has his shot in a
Grapevine uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my mom that's all I want for Christmas,'' he said.
``It's the only thing I can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wilson will get his chance.
</P>
<P>
   So will the rest of the Mustangs, who will try to give the high
school and city its second state title in three years. A victory
today against Bay City will be the perfect cap to an imperfect
season, coaches and players said. In 1996, Grapevine was supposed
to win it all. Today, the Mustangs weren't supposed to even be
here.
</P>
<P>
   So what would a championship earned today at Texas Stadium mean?
</P>
<P>
   Everything.
</P>
<P>
   Junior nose guard J.J. Barnett remembers. He was on the field in
1996, another seldom-used call-up who stood and watched Grapevine
stars like Jack Brewer and Tellis Redmon hold high the hardware,
the same state-championship trophy that occupies the trophy case at
Grapevine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe today he will be holding a trophy, too. Maybe today he
will know what it feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean more than the world to me,'' said Barnett,
Grapevine's defensive leader. ``This would be something that I
earned. I'll never let this go, even when I go home, even when I'm
in college, even after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmon and Brewer now are at the University of Minnesota, but
they remember. The only thing that this year's Grapevine players
wanted was a chance at that same memory. And now they have it.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been a tale of two teams, a tale of two seasons and a
tale of two fortunes. Hopefully, coach Mike Sneed said, the ending
today will be just as fairy-tale as it was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Mustangs were loaded. They won a state
championship because they were supposed to, Sneed said. The
pressure they played under wasn't so much to win, but more ``not''
to lose.
</P>
<P>
   This season, however, has been different. Eight games decided by
five points or less. Consecutive victories against highly regarded
Colleyville Heritage and Keller simply to make it to the playoffs.
Second-half rallies in playoff victories against Greenville and
Plainview, including one in triple overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sneed's coaching accomplishment of 1996 was dimmed because of
the opinion that anybody could have coached that year's Mustangs to
the summit of Class 4A. But this season, few _ if any _ seriously
picked Grapevine in August to be playing today in Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, here they are.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sneed says, he will start his day just as any other game
day. He will rise from bed at 5:30 in the morning, let his dog,
Daisy, out and then settle down at the kitchen table, reading the
newspaper and reflecting.
</P>
<P>
   But today, those reflections may be a bit more intense than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   He will remember 1996. How can he forget?
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting this week, I've been trying to go back to that time
two years ago,'' Sneed said. ``I try not to do it too much because
I get anxiety attacks, but the feeling is almost the same: the
anticipation, the questions. Can we win? Will we win? Every time I
really start thinking about things, I get that rush.''
</P>
<P>
   A new ring to call their own. Validation for a coaching job well
done. The satisfaction that working out in 100-degree heat during
August was worth it. All the hours put into the weight room, away
from Friday night's lights, away from the crowds and the
cheerleaders and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   These are the things a state title would bring today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really think we'd make it out of district, and now,
here we are,'' senior receiver Jason Schindler said. A title today
would place an emphatic punctuation mark to a season of highs and
lows. He is the only starter from that 1996 season playing today.
</P>
<P>
   Schindler wants to finish his high school career by coming full
circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the Colleyville Heritage game, we've come back and
won,'' he said. ``I don't know if this is luck. It happens to
people who do things right. Luck doesn't just happen. We've had our
ups and downs, but I'm glad that we're on an up right now. It
drives us. We want to be picked to lose. It gives us a little edge.
We want to win the game not only because we want to win, but
because we want to prove people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler and his teammates can do that again today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A state championship is like life's ultimate goal,'' Wilson
said. ``That's all my mind has been set on since 1996. I don't wear
my ring because I don't think I earned it. I would like to have my
own. I would never take that one off.''
</P>
<P>
   Every game as the team captains walk to midfield for the pregame
coin toss, Wilson and Barnett stroll side by side. In the
regular-season finale against Keller, knowing the Mustangs needed a
victory or miss the playoffs, Wilson turned to Barnett on the way
to midfield and said, ``You know, this isn't my last game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past five weeks, Wilson has told Barnett the same thing.
It has become part ritual, part good luck charm, part promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, J.J. is telling me that this next one ``is'' my last
game,'' Wilson said. ``I say fine to that. I just want to go out a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   And a champion.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Tijerina writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 685-3871. Visit
the Star-Telegram's high school site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
