<SLUG> BC-FBO-DUNCANVILLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERSE JUDSON MYSTIQUE DOESN'T AWE DUNCANVILLE
</HEADLINE>
 FOOTBALL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE IVEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNCANVILLE _ The Duncanville football players were not
intimidated by six-time state champion Odessa Permian and they are
not at all intimidated by five-time state champion Converse Judson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we be?'' said Panthers coach Bob Alpert. ``None of
those kids played on any of their state championship teams. We've
won more playoff games in the last two seasons than they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers (11-3) and Rockets (14-0) meet at 12:05 p.m. today
in Houston for the Class 5A Division I championship.
</P>
<P>
   Converse Judson, state champions in 1983, '88, '92, '93 and '95,
enter the game ranked No. 2 in the state and No. 5 in the nation.
Alpert is exactly right, however. The Rockets have won four playoff
games in the past two years while the Panthers have won seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't fear them. We don't fear anyone,'' Alpert said. ``We
do respect their program, their players and their tradition. But
there's no fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncanville might be playing in its first title game, but the
program is not without its own traditions. The alumni include
ex-Pittsburgh Steelers running back Barry Foster, Broncos defensive
back Ray Crockett and Texas Tech running back Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But when Alpert took over before the 1996 season, he became the
third head coach in four years. In the three seasons before
Alpert's arrival from Aldine MacArthur, the program won a total of
13 games. Alpert won 10 his first season, 12 the next and has 11
victories so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Duncanville, which has won numerous state titles in other
sports, is now a fixture on the Texas football map. Alpert gives
credit for a quick turnaround to his coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that it takes great players to win,'' he said.
``But they had great players here before and didn't always win.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 assistant coaches in the Duncanville school district
(10 varsity assistants, eight ninth-grade coaches and 12
junior-high coaches), 23 were hired by Alpert. That number includes
assistant head coach and offensive coordinator Dan Schreiber and
defensive coordinator Mark Howeth.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert praised his staff's ability to get the Panthers prepared
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not how hard you work, it's how smart you work. I'm
fortunate to be surrounded by some smart workers,'' he said. ``They
are the foundation of our success and they deserve the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that would make the turnaround complete is within
reach this afternoon at the Astrodome _ a state championship.
</P>
<P>
   Alpert won a Class 4A state title in 1980 as the defensive
coordinator for the Huntsville Hornets. He was on the losing end in
1993 as head coach at Aldine MacArthur in the Class 5A final
against Lewisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst loss of your life is losing in a state championship
game,'' he said. ``Twenty years from now, only one team has those
rings. Five years from now, nobody remembers who lost in the
finals.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ivey writes about high school sports for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 548-5481. E-mail:
arlsports(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's high
school site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
