<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAFIA-REVIEW-2TAKES-N     12-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAFIA-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET AHEAD BY BUSTING HEADS, BREAKING FINGERS AND DRESSING
NEATLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDS: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN ITALICS
HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a grand piano-sized floral arrangement at a mob funeral,
historical respect has finally been laid before the memory of
Charles (Lucky) Luciana, who changed his surname to Luciano as a
rising young mafioso because he somehow thought it was easier to
spell. Last week, Time magazine included the original Godfather,
who consolidated the blood-feuding gangsters of the Prohibition era
into a centrally supervised criminal syndicate that became known as
the Mafia, on its list of the 100 ``most influential business
geniuses of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Luciano, enthused Time, ``used Standard &AMP; Poor's as much as
Smith &AMP; Wesson'' to succeed in business. But New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, a former prosecutor, took issue, pointing out
that Luciano's rise to the top was based mostly on ``murdering lots
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his recipe for success, Luciano was undoubtedly the
mob's first modern business visionary. Today's bookshelves are
crowded with self-help books from celebrated tycoons. If Luciano
had written one, here are some lessons he might have offered.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOE SHARKEY
</P>
<P>
   Start Networking Early
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In 1907, the 10-year-old Luciano, a
Sicilian immigrant on the tough streets of Manhattan's Lower East
Side, was arrested for shoplifting:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   During the same year he started his first racket. For a penny or
two a day, Luciano offered younger and smaller Jewish kids his
personal protection against beatings on the way to school. If they
didn't pay, he beat them up. One runty kid refused to pay, a thin
little youngster from Poland, Meyer Lansky. Luciano attacked him
and was amazed when Lansky gave as good as he got. They became
bosom buddies after that.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Mafia Encyclopedia,'' by Carl Sifakis (Facts on File,
1987)
</P>
<P>
   Don't Settle for Chump Change
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Luciano dropped out of school and worked
briefly for $7 a week in a hat factory. But after winning $244 in a
craps game, he never did another honest day's work.(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to wind up being a crumb?'' he remarked to a friend.
``I'd rather drop dead.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Luciano Story,'' by Sid Feder and Joachim Joesten (Da
Capo Press, 1994)
</P>
<P>
   All Work and No Play . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)One day, when Luciano and an associate were
pulled over for running a red light on Fifth Avenue, Luciano
explained to the officer that the arsenal of pistols, shotgun and
bullets plainly visible in the back seat were actually sports
gear.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``We just come back from hunting,'' was his easy explanation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What were you hunting?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, peasants.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pheasants?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's right. Pheasants.'`  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   Respond Quickly to Public Relations Crises
</P>
<P>
   In 1931, Luciano decided that merger and acquisition was the way
to expand his fledgling mob empire. He lured the reigning kingpin,
Giuseppe (Joe the Boss) Masseria, to lunch at a Coney Island
restaurant, where four of his henchmen barged in and riddled the
old-timer with bullets after Luciano excused himself to go to the
men's room. Luciano later told reporters that of course he had
heard the gunfire:
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I finished drying my hands, I hurried out and
walked back to see what it was about.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Murder Inc.,'' by Sid Feder and Burton Turkus (Farrar, Straus
&AMP; Young, 1951)
</P>
<P>
   Be Upwardly Mobile
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to Prohibition,'' Sol Gelb, a New York criminal attorney
in the 1920s, said . . . ``a hoodlum was a hoodlum. A fellow who
committed crimes never mixed with respectable people. (After
Luciano) they began to look and act the same as respectable
people.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Blood and Power: Organized Crime in 20th-Century America,''
by Stephen Fox (William Morrow, 1989)
</P>
<P>
   Dress for Success
</P>
<P>
   Luciano's men were ordered to dress neatly and conservatively,
like office workers, to avoid wide-brimmed hats, loud shirts and
ties, garish suits completely. ``Let Capone and the Chicago guys do
that. We won't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _``The Last Testament of Lucky Luciano,'' by Martin A. Gosch and
Richard Hammer (Little, Brown, 1974)
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaned maybe a degree or two to the liberal side of
conservative,'' is the way one gentlemen's couturier put it. ``But
always in the height of style.'' _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Encourage Zero-Defect Productivity
</P>
<P>
   Of recalcitrant employees, Luciano recalled:
</P>
<P>
   I just tried to make 'em understand the penalties of stupidity.
. . . Some guys got their fingers broke or their knuckles cracked
or maybe had their heads busted. They hadda learn how to do it the
right way the next time.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Last Testament''
</P>
<P>
   Maintain Tight Inventory Control
</P>
<P>
   We knew more about trucks and tight schedules than any company
in the country. So we looked over the market and decided to put a
little squeeze on here and there. . . . For example, milk spoils
pretty fast and so does bread and vegetables. In no time at all, we
had a lock on three or four of the biggest fresh-food businesses in
America. . . . After all, nothin' spoils faster'n fish.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Last Testament''
</P>
<P>
   Look for New Synergies
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Luciano teamed with the Chicago newspaper
executive Moses Annenberg to operate an illegal telephone wire
service to supply instant horse-race results to bookie joints
nationwide:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The new racing wire had been worked out with the telephone
company. To this day, that high-class corporation knows that it's
the heart of the biggest gamblin' empire in the world. As far as
Annenberg was concerned, he never could've operated without us. He
needed us and we needed him. It was a good thing all around.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Last Testament''
</P>
<P>
   Beware the Taxman
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In 1936, the New York federal prosecutor
(and future governor) Thomas E. Dewey indicted Luciano on 90 counts
of extortion and ``direction of organized harlotry.'' At his trial,
Dewey ridiculed the multimillionaire Luciano's obviously bogus
federal tax returns, which showed he never made more than $22,500 a
year. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``You just picked those figures on your income out of the sky,
didn't you'?'' Dewey finally charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was the proper amount I should give the
government,'' responded Lucky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   Play to Your Strengths
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) When Luciano was convicted, his
pre-sentencing report stated: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   He possesses average intelligence, but is a shallow and
parasitic individual who is considerably wrapped up in his own
feelings. His ideals of life resolved themselves into money to
spend, beautiful women to enjoy, silk underclothes and places to go
in style. His social outlook . . . is dominated by recklessness and
a craving for action. His only asset as a leader consists of his
apparent calmness in times of stress.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   Think Globally
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) During World War II, authorities sought out
Luciano in prison to use his influence to prevent wartime sabotage
or work slowdowns on the mob-controlled shipping docks. (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he continued to maintain active leadership of the
syndicate from behind bars. In 1946, Luciano was paroled for what
was described by Governor Dewey as wartime services to the country
. . . When he was released . . . Luciano was deported to Italy. He
sneaked back to Cuba later that year to run the American syndicate
from that off-shore island. From Cuba, Luciano approved the
execution of Bugsy Siegel for looting the syndicate's money
building the Flamingo Hotel in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Mafia Encyclopedia''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Forced back to Italy, Luciano began
arranging the mob's expansion into the global drug trade.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Narcotics Bureau Supervisor Garland Williams charged that three
months after Luciano's return (to Italy) from Cuba in 1947, the
first large shipment of heroin, worth $250,000, was smuggled into
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   Don't Trust Reporters . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In exile, Luciano blamed the press for
depicting him as the ``capo di tutti capi,'' the boss of all bosses
of organized crime. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The American press is disgraceful,'' he blurted out. . . .
``There is too much freedom of the press in America. ... Someday,
I'm gonna write my own memories,'' he said. ``Then the real story
is gonna come out.''
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story''
</P>
<P>
   . . . and Protect Your Movie Rights
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, Luciano bragged about what he felt was the
inevitable movie deal. `I got a lotta offers _ offers to pay me
good, too. I'm not puttin' up a nickel of my own for it.''
</P>
<P>
   _``The Luciano Story'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 1134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
