<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY LOCKED IN STALEMATE WITH TURKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ On a June evening five years ago, a squad of
Kurdish rebels arrived at a village in southeastern Turkey and
marched to the home of a young man who had just decided to quit the
rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   By quitting, the former guerrilla had violated a central tenet
of the movement, which is called the Kurdistan Workers Party, or
PKK. It demands that all its fighters commit themselves to serve
until ``victory or death.''
</P>
<P>
   The defector was not at home when his erstwhile comrades
arrived, so instead they killed his mother and five brothers and
sisters, ages 4 to 13. Later the New York-based group Human Rights
Watch asserted that this action and dozens like it ``were not
committed by rogue units or commanders, but were PKK official
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The founder and leader of the Kurdish rebel movement, Abdullah
Ocalan, was arrested last month in Italy, and Turkey is demanding
that he be returned here to face trial for the 1994 massacre and
dozens of others committed by his troops. Italy refuses to return
him, because its Constitution forbids extraditing prisoners to
countries where they might face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Italian leaders have little desire, though, to put Ocalan on
trial in Italy. Officials in Germany, where prosecutors say the
Kurdish group has used killings and arson to support lucrative
heroin-smuggling operations, are also reluctant to try him. Both
countries fear that the Kurdish rebels' supporters would erupt in
violent anger against any government that seeks to prosecute
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Italian and German leaders have proposed sending
Ocalan to an international court. Ocalan has seized on the idea,
evidently seeing it as a way to turn the table on his Turkish
pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready to go before an international tribunal made up of
independent judges to decide whether we or the Turkish government
are responsible for the escalation of armed conflict that has led
to thousands of deaths on both sides,'' he told an interviewer last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot accept a trial of Apo as a person,'' he said, using
the pseudonym by which he is widely known. ``The argument over a
trial must be related to the war in Kurdistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan suggested that an independent panel be asked to examine
the Kurdish problem and then decide who should be tried for human
rights abuses. ``It could be me or members of my party, or Turkish
officials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These proposals have outraged Turkish officials and many
ordinary Turks. They believe Ocalan is seeking to escape
responsibility for savage killings by putting the Turkish army into
the defendant's chair instead of sitting there himself.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strategy that could have political benefits for Ocalan.
Groups like Human Rights Watch that have accused him of crimes
against humanity have also been strongly critical of the Turkish
military.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said that an international tribunal
would be ``simply a forum to politicize the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italian and German premiers have tried to transfer the
prosecution to a European forum, but this can only aggravate the
situation, intensify the conflict with Rome and create a situation
which is even harder to manage,'' Cem said. ``Ocalan's trial in an
international court will be nothing other than a comedy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides Turkish objections, there is another obstacle to the
idea of bringing Ocalan before an international court, either alone
or with co-defendants. No such court exists. More than 60 countries
agreed earlier this year to create one, but it will be years before
it begins to function.
</P>
<P>
   Although tribunals have been set up to try accused war criminals
from Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia, they have no broader
mandate. The International Court of Justice in The Hague,
Netherlands, which is widely respected for its prudence and
sophistication, accepts only disputes among nations and is not
equipped to try individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
