<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-FORBES-750&AMP;AD     12-12 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-FORBES-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 UNDECIDED, AND FEELING ALL THE WEIGHT OF WORRY AND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president has not called and the speaker-elect
has told him to vote his conscience. But the considerable pressure
on Rep. Michael Forbes, one of maybe a dozen Republicans still
genuinely undecided on impeachment, is subtler than that, and in
the end, mostly internal.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been en route to Israel with President Clinton
this weekend, along with at least one other Republican
fence-sitter, fellow New York Rep. Rick Lazio. Initially, he
accepted the president's invitation, then backed out at the last
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is sitting among the empty boxes in his bare-walled
new congressional office on a Friday night _ Hey, how come nobody
told him the subway rumbles right beneath his floor? And he is
wondering how to make the decision he fears will haunt him in old
age.
</P>
<P>
   Roughing out the arguments, pro and con, he sounds less like
Hamlet than Tevye: On the one hand, party elders have suggested
that defectors will not get so much as a new stop sign in their
districts, and who needs that? On the other, he says, impeachment
is ``very, very serious stuff. And I can't shake this thing inside
me that says this is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he just spent two years on the outs with his party.
Forbes was the first to break ranks and announce that he would not
support Newt Gingrich for speaker in 1996 because of ethical
violations. A pariah within his caucus, Forbes was on his way to
legislative oblivion before his friend, the Speaker-elect Robert
Livingston, reprieved him. And only recently, Livingston made the
rehabilitation complete, naming him to a minor leadership post as
one of the speaker's four assistants.
</P>
<P>
   So why jeopardize this new status? Already, the conservative
magazine Human Events has put him on a list of Republicans branded
the ``pro-perjury caucus.'' And a few days ago, someone leaked an
item to The Washington Times showing that he contributed money to
Democrats in last month's elections. (He says he was in charge of
raising about $700,000 for Livingston's political action committee,
which handed it out to other Republicans. But Forbes also
personally gave $1,000 each to two Democratic friends, Reps.
Loretta Sanchez of California and William Pascrell Jr. of New
Jersey.)
</P>
<P>
   When it is pointed out that it sounds like he thinks the true
vote of conscience is a vote against impeachment, he says that is
not necessarily the case. He has a 19-year-old daughter and says he
does believe that Clinton's behavior with Monica Lewinsky amounted
to the sexual harassment of a young woman only a few years older.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was despicable,'' Forbes said, taking a swig of
Diet Coke. ``You had an immature, impressionable kid, albeit an
aggressive pursuer, but a kid. Even though she apparently agreed to
all this, she was a child, and that is gnawing at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, on yet another hand, he genuinely likes the
president on a personal level, and that counts for something, too.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was a Gingrich acolyte with great enthusiasm for the
Contract With America when he was elected in 1994. But he has
steadily been getting more moderate and now tends to agree with
Clinton on some issues. At the president's invitation, he flew on
Air Force One to an event in the Hamptons last summer on the
patient bill of rights they both support and was clearly wowed. He
thinks a lot about the phrase, ``punishment to fit the crime,''and
wonders if impeaching Clinton would be ``overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, constituents in his district on New York's
eastern Long Island seem just as divided. Everywhere he goes at
home, he is stopped by people with strong opinions one way or the
other. When they say, `I'm sure you'll do the right thing,'' he
does not ask what that might be. He notes that the half of voters
in his swing district who support him would hate a vote against
impeachment, but as of Friday, calls were running incredibly close,
with 2,233 lobbying for impeachment and 2,235 against it. Among the
callers was his wife, Barbara Forbes, who had phoned to voice her
support for impeachment, and told the staff member who answered
that she was calling as just another constituent. And another,
apparently; she called more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes laughed that his wife had already won one round in the
decision-making process, helping him to see why, after some
flip-flopping, he should skip the trip to Israel with the
president. In the end, he says, he stuck around mostly because he
did not want to miss celebrating his son Sam's first birthday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But on the far trickier question of how to vote, he goes on
worrying about literally dozens of things: the verdict of history,
how an impeachment might affect the stock market, and his party's
future, as well as Clinton's. And his own: if he votes against
impeachment, he suspects he will have a tough time running for the
Senate one day. That there will be no censure option, he believes,
makes things even more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   He even worries about looking like he is enjoying his worrying,
still mindful of the teasing he took two years ago from colleagues
who thought he was milking his ethical objections to Gingrich a
little too obviously. And as a result, he has mostly been laying
low in recent weeks, even turning down an invitation to go on
``Meet the Press'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He says he did not find the debate in the Judiciary Committee
particularly helpful. In the end it did not sway him one way or the
other.
</P>
<P>
   And he does not plan to decide until he absolutely has to, after
calling a couple dozen friends and supporters on Long Island this
weekend. And though, as of Friday night, he appeared to be leaning
ever so slightly against impeachment, he denied that that meant
much: ``I've been on both sides of this,'' he said. ``Over and
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
