<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4874 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-DRIVETHRU-REV     12-12 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-DRIVETHRU-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'LL HAVE SOME CHITLINS, FRIES AND AN OXYGEN TANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Opening a debate here Tuesday night, City Councilman
Lee Morris wanted to make one thing clear. ``I don't think
drive-throughs are evil,'' Morris said. ``And I don't think that
folks who use drive-throughs are evil.'' Then he admitted his own
pathetic dependency: ``Uh, I use them myself _ because they're
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The shame of it all.
</P>
<P>
   So began Morris' plea for votes for his proposed ordinance to
ban the construction of new drive-through windows in Atlanta, the
national leader in what Morris refers to as ``autodependency.''
Under his bill, the city would effectively declare an end to more
convenient but bloodless car-bound transactions at banks, fast-food
eateries, dry cleaners, pharmacies, liquor stores and cappucino
cafes. In Atlanta, you can even drive through for chitlins.
</P>
<P>
   To Morris' thinking, autodependency in Atlanta is responsible
for dirty air, traffic congestion, obesity, global warming,
respiratory illness, an epidemic of pedestrian deaths and the
deterioration of community. The Atlanta Regional Commission, a
coalition of local governments, has concluded that Atlantans drive
an average of 33 miles a day, more than residents of any other
major city, and 52 percent more than people in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After debate, and some lobbying by bankers and burger barons,
the Council rejected Morris' admittedly modest proposal by an 8-5
vote. But the measure spoke to the desperation of this city, and so
many others, trying to control problems like air pollution and
sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Atlanta has been on the go for nearly 30 years,
emerging unscathed from the civil rights movement. And after more
than doubling its population in that period, to 3.1 million, it
suffers from severe traffic and environmental woes. The area's
leaders, including Gov.-elect Roy Barnes, are increasingly
concerned that ozone days and creeping traffic are becoming an
intractable part of Atlanta's international profile. A poll of
Atlanta business and political leaders this year showed that air
quality had replaced crime and public education as their greatest
concern.
</P>
<P>
   With no mountains or oceans to block Atlanta's growth, farmland
and forest have been swiftly paved into nondescript exurbia. And
despite the relentless expansion of the road system, drivers have
come to expect delays any time and anywhere. The recent addition of
high-occupancy-vehicle lanes on the three Interstate highways
converging in downtown Atlanta have had little noticeable impact.
</P>
<P>
   The city's air quality is considered so hazardous that federal
financing for new highway projects has effectively been frozen.
Studies have found that more than half of the nitrogen oxides in
Atlanta's air comes from cars, and environmental officials project
that pollution will worsen in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Atlanta was founded as the terminus of the Western &AMP;
Atlantic Railroad in 1837, transportation has been central to its
character. Although a few in-town neighborhoods, like Midtown and
Virginia Highlands have retained a pedestrian charm, the area's
suburban design and personality have largely made it a driving
city. While the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority's
trains are clean and efficient, its service area remains limited.
Many of those who do take the trains commute to the stations by
automobile.
</P>
<P>
   Several smaller cities, including Burbank and Sierra Madre,
Calif., and Carrboro, N.C., have imposed limits on drive-through
windows in recent years, although usually to preserve their
character rather than to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Morris understood that his proposal to ban the construction of
new drive-throughs fell somewhat short of a panacea. Robert King,
president of the Georgia Hospitality &AMP; Travel Association, called
it ``a Band-Aid on a blowout.'' It is not even clear that an idling
car at a drive-through pollutes any more than a car that is stopped
and then started again. But with the hundreds of competing
governments in the metropolitan area flailing in their efforts to
improve air quality, Morris felt it was time to do something,
anything, to get Atlantans out of their cars, to show some
determination to change the city's culture.
</P>
<P>
   He also understood that his measure would cause inconvenience,
especially for the elderly, the handicapped and parents of young
children. But he recalled that it was not so long ago that the
culture deemed it inconvenient to toss soft-drink bottles and
litter into trash cans rather than into rivers and gutters.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters noted that the city and its suburbs had to start
somewhere. ``Everyone says that they're supportive of cleaning up
the air,'' said Councilwoman Debi Starnes. ``Everyone says that
they're supportive of making our city and the world more pedestrian
friendly. And everyone says that they realize that in order to
accomplish those two objectives that we're going to have to do a
lot of little and medium things. There's no one big thing that will
solve these problems. And almost every time one of these little or
medium things comes up, people say, `Well not this little or medium
thing. This won't make that much difference.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the measure failed, with its opponents
lauding Morris' intentions but condemning his methods. They argued
that the ordinance would place an unreasonable burden on
businesses, would put Atlanta at a competitive disadvantage with
surrounding jurisdictions, would undercut its tax base and would
inconvenience the disabled. Black members of the Council opposed it
unanimously, with many arguing that it would stifle badly needed
development on the city's predominantly black south side.
Councilman Derrick Boazman took a shot at Morris' moralizing by
observing that he had not noticed any donkeys or electric cars in
the City Hall garage that day.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, not surprisingly, found the outcome a bit frustrating.
``Atlanta is known for its rah-rah pro-business attitude,'' he
said. ``And the pursuit of the almighty dollar tends to overwhelm
good public policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
