<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNER-CITY KID FINDS OUTDOORS UP HIS ALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's been some wild ride the kid's been on the
past few months _ going from the asphalt streets of his
neighborhood to the dirt horseback trails of Mammoth Lakes, then
back again to get ready to ride down Colorado Boulevard on
horseback in the 1999 Tournament of Roses parade.
</P>
<P>
   A heck of a ride for a 12-year-old city kid who until last June
thought the great outdoors was shooting hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Camping? Horseback riding? Backpacking in the wilderness? Forget
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Bellamy was no urban cowboy. Anything outside his
well-traveled route from home to school to the rec center and YMCA
every day was wilderness to him.
</P>
<P>
   Then one weekend this summer, he and about 40 other neighborhood
kids spent the weekend camping out overnight at the Sepulveda Rec
Center. The next thing you know, Felix Bellamy is getting ready to
climb up on a horse New Year's Day and go riding down Colorado
Boulevard in a parade that was seen on TV last year by an estimated
425 million people in more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The kid's great outdoors just expanded a little.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids just stick out, Mike Hogan says. This kid sticks out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix really got into all the stuff we were trying to teach
our neighborhood kids about camping and the outdoor life that
weekend in June,'' said Hogan, director of the Sepulveda Recreation
Center. ``You could just see the excitement in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the WOW _ Wonderful Outdoor World _ program
for the Los Angeles Department of Recreation and Parks, saw the
same excitement in the kid's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the look they were searching for to make the world a little
more far-reaching and interesting for city kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope to reach some of them, show them there's something
beyond video games and hanging out on the streets,'' says Mary
Braunwarth of the Recreation and Parks Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how Felix and the other seven kids were chosen for the
equestrian unit in the parade,'' she said. ``They were the most
wide-eyed going through the program.''
</P>
<P>
   From that June overnight camp-out at the neighborhood rec
center, Felix was invited to attend a weeklong camp up at Mammoth
Lakes in late August, where he backpacked in the wilderness with
kids from other rec centers.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who had the same look in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Felix jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode mules and horses, and learned all sorts of great stuff
that was fun, once I got the hang of it, and wasn't so sore
anymore,'' he said Friday. He was preparing for another practice
session, riding horseback on cement streets to duplicate the
conditions of Colorado Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about how better it is out in the wilderness with
all the trees, and how different it is in the city with all the
things going on on the streets,'' Felix said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends think I'm lucky, and so do I. This is exciting,
getting to be in the Rose Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye out for the kid if you watch the parade on TV or
attend it in person. Felix will be one of eight riders following a
mule train.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Los Angeles Recreation and Parks Department's entry
this year, playing on the theme of eight city kids getting the
chance to take a wilderness trip to a national park.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that more inner-city kids will take advantage of
great programs like WOW so they'll have their outdoors expanded,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Riding with Felix will be David Tamayo and Devin Mills from the
Valley Plaza rec center; Melvon Broussard, Jarone Sanford, Shanta
Shield and Reniya Ware from the St. Andrews rec center; and Marisa
Milani from the Sunland rec center.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's become an official urban cowboy, I asked Felix
whether he wanted to be a full-fledged cowboy when he grew up?
Maybe move to Wyoming?
</P>
<P>
   The kid shook his head no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be an environmental lawyer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids just stick out.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
