<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARL-CAMPBELL13-COX     12-12 3341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARL-CAMPBELL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet man brought UT's first Heisman back home
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It should be no surprise that the entire living
room showcases the trophy, for this home on the northern outskirts
of Tyler is the house that Heisman built.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall to the right is a photo of Earl Campbell hugging his
mom at the award ceremony in New York 21 years ago. On the wall to
the left is a tapestry of Jesus. On the opposite wall, facing the
trophy, is a framed photo of Campbell holding the Heisman with his
former coach, Darrell Royal.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of such decorative embellishment, the focus of
attention is the corner of the room, the Heisman corner, where the
bronze statue stands on a 4-foot-tall, ivory-colored pedestal. A
chandelier above it showers the trophy with light, reflected by the
two wall-sized mirrors that meet in the corner behind it. At the
foot of the football altar are dozens of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   It makes a statement, no question about it, this Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who built the house had the idea to display it like
that,'' said the owner's mom, Ann Campbell. ``Earl told me he was
going to build me a house I'd be comfortable in, and that the
Heisman should stay in his home place. As long as I live, this will
be the home for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Earl Campbell won the 1977 Heisman _ awarded each year to
the best college football player in the country _ Ann Campbell had
raised her family in a wooden shack on this rural road, a few
winding miles behind the smoke of the Tyler Pipe plant. Her husband
had died of a heart attack when Earl was 10.
</P>
<P>
   As the sixth-oldest of 11 children, Earl wasn't even considered
the best football player among the seven Campbell sons, but he was
the first to play for integrated schools. He was also, everyone
agrees, the one who was least interested in working the rose-bush
crop that was the impoverished family's means of subsistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: If it wasn't for football, Earl would
have starved to death,'' said his brother Tim, a year younger and
one of the twins (Steve is the other) who also played for the
University of Texas Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Campbell vowed that if he ever made something of himself in
football, the first thing he would do was buy his mother a house.
Sturdy brick, it was built just a few yards from where the shack
previously stood, alongside the two-lane blacktop that is now known
as Ann Campbell Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl has always been kind of a quiet guy, a slow-acting guy,''
said his mom. ``He was never outgoing like the twins. He could have
easily forgot about us, but he never felt like he was any better
than his brothers or sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of guys who won the Heisman who were (jerks),
and nobody remembers anything about them now,'' said Tim. ``If
you're an upstanding member of the community and carry yourself the
way you should, people remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The other trophy Two hundred and thirty or so miles southwest of
the Campbell home is another Heisman, a duplicate. It serves as the
silent greeter for those who enter the University of Texas football
offices, behind the south end zone of Royal Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This Heisman makes a different sort of statement. Encased on a
mahogany stand with a rotating base, it looks like it belongs in
the most elegant corporate boardroom or the swankiest
expense-account steakhouse. What it says to the prime beef among
Longhorns recruits is that you, too, could be like Earl Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Or Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky had better get ready, because once you get it,
everything changes,'' Earl Campbell said, anticipating that tonight
Williams will become the second Heisman Trophy winner in Longhorns
football history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your name is never the same,'' Campbell said. ``Heisman is
included in whatever you do, for the rest of your life. If he tries
to do everything that people want him to do, there's not going to
be a lot of time for Ricky. Even at age 43, there are always people
tugging at Earl: Earl do this, Earl do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the glass wall of Campbell's office as special assistant
to the athletic director (or Longhorns football ``ambassador,'' as
he describes his role), a visitor can see that duplicate Heisman
over his shoulder, rotating slowly. Though it provides a constant
reminder of the glory season of 1977, Campbell pays it no mind.
Whatever the changes that Heisman wrought, it is quite likely that
no Texan has been less impressed with the football accomplishments
of Earl Campbell than Earl Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fit the number 20 that everybody used to see,'' he
said, referring to the jersey retired by the Longhorns to honor his
exploits, the one framed on the wall of the office he shares with
Royal. ``They think that guy should be flashier. And I'm a
no-socks, laid-back, T-shirt and shorts guy. A guy who talks real
slow. I don't go out; I don't party. Things that people wouldn't
think make me very happy. It's not the high-rolling lifestyle, but
I can have more damn fun over a beer and a country music song. The
only time in my life when I'm by myself is when I'm in my
Suburban.''
</P>
<P>
   Some time alone that he hadn't anticipated occurred earlier this
fall, when Campbell was hospitalized for six weeks after he was
diagnosed with a congenital spinal condition that, by all rights,
should have prevented him from playing football. Suffering from
spinal stenosis, a narrowing of the spinal canal, he now realizes
that every tackle left his mobility in far more jeopardy than he
had ever suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just God's blessing that I was never hit just right, and
it's also God's blessing that I made it to the hospital when I did,
because if I had waited any longer, I might have been paralyzed,''
Campbell said. ``If I'd ever had a real physical, with MRIs and all
the stuff you go through now, I probably never would have played
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Running to glory ``I think Earl might have been the last one to
have absolutely won the Heisman on the field,'' said Fred Akers,
who replaced Royal as Longhorns coach in 1977 and tailored his
offense to highlight Campbell. ``Today, it's much more publicized;
the hoopla starts at least a year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Earl is that he was very, very good on
the days that we had national TV coverage. He just kept getting
better and better and better. You'd watch him and say, 'My God, how
could anybody do that?' It wasn't just one explosion; there were
five or six explosions on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal made Campbell his prime recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him in the state high school playoff game (in which
Campbell's undefeated John Tyler team beat Reagan for the 1973 4A
championship), it was a man against boys,'' Royal said. ``He ran
over high school kids, and people said, 'Well, he won't do that in
college.'
</P>
<P>
   ``After he ran over them in college, people said, 'He won't do
that in pro ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran over them there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there are plenty of differences between Campbell and
Williams _ Earl is as country as East Texas, Ricky as sunny as San
Diego; Earl bulled through people, Ricky glides over and around
them _ Campbell recognizes some amazing parallels. Both initially
played fullback in college before switching as upperclassmen to the
showcase slot of tailback. Both saw their Longhorns suffer dismal
seasons their junior year, only to transcend all expectations with
a new coach as seniors. Both trampled all over Texas A&AMP;M in their
climactic rush to the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start of the season, nobody was even thinking about the
Heisman,'' recalled Tim Campbell. ``And then when Earl won it, if
you'll pardon the expression, all hell broke loose, all over the
campus and on Guadalupe.''
</P>
<P>
   A Campbell career The irony of Campbell as reluctant celebrity
is that celebrity has provided his livelihood ever since he retired
from professional football in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He extended his Lone Star legend with a stellar career as a
Houston Oiler, followed by a swan song season as a New Orleans
Saint. A No. 1 draft choice in 1978, he was rookie of the year, a
two-time Most Valuable Player, a four-time All Pro and a Hall of
Famer selected during his first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Following Campbell's retirement, he returned to Austin from
Houston at the behest of the UT Athletic Department, where he
serves as a high-profile symbol of an illustrious past. His
assignment as special assistant makes him available to recruits and
athletes when he stops by once a week or so, without otherwise
making much of a demand on his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the business that I do is with UT people,'' Campbell
said. ``I think it speaks very highly of the University of Texas
that if you do the right things and keep your hands clean, you can
always go home.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he was approached by a couple of businessmen to start
Earl Campbell Foods, which sells ``pretty close to a million
dollars worth of sausage a month,'' according to Campbell. The
company also sells other items ranging from fajitas to
chitterlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl's a responsible businessman,'' Royal said. ``He handles
the PR mainly, and he's very diligent about showing up where he's
supposed to be, and on time and staying and visiting and signing,
and doing what he's supposed to when he's promoting that sausage
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's spending the morning at UT, the afternoon at his
Sixth Street office of Earl Campbell Foods or the entire day with
business associates on the golf course, being Earl Campbell isn't
simply his identity. It's his job.
</P>
<P>
   A bladder message UT can bless a weak bladder for bringing
Campbell to Austin. Recruited by coaches from coast to coast, he
had narrowed his options to two: Royal at Texas or Barry Switzer at
Oklahoma. As a believer in signs and serendipity, he decided to let
nature run its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night I went to bed and prayed that if I got up to use the
bathroom during the night, I'm going to come to the University of
Texas,'' Campbell said. ``And if I slept through the night, I would
go to Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Switzer was known for enjoying an easy relationship with
African-American athletes, the Longhorns carried a stigma of
integrating belatedly and grudgingly. Campbell had thrilled to the
televised exploits of Roosevelt Leaks, whose junior season had made
him a strong Heisman contender and who would be a senior teammate
of the freshman from Tyler. But as far as Campbell could see, Leaks
was pretty much the whole show, one of the few African Americans
and easily the best player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still remember people taking bets when I was in Tyler,
after I had signed to come to school here, that I wouldn't make
it,'' Campbell said. ``Because this guy Darrell Royal was supposed
to be such a racist. I figured that he was a man and I was a man.
And he was going to have to go a long ways to convince me that he
was a racist, because I was going to make a hell of an effort to be
a friend to him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the recruitment, Royal had already won a more important
friend: Ann Campbell. Earl's mom simply didn't trust Switzer, who
kept taking Earl for walks outside the house, out of Ann's earshot.
Royal had nothing to hide, and he told Ann that she didn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really ashamed of my house and everything, and when
Royal came, he sat on the foot of my bed,'' Ann Campbell said.
``And he visited with me and said, 'I want you to know, I was
raised in a shack. You don't have anything to be ashamed of.' He
said Earl would have to apply himself to his books, but that UT
could be a help to him, and that he could be a help to UT.''
</P>
<P>
   The top recruit said he ``came to school here because I like it,
it fits me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come from a family with wealth of any sort, except
for love,'' he said. ``I didn't have a lot of clothes, and you can
wear the same pair of pants here for a week. If you don't bother
nobody, nobody's going to bother you. The only thing that really
bothered me was people looking at me when I walked across campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Because you were big? Or black? Or because you were recognized
as an athlete?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of all of them,'' he replied. ``When I came to
the university, racism was at the point where there was a lot more
publicity about UT not wanting blacks here. Winning has a way of
hiding that, or putting it to the side. Everybody probably thinks I
was the main guy on our football team the whole four years. I
wasn't the main guy. The guy who kept our whole football team
together was an offensive lineman named Rick Ingraham . And he was
a white guy, from Westlake of all places. Every Saturday in the
huddle, Rick Ingraham would say, 'We're going to win the Heisman
for Earl. Let's go!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell helped blacks feel more welcome at UT, Royal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roosevelt Leaks was our first black star, and he had
tremendous influence as well, and following right behind him came
Earl,'' the former coach said. ``And Earl certainly has his
African-American friends, but he has a helluva lot of white friends
as well. He just mixes and mingles with everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell credits his success to UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like that guy from the Dominican Republic (Sammy Sosa) saying
everything he has he owes to baseball, everything I have I owe to
the University of Texas,'' said the football star turned sausage
king. ``I've met Who's Who in America because of going to school
here, and this was way before pro football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out beautifully,'' said Royal, reminded of how he
had promised Ann Campbell that her son and the university could do
each other some good. ``I know of plenty of situations since Earl
has been out of school where his contacts with the university have
been helpful to him. And goodness knows what he meant to us.'' A
Campbell courtship Once upon a time, a boy and a girl fell in love
at first sight and knew that they would stay together forever. If
you don't believe in fairy tales, you'll never accept the courtship
of Reuna and Earl Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It began on the first day of ninth grade, which was also the
first day that busing for integration came to the Tyler school
system. If not for that, a poor country boy such as Earl Campbell
might never have crossed paths with Reuna Smith, an African
American who lived in a more privileged part of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first day, when he stepped off the bus, there was this
halo over his head,'' said Reuna (pronounced like Rene). ``I'm from
what Earl would call a basically middle-class home, and I think he
was embarrassed when he met me, because of my home, the things that
my family had. He has always been a nice young man; that's what I
called him back then. You could tell he was a devoted athlete,
because he worked very hard at it. We weren't allowed to date until
the 10th grade, and I felt like he did not want me at his home.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Reuna remained in Tyler while Earl was in Austin with the
Longhorns and then in Houston with the Oilers, she says they never
broke up or gave serious thought to a future without each other.
Even so, she was surprised by Campbell's spur-of-the-moment return
to Tyler on Valentine's Day 1980. He had hired a limousine to drive
him from Houston, and he was carrying a ring in his pocket when he
asked Reuna's father for his daughter's hand in marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother said, 'What are you doing home?' '' Campbell
recalled. ``And I said, 'I left something here years ago, and I
came back to get it. I want to ask Reuna if she'll be my wife.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years of marriage and two sons who are following in the
football footsteps of their daddy _ 16-year-old Earl Christian II
(who goes by Christian) plays for Westlake High, and 12-year-old
Tyler Christian for Hill Country _ the Campbells maintain that they
have never had so much as a serious argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife will tell you it does no good to argue with him,
because if she argues, he just leaves,'' Earl said.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that frustrating?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course!'' Reuna said with a laugh. ``You want somebody to
say something, and he's not that way. It's not that either one of
us is perfect, but I guess we have that understanding that has
bonded us together. It's all good. He is just a special guy, a good
husband and a great father.''
</P>
<P>
   When the boys play football, their father is a lot more likely
to miss the game than their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm around, I think I'm more of a distraction than
anything,'' he explained. ``I want my children to do their own
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want the focus to be on him,'' Reuna said. ``When
Earl comes, he tries to remain anonymous and go to the end of the
field or sit on the opposite side. You know, the mom is always the
best cheerleader, anyway.'' Weakness well hidden Though Campbell
appeared invincible on the field _ the irresistible force, the
drive that would not be denied, the player who once ran into Bevo
and saw Bevo go down _ he discovered this fall that his spine is so
weak that he should never have played football.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned over a lack of feeling and control in his feet, he
drove himself to Houston, where upon his arrival he couldn't even
get out of his car. Two operations and resulting complications left
him hospitalized there for six weeks; he has yet to risk a round of
golf, after more than two months of convalescence.
</P>
<P>
   For the Campbells, the toughest part was the realization that
their sons might suffer from the hereditary condition, and that, if
so, they would no longer be able to participate in the sport they
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not want to tell our boys that they couldn't play
football,'' said Reuna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God they don't have it,'' said Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Winner's new world ``You ought to be doing an article on Ricky
Williams,'' said Campbell. ``I'm old, can't move no more.''
</P>
<P>
   It took two weeks and a couple dozen phone calls before Campbell
would consent to sit for an interview. Once he began talking, his
gruffness began to thaw, his game face to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   Among those he keeps at arm's length, the media in particular,
he is often considered difficult at best. By contrast, those who
get close to him seem to remain close forever, unanimous in their
opinion that Campbell is as fine a man as Heisman has ever chosen,
and that winning the Heisman didn't change him one bit.
</P>
<P>
   What changed was Campbell's world, a world that was bigger and
more demanding than he had ever envisioned in Tyler. This world
expected him to be more than the slow-talking, easy-going country
boy who resisted the dazzle of the spotlight. It expected him to be
comfortable in his celebrity, a polished package, suave and
articulate. It expected him to handle constant demands on his time
with amazing grace. It expected him to be as accessible and
accommodating with the media as he naturally was with children. It
expected him to be something he wasn't, now that he was Earl
Campbell, Heisman winner. What the trophy confirmed for Campbell
was that he could run, but he couldn't hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very careful doing interviews about Ricky,'' said
Campbell, who has been besieged by such requests over the course of
Williams' Heisman run. He said he has declined 150 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I'm jealous of him or anything, but I wouldn't
want to say anything to hurt his chances,'' Campbell said. ``I
don't wear my hair like he does, but outside of that, he looks like
he could be my son. He'd better get ready, because it's going to
get tougher. He's such a great guy. I know Ricky understands this,
but winning the Heisman isn't an 'I' thing. It's the whole team,
for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   And if a trophy for Williams gives Campbell some company, all
the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing needs a twin,'' said Campbell, finally
acknowledging the Heisman behind him. ``It's been sitting there for
20 years by itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-11-98 2045E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
