<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSTICK-HISTORY13-CO     12-12 2489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSTICK-HISTORY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lipstick a history, glossed over
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wax on, wax off.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to be more specific, beeswax, carnauba, paraffin, ozokerite,
microcrystalline and candelilla.
</P>
<P>
   This is just some of the goo that gives lipstick its stick,
according to authors Meg Cohen Ragas and Karen Kozlowski in the
recently released Read My Lips, a cultural history of the painted
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Cleopatra slathered henna on her lips to woo the
boys, most women haven't been content without a little color _ even
though lipstick was once outlawed, first for being provocative,
then for being poisonous. And even though a '96 survey by Shiseido
Cosmetics revealed that 54percent of men say women should ditch the
stuff because it's messy.
</P>
<P>
   A clean collar over a gorgeous gal? Come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lipstick is to the face what punctuation is to a sentence,''
says designer Diane Von Furstenberg (who carries a silver bullet of
MAC ``3-D'' in her purse). ``It says a lot about the intent of `the
author.'''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot about personal style. A mouth coated with Cover Girl
clear gloss speaks as loudly as one lacquered with L'Oreal
``Drumbeat Red.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire makeup industry developed around lipstick,'' says
Jean Ford Danielson, co-founder of BeneFit Cosmetics. ``Not around
eye shadow or cheek color, but lipstick.''
</P>
<P>
   (Danielson, by the way, named one of her lipsticks ``But,
Officer'' because she'd just gotten out of traffic school, notes
Read My Lips.)
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there's today's collagen-fueled fetish for large lips, a
la model Esther Canadas, who pouts in DKNY ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years they've become very desirable,'' says model
Tyra Banks in her book Tyra's Beauty Inside &AMP; Out. ``I know a lot
of women who have spent a fortune trying to plump theirs up with
cosmetic surgery, so if you are blessed with full lips, make the
most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With lipstick, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, is a salute to the totally tubular cosmetic that
started it all thousands of years ago. And to a future so bright,
we've gotta wear shades _ of ``Spice,'' ``Vamp,'' ``Toast of New
York,'' ``Cherries in the Snow''...
</P>
<P>
   LIPSTICK: IT WASN'T BORN YESTERDAY
</P>
<P>
   69-30 B.C. _ Cleopatra paints her lips with henna and carmine.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth century _ Lip rouge is the rage among prostitutes and the
lower class in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   13th century _ Lipstick becomes fashionable among all classes,
but society gals prefer bright pink to the masses' less
sophisticated earth-tone red.
</P>
<P>
   17th century _ In Paris, even nuns are spotted with painted
mouths (heavens!), and lipstick is denounced by the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   1770 _ British Parliament passes a law condemning lipstick and
stating that women who use makeup to seduce men into marriage can
be tried for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   1781 _ The French slather on about two million pots of lip rouge
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1800s _ Repressed Victorians press red crepe paper to
their lips to create a rosy glow (although the rich could sneak off
to Paris for a pot of lip pomade by Guerlain, the first company to
produce commercially successful lipstick).
</P>
<P>
   1860s _ Makeup becomes more accepted around the world, and
cosmetics experts, called ``enamelers,'' pop up en masse.
</P>
<P>
   1897 _ The Sears Roebuck catalog offers 50-cent rouge, ``a
harmless preparation for giving color to the cheeks and lips.''
</P>
<P>
   1915 _ Maurice Levy designs the first American lipstick in a
sliding metal tube.
</P>
<P>
   1924 _ The N.Y. Board of Health considers banning lipstick for
fear that it might poison men who kiss women wearing it. By now,
50million American women wear lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   1939-45 _ During World War II, lipstick ingredients such as
castor oil and petroleum jelly are in short supply. Metal cases are
replaced with paper and plastic.
</P>
<P>
   1958 _ ``A woman who doesn't wear lipstick feels undressed in
public,'' says makeup artist Max Factor in Time magazine. ``Unless
she works on a farm.''
</P>
<P>
   1966 _ White lips hit the scene in London. How mod!
</P>
<P>
   1973 _ Bonne Bell introduces flavored Lip Smackers (today's
gloss of choice for supermodel and part-time Wellington resident
Stephanie Seymour).
</P>
<P>
   1979 _ Black lipstick, made hip by punks, emerges as a statement
(years before Chanel's ``Vamp'').
</P>
<P>
   1983 _ Elizabeth Arden's Lip Fix _ a primer that goes under
lipstick to keep it from ``bleeding'' onto the skin _ is the
biggest seller in company history.
</P>
<P>
   1988 _ Revlon's Ultima II line debuts colors dubbed The Nakeds,
heralding the return of the natural look (as opposed to the
decade's screaming fuchsias).
</P>
<P>
   1994 _ Revlon debuts ColorStay, igniting a cosmetics war to
create ``indelible'' lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   1995 _ MAC appoints drag queen RuPaul the spokesman (woman?) for
its Viva Glam lipstick campaign. Work it, girl!
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Read My Lips by Meg Cohen Ragas and Karen Kozlowski
(Chronicle Books, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   ON THE MOUTHS OF BABES
</P>
<P>
   You'll notice a lot of ``Spice'' girls (as in MAC lip liner) on
this list of what today's hottest stars are wearing:
</P>
<P>
   MODELS
</P>
