   Michelle Pfeiffer: Lancome ``Matte Nu,'' Philip Douglas
``Adobe,'' Nars ``Roman Holiday''
</P>
<P>
   Meg Ryan: Bobbi Brown ``Brown''
</P>
<P>
   Winona Ryder: Bobbi Brown ``Plum Stain,'' Poppy ``Anger''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts: Stila ``Kate''
</P>
<P>
   Rene Russo: Christian Dior ``Ginger Rose''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon: Stila ``Loree,'' Bobbi Brown ``Nude,''
``Raisin'' and ``Toasted Pink''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Shields: Bobbi Brown ``Beige''
</P>
<P>
   Mira Sorvino: Lancome ``Brun Fresque''
</P>
<P>
   Tori Spelling: MAC ``Del Rio'' and ``Spice''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Stone: Nars ``Red Lizard,'' MAC ``Vino,'' ``Media'' and
``Viva Glam''
</P>
<P>
   Uma Thurman: Il-Makiage ``Natural Rose''
</P>
<P>
   Liv Tyler: Nars ``Harlow''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Winslet: Body Shop ``Cranberry Spice,'' Aveda ``Camelia,''
MAC ``Spice''
</P>
<P>
   SINGERS
</P>
<P>
   Mary J. Blige: MAC ``Viva Glam II'' and ``Spice''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Denton: MAC ``Hyper,'' ``Chelsea'' and ``Film Noir''
</P>
<P>
   Jewel: Clinique ``Honeybee''
</P>
<P>
   Amel Larrieux: MAC ``Touch'' and ``Spice''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna: MAC ``Russian Red,'' Trucco ``Blood Red''
</P>
<P>
   Monika: MAC ``Odyssey'' and ``Media''
</P>
<P>
   Alanis Morrisette: Nars ``Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Sinatra: MAC ``Bardot'' and ``Spice''
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Stefani: Urban Decay ``Gash,'' MAC ``Viva Glam''
</P>
<P>
   Jody Watley: MAC ``Chestnut''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Williams: Trucco ``Sienna Suede''
</P>
<P>
   Source: www.users.wineasy.se/bjornt/star.html
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FROM THE PROS
</P>
<P>
   TYRA BANKS: ``I prefer flavored lip gloss to any kind of
lipstick. Sometimes people say, `Tyra, that shiny lip gloss look
went out years ago,' but I like it, and I'm gonna keep on wearing
it. When I was younger, my friends and I bought every flavor _ from
watermelon and strawberry to bubble gum, and I guess I haven't
outgrown that. If you want a look that's a little more
sophisticated, you can always layer on lip gloss over lipstick. I
don't believe in lipstick rules.''
</P>
<P>
   TYRA'S TIPS
</P>
<P>
   Beware of in-store testers. If there aren't individual samples
available, ask the salesperson if she keeps alcohol at the counter.
Have her disinfect the tip of the tester, then wipe with a tissue
before you try it out. If there's no alcohol, your best bet is to
test the color on the back of your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Don't smack your lips together because that tends to make the
lipstick go outside your lip line.
</P>
<P>
   CINDY CRAWFORD: ``Lipstick is the one thing I sometimes get
trendy about. Not only is it quick and easy to change, but trying
on different colors is fun. I'm a firm believer that lipstick
should match your mood and not your clothes. Everything else can
remain unchanged _ your dress, hair, other makeup _ but add a new
lipstick and nothing feels quite the same. A change of lipstick can
transform the face, and in the process, your whole attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   CINDY'S TIPS
</P>
<P>
   Makeup artists often create their own lipstick by combining
several shades. Buy a pill-per-day box from a drugstore and insert
cut-off pieces of lipstick in each little compartment to create
your own colors.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid getting lipstick on your teeth, stick forefinger in
mouth, close lips around it and pull finger out. Any excess should
come off on your finger.
</P>
<P>
   To change a creamy gloss to a matte color, simply blot with
loose powder. Or you can separate a tissue, press one layer on your
lips, and apply powder on top of the tissue _ a doubly whammy.
</P>
<P>
   BOBBI BROWN: ``If I had to teach someone just one thing about
lip color it would be this: Find a lipstick that looks good on your
face when you're wearing absolutely no makeup. This is the magic
color that will make your skin, hair and eyes look their best. By
definition, it will be a lip-toned color _ somewhere in the range
of brown-pink, nude, beige-pink or rosy brown.''
</P>
<P>
   BOBBI'S TIPS
</P>
<P>
   A lip brush is necessary when applying deeper shades _ red,
plum, burgundy _ any color that's in big contrast to your natural
lip tone. A brush allows a richer, more accurate application of
color.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a lip pencil that's the same color as your lipstick or
one shade darker. For longer-lasting color, use a soft lip pencil
to fill in entire lip before applying lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Beware the vampire look. Even if dark lips are the trend, fair
women almost never look pretty in purple or nearly black lipstick.
It's too high a contrast to their skin tone. (Women with darker
skin, however, can pull this off.)
</P>
<P>
   KEVYN AUCOIN: ``I guess I've always been fascinated with
lipstick because of its candylike appearance. I remember climbing
on our bathroom counter and opening the medicine chest in search of
my mom's orange lipstick. I decided to take a bite, and the waxy
texture yielded not a single iota of orange taste. I've learned a
lot about lipstick since then.''
</P>
<P>
   KEVYN'S TIPS
</P>
<P>
   For longer-lasting color: Put powder over the first coat of
lipstick, then apply another coat.
</P>
<P>
   To blot lips more evenly, separate a two-ply tissue and use one
sheet at a time. Blot lips, then reapply lipstick, then blot again.
This absorbs excess oil and leaves the pigment.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to reshape the mouth, a bit of concealer covering
the natural lip line will help make the finished shape look more
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   THE EYES HAVE IT: WHAT COLOR LIPSTICK SHOULD YOU WEAR?
</P>
<P>
   Beauty guru Gale Hayman _ co-founder of Giorgio of Beverly Hills
and creator of her own makeup line _ says eye color is your best
clue:
</P>
<P>
   Blue/gray eyes: Choose lipstick colors with blue or mauve
undertones, neutrals with rose and mauve undertones, light pink to
fuchsia, peaches and reds (light to dark reds with blue
undertones).
</P>
<P>
   Brown eyes: Choose colors with yellow, orange or brown
undertones, orange to terra cotta, corals and reds (medium to dark
reds with yellow or brown undertones) and warm neutrals. No mauve
or blue undertones.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel/green eyes: Choose colors with burgundy or brown
undertones, neutrals with brown or rose undertones, medium pinks
with rose undertones and reds (light to medium with brown
undertones).
</P>
<P>
   A LIPSTICK LEXICON
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line is, different types of lipstick are like different
types of paint finishes:
</P>
<P>
   Creme _ The most popular finish for its balance of shine and
texture. Added oil provides a tad more sheen than matte, but not as
much glisten as gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Gloss _ Lots of emollients (like oil) mean high shine, low
color. Because it's made with softer wax, it's likely to be
packaged in a pot instead of a stick. A more natural alternative to
creme and matte.
</P>
<P>
   Liner _ Contains less emollient and more wax than regular
lipstick so is used to outline the mouth and help prevent lipstick
from ``bleeding'' onto the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Long lasting (i.e., Revlon's ColorStay brand) _ Lipstick that
can survive a kiss or cup of coffee because it contains silicone
oil, which acts as a sealer.
</P>
<P>
   Matte _ Heavy in wax and pigment but light in emollients, matte
provides a lot of texture without shine. Usually wears longer than
average lipstick. Today's versions are less cakey and dry, thanks
to added moisturizers.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer _ Subtle formula with a lot of oil and a medium amount of
wax. Similar to a gloss but with a little more color.
</P>
<P>
   Shimmer _ The '90s version of the '70s frost. Extra glimmer
comes from mica or silica particles (or even ground fish scales).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
