<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6538 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCE-EGYPT13-COX     12-12 1911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-EGYPT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Prince of Animation?
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jeffrey Katzenberg crooks his index
finger to meet his thumb, forming a zero.
</P>
<P>
   He has just been asked, for the umpteenth time in his trek
across the country promoting ``The Prince of Egypt,'' how many
people are waiting for a feature-length cartoon about the story of
Moses and the Jews' exodus from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Zero, he indicates again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to do a study to know that,'' says the
bespectacled, smartly tailored movie studio executive as he fields
reporters' questions at a trendy Miami Beach hotel. ``We didn't
have to go out and ask anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He raises his voice, suddenly amused by the thought of such a
survey. ``All those people who are interested in an animated Bible
story, raise your hand.'' Pause. ``Anyone? Any takers, anywhere?''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, the ``K'' of DreamWorks SKG, the upstart production
company that he partners alongside director Steven Spielberg and
record producer David Geffen, is betting his reputation as an
animation prophet on ``The Prince of Egypt.'' After leaving Disney,
where he shepherded such blockbusters as ``Beauty and the Beast''
and ``The Lion King,'' but was refused the job of president and
chief operating officer by Chairman Michael Eisner, Katzenberg
desperately wants to beat his former colleagues at their own game.
</P>
<P>
   But what if he releases his $70 million animated remake of ``The
Ten Commandments'' in more than 1,000 theaters worldwide _ as he
will Friday _ and moviegoers shrug?
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old college dropout can recall with great clarity
the moment the idea struck, soon after DreamWorks was founded in
October 1994. ``Steven and David and I were talking about what my
larger goals were for animation,'' Katzenberg says. Having worked
for years in a Mouse Factory where you could make any type of
cartoon, as long as it was a fairy tale, he yearned to stretch into
new territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said to Steven that day, `I'd like to do a movie like
`Raiders of the Lost Ark,' a big action hero story. I'd love to do
a science fiction action movie, like `Terminator 2.' And I said,
`I'd love to do something with sort of an epic scale and the
personal intimacy that David Lean did in `Lawrence of Arabia.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And as soon as I said that, he said, `Good, you ought to do
`The Ten Commandments.' It was his idea. I didn't sell him, he sold
me,'' says Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Now _ after four long years caused by DreamWorks' start-up
pains, labor-intensive animation by 380 artists and extreme efforts
to consult a raft of experts _ he has to sell the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the story of Moses is one of the most remarkable
stories of all time,'' he says with practiced delivery. ``It has
been told and retold and retold again for 3,000 years.'' It's the
tale of a Jewish baby raised by Egyptian royalty, until he learns
his true heritage and persuades the pharaoh Rameses II into letting
him lead his people out of bondage to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The lively, serious and spiritual Prince of Egypt is hardly a
warm and fuzzy cartoon. But, curiously enough, it began with
elements of the box office-tested Disney formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started making your typical animated film,'' concedes
Brenda Chapman, one of the movie's three directors. ``We had a
kitty for Rameses, we had dogs for Moses, we had a sidekick valet
comic character for Moses, a confidant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we screened the first act, probably six months or so into
the project, we realized _ y'know what? _ we didn't want to make
the wacky Moses movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how jarring it was,'' says Katzenberg of the
comic shtick.
</P>
<P>
   Before it ever got to full animation, revisions were made in the
direction of reverence. ``A camel is like the funniest animal
you'll ever see, and we had this great camel,'' says co-producer
Penney Finkelman Cox. ``But you know, the story had this integrity,
and we couldn't violate it.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Disney animated features, the voice talent includes some
of Hollywood's bankable stars. Val Kilmer is cast as Moses, pitted
against Ralph Fiennes as Rameses. Michelle Pfeiffer plays Moses'
wife Tzipporah, while Sandra Bullock and Jeff Goldblum are his
sister and brother, Miriam and Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   To Katzenberg, the voices were a critical element, because they
had to invest the characters with enough feeling to stop moviegoers
from thinking of them as cartoons. ``We didn't need this talent
because they're superstars, we needed them because they're the
best,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then an appropriate, anti-Disney visual style was devised, an
angular, adult look which suggests live action. ``What we came to
call it is a painted reality, a painted realism,'' says Katzenberg.
``It's either a painting that's been brought to life, which is the
way I choose to describe it, or it's life that's been painted. I
hope that 20 seconds into that movie, when those characters start
talking and moving, you actually relate to them as human beings.
You don't think of them as cartoony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' takes 3-D computer graphics imaging
further than previously possible. ``We used state of the art visual
tools that weren't even available four years ago,'' beams
Katzenberg. ``They were designed for this movie, to allow our
camera to go in and see, so you as the audience are not standing
outside looking, as you are with a traditional cartoon. When you
move around those characters like we do, at the marketplace with
Miriam and Moses and Aaron, they come to life, they become
dimensional to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The dimensional look was necessary to match a dramatic,
involving storyline. Sometimes that meant diverging from the Bible
or filling in events it never specified. ``For instance, nobody
knows what the relationship was between Moses and Rameses in the
palace,'' notes Katzenberg. ``Maybe they were raised as brothers.
Maybe they weren't.'' So the screenwriters felt comfortable
building their tale around a friendly sibling rivalry that grows
into a chasm once Moses realizes he is a Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age years of Moses and Rameses are skipped in Cecil B.
DeMille's 1956 epic movie, which Katzenberg ordered his filmmakers
to avoid. ``You'd either try and do something different from what
they did, to make sure that you were different, or it leaves an
image in your mind that you don't know how to get away from,''
explains Katzenberg. ``It is incredibly corrupting on both
fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg gets high marks from the movie's creative team for
his involvement. ``He's got a really good story sense, which is
unusual for an executive,'' says Chapman. ``That's a huge reason
why I came over from Disney to work with him, because I grew to
respect his judgment. His strength, I think, is being able to stand
back and look at the whole and make a general statement of what's
not working for him.''
</P>
<P>
   At various points throughout the movie's development, Katzenberg
invited some 685 experts, scientists, theologians, scholars and
faith leaders to view the work-in-progress. ``We went out and spent
an unbelievable amount of effort and resources getting this to the
point where it was faithful and it was accurate,'' says Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   These visitors were questioned extensively about what they saw
in the film, particularly for erroneous details. In an early
version, Moses stomped on a glass at the end of his wedding
ceremony. It was a great visual representation of a Jewish ritual,
but an anachronistic one, Katzenberg learned. The ritual symbolizes
the destruction of the first temple, which occurred a thousand
years after the life of Moses. Out it went from the film.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that had never seen eye-to-eye watched ``The Prince of
Egypt'' and found themselves suddenly in accord. ``At one point, we
got the leadership of the Conservative, the Reformed and Orthodox
Jewish faiths in a room together,'' says Cox. ``And they said
they'd never been in a room together, they've never agreed on
anything, except the way they responded to the movie. They were so
overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has arisen over these seeming attempts to gain
endorsements from religious leaders, ranging from Vatican cardinals
to the Rev. Jerry Falwell. Although DreamWorks spent millions to
avoid any group taking offense _ as happened with Disney's Aladdin
and Pocahontas _ Katzenberg is still bracing for protests. ``I
would actually be kind of surprised if it didn't,'' he says.
``Wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg is certainly taking precautions against pranks
embedded in the film, as happened in other animated features. ``We
literally had a team of five or six people whose job it was to go
with a magnifying glass and look at every frame of everything in
this movie,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if The Prince of Egypt is so mischief-free and biblically
reverent that it might be suitable for toddlers, they were never
the target audience. ``I wouldn't take a 4-year-old to this movie,
because I just don't think they'll understand it,'' says
Katzenberg. ``I think some of the complexities of the story, some
of the ideas and stuff, they'd just go over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie carries a PG rating, which the filmmakers expected all
along. ``Jeffrey has often said he would have asked for it if he
hadn't gotten it,'' adds Cox. ``Because we felt it's appropriate to
say, `Parents, you need to evaluate this for your children.'''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you sell the movie to grown-ups? ``It's a challenge,
because we have to convince a huge number of people who think, `Oh,
animation. That's a kiddie flick. That's a cartoon','' says Cox.
``It's not just for kiddies and the parents that they drag along.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, how do you sell a cartoon without the traditional
marketing tie-ins? ``There's no merchandise, no toys, no lunch
pails,'' says Katzenberg, who says ``Red Sea shower curtains'' and
the like would have been inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he has approved not one, but three CDs of the movie's
Stephen Schwartz songs (including a big Whitney Houston-Mariah
Carey duet) and a library shelf of books inspired by the movie. And
a deal has been struck with Wal-Mart stores to sell a gift package
of a book, a recording and two tickets to ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   And Katzenberg is doing a lot of publicity globe-trotting,
something you rarely see from studio executives, but crucial to
promoting what he admits is a difficult movie. If ``The Prince of
Egypt'' helps break Disney's hammerlock on the animation market,
that will be an extra bit of satisfaction for Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   His legal battle with Disney over severance pay gained him a
judgment _ though not yet a payment _ estimated to be more than
$100 million. And Disney officials tried to dilute his reputation
and downplay his contributions to its animation successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will admit to having a couple of months that were very hard
for me on a personal level, not understanding how you could give as
much of yourself to someone and to an organization, and then have
them try and kill you,'' Katzenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   He genially claims that he's not a vindictive man. But he knows
the effect a successful movie would have on Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you, nothing will pain them more _ nothing _ than
if this movie went out and did a trillion dollars. For somebody who
wants them to get some religion, that would do it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
