<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6539 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATION13-COX     12-12 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATION13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anthologies of 2Pac, Bone Thugs dispense with the usual
throwaway tracks
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There isn't a hip-hop album out there that
doesn't have at least two or three throwaway tracks on it. It's
part of hip-hop's singles-driven philosophy. Rather than creating
unified albums, rappers concentrate on singular blasts of energy
and rhythm that make one song stand out. Inevitably, though, some
tracks even fail to stand up.
</P>
<P>
   That's why greatest-hits albums work so well for hip-hop
artists, and why new compilations from Tupac Shakur and Bone
Thugs-n-Harmony qualify as each artist's definitive effort. For
Cleveland's R&AMP;B-flavored Thugs, ``The Collection, Vol. 1'' serves
as a grab bag of the various singles, soundtrack contributions and
worthwhile oddities the quartet has offered since its 1994 debut.
For 2Pac (Shakur's rap moniker), ``Greatest Hits'' proves that the
slain West Coast hip-hop icon wasn't just immortalized after his
1996 murder _ he had found his place in history long before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all hoods, and all we ever had was dreams,'' Shakur
reminds us of his real-life situation on ``God Bless the Dead,''
one of two previously unreleased tracks on the two-disc, 25-track
collection. With the opening call-out, ``Rest in peace to my
brother, Biggie Smalls,'' and several other references to the
rapper better known as Notorious B.I.G. _ who was slain six months
after Shakur _ ``God Bless the Dead'' proves 2Pac to be a prophet,
a walking ghost or just another rapper too caught up in gangsta
posturing. Indeed, ``Hit 'Em Up,'' which came out before Shakur's
death and includes all kinds of inane threats to Smalls and the Bad
Boy Records crew, suggests the latter.
</P>
<P>
   2Pac's ``Greatest Hits'' is hardly all about gangstaism, though.
Shakur had a softer, vulnerable side that, along with the charisma
he demonstrated as an actor, made him beloved by millions.
``Unconditional Love,'' ``Keep Ya Head Up'' and, of course, ``Dear
Mama'' all show this. What's more, he and his production crew
created some of the best hip-hop sound-spaces this side of Public
Enemy, with ``How Do U Want It,'' ``2 of Amerikaz Most Wanted''
and, especially, ``California Love'' offering the proof here.
</P>
<P>
   With tracks from all seven of his albums, including the Makaveli
disc, 2Pac's ``Greatest Hits'' truly is the best of one of the best
there ever was. Or, if you buy the rumors (see related story) the
best there still is.
</P>
<P>
   Bone Thugs-n-Harmony's ``The Collection'' is certainly less
monumental or called for, but for fans of the fast-rapping,
slow-grooving foursome, it offers a condensed version of the
quartet's widespread appeal. Clearly, it's easier to get through
than last year's two-disc ``Art of War,'' from which the fiery
``Body Rott'' is taken. Original versions of ``Foe the Love of $''
(featuring the group's late mentor Eazy E), ``Crossroad'' and ``1st
of Tha Month'' show the Thugs' unique rap power and strong grooves,
while ``War'' (with Henry Rollins) and ``Thuggish Ruggish Bone''
demonstrate their adventurous spirit. Best of all, there's nary a
throwaway between them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the least likely musical pairings pay the greatest
artistic dividends. Take ``River Man,'' the cello-shaded
centerpiece of ``Shades of Bey.'' It was written by Nick Drake, a
fragile British folksinger who died in 1974 at age 26 from an
overdose of anti-depressants. Almost a quarter of a century later,
it is given exquisitely sonorous voice by an African American jazz
singer in his late 50s, whose style fell from fashion around the
time that Drake's creative star was rising.
</P>
<P>
   Though Andy Bey hadn't recorded as a band leader in more than
two decades before his re-emergence in 1996 with ``Ballads, Blues &AMP;
Bey,'' this superb follow-up finds him making up for lost time.
There's a tragic sense of life at the heart of his bittersweet art,
a tender sadness that suffuses his romantic balladry _ a
recognition that desire, like life itself, is a flicker.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to conjure a deeper shade of blue than that expressed
through Bey's reading of Billy Strayhorn's ``The Last Light of
Evening (Blood Count),'' where the midnight of the soul offers the
faintest hope of dawn. From the time-stopping elegance of Duke
Ellington's ``Pretty Girl (The Starcrossed Lovers)'' to the sensual
persistence of the Brazilian-tinged ``Like a Lover'' and ``Drume
Negrita,'' the subtle spareness of the arrangements makes Bey's
limber, supple baritone and unearthly falsetto sound all the
richer.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison with Bey's sophisticated balladry and the
supper-club bluesiness of his piano playing, the two up-tempo cuts
sound more like scat-and-jive exercises that skirt the emotional
surface, as Thelonious Monk's ``Get It Straight (Straight, No
Chaser)'' mainly provides a workout for the rhythm section and
``Believin' It (Half &AMP; Half)'' leaves the singer a little
breathless. Yet the album as a whole is so deeply reflective of
life's experience that it seems that Bey's hiatus from recording
was well spent; it's hard to imagine the Andy Bey of the '60s or
'70s achieving anything this profound.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don McLeese
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
