<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDBOOKS-MAIN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding best tales is easy: Just open this $40 treasury
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Janet Schulman, editor of the late Dr. Seuss and a
powerhouse in children's publishing, has gathered 44 of the most
beloved children's books of our time for ``The 20th Century
Children's Book Treasury'' (Knopf, all ages, $40).
</P>
<P>
   One and all can get reacquainted with many favorite characters:
Petunia the silly goose, Stellaluna the fruit bat, Babar the
elephant, the mixed-up Amelia Bedelia, Madeline the schoolgirl, and
Alexander, the boy who had a ``terrible, horrible, no good, very
bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Are your old copies of ``Harry the Dirty Dog'' by Gene Zion
(1956) or ``A Chair for My Mother'' by Vera B. Williams (1982) worn
and tattered beyond use? You'll find ``Harry'' and ``Chair'' here,
too, spiffed up and begging for your lap again.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman has selected read-aloud favorites for this keepsake,
taking care to offer a nice balance of stories for a variety of
ages. Included are most of the books' original illustrations,
created by sterling talents such as Maurice Sendak, William Steig,
Lane Smith, Jan Pienkowski and Mercer Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of scope, breadth and quality, this 305-page volume
truly is a treasure. And if you enjoy compilations, you also might
consider ``A Family Treasury of Myths From Around the World'' by
Viviane Koenig, illustrated by Koenig, Veronique Ageorges and
Daniel Henon, translated by Anthony Zielonka. (Harry N. Abrams,
ages 9 and up, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   Striking, original art enhances this collection of 10 myths.
</P>
<P>
   Also new in stores:
</P>
<P>
   _ AGES 4-8: ``Music Over Manhattan'' by Mark Karlins,
illustrated by Jack E. Davis (Doubleday, $15.95). The text is flat
and twice as long as it needs to be for this ditty about Bernie
learning to play the trumpet. On the other hand, the art is
bursting with wit, personality and zany relatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ AGES 8 AND UP: ``Laura's Album'' by William Anderson
(HarperCollins, $19.95). Anyone who treasures the ``Little House''
books should know about this dandy addition for the bookshelf.
Historian Anderson has combed public and private collections to
assemble an intimate 80-page biography based on the life of Laura
Ingalls Wilder. It turns out that Wilder was a pack rat who saved
everything from church programs and greeting cards to childhood
drawings and routine personal correspondence. The scrapbook-style
layout, filled with rare photographs and mementos, makes this a
real gem for fans.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALL AGES: ``A World of Words: An ABC of Quotations'' by Tobi
Tobias, illustrated by Peter Malone (Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard, $16).
The alphabet is treated to glorious illustrations and 26 quotations
from famous writers. For example, ``P'' is for ``Pocket,'' and the
quote is from D.H. Lawrence: ``You love me so much, you want to put
me in your pocket.'' The illustration is of a girl sharing her
orange with a kangaroo mama, who in turn shares it with the 'roo in
her pocket. Among the quoted: Shakespeare, J.R.R. Tolkien, Carl
Sandburg, Edna St. Vincent Millay and e.e. cummings. And this from
Joel Chandler Harris on the ``F'' is for ``Fire'' page: ``Youk'n
hide de fier, but w'at you gwine do wid de smoke?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALL AGES: ``Bridges Are to Cross'' by Philemon Sturges,
illustrated by Giles Laroche (Putnam, $15.99). Learning about 15
exceptional bridges is less interesting than the magnificently
detailed ``paper sculpture'' illustrations of the bridges. The
artistic technique results in a vibrant three-dimensional look.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
