<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETNEWS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The 3 faces of news
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Viewers who flip from one network newscast to
another often see the same stories in the same order _ sometimes
with the exact same footage.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekday at 5:30 p.m., ABC, CBS and NBC all began
their newscasts with updates about the impeachment hearings. Next
up was a story about this year's deadly hurricane season. On all
three newscasts. At the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference on most nights seems to be the anchors
introducing the stories. On ABC the ever-poised and
camera-comfortable Peter Jennings perches on a stool before a video
wall. On CBS, clench-jawed Dan Rather sits behind a desk looking
intently into the camera, while on NBC the easy-going Tom Brokaw
stands or sits before another, bigger video wall.
</P>
<P>
   Are the network newscasts, from which a vast majority of
Americans get their daily dose of news, really all the same except
for the famous men who front them? The short answer is yes, but the
long answer is there are some subtle and some not-so-subtle
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrust of much of our commentary has been sameness,'' said
Janine Jackson, research director of Fairness and Accuracy in
Reporting, a media watchdog group that monitors print and
electronic news reporting. ``Not every day, but generally we've
been struck by the similarities. There's not one that's
significantly better or worse. Each has certain features that are
good or not-so-good, but as far as the whole newscast, we don't see
one as standing out.''
</P>
<P>
   But viewers who flip from one network to another are likely to
see subtle differences. Rather, who often refers to himself in the
old-fashioned journalistic style as ``this reporter,'' likes to
give his newscast a newspaper feel. Sometimes he'll introduce a
story with, ``The headline this hour ...'' Jennings, perhaps
because of his clipped Canadian accent, comes off as cooler and
more conversational, while Brokaw seems like a laid-back insider.
The personalities of the anchors seem to spill into their
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Peterson, a typical viewer who is a retired flight attendant
and sports shop owner from San Marcos, has been watching ABC's news
for several years because she likes the way Jennings ``delivers the
news. ... He seems a lot more friendly and comfortable'' than the
other guys. She used to watch Brokaw but switched because she
didn't like his personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought he seemed cocky,'' Peterson said. ``He didn't
seem warm or friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Ortiz, executive producer of ``The CBS Evening News,'' says
his anchor's characteristics are ``absolutely'' stamped on the
newscast. ``Dan Rather's personality and influence are all over
this broadcast. He's constantly reading, researching, reporting and
suggesting stories. He's very much engaged in helping steer the
broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tyndall Report, a weekly analysis of network newscasts by
former journalist Andrew Tyndall, supports the sameness theory of
network news in the top half of the programs but discounts it in
the second half. Tyndall also discounts the anchors' influence on
the substance of their respective newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These newscasts have all gone through different journalistic
styles over the years when the same anchors were in position,''
Tyndall said. ``There was a time when NBC was heavy on political
coverage, CBS had more lifestyle features and ABC was the leader in
foreign coverage. I'm sure Peter would like to continue to lead in
foreign coverage, but the fact that that no longer happens is
evidence that he doesn't have that much influence.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS now has slightly more foreign news than ABC and considerably
more than NBC.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do the three newscasts stack up today in terms of
content? Tyndall's research has shown that the first half of the
programs on all three networks is basically the same, dictated by
the major national and international news of the day. The three
programs tend to have the same top story lineups. For example, all
three networks focused on the Monica Lewinsky scandal this year,
with NBC covering it the most and CBS covering it the least.
</P>
<P>
   Features vary in style
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not talking about enormous differences,'' Tyndall
said. ``We're talking about tendencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyndall's analysis found that the main content differences among
the three newscasts comes after the second commercial, ``when the
features come in and the individual style of the network comes
out.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Tyndall found, has more hard news all the way through its
newscast, including the second half. CBS's only designated feature
segment is the nightly ``Eye on America,'' which explores topics
related to current news stories, such as a recent piece on a family
that sued its HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to make it feel like a hard news broadcast,''
Ortiz said. ``But it can't just be a machine-gun wire service. It
has to show some thought, analysis and context. That's where 'Eye
on America' comes in. It helps us get the length of airtime to
develop a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Although all the networks have faced budget cutbacks and layoffs
at their foreign bureaus, Ortiz said CBS has fought hard to keep
foreign news on the newscast. And they do so despite surveys saying
viewers aren't particularly interested in foreign news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think viewers are interested in coming away feeling like
they've had some kind of authoritative report on the world around
them,'' Ortiz said. ``Most of that's going to be national, but we
do think it's important to find interesting foreign stories. It's
not necessarily the winning edge, but it does distinguish us from
the fare viewers see on our affiliates' local newscasts.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tyndall, NBC's ``Nightly News'' has more features
than the other newscasts, and they're showcased in regular segments
such as ``In-Depth,'' ``The Fleecing of America'' and ``In Their
Own Words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not skimping on the major stories,'' Tyndall added.
``Before the second commercial, NBC is covering hard news, but in
the bottom half, they overwhelmingly do features on the minor
stories, a lot of them lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings too close to call
</P>
<P>
   NBC News overtook ABC News in the ratings last year after an
eight-year dominance by ABC. But now the two find themselves in a
ratings race that's too close to call most weeks (ABC eked out a
win in November), and CBS is not far behind. NBC's executive
producer David Doss believes his broadcast's treatment of the news,
including special features, is a big reason people watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think of it in terms of features,'' Doss said. ``Our
'Fleecing of America' segments are investigative pieces about how
taxpayers' money is squandered. Tom Brokaw has an expression we all
use here, and that is we're not doing the news because it interests
the newsroom but because it's of vital interest to our audience.
... There are so many places for people to get information now that
it doesn't serve any real purpose for us to tell them what they
already know. So, we try to provide more context and explain what
it means, how it affects their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``World News Tonight,'' according to Tyndall, has more
hard news than features but not as much hard news as CBS. ABC's
features in the second half of the broadcast tend to be ``more
abstract, things on the economy, high-tech stuff and the coming
millennium. They're more futuristic.'' Regular feature segments
include ``Close-up,'' ``It's Your Money'' and ``Reality Check.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another quirky thing about ABC is that their human interest
features often go to sports,'' Tyndall said. ``Perhaps because of
their tie-in to ESPN.''
</P>
<P>
   With subtle differences in content and anchor style, one may
wonder what prompts viewers to choose a certain network newscast.
Some people instinctively watch the same network for years, while
others may change from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important factor turns out to be the local newscast
that airs before the network news,'' said Larry McGill, director of
research for the Media Studies Center, an education-based group run
by the Freedom Forum. ``The network newscast rating tends to be
close to the local lead-in. Typically all the network news can do
is gain or lose up to 5 percent of its local lead-in. Because the
network newscasts are all seen as similarly credible, it's an easy
decision for people to continue watching one network.''
</P>
<P>
   If people do switch, however, it's usually because of an anchor
preference. A survey in 1997 conducted by the Freedom Forum's
Newseum in Arlington, Va., found that NBC's Brokaw was favored by a
small majority, followed by Jennings and then Rather.
</P>
<P>
   ``All are usually seen as equally competent, knowledgeable and
experienced,'' McGill said. ``If anything differentiates them, it's
a perceived attractiveness and a more generalized likability.''
</P>
<P>
   The last big shift in network news viewing habits came about
when top-rated CBS slipped a couple of years after the
hard-charging Rather replaced the avuncular Walter Cronkite in
1981. Today the three newscasts are so close in the ratings that
half a rating point _ a mere 620,000 viewers _ separates them.
</P>
<P>
   CNN a distant fourth
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans still do watch evening newscasts. On an
average weeknight, 23.7 million TV households watch one of the
network news programs. Although there has been some audience
erosion in the past decade, it is minor compared to the losses in
prime-time entertainment. During a breaking news story, like a
plane crash or natural disaster, lots of people turn to CNN, but
for a regular news diet, they watch ABC, CBS and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks' performance that has stayed potent the longest
and resisted erosion from cable the best is the network news,''
McGill said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have drifted away from the evening newscasts may have
done so for reasons other than journalistic style or content.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is we don't have as much of an attention span,''
McGill said. ``We're used to the fact that there are lots of
alternatives, so people are less patient in sitting through a
newscast. Another factor is we live in times when the need to
follow the news is not as pressing. We don't have a Cold War, and
we're not worried about some cataclysmic event. We can be kind of
blase and fill our time with amusements. That's why you see
newscasts going to more entertainment hooks, like the
Clinton-Lewinsky story that has been played up so much. It has all
these soap-opera elements.''
</P>
<P>
   But for millions of news hounds, dinner is always preceded by a
wrap-up of the day's events, brought to us by a member of the
likable trio of Tom, Peter and Dan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
