<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMANIAN-UT-FULBRIGHT     12-12 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANIAN-UT-FULBRIGHT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Romanian trying to open country's libraries, society
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ She was born into a closed society, blacklisted
by the communists, scorned for studying foreign cultures and
repeatedly denied a passport. Her mission now: push her native
Romania to become more open.
</P>
<P>
   How do you change a country?
</P>
<P>
   Fulbright Scholar Hermina Anghelescu has ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Anghelescu, a doctoral student in library science at the
University of Texas, sees public libraries as a reflection of the
societies they serve. The more open a nation's libraries, the more
open the society.
</P>
<P>
   Romania has been struggling with openness since communism fell
in 1989. The country, along with its libraries, has a long way to
go, she said. Could she help the libraries advance by sharing her
knowledge of American libraries?
</P>
<P>
   That has been her goal since coming to UT in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a master's degree and with work under way on a
doctorate, Anghelescu asked the National Library of Romania in 1995
to host a training workshop for librarians. She had worked there
and was expected to return after her studies abroad. She would find
the money and organize a U.S. delegation of scholars and
professionals to teach Romanian librarians to be more professional
and to make their collections more open, more modern and easier for
the public to use.
</P>
<P>
   The library gave the go-ahead. But when she won a $15,000 grant
to make it happen, officials said no. She contacted other Romanian
libraries to see if they were interested. None responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the blue I receive an eight-line fax from the National
Library announcing that I was no longer affiliated with them. I was
fired,'' she wrote in her journal in June 1995. ``That was a common
strategy employed during the communist regime to let Romanians
living abroad know that they had become persona non grata.''
</P>
<P>
   She got the grant extended and solicited more Romanian
libraries. Two stepped forward in 1996, and Anghelescu has
coordinated training workshops each of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here is that she basically taught her country
about library science and she taught us about her country,'' said
Teresa Sullivan, UT's dean of graduate studies. ``It took a student
to put it together.''
</P>
<P>
   `A noxious element'
</P>
<P>
   It has not been easy to work with a country that blacklisted her
parents because they were well-to-do and were not members of the
Communist Party, Anghelescu, now 42, said. Romanian officials
remain skeptical of her and have intercepted mail to her mother,
including Christmas cards, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called a noxious element. If you were not a peasant, you
were not `of healthy origin,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents lost their property after World War II and moved in
with her father's parents. About the only thing they didn't lose
was her father's precious books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up surrounded by books,'' she said. ``My father had a
private library, 4,000 volumes. I remember sometimes my mother was
kidding with him, `If you were to choose between me and your
library, what would you choose?' I was just a little girl, and my
father would say, `My library.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hermina didn't realize he was joking. She knew he loved his
books, and the love was contagious. At age 7 she was reading so
well her parents hired a private tutor to teach her English and
French. She is fluent in both and also speaks Italian.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from college in 1979, she used her language
skills to get a job at the National Library's international
exchange division.
</P>
<P>
   One night, she went to a Canadian exhibition in Bucharest
without reporting to her boss that she would be near foreigners.
Afterward, the secret police accosted her and ordered her to write
down everything that had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the mistake of breathing the same air with the Canadian
ambassador at the Canadian exhibition,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The police were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they would put me in prison,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't. But the government constantly denied her a
passport. It considered her a defection risk.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to America
</P>
<P>
   She didn't get one until 1990, the same year she was named
international relations officer at the National Library. The
American cultural attache urged her to apply for a Fulbright
scholarship, which pays for Americans and foreigners to study
abroad. She won the prestigious scholarship and chose UT, attracted
by its national reputation in library science.
</P>
<P>
   She has been amazed by the school's support of her work and its
resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``This library is wonderful,'' she said, strolling the aisles of
the Perry-Castaneda Library, one of the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libraries in Romania have closed stacks,'' she said, brushing
fingertips across the books. ``What we have here are open stacks.
That's an American concept.''
</P>
<P>
   She is sharing such concepts at the Romanian seminars.
</P>
<P>
   The workshops have made a difference, said state librarian
Robert Martin, who has taken two of the trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've expanded the horizons of the librarians who
participated, opened up new frontiers for them and given them new
ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Davis, a UT professor of library science and history,
considers the trips with Anghelescu, his teaching assistant,
highlights of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good lesson for us in humility,'' Davis said. ``We may
have a lot of resources in this country, but they've got a lot of
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The librarians in Romania are eager to learn, and UT faculty
have responded by paying their own way the past two trips, said
Brooke Sheldon, a library science professor and former dean of the
college.
</P>
<P>
   Serving her country
</P>
<P>
   Anghelescu ``is imbued with the essence of our profession, which
is service,'' Sheldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Anghelescu, a single mother of a 16-year-old, expects to
graduate in May. She can stay in the United States another 18
months, but after that, her student visa requires her to spend two
years in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   She said she will continue her work with the librarians but
worries she won't be as effective.
</P>
<P>
   Romanian officials ``like me when I come and go,'' she said.
``They don't like me when I stay there and teach American ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But if she leaves, she won't give up her mission. She loves her
country and blames ``the system'' for her painful past, not the
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 28 years, and I have encountered a lot of
international students,'' Davis said. ``But I have not known any as
eager to return the benefits ... to her own country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
