<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SICKLE-TRANSPLANT13-C     12-12 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICKLE-TRANSPLANT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Sickle cell patient gets cord blood transplant
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Medical history unfolded at Egleston Children's
Hospital on Friday at noon with the world's first cord blood
transplant for sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   As a syringe of dark, red blood plunged into the intravenous
line of Keone Penn, relatives and friends bowed their heads in
prayer and talked of miracles, cures and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   They also gently told the center of attention to wake up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Keone. God's working it out just like we said. Wake up
and see your miracle happening,'' said Beverly Kennedy, a close
friend of Leslie Penn, Keone's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Keone was sleepy from 10 days of chemotherapy to kill his
unhealthy bone marrow, and painkillers. But he awoke long enough to
help pediatric nurse practitioner Ellen Olson squeeze stem blood
cells into his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors will know in three to four weeks if the transplant has
taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the transplant itself is kind of anticlimactic,''
admitted Leslie Penn. ``It's just a bag of blood dripping into
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the procedure work, it could help many severely ill
children with sickle cell anemia who do not have a relative with
matching bone marrow, as in the case of Keone.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow is the spongy liquid inside bones where blood cells
form and mature. The experimental procedure poses great risk
because the patient's immune-fighting white cells are wiped out,
leaving him open to infections.
</P>
<P>
   Since infancy, Keone has suffered numerous infections and a
stroke at age 5. He's received monthly blood transfusions the past
seven years. Without a transplant, doctors feared he would suffer a
second stroke or further complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This protocol is ahead of its time,'' said Dr. Angela Ogden,
one of the Emory specialists treating Keone. ``But he's not your
typical sickle cell kid. Taking the additional risk ... is
acceptable in his case, until we know that umbilical cord
transplant will work for sickle cell. If it does, we can offer it
to kids with less severe disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Centerville boy, a seventh-grader at Gwinnett's
Shiloh Middle School, received the equivalent of about eight
tablespoons of stem cell blood. It came from an anonymous woman who
consented to have her placenta and umbilical cord donated to the
New York Blood Center.
</P>
<P>
   Rich in stem cells that grow into the three components of blood,
cord blood has been used in nearly 600 procedures around the world
in patients suffering from leukemia and other immune and genetic
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure has never been tried on sickle cell disease, which
affects 70,000 people nationwide, most of whom are
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One hoped-for result of Keone's cord blood transplant is that
his blood type will slowly change from O to B, which will signal
the transplant is taking hold. His donor's type was B.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time. That's the next step,'' said Olson. ``The average is 28
days from the time we give them the stem cells until they form bone
marrow and start growing. What we'll do now is watch him for fevers
and put him on antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
