<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG13-C     12-12 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A historic pony ride
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter whether you're a casual observer or an
enthusiast obsessed with the original pony car, there's only one
way to look at the 1999 Mustang: It's an enticing bridge between
the near-antediluvian 'Stang of the early and mid-'90s and the
totally rebuilt model coming soon into the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This Mustang boasts refined engines, noticeably better
performance, styling updates that prevent staleness, and driving
characteristics that should manage to please both performance
addicts and just-transport-me drivers. Rev its nicely growly
engine, make sure the front wheels are in line with that visually
pleasing long hood, drop the clutch and this Mustang briskly
launches driving fun.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, which inadvertently birthed the term ``pony car'' when it
introduced the 1964 1/2 Mustang, is marking time with the '99
models, but that doesn't mean they won't sell. The edgy styling,
increased horsepower for both V-6 and V-8 engines and interior
refinements should team with pricing to help the Mustang keep
annual sales convincingly above the 100,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-production test V-6 coupe arrived with a base price of
$16,995 that includes delivery. The V-6 convertible is based at
$21,595 with the V-8-powered GT at $21,395 and the convertible GT
at $25,395. Prices for the hopped-up Cobra Mustang _ a
320-horsepower tire-shredder _ will be announced early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Most option prices for the base and GT versions were still being
set at press time, but all-speed traction control will list for
$230 with a convenience package combining a six-way power driver's
seat, rear defroster, cruise control and front floor mats costing
$550. Although the '99 went into production Nov. 2, prices are just
now coming because the big advertising launch is to hit next week.
</P>
<P>
   There is some noteworthy irony packaged with the new Mustang. It
was only a few years ago that Ford was leaning toward easing out
the Mustang in favor of the import-fighting Probe. Now Ford is
catering to the Mustang faithful by introducing the '99 in
Nashville during a Mustang Club of America meeting and by
earmarking a $1.5 million donation as seed money for the $30
million Mustang museum, which will be built in metro Atlanta or
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where the museum goes, the '99 Mustang will rate a
prominent place. Historians will point to that long hood and
trapezoidal rear that gives it a chunky, low-centered look and the
mix of rounded lines and creases and pronounce it ``good looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Older enthusiasts who'll remember driving the base V-6, which
gets its horsepower upped by 40 to 190 (the V-6 jumps from 225 hp
to 260), will recall how the switchable traction control permits a
bit of wheelspin during a high-revving start, but then cuts the
power or applies the rear brakes to put a stop to that nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers will remember the nice feel of an air-conditioned
two-cockpit cabin with brown and gray plastic, good console drink
holders, storage and rounded dash, the high-end stereo with CD
player and controls centered between the driver and passenger, and
the body-fitting, easily adjusted bucket seats. The poor souls who
had to ride in the rear will still be whining.
</P>
<P>
   The ergonomics are basically simple _ no clutter or redundancy
here _ and convenient, although the switch for the optional rear
defroster is mounted not with the heater/AC controls on the center
of the dash, but behind the left edge of the steering wheel.
Visibility is about as good as it gets in a coupe with sizable rear
pillars.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed shifter (a four-speed automatic is available) has
a solid feel not unlike that of expensive sport cars, the steering
has been tightened and given more feel and the V-6, despite a
willingness to rev to 5,500 rpm, is best enjoyed when its 220
pounds-feet of torque peaks at 2,750 rpm, which is particularly
useful in second and third gears.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it: A new Mustang that's basically a solid
driver with a relatively flat ride, reasonable performance and a
good two-passenger cabin. It's a lot better than in the past, but,
Ford assures fans, certainly not all that it's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THEY'RE SAYING ABOUT THE NEW MUSTANG
</P>
