<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee continues
to vote Saturday on articles of impeachment. The matter will go to
the full House for a vote, possibly this coming week. (Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON _ JERUSALEM _ Escaping Washington, but not the
prospect of impeachment, President Clinton flew to Israel Saturday
for a three-day visit in which he will once again try to rescue the
faltering Middle East peace process. A scene setter, wrapping in
Saturday events in the Middle East. (Kaplow/Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: We expect to top this story with Clinton's remarks at his
arrival ceremony, which is tentatively scheduled to begin about
5:30 p.m. EST
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PLO _ GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ The gathering that
President Clinton will face in Gaza Monday is a collection of
former guerrillas, terrorists, politicians-in-exile and Intifada
rebels. The Palestine National Council is sort of the defunct
Legislature of the PLO. Many will boycott, but the group, like
leader Yasser Arafat, illustrates the PLO transition from guerrilla
war to politics. And, if Rabin could shake Arafat's hand, Clinton
can too. ``We gave him our kosher certificate,'' says Israeli
political scientist Efraim Inbar. 700 words. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Sat., Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-DEVELOPMENT _ GAZA or RAMALLAH Since the start of the
Oslo peace process, Palestinian per capita income has fallen at
least 10 percent. Economic growth has been stalled or negative.
Outside aid has indeed improved roads and sewers and the $3-4
billion in aid promised will help, but it will take more to apply
the theory that economic prosperity leads to peace. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/PALESTINIAN-BOX _ Information suitable for a graphic
highlighting some of the key economic projects being undertaken
with U.S. and other foreign aid. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-STATE _ DATELINE TO COME _ On the idea of
Palestinian statehood, the whole theme of building a Palestinian
society and economy truly begs the question: Are we building
Palestine? (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-CHARTER _ GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip The reason for
Clinton's visit is to witness the revision of the Palestinian
National Charter. What is that? Hasn't it already been revised?
And, why is it almost certain that this visit will not settle this
issue? (Because Israel has already said it does not agree with the
procedure that will be followed.) (Kaplow, Cox News Service). EDs:
To move Thurs., Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON-ANNIVERSARY _ SARAJEVO, BOSNIA-HERCEGOVINA _ Three years
after the Dayton Peace Accords ended the ethnic war here, a lot of
progress has been made in the reconstruction of Bosnia. Bridges and
roads have been rebuilt, schools reopened, electric lines
re-connected. Food shortages are a thing of the past, as is the
systematic violence of the war. But the peace here remains tenuous.
The reason, and the result, is 1.1 million Bosnian refugees who
haven't gone home yet. The Dayton Accords, reached at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in 1995, divided Bosnia into two
states, the Serb Republic, and the Muslim/Croat Federation. The two
states are largely autonomous, each with the right to elect its own
president and parliament, maintain its own military and even
negotiate agreements with other countries. The Peace Accords
accomplished its most important goal, ending the war and the ethnic
cleansing that so horrified the world. But it has been unable to
undo the damage of ethnic cleansing. Bosnia is still sharply
divided along ethnic lines. And while enabling people to go home
wasn't the first goal of the peace plan, it remains the one that
cannot be achieved. That failure has confounded all other attempts
to rebuild Bosnia into a country that doesn't need international
peace keepers to keep it from tumbling back into war. (Nesmith,
Special to the Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   w/BOSNIA-FAMILY _ PALANKA, BOSNIA-HERCEGOVINA _ Sevala and Suad
Pobric were supposed to move into their new house on May 1, 1992.
The young couple had spent their entire savings building the
four-bedroom house, their dream house, with plenty of room for the
family they wanted to raise together. But on April 28, a unit of
the Serbian Special Forces arrived in their hometown of Brcko and
the Pobrics, who are Muslims, had to flee. More than six years
later, they still can't go home. A Serbian family that fled
fighting in another part of the country is living in the Pobric's
house now. Sevala has met them, even had coffee with them. The
Pobrics, and the Serbian family occupying their house, are among
the more than one million Bosnian refugees who either aren't able
or aren't willing to return to their pre-war homes. They are all
survivors of ethnic cleansing and war. And three years after the
war ended here, they each represent a weakness of the fragile peace
here. (Nesmith, Special to the Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/DAYTON-TIMELINE _ Timeline of war and peace in
Bosnia-Hercegovina. (Nesmith, Special to the Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON-PLAYERS _ Thumbnail sketches of a half-dozen major
players in Bosnia-Hercegovina. (Nesmith, Special to the Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDs: There are maps available from IFOR, the Implementation
Force which proceeded SFOR, the Stabilization Force. The maps are
called ``BH Majority Ethnic Distribution 1991'' and ``BH Ethnic
Distribution (majority) 1996'' IFOR's Web site address:
www.nato.int/ifor/ifor.htm
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Tues., Dec. 8, in both the International and
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD _ MIAMI _ Puerto Ricans go to the polls
Sunday (Dec. 13) to choose between statehood, independence, or the
current ``commonwealth'' status. Gov. Pedro Rossello is pushing
hard for statehood and has flooded TV and radio with
advertisements. The U.S. Congress refused to approve a bill earlier
this year aimed at unraveling Puerto Rico's complicated legal ties
to the United States. So in frustration, Rossello called a local,
non-binding vote in the hope it will spur Congress to act next
year. (Emling, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/STATEHOOD-BOX _ MIAMI _ A bullet-item box defining what each
of the three status choices for Puerto Rico means. (Emling, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   COLIN _ OXFORD, England _ This is a very literary town, with
writers of all stripes. (Campbell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ MARIETTA, Ga. _ Gingrich's last town hall meeting in
the district is scheduled for Saturday, Dec. 12. If an impeachment
vote is going on then, he may have some interesting comments,
either at the meeting or afterward. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON _ Speaker-to-be Bob Livingston speaks at Southeastern
Louisiana University, in his district, on Saturday. (Konigsmark,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LINDERYEAR _ John Linder knows a little something about pain.
The former dentist woke up Nov. 4 with the equivalent of a root
canal. He spent two years prepping for Nov. 3, when he was supposed
to lead a major expansion of the Republican majority in the House.
It didn't turn out that way, of course. Linder reflects on the
shocking turn of events that led to his mentor Newt Gingrich's exit
from Congress and Linder's return to the GOP's rank-and-file in the
House. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERRACE _ Interracial marriage, banned by the Alabama
Constitution but rendered moot by U.S. Supreme Court rulings, will
draw scrutiny during the upcoming session of the Alabama
Legislature. A Montgomery lawmaker says he'll draft a bill to kill
the statute, and the majority of those who participated in a recent
survey favored dumping the archaic legislation. But at least one
state representative says he's still opposed to interracial
marriages. In South Carolina in November, voters decided to erase a
similar ban from their state constitution. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   YAGER _ Once the out-spoken, publicity-hungry leader of a
clandestine empire established to hide the children of allegedly
abusive parents, Faye Yager is now a somewhat reclusive innkeeper
in a small mountain town in North Carolina. Yager, under increasing
pressure from a series of lawsuits and bounty hunters seeking a $2
million reward, bought a B&AMP;B in Brevard, N.C., this summer. But
trouble has followed her. Bounty hunters have harassed her and a
neighbor is suing her, claiming Yager is harassing her. (Williams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ County mutual insurance companies
for decades have provided insurance to the highest-risk drivers _
at some of the highest rates. Consumer advocates for some time,
however, have worried that county mutuals, which have unregulated
rates, are being used by their regulated affiliates, to dump good
drivers who live in low-income or minority dominated area. Now,
analysis of industry-wide data shows even people in affluent areas
of Austin are getting insurance more often through county mutuals,
where their rates could be raised without repercussion or
oversight. (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SMART-GROWTH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin won the right to hold the
second annual national Smart Growth conference on the strength of
its own Smart Growth initiative. This advances the conference and
updates local folks on the status of the city initiative. (Lindell,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-JEWS _ Guacamole gracing the Passover plate, spurs for
making unleavened bread, and peddlers selling bananas are pieces of
Texas history not generally recorded in the annals of the Mexican
territory, the Republic and the state. This is Texas' Jewish
history, which dates back to the first Spanish explorers to step
foot on the land. Now, the stories of past and present-day Jewish
families are in ``Shalom Y'all - The Jewish Experience in Texas,''
a new exhibit at the Institute of Texan Cultures in San Antonio.
The institute is part of the University of Texas. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JEWSBOX _ if you go box. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ELBERT-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ It is difficult to imagine how people
who had so little - those who were poor, retarded and isolated -
could be perceived as an ideal group to steal from, but state
officials believe that is exactly what happened in Elbert County -
for years. They allege that many of this county's most vulnerable
residents were systematically preyed upon by the very people
charged with their protection. They became vehicles for others to
attach life insurance policies to, and then collect on when they
died, sometimes of starvation and dehydration. A probe that began
here last February into allegations of insurance fraud has now
widened to include Social Security fraud, Medicaid fraud, misuse of
state funds and allegations of criminal neglect and abuse of
clients. Seven deaths are under investigation. (McCarthy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/ELBERT-STATE _ ATLANTA _ The investigation of fraud and abuse
of the mentally retarded in Elbert County is not yet complete, but
findings in the case have galvanized the state to work to fill in
some large holes in its community care network. ``If there's any
good that came out of that situation, it's the fact that it was a
wake up call to all of us,'' said Carl E. Roland, head of the
Division of Mental Health, Mental Retardation and Substance Abuse
for the Department of Human Resources. ``Going on trust and the
belief that people are going to do the best they can do, you can't
count on it. We better have some systems in place. You need
safeguards.'' (McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/ELBERT-SIS _ DECATUR, Ga. _ Ruby Lawrence Clark remembers the
Sunday evening in 1992 when Elberton resident Mary Arnold called
and said that her younger sister, Minnie Lawrence, 45, had died.
Arnold told her that Lawrence began choking on a chicken bone and
bolted from the table into a nearby field, where she died before
someone could reach her. Fact is, much of what Ruby Clark was told
was not the truth. Minnie Lawrence died after choking on a piece of
barbecued meat in the basement of Mrs. Arnold's home, where she and
two other retarded women had been left alone to eat. (Workers at
the day center Ms. Lawrence attended said they never left her alone
while easting because she had a propensity to choke). Close-up of
one case. (McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
