<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WHITEWATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE DELIBERATIONS, JUST A WHIFF OF WHITEWATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-REACT, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-FORBES, IMPEACH-REVIEW, IMPEACH-JACKSON-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-MODERATES) 
(lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee's four articles of
impeachment contain only the barest hint of the long-running
investigation into the role of President Clinton and his wife in a
complicated Arkansas real-estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   The only trace of the Whitewater investigation, almost a hidden
reference, is buried in Article III. That article, which involves
obstruction of justice, refers to allegations that Clinton tried
through his ``agents'' to find a job for Monica Lewinsky to help
secure her acquiescence in concealing their sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   That issue has nothing itself to do with Whitewater, of course,
but it is a reminder of how the investigation into the land deal
led in fits and starts to the sex-and-lies scandal that is at the
heart of the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to ``agents'' refers most prominently to Vernon
Jordan, a well-connected Washington lawyer and good friend of
Clinton. Jordan worked hard to find a job for Ms. Lewinsky in New
York City that she would find satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Article III contains the charge that beginning in December 1997
and continuing through January 1998, Clinton ``intensified and
succeeded in an effort to secure job assistance to a witness in a
federal civil rights action brought against him in order to
corruptly prevent the truthful testimony of that witness.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chief Democratic counsel, Abbe Lowell, argued at
length on Thursday that Jordan's efforts were not designed to buy
Ms. Lewinsky's silence. Rather, he contended, the job search in
which Jordan aided Ms. Lewinsky began well before she had been
subpoenaed in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, saw Jordan's efforts
in a different light. He used them as the justification for
expanding his Whitewater investigation to include the president's
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, arguing that the job help
paralleled earlier efforts by the president's allies, including
Jordan, to provide help to an important Whitewater witness, Webster
Hubbell. After he was forced to leave the Clinton administration,
Hubbell received several lucrative contracts, some with the
assistance of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has contended in court papers that Hubbell has been
concealing important information about the Clintons' involvement in
Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitewater figures only indirectly in the impeachment
articles, the other avenues of Starr's investigation are wholly
nonexistent. Starr told the Judiciary Committee last month that he
had found no wrongdoing on the part of Clinton or his wife,
Hillary, in dismissing a group of longtime employees in the White
House travel office or in the improper collection by the Clinton
White House of some 900 confidential FBI files, many of them on
prominent Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
