<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Dec. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A soaking rain will fall near the coast Sunday from southeast
Virginia to eastern Georgia as low pressure moves northeastward.
The rain will be heavy at times and will be punctuated by a few
rumbles of thunder, especially across Georgia. More intermittent
rain will occur to the west in the foothills of the Appalachians
and the Tennessee Valley as a jet stream disturbance interacts with
a flow of moist Atlantic air.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front draped from the low pressure will cross Florida on
Sunday afternoon, accompanied by lines of showers and
thunderstorms. Some of the thunderstorms will be heavy with gusty
winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance moving into the Northeast will bring little more
than high cirrus clouds to dim the sunshine over interior areas,
while ample sunshine and mild readings grace areas of eastern New
England from Maine to Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to mostly sunny conditions will occur across the Plains
and central and southern Rockies as large high pressure remains in
control. It will be unseasonably mild with temperatures approaching
record maximums of 55 to 60 degrees from central Montana to
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty onshore breezes and heavy showers will occur in the
Pacific Northwest and northern California as a vigorous cold front
moves onshore. The rain will be most persistent near the coast.
Snow levels in the Cascades will lower to around 3,500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California and the desert Southwest will be dry with a
few high clouds. Readings will be seasonably warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Season's Snow
</P>
<P>
   While sections of the Northeast are awaiting their first
measurable snow of the season, residents of Midland, Texas, had
several years' worth of snow Friday. Usually, the west Texas town
measures 4.4 inches in a typical year, but the snowstorm that
enveloped the western part of the state dumped 9.75 inches on
Midland, a 24-hour record and a new monthly record. In January
1985, nine inches fell in one month. The seasonal record of 13.9
inches, set in 1946-47, could be in jeopardy if a storm off the
West Coast takes a predicted similar path during this coming week.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
