<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY PRESIDENT TO LEAD MACARTHUR FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (lb) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, known for its
``genius'' grants, has named Jonathan Fanton, the president of the
New School, in New York, as its president.
</P>
<P>
   Fanton, who will succeed Adele Smith Simmons next September,
will earn about $400,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, based in Chicago, is one of the 10 largest in
the United States, with assets of about $4 billion and annual
spending of about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being president really fits with the things I've done all my
life,'' Fanton said in a telephone interview last week from the
foundation's headquarters in Chicago, referring to his work in
human rights, community development, education and the arts. ``It's
just a wonderful match.''
</P>
<P>
   John Corbally, MacArthur's chairman, said that the trustees had
been drawn to Fanton because of his ``deep concern for the healthy
development of communities and individuals,'' and that the board,
too, thought it was a good match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absolute agreement between his interests, his life's work
and his activities and the program activities of the foundation is
little short of amazing,'' Corbally said.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur is best known for the no-strings-attached ``genius''
grants ranging from $30,000 to $75,000 for five years. The dozens
of grants made yearly are bestowed on intellectual and creative
figures, with the focus on human and community development and
global security and growth.
</P>
<P>
   Fanton, 55, has spent his career in universities. Before moving
to the New School in 1982, he was a vice president at the
University of Chicago and associate provost at Yale, where he
earned his bachelor's degree and a doctorate in American history.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been active in a variety of foundations and nonprofit
organizations. He has been chairman of the board of Human Rights
Watch and co-chairman of its International Committee for Academic
Freedom. He is also a trustee of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund and
other foundations.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the New School, formerly the New School for
Social Research, Fanton has shaped it into a leading educator in
the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The university, which has 7,000 students, includes the Mannes
College of Music, the Parsons School of Design and the Actors
Studio School of Dramatic Arts, as well as traditional liberal arts
programs. Just last week, it announced a new partnership with the
Joffrey Ballet School that will allow students to study dance and
earn a bachelor's degree simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Under Fanton, the university's endowment has grown to $80
million from $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur seems to have a predilection for choosing college
presidents as chiefs. Ms. Simmons was president of Hampshire
College when she was chosen to lead the foundation a decade ago.
And Corbally, her predecessor as president, was president of the
University of Illinois before moving to the MacArthur helm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 1434EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
