<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MACHO MOMENTS BETWEEN A FATHER AND A SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The letters used to come by the dozens, grown men, football
fans, thanking Jim Burt for providing them the impetus and courage
to kiss their sons.
</P>
<P>
   They would tell him he had made it all right to shower a young
boy with love in public. Some would claim they had always thought
this was ``a woman's thing'' to do, a ``gay thing.'' Until they saw
Burt, a strapping nose tackle, a Super Bowl champion, handle his
5-year-old namesake as he would a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would say things like, `When we saw a macho guy like you
do it ...,''' Burt said from his Bergen County, N.J., home. ``I
remember thinking, `I can't believe this.' I couldn't believe men,
fathers, could actually think that way. I always thought the macho
thing to do was hug your kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 12 years ago, it made for poignant fourth-quarter
television, as the Giants were blowing the Denver Broncos into
Super Bowl oblivion in Pasadena, Calif. ``Take the pads off, you're
done,'' Burt recalls Coach Bill Parcells telling his core
defenders, and him thinking that if he was going to enjoy the
remainder of his defining athletic event on the sideline, his
firstborn was going to be right there with him.
</P>
<P>
   Soon little Jimmy was down on the field, slapping palms with
Lawrence Taylor, 5 yards onto the actual playing field as the game
wound down at the far end. Then he was on his father's shoulders,
which is where most of us remember him, can still picture him, even
though he is now 5 feet 11 inches, 225 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all kind of vague in my mind,'' 17-year-old Jimmy Burt
said of his wild Rose Bowl ride. ``But it's all in there,
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Materially, there is little resemblance between the teen-age
lives of father and son. Jim Burt, now 39, makes a living as the
proprietor of a limousine service, and he also has a seat on the
New York Stock Exchange. He raises two children with his wife,
Colleen, in an upscale suburb, but he grew up in Buffalo, a
blue-collar kid whose Christmas vacations were spent braving the
blustery winter aboard his father's truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a Pepsi distributorship,'' Burt said. ``My brother and
I were out there with him. We knew the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt went to the University of Miami on a football scholarship,
and his son already has a three-quarter scholarship offer to the
same school. Except the younger Burt's deal is for baseball, and
his father would rather he go someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him go to Harvard,'' Burt said, proud to say
that his son, with a 97 average and 1400 board score, is wanted in
such high academic places as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Burt is an all-state center fielder at Bergen Catholic,
where he has also anchored the football team's defense from his
linebacker position. Four years running, he has gone to school, to
practice, to the gym to lift, to the batting cage to hit. His
father could see in him a familiar determination, a common grit,
and something more, what Jim Burt called ``a work ethic four years
beyond my own maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a ball was hit, a weight was lifted, every page of
homework had to be done. ``That's my wife's influence,'' Burt said,
laughing. ``We call her the warden.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also realizes that no child can be forced to achieve at
that level if it isn't coming from deep inside. His son has
evolved. Burt has watched him make the same football hits he did,
and as good as that feels, nothing compares to the instant an
offspring's life comes sharply into focus as one that is caring,
and smart.
</P>
<P>
   And this brings Jim and Jimmy Burt to what was most likely the
boy's last football game, two Friday nights ago, a scholastic title
showdown at, of all places, Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jim Burt has relished standing on the sideline,
helping out when he could along with his former teammate, George
Martin, whose son, Aaron, has been the team's star receiver. But
football is not forever, and it isn't always the destined path for
a football player's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is the ultimate bonding game, and if he were a couple
of inches bigger, he could play at a Miami,'' Burt said. ``But he's
got his own stripes to earn. I just didn't want to see him finish
up on a sour note, after all he's put into it. I wanted him and the
other kids to have this one, so when they are 50 years old, it'll
feel like yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The way, he might have said, 1986 still feels to him.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent for Bergen Catholic that night was St. Joseph's of
Montvale, two parochial powerhouses, a rematch of last year's St.
Joe's victory. The score this time was 35-9, the result reversed,
the game essentially over by the fourth quarter, but not ending
fast enough for Jim Burt.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd of about 16,000, he sat behind the bench, near
midfield, with his wife and 9-year-old daughter, Ashley, and so
many others who knew young Jimmy when he was that wide-eyed kid
atop the Super Bowl wave. Only now he was the one celebrating on
the field. He was the one working his way up to the stands,
climbing the rail, reaching out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for everything,'' he told his father. ``Thank you so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a hug, a kiss, some tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best moment ever,'' said Jim Burt, from the other side of
a bridge he began building 12 years past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
