</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEHOOD-BOX13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A primer on Puerto Rico statehood
 &HT;    By Shelley Emling
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Population: 3.8 million; about another 2 million Puerto Ricans
live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 100 miles by 35 miles; an area smaller than Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Both Spanish and English were made official languages
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment rate: 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Governor: Pedro Rossello; took office in January 1993 and was
re-elected last year; is pro-statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Per-capita personal income: about $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Economy: Manufacturing-based; produces electronics, apparel, and
about half the prescription drugs in the United States; currency is
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Government: Puerto Rico is a self-governing commonwealth. The
chief of state is the U.S. president. The head of government is an
elected governor. There are two legislative chambers: the House of
Representatives with 51 seats and the Senate with 27 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Politics: Local parties are neither Democrat or Republican, but
instead favor statehood, independence, or commonwealth. Puerto Rico
has one non-voting representative in Congress, who is currently
Carlos Romero Barcelo. Residents can't vote in U.S. federal
elections, nor do they pay federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Puerto Rican government.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHOICES:
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's vote, Puerto Rico residents will be asked to pick
from the following options for the island's future:
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth: Puerto Rico would continue as a U.S. territory and
maintain local self-government. Puerto Ricans still wouldn't be
allowed to vote in U.S. federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Free association: Similar to the former U.S. territories of
Palau and the Marshall Islands, Puerto Rico would be considered
independent, but with some ties to the United States. For example,
Puerto Rico would use the U.S. monetary and postal systems.
</P>
<P>
   Independence: Puerto Rico would become an independent nation.
Puerto Ricans would have their own citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Statehood: Equal standing as a U.S. state with guaranteed U.S.
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
