A6649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELBERT-SIS13-COX     12-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELBERT-SIS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grieving woman left with doubts after disabled sister chokes to
death
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Ga. _ Ruby Lawrence Clark remembers the Sunday evening
in May 1992 when she says Mary Arnold of Elberton called and said
her younger sister, Minnie Lawrence, 45, had died. Clark says
Arnold told her that Lawrence, one of three mentally disabled women
living in Arnold's personal care home, began choking on a chicken
bone and bolted from the dinner table into a nearby field, where
she died before someone could reach her.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 55, owner of a DeKalb hair salon, sits in the kitchen of
her suburban split-level. ``Why couldn't they reach her?'' she
asks. ``Something wasn't right about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark is not the only one with lingering questions. Six years
after it happened, the deaths of Lawrence and six other mentally
disabled adults in Elbert County are being re-examined, said
District Attorney Bob Lavender, to determine if neglect was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Official accounts differ from Clark's memory of what she was
told. Arnold declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to coroner's records, by the time medics arrived at
Arnold's personal care home that sunny May afternoon, Lawrence was
lying on the basement floor, the hunk of beef that choked her still
lodged in her throat. Her two mentally disabled roommates were also
in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   At Quali-tech, the day rehabilitation center that Lawrence
attended, workers who remembered her said she had a disorder that
led her to try to eat inedible objects. On the rare occasion when
lunch included meat, workers said they made sure to cut Lawrence's
portion into small bites and to monitor her eating.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of Lawrence's death, coroner records say,
Arnold's adult daughter Margaret Burton told EMS workers that she
brought the women dinner _ squash, cornbread, beans and boneless
ribs _ in the basement at 3:30 and then went next door, while her
mother stayed upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   When Arnold found Lawrence in the basement, she ran and got her
daughter, who called EMS workers at 4:50 p.m., records indicate.
When they arrived a few minutes later, Lawrence had no pulse.
</P>
<P>
   According to records from the State Long-term Care Ombudsman's
Office, an advocacy agency for residents in personal care homes and
nursing homes, Arnold later told its inspector that she had sat
with the women while they were eating dinner but then had gone
upstairs for ice and returned to find Lawrence choking. She told
the inspector that she didn't know where Lawrence had gotten the
meat that choked her and that she had performed CPR.
</P>
<P>
   A photocopy of notes taken from a meeting with the Ombudsman's
Office show that center officials Lisa McKinney and Christine Wren,
along with former Region 3 Director Andrew McCollum, were among
those who met with the ombudsman. The notes say that ``Minnie
Lawrence _ did not require supervision while eating _ was allowed
to cut her own meat _ was allowed to be left unsupervised for short
periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   At Elbert Memorial Hospital, where Lawrence's body was taken,
the coroner's report said a doctor used forceps to remove from
Lawrence's trachea an inch-thick piece of meat, a little smaller
than a business card. The coroner ruled the death an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and Lawrence grew up on a Greene County farm with their
parents and five other sisters and brothers. After Clark and her
siblings left Greene County, Lawrence continued living at home in
the country. In the late 1960s, Lawrence was raped, says Clark, who
was then living in California with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my mother passed, and Minnie went into (Central State
Hospital), she was never the same again,'' Clark says. The baby
Lawrence was carrying from the rape was delivered there, but Clark
doesn't know who adopted the baby. Lawrence remained in Central
State Hospital a few years, and then lived with an aunt and uncle
in Greene County after she was released.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, relatives could no longer care for Lawrence.
She entered the residential program of the Northeast Georgia Center
and was moved to Elbert County, where she was placed in Arnold's
home.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Clark and her family were in metro Atlanta. Her
husband's heart disease and the needs of her three children kept
Clark close to home, but she says she called about her sister
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I told Mrs. Arnold I was coming to see Minnie, she'd
tell me she was going to take Minnie and the other children on a
picnic or a field trip,'' says Clark, who admits to feelings of
regret and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell her I'd just wait till another time. My husband would
tell me to go on anyway, but I just never did. Now I wish I had.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
