<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELBERT-STATE13-COX     12-12 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELBERT-STATE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `A wake-up call': Lessons learned bring about change
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELBERTON, Ga. _ The state investigation of fraud and abuse in
Elbert County is not complete, but early findings have had a
galvanizing effect on state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any good that came out of that situation, it's the
fact that it was a wake-up call,'' said Carl E. Roland, head of the
Division of Mental Health, Mental Retardation and Substance Abuse
for the Department of Human Resources. ``Going on trust and the
belief that people are going to do the best they can do, you can't
count on it. You need safeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   DHR officials say the agency is devising policies aimed at
plugging holes in the community-based care network that has
developed in recent years as the preferred alternative to hospital
care. They are also working to put into place a review procedure
for all deaths and critical incidents, such as someone falling down
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the early 1990s, Georgia was a hospital-based
system,'' Roland said. ``We could tell you if someone skinned their
knee in a hospital but not if they got run over in the community.
We've got to have a system in which we can give assurances of
monitoring people.''
</P>
<P>
   This session of the General Assembly, the agency will ask for
$750,000 to be used statewide to pay for oversight and monitoring
of developmentally disabled clients. The agency also wants to build
into service contracts a requirement that all clients be evaluated
routinely by an outside monitor.
</P>
<P>
   While applauding these changes, many in the disability community
fault the state for continuing to focus on process instead of
outcome. They say DHR has devised a system in which issues such as
infection control and checklists take precedence over quality of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say the Albany Association for Retarded Citizens
embodies a ``person-centered'' philosophy the state should seek to
replicate. A private, nonprofit agency that promotes the welfare of
the developmentally disabled and works to establish programs in
their behalf, the AARC serves 330 people in Lee, Mitchell and
Dougherty counties.
</P>
<P>
   One client is Emily Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other developmentally disabled Georgians, Wallace had
spent most of her life in institutions, moving from Bainbridge to
Milledgeville before returning to her native Dougherty County when
she was 34.
</P>
<P>
   There, she eventually moved into an AARC group home. Initially,
things didn't go well; her disrupting ``behaviors'' made her
parents think she needed to return to an institution, says AARC
Director Annette Bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling asked Wallace what she wanted and then, with her help,
drew up a step-by-step plan for attaining Wallace's goal of
independence. Wallace, 47, made steady progress: She developed the
skills needed for living in her own apartment; she fell in love;
and five years ago, she married Richard Wallace, 45, also an AARC
client.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Wallaces have their own house. Favorite videotapes
fill the den and a wedding photo hangs behind their bed. A plaque
over the kitchen table says ``Bless This Home with Happy Hearths.''
</P>
<P>
   They both travel on public transportation to their jobs. On
weekends, they may go out to dinner or to the movies. They visit
with friends and family. They're even saving for a Hawaiian
vacation, which they plan to take with Bowling and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   They reflect the philosophy driving the AARC, the Albany
Community Service Board, the Southwest Georgia Easter Seal Society
and other agencies in the Southwest Georgia Integrated Services
Network: Meet developmentally disabled people where they are and
help them get where they want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming a network client, every person needing help
first meets with a caseworker, along with a family member or
guardian, to decide appropriate services and programs. Once in the
system, clients offer criticisms or suggestions about the services
they're receiving or even ask for changes. One AARC client was
instrumental in having an employee fired, Bowling said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Albany CSB, the AARC offers various residential
possibilities, including group homes, semi-independent and
dependent apartment living, care provider homes _ in which a client
lives with a family _ and personal support homes. The organization,
which has a $1.5 million budget, owns two apartment complexes and
uses special funds to help clients, like the Wallaces, buy their
own homes.
</P>
<P>
   The AARC's policy-making board has numerous safeguards to
prevent problems from developing. Clients call Bowling or her
second-in-command, Kay Hiedt, at home, any time. Case managers
visit clients in their homes three or four times a week, offering
comments and suggestions, just as clients do. Members of the AARC
board also drop in, unannounced, throughout the day and evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to have as many different eyes as possible looking at
things,'' Bowling says. ``We don't want to miss anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
