<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBILE13-COX     12-12 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBILE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quirky Mobile flexes its political muscle in Alabama
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Quirky compared to the rest of Alabama _ there are
Catholics and Mardi Gras here _ the Gulf Coast city of Mobile long
has been the state's political doormat.
</P>
<P>
   But after November's general election, the Port City seems more
like the Capital City. Mobile is hometown to Gov.-elect Don
Siegelman, Lt. Gov.-elect Steve Windom, Attorney General Bill Pryor
and Congressman Sonny Callahan, an assistant of incoming U.S. House
Speaker Bob Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new position for a city more akin to New Orleans than
Birmingham or Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unprecedented to have Mobile play the role it is now _
even during the antebellum period,'' said Wayne Flynt, a history
professor at Auburn University. ``It's certainly meaningful. It
would be like if Georgia politics were dominated by Savannah.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1860s, Mobile was the third largest port in the country,
behind New York and New Orleans, Flynt said. But railroad
construction the next 20 years shifted the economic and political
power base north to Birmingham and Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   That left Mobile something of a ``backwater'' town, said Flynt,
though the city re-emerged as a political participant _ but not a
significant player _ after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the city has struggled to claim its share of the
state budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobile in past years has not been progressive in moving itself
toward the center of the state and not being part of north Alabama.
Now, we're at the state table'' said Mobile Mayor Mike Dow, who has
overseen the construction of a new civic center and helped direct
the revitalization of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most ardent political debates every year in the state
Legislature swirls around highway funding, and Mobile nearly always
comes up short, said Scott Posey, government liaison with the
Mobile Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a little bit of isolationists as far as
government and politicians,'' Posey said. ``We've kind of kept to
ourselves and that's hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an Old South city, and like any Old South City, Mobile
wasn't big on change and didn't involve itself in a lot of the
debates over public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before rail lines, interstates and the Internet, Mobile might as
well have been four weeks away from Birmingham, not four hours.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Chris Pringle, a Mobile Republican and the former
minority leader in the state House, said the old joke with
lawmakers in his delegation is that from Mobile ``it takes two
hours to get to Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   But with transportation and communications growth, Mobile isn't
as far flung as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regionalism used to be a huge factor,'' said Gerald Johnson, a
former political science professor and currently a pollster for the
Alabama Education Association. ``But generally, regionalism has
lost its defining power.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobile state legislators will try to capitalize on having
friends in high places by pushing for public funding for the
Alabama State Docks, headquartered on Mobile Bay. Dedicated in
1928, the self-sustaining port generates annual revenue of roughly
$58 million _ including a profit totaling $13.5 million the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Gulf Coast, Alabama is the only state that does not
fund its port facilities, which are aging and need new construction
to keep up with places like Galveston, Texas, New Orleans and
Biloxi, Miss. The Alabama docks are run by annual revenue and a
combination of general obligation and revenue bonds. The facility
receives no money from the annual state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The docks, a key to the economy throughout the state and not
just Mobile, are near their annual debt ceiling at $12 million to
$15 million a year. The last general obligation bond was passed in
1990 for warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Bills that would secure state funding for new warehouses and
cranes are certain to be introduced in the March session of the
state Legislature. ``With the number of people from Mobile in
office, hopefully it will improve our chances,'' said Pringle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
