<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-STRESS-KAN &LR;      12-12 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-STRESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRESSORS ABOUND, MAKING CHRISTMAS THE SEASON TO BE ANXIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Deck the halls with boughs of holly
</P>
<P>
   E-mail, voice mail, laptops and telecommuting lengthen work days
and make it possible to never leave work, reports the Conference
Board, a business research organization.
</P>
<P>
   'Tis the season to be jolly
</P>
<P>
   ``The added stress of holiday activities tips the balance of an
already busy lifestyle,'' says Betsy Vander Velde, president of
Heart of America Family Services, whose counselors are hearing more
clients complain of ``trying to do too much'' and encountering more
cases of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Don we now our gay apparel
</P>
<P>
   Cookie baking. Shopping. Parties. Shopping. School pageants.
Shopping. A British study this year found that men's (not women's)
stress levels soared _ sometimes to levels found in fighter pilots
and police officers in danger _ after battling crowds of shoppers,
long lines and gift decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Troll the ancient Yuletide carol
</P>
<P>
   Layoff notices (instead of greeting cards) are going to
thousands of merger and downsizing victims around the country. The
fourth quarter is a traditional employee-layoff time as companies
prepare for new budget years, according to Richard Ornce, managing
director of Human Resource Management Corp. of Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Fa la la la la la la la la
</P>
<P>
   Even people who are determined to hum through the holidays may
encounter stress at events as ``innocent'' as office parties.
Excess alcohol consumption, inappropriate sexual or aggressive
behavior, loose lips, even car accidents from drunk driving, can
have nasty boomerang effects, notes Sondra Meyer Raile, a human
resource consultant in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the sometimes awkward assemblage of family members
who _ for most of the rest of the year _ may have little to do with
each other. Archie Bunker and Meathead had nothing over some real
families, whose holiday dinner tables are marred by squabbles or
skittishness.
</P>
<P>
   As surely as ``Jingle Bells'' blares from mall sound systems,
stress shifts into higher gear for the holidays. But authorities
say tensions can be managed by planning ahead, organizing time
well, staying flexible, keeping good humor and having a clear
understanding that no one _ not even Super Mom _ can do everything.
</P>
<P>
   Some people try to ``do it all'' and feel resentful of those who
don't, notes Christine McAtee, a counselor at Heart of America
Family Services. These doers need help to set priorities, delegate
and relax, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Stress experts also recommend eating healthily, exercising,
taking private-time or meditation breaks and getting enough sleep.
And, they emphasize, be sure not to blow the budget.
</P>
<P>
   For many, that's easier said than done, particularly if
job-related setbacks, such as layoffs, are working double-time to
challenge self esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees who are laid off should not blame themselves _ or
anyone else _ for losing their jobs,'' Ornce advises.
Fourth-quarter layoffs often are due to business restructuring and
aren't a reflection of individual performance or capabilities, he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that won't make it easier to wear a happy holiday face,
but it may minimize the chance of being debilitated by depression
or stress.
</P>
<P>
   The American Institute of Stress in Yonkers, N.Y., monitors
different stressors according to the Holmes-Rahe scale, which
measures the magnitude of events. The stress of Christmas ranks as
high or higher than the stress of getting a speeding ticket, says
Paul J. Rosch, stress institute president.
</P>
<P>
   Recent research suggests, though, that the holiday itself might
not be the stress agent. The stress institute notes other
contributors:
</P>
<P>
   - Shorter daylight hours. The shortest day of the year falls
just a few days before Christmas. Less daylight contributes to
seasonal affective disorder, a cause of depression.
</P>
<P>
   - Overindulgence. Eating more or richer foods than usual at
parties, coupled with getting less exercise than usual because of
time or weather constraints, may contribute to ``holiday heart
syndrome,'' episodes of abnormal rhythms that tend to follow eating
or drinking sprees.
</P>
<P>
   - Altered sleep patterns. Heavy drinking, late-night parties or
gift-wrapping sessions may cause sleep deprivation that, in some
cases, manifests itself in headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The stress institute's publications also suggest that holiday
stress, sometimes called the ``holiday blues,'' could be a fairly
recent media fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1974, the Readers Guide to Periodical Literature did not
list a single article related to holiday depression,'' one of the
institute's newsletters notes. ``However, 10 years later, so many
had appeared that a separate subject heading for this had to be
created.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute for Healthcare Research issued a news
release this week stating that ``recent studies have shown that
spirituality can be a factor in the holiday blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosch, the stress institute president who also is a clinical
professor of medicine and psychiatry at New York Medical College,
notes, though, ``Although most research shows that religiosity and
strong faith are powerful stress buffers that can relieve
depression, other reports indicate that it can have the reverse
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Only partly in jest, the stress institute recommends that if the
holidays seem overwhelming, one might chuck tradition and
``consider taking a vacation to some sunny climate'' instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
