<HEADLINE>
TALKS PROGRESS BETWEEN TWA, MACHINISTS UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Trans World Airlines on Friday reported progress in
federally mediated contract talks with its union Machinists, but
they have not yet reached a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to return to the negotiating table,'' said Jim
Martin, the TWA executive leading the airline's negotiators at the
talks in Florida. The latest round of talks began Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But union negotiators think no real progress was made, said
Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650 in Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing bulletins that union negotiators provided to union
leaders around the country indicate that the airline continues to
seek wage and other concessions that workers are unwilling to give,
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely frustrating for our people,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped federal mediators would approve a 30-day
countdown to a potential strike instead of another round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, nothing is resolved until the last minute of the
last hour of the last day of the countdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal mediators Friday did not indicate whether or when talks
would resume.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union represents about 16,200 mechanics,
passenger service employees and flight attendants in TWA's
22,000-member work force.
</P>
<P>
   TWA said that during this month's talks in Florida, the airline
and the Machinists reached a tentative agreement on more than 30
issues affecting mechanics and passenger service employees, but
none on issues affecting the airline's flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the airline offered employees a package that
included wage increases designed to lift TWA employees to 90
percent of industry parity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offers were similar in scope to the pilots' contract that
was ratified Aug. 31,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   That four-year settlement with the TWA unit of the Air Line
Pilots Association boosted pilots' wages to 90 percent of the
industry average from 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Machinists said at the time that they would not accept
a contract bringing their pay to 90 percent of the industry
average.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis-based carrier this week moved to upgrade its fleet
by ordering 125 new jets in the largest aircraft order in its
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
