<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED REGULATIONS WOULD PUSH BANKERS INTO ROLE OF BIG BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The face of tyranny takes many forms. Its latest is a
set of proposed federal banking regulations innocuously
characterized as ``Know Your Customers'' rules.
</P>
<P>
   It's an article of faith among those who value what America
stands for that there cannot be political freedom without economic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   This regulatory proposal is offered as a means to further crack
down on money-laundering criminals involved in the drug trade and
other illegal activities generating substantial amounts of cash.
What it is, in effect, is yet another attempt by the federal
government to transform private enterprises into Orwellian Big
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators in general and the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. in particular are reportedly being deluged with letters from
angry citizens protesting this threat to their financial privacy.
Their fears are well-founded because forcing bankers to become
undercover agents propels this society further down a slippery
slope that already invests too much power in governments.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the regulation is that it expands significantly
the types of private transactions that banks must report to federal
regulators. It calls for banks to determine customers sources of
funds, ``determine, understand and monitor normal and expected
transactions,'' and report any ``unusual and inconsistent''
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Such mandates are so ambiguous that banks may find themselves
disposed to report customers for even the slightest deviation from
normal activity just to stay on the safe side of the feds. In other
words, it makes bankers and their customers adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of such dangers, the proposed rules also require
banks to let federal regulators see private financial records
within 48 hours of a request, even without a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   This is the American way? Is it healthy for a democratic
republic to allow governments this sort of latitude to pry into the
financial affairs of its citizens? It would be difficult to justify
such power even if it were proved to be effective in fighting
society's most heinous criminals. Unfortunately, such expansions of
power have sometimes been found to be more a problem than a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Using banks as Big Brother has been typified in the past by
forcing them to report transactions of $10,000 or more. The
problem, as it usually is with one-size-fits-all regulation, was
the unmanageable volume of reports that mostly go unexamined.
</P>
<P>
   Author James Bovard, a prominent libertarian theoretician, noted
an example of how such laws backfire in a recent Investor's
Business Daily analysis of the issue. The CIA
employee-turned-traitor Aldrich Ames went undetected, Bovard said,
despite regularly receiving wire transfers of $50,000 and more from
his communist masters in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Although the spy's banks notified regulators of his
suspicious activity, the warnings were apparently overlooked
because the feds were distracted by the mountains of minutiae
created by the mass of routine Currency Transaction Reports.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here is that such laws not only are hazardous to
political and economic freedom, but also often impede rather than
enhance efforts to protect Americans from the real bad guys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 1704EST &QL; 
