<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDERNESS13-COX     12-12 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDERNESS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers' wilderness proposal falls outside her district
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ U.S. Rep. Diana DeGette (D-Denver) is
writing legislation that would create as much as 1.4 million acres
of lower-elevation wilderness in Colorado _ none of which is within
her district.
</P>
<P>
   Third District Congressman Scott McInnis (R-Grand Junction),
whose district includes most of the lands in question, said he
hasn't been contacted by DeGette about her proposed bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which DeGette expects to introduce early next
year, could include Black Ridge Canyons Wilderness Study Area west
of Grand Junction. Two areas the U.S. Bureau of Land Management
will survey again this summer to determine if they have wilderness
attributes, Bangs Canyon and South Shale Ridge, could also be
included in the bill, said Jamin Spitzer, an aide to DeGette.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, geographically (Colorado) is a large state, but
politically it is a small state,'' Spitzer said. ``In a small state
like Colorado, in terms of clout in Washington D.C., No. 1, you
work together and No. 2, you think about the impacts on all of
Colorado. Diana has a undying love for the state. Her dedication
and love isn't restricted to the political boundaries of the First
Congressional District.''
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said he doesn't know the details of DeGette's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their office has been very secretive about it,'' McInnis said.
``We can't get the details. We can't get them to tell us they will
do it. One of the courtesies of Congress is when you have a bill as
dramatic as what she would do, and it has tremendous consequences,
the thing is you extend the courtesy to the congressman whose
district it is in. None is in her district. In fact, it is a
playground for her district.''
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of wilderness involving mostly BLM lands has
been controversial for many years. Several areas, including Black
Ridge, have already been designated as wilderness study. An area
designated as wilderness study is one awaiting congressional action
designating it as wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The BLM a month ago decided it wanted to restudy three areas in
western Colorado next summer to determine if those areas meet the
criteria necessary for consideration as wilderness study.
Vermillion Basin in the northwest corner of the state, Bangs Canyon
and South Shale Ridge will be part of that review.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness is the strictest public-use classification of public
lands. Hunting and grazing are allowed in wilderness areas, but
off-highway vehicles, mountain bicycles, timber cutting and mineral
extraction are prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, for an area to be declared as wilderness, it
must meet the following criteria:
</P>
<P>
   _ It must be without permanent improvements or human habitation.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must be affected primarily by forces of nature, with the
imprint of man's work substantially unnoticeable.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must offer outstanding opportunities for solitude or a
primitive and unconfined type of recreation.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must have have at least 5,000 acres of land or be of
sufficient size as to make practicable its preservation and use in
an unimpaired condition.
</P>
<P>
   It may also contain ecological, geological, or other features of
scientific, educational, scenic, or historical value.
</P>
<P>
   Other areas near Grand Junction that could be included in
DeGette's bill include Sewemup Mesa, Dominguez Canyon, Dolores
River Canyon, Gunnison Gorge, Hunter Canyon, Demaree Canyon, the
Adobe Badlands and Little Bookcliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado currently has no designated wilderness below 9,000 feet
in elevation, according to the Montrose-based Western Colorado
Congress. The environmental group is part of the Colorado
Wilderness Network, an ad-hoc association of several environmental
groups working on the wilderness proposal.
</P>
<P>
   DeGette's work is based in part on a Colorado conservationists'
wilderness proposal floated in 1994, said Pete Kolbenschlag, Grand
Junction representative for the Colorado Environmental Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The conservationists' proposal spurred the BLM to do a roadless
inventory of BLM lands in Western Colorado that resulted in the
federal agency agreeing this fall to re-study Bangs Canyon, South
Shale Ridge and Vermillion Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Public comments submitted to the BLM about that review indicated
1,661 Coloradans favoring more protection with 660 against,
Kolbenschlag said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the activity and what we think to be tremendous
public support for our proposal, we thought it a good time to see
if anyone is interested in introducing legislation,'' Kolbenschlag
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Udall, a Boulder Democrat who was elected in November to
succeed retiring U.S. Rep. David Skaggs (D-Boulder), is interested
in the bill, as well, Kolbenschlag said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said DeGette has studied the issue for some time. He
said she is interested in finding a way to protect the remaining
wilderness-applicable lands before they are all gone.
</P>
<P>
   DeGette has been contacted by environmentalists, ranchers and
hunters who have all felt that without a comprehensive plan, the
state could lose the rest of its potential wilderness, Spitzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vital to put as much work in the front end to figure out
a good strategy and a good starting point for discussion,'' Spitzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis, though, said he is concerned that DeGette, while a
capable legislator, may not have sufficient knowledge of Western
Slope issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her bill will have a dramatic impact. I don't want to
underestimate, if it passes, it will have a dramatic impact on the
lifestyles of the Third Congressional District,'' McInnis said.
Those range from community economics and recreation to state and
federal water issues.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said at this point the map DeGette is using is in flux.
He said DeGette intends to continue discussions with people in
western Colorado, around Colorado and nationally before she drafts
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said she might want to take note of the way Skaggs
approached a wilderness proposal in McInnis' district. McInnis said
Skaggs' staff spent time working with McInnis on submitting a bill
to create the Spanish Peaks Wilderness in southern Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to my colleague, she has very limited
experience in any of those fields,'' McInnis said. ``I'd be happy
at any point in time to sit down and talk about water, for
instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
