<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH13-COX     12-12 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judiciary approves fourth impeachment article
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting the stage for a momentous showdown in the
House of Representatives this week, the House Judiciary Committe
adopted a fourth article of impeachment Saturday against President
Clinton and was poised to reject a Democratic proposal to censure
the president instead.
</P>
<P>
   A rare Saturday session lasted all day as the committee's
Republicans and Democrats kept up their robust, intensely partisan
debate on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   With their work nearly finished and the debate on impeachment in
the closely divided House set to begin Thursday, committee members
grappled with the potential impact of impeachment if, as it
appears, the Senate would be unlikely to remove Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether any of the four articles calling for
Clinton's impeachment for perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse
of power will pass the House. They all relate to Clinton's affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and the president's
efforts to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans sought to assure the public and their colleagues
that a vote for impeachment does not equal a vote for Clinton's
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, seeking to build support for the lesser punishment of
censure, criticized Republicans for cavalierly voting for
impeachment, knowing that the Senate most likely will not convict
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Coble (R-N.C.), however, drew bipartisan praise for
his assessment of the gravity of the upcoming votes on the
president's fate. ``I'll have knots in my gut next week when we
cast votes,'' Coble said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could become the second U.S. president to be impeached.
Andrew Johnson survived a trial in the Senate by one vote in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the Judiciary Committee voted three articles of
impeachment against President Nixon, who resigned his office before
the House could act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was out of the country, en route to Israel aboard Air
Force One, when the committee's 21 Republicans voted for a
watered-down article of impeachment that charges Clinton with
abusing his office. All 16 Democrats opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, a White House lawyer, gave a stinging statement
of rebuttal: Impeachment, he said, will ``divide the country,
gridlock the government and defy the will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prediction that Republicans may pay a political price for
their actions, he added, ``in the end, the American people will
make the final judgment about whether the impeachment of the
president is in the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth impeachment article stemmed from what it called
``perjurious, false and misleading sworn statements'' Clinton made
in his written response to 81 questions posed by Republican
committee investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) called those answers ``an assault on
the Congress'' in justifying a vote for a separate article of
impeachment, rather than including the charge in one of the two
articles on perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans stripped from the abuse of power article allegations
that Clinton merited impeachment because he lied to the public and
to his aides, and because he invoked the legal doctrine of
executive privilege in a bid to keep several close advisors from
testifying to a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.) said the Republicans' willingness to
weaken the article demonstrated a judiciousness that Democrats have
said has been lacking.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee Democrats viewed the deletion of the
provisions, proposed just three days ago, as a transparent
political tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an orchestrated dance in order to create an illusion of
respectability,'' Rep. Howard Berman (D-Calif.) said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans mounted a similar argument to explain their
opposition to the Democratic censure resolution, a formal rebuke of
Clinton that would be less severe than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   With the defeat of the censure option a forgone conclusion in
the committee, Democrats targeted their remarks to winning the day
on the only unresolved issue before the full House: convincing Rep.
Bob Livingston (R-La.), virtually certain to succeed Newt Gingrich
as speaker, and other GOP leaders to permit a censure vote on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would plead with Mr. Livingston, do not force the House to
choose between two unpalatable options, impeachment or nothing,''
said Rep. Charles Schumer (D-N.Y.). ``Please ... allow a censure
resolution ... and let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt also sought to raise the
political stakes, urging Livingston in a letter to permit a censure
vote when the issue reaches the floor. ``Your decision ... will
decide whether or not history will mark our actions as a purely
political exercise or a high-minded debate on the impeachment of a
president,'' Gephardt wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At home in Louisiana, Livingston told reporters, ``'Frankly we
haven't decided yet.'' But, according to the New York Times, when
asked if he would allow the full House to vote on censure even if
the Judiciary Committee voted against it, Livingston said: ``Not
very likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he would leave the decision to Livingston and
other Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans on the Judiciary Committee roundly denounced the
censure option, either because they believed it was
unconstitutional or because it was too lenient a punishment of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's similar to yelling at a teen-ager,'' said Hyde. ``It
purges you of some of your feelings, but I don't see what it
accomplishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also argued that Republicans do not want to consider
the censure so that fence-sitting GOP moderates would feel
pressured to choose impeachment rather than no punishment at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country will not accept a partisan solution to this
matter,'' said Rep. Thomas Barrett (D-Wis.). ``It will show only
that we are divided.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one U.S. president, Andrew Jackson, has been censured. The
Senate censured Jackson in 1834, but expunged it from its record in
1837, by which time Jackson's Democrats had regained their
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats warned that an impeachment trial in the Senate
next year would snarl the business of the Congress for many months,
arguing that a bi-partisan censure resolution was the fastest way
to condemn the president and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject the notion that an impeachment trial will tie up the
Senate for months and months,'' said Rep. Charles Canady (R-Fla.).
``Such tactics are scare tactics ... designed to scare us away from
our constitutional duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats even held up one of the GOP's own to make their case.
Schumer noted that Gingrich was found by the House ethics committee
to have made false statements under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet I didn't hear a single member from the other party
call for Mr. Gingrich's removal from office,'' Schumer said. ``I
would remind my colleagues again to be fair and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
