u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DNA-POLICE-700&AMP;ADD     12-12 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DNA-POLICE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE COMMISSIONER WANTS DNA FROM ALL ARRESTED PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With violent crime down sharply, Police Commissioner
Howard Safir has proposed taking DNA samples from everyone arrested
in New York City _ from subway turnstile jumpers on up _ so that
police can use new technology to lock up career criminals like
burglars and car thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Under Safir's plan, police would take a saliva sample from
anyone who is fingerprinted after an arrest. The sample would be
tested and loaded into a database at an estimated cost of $50 per
person. A suspect's DNA record would be expunged if there were no
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking myself how am I going to continue to reduce
crime,'' Safir said in an interview, noting that the homicide rate
this year is expected to be the lowest since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he said, was in focusing on crimes against property,
like burglary and auto theft, which are usually committed by career
criminals. Thus, arrests in such cases might also clear past
unsolved crimes and prevent new ones, and DNA evidence could prove
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   A professional burglar or car thief, for instance, might leave
skin or sweat cells when forcing open a door or window. ``As long
as there's one cell,'' Safir said, ``you could use this to help
solve just about any crime you could think of.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, who publicly proposed the DNA testing plan
earlier this month, is to describe it in a speech Monday at the
Bronx High School of Science.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would require state legislation to expand the
circumstances under which DNA testing is allowed. Under current
law, police take DNA samples from people convicted of certain major
felonies, primarily crimes like murder or rape. The data is sent to
a state databank.
</P>
<P>
   Every state has some kind of databank of convicted felons' DNA
and, in October, the FBI, after nearly a decade of preparation,
opened a national database linking the state systems. To date, only
Louisiana takes samples from everyone charged with a crime,
although South Dakota has authorized a similar program.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, DNA, the material in human cells that records each
person's genetic inheritance, has been used primarily to identify
positively a suspect already in custody or to eliminate a suspect
or clear someone wrongly convicted. It has been used mainly in such
violent crimes as murder or rape, when a criminal leaves blood or
semen on a victim or crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say the rapidly developing science could be used
more aggressively to establish a pattern of crimes or to tie
someone arrested for one crime to others committed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is based on an extensive system developed over the
last five years in Britain. Officials there say the system has led
to a marked increase in solving crimes, particularly burglaries.
Like police practice here of staking out subway stations to arrest
fare beaters who often turn out to be wanted on other charges, the
system in Britain is based on the idea that people who commit big
crimes, particularly career criminals, are also likely to commit
small crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain has less of a tradition of civil liberties than the
United States, and Safir's plan is certain to draw objections.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Safir said he was making his proposal public precisely
because ``this needs a lot of discussion and debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
said he would oppose the plan as violating the Constitution's
Fourth Amendment protection against unreasonable search and
seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's plan grew out of a series of meetings he had
with Barry Scheck, a lawyer who is a leading expert on the use of
DNA evidence and who took part in the defense of O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   But Scheck, who sits on the state's new Forensic Science Review
Board, which regulates crime labs, said he disagreed with the
commissioner's plan on a number of grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck described Louisiana's testing of all those who are
arrested as a ``logistical nightmare'' and suggested it was simply
impractical under current conditions to do the same thing in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an unreasonable idea,'' he said. ``I just don't think
its time has come.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Instead, Scheck said, the city's police should ``front-load the
system'' with more limited initiatives involving new DNA technology
to solve old crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he said, the evidence in unsolved rape cases was
routinely thrown away after five years. This practice should be
stopped, he said. Evidence from all unsolved rapes should be tested
for DNA and there should be an emphasis on checking for DNA
evidence in all rape and homicide cases, he said. The department's
Cold Case Squad, Scheck said, should re-examine all old homicide
cases for DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Scheck said, a pilot program should be set up to
train a special burglary detective squad in DNA evidence-gathering
to see if it would result in more arrests and cleared cases.
</P>
<P>
   Although Safir favors the broader DNA testing program, he agreed
with Scheck's more modest initiatives, Scheck said, and delegated
his deputy commissioner for operations, Edward Norris, to look into
putting them into effect.
</P>
<P>
   A major barrier to expanded use of DNA is the cost of equipment,
training and additional personnel. When the Police Department built
a new $30 million crime lab in Queens, the state regulatory board
on which Scheck sits required another $30 million in improvements
for DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel of the Civil Liberties Union argued against a broad
program of DNA testing. ``They're using the DNA sampling for some
future event,'' he said. ``The information they will be receiving
is much more personal and private, including your genetic makeup,
than fingerprints.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that in one case in Massachusetts, courts had held that
the involuntary taking of DNA samples from prisoners, those on
probation and those on parole was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he had just been invited to debate Safir on the DNA
question at a state law enforcement conference in February, Siegel
vowed to ``make this a high priority research project.''
</P>
<P>
   The police commissioner was unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman is my reality check,'' he said. ``Any time he agrees
with me, I know I'm wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
