<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livingston appears ready to let process go forward
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, La. _ Bob Livingston, the presumptive speaker of the
House, told graduates of Southeastern Louisiana University Saturday
to move forward and leave past mistakes behind. But he didn't
appear ready to leave behind President Clinton's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Before giving the commencement speech, Livingston told reporters
that Clinton's public apology Friday didn't make him feel
differently about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate it won't make a great deal of difference (for
me),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston repeated earlier statements that he will not make any
decisions about how the full House of Representatives will proceed
with impeachment until the House Judiciary Committee finishes
voting on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he wished Clinton would do something in addition
to Friday's apology to affect the process, he said, ``The president
has his own actions to justify. I will not seek to give him counsel
at this late date.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's speech to the 961 graduates of this university an
hour north of New Orleans was full of self-deprecating stories of
his own mediocrity. He attributed his ascent to the third-most
powerful position in the country to good luck and a good mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not to the manner born, I was not gifted with athletic
skills, and I was not gifted with scholarly skills, to put it
mildly,'' he said. ``But I learned from my mother to work hard for
what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a good politician is just ``an average person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a person who holds a high office who is without .
. . some degree of human frailness,'' he said. ``A good politician
not only accepts that but revels in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before mounting the podium to give the commencement address,
Livingston paid a visit to the ``Golden Graduates,'' alumni who
graduated 50 years ago or more. They warmly welcomed him with
applause and said, ``We're so proud of you'' and, ``We're behind
you'' as he worked the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my man,'' said W.E. Wild, Class of 1936. Wild said he
thinks Livingston is right to remain silent on the impeachment
issue for now. He also believes Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a good president, but I think the law should apply
the same to him as to everyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Tillis, a 34-year-old graduate in the nursing school, has
no doubts about what should happen to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should he be impeached?'' she said. ``Yes, he lied.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
