<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAGER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No safe haven for Faye Yager
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREVARD, N.C. _ Like a lot of people in this mountain town known
for waterfalls and white squirrels, Faye Yager came for the quiet.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Yager was known throughout metro Atlanta
as the operator of a network of safe houses that hid women and
children from allegedly abusive fathers.
</P>
<P>
   She has given up the clandestine enterprise of sheltering
fugitives for the commercial enterprise of sheltering tourists, as
operator of The Inn at Brevard. Yager has told people she left
behind the Children of the Underground when she left her home in
Sandy Springs, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   But hometown troubles have followed Yager to North Carolina.
Bounty hunters chasing the $2 million reward announced a year ago
by Philadelphia millionaire Bipin Shah for the return of his
children continue to harass Yager, according to a report she has
filed with local police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watch me. They come into the hotel. They threaten my life
and, worse, they terrorize my children,'' Yager said this month.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the trouble she stirred up after moving in
only five months ago: Yager is being sued by her next-door neighbor
for blocking access to a shared alleyway.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking to start over, Brevard is a pleasant place to
do so. The town of 7,000 sits next to the Pisgah National Forest, a
deep green preserve where trout streams and black bear meander.
</P>
<P>
   Brevard College, a small liberal arts school, and Brevard Music
Center offer cultural diversions not generally found in a town this
size. Fed with the money of college students, tourists and affluent
retirees, the downtown hums, despite a nearby Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The Inn at Brevard _ purchased by Yager's husband, Howard, in
July for $695,000 _ was built in 1885 as a private home. The house
was converted to an inn in the 1940s. The inn now includes five
rooms in the main house and an adjacent lodge with 10 rooms. The
first floor of the main house is a series of dining rooms, each
currently decorated with a ceiling-scraping Christmas tree, that
seat a total of 150-or-so patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Yager appears to be a hands-on innkeeper, stopping by the
Bracken Mountain Bakery on South Broad Street for bags and bags of
fresh bread and baking coconut cakes _ mighty fine coconut cakes _
for dinner dessert.
</P>
<P>
   She is simply trying to run a business, she said while scurrying
to load a van with equipment for a catered luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing the best I can to survive Mr. Shah,'' Yager said,
declining to sit still for a lengthy, formal interview. Yager has
told magazine and television reporters that she helped Shah's
ex-wife, Ellen Dever, vanish in June 1997 with Sarah, now 9, and
Genevieve, now 7, despite the fact that no one had accused Shah of
harming the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he takes every single thing I have,'' she
said. ``He can take everything I have, but he can't take my soul
and he can't take me from my husband. He can take everything. I
don't care about money. I'm not a money freak like him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bipin Shah, the man who has put the price on the return of
his two daughters, said it's not money he is after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in taking her bed-and-breakfast or her
assets,'' Shah said. ``I want my children back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dever claimed Shah battered her, and Yager has likened Dever's
situation to that of Nicole Brown Simpson. No one, not even Dever,
has accused Shah of harming his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Shah, who made millions developing electronic banking systems,
learned of Yager's involvement in the disappearance of his children
on Dec. 18, 1997, just as the news conference announcing the $2
million reward was breaking up. He has been after her ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he filed a $100 million lawsuit against Yager in
federal court in Atlanta. The lawsuit, Shah said earlier this year,
is an essential element in his strategy to find his children. It
allows Shah to subpoena telephone and airline records and other
pieces of a paper trail that might lead to Dever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second thing it did was what I call `bleeding' Faye Yager
financially,'' Shah said this summer. ``If you're bleeding you'll
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager on Thursday told a federal court judge she had dismissed
the attorney defending her against Shah because she no longer can
afford to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence gathered for Shah's civil suit is also passed on to a
federal grand jury in Philadelphia that is investigating Yager's
role in aiding Dever. A federal arrest warrant has been issued for
Dever, charging her with unlawful flight to avoid prosecution for
concealment of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Shah said he feels sure Yager still has contact with his
ex-wife, and it is important to keep track of Yager and her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get as much intelligence as we can on what
the Yagers are doing so that it leads us to my children,'' Shah
said last week. ``They are our connection to my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager claimed Shah has used illegal wiretaps to gather
information, a charge Shah denied.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Shah's lawsuit, the Yagers are being sued for $80
million by a Connecticut man whose ex-wife disappeared with their
son in September 1997. The Yagers also are being sued by Henri and
Dennis Minick, who live next to The Inn at Brevard.
</P>
<P>
   The inn shares a 10-foot driveway with the Minicks, according to
the suit filed in Transylvania County civil court in November. The
suit states that when Henri Minick tried talking to Faye Yager
about the driveway shortly after Yager took over the inn, she was
rebuffed ``and has continued to be rebuffed and confronted in a
belligerent and aggressive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the suit states, Faye Yager came to the Minick home
at 10 p.m. one night in October ``and in a loud and boisterous
manner, confronted (Minick), repeating her threats to close the
alley.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing in the Brevard lawsuit is scheduled for later this
week. Faye Yager also is expected to appear in federal court in
Atlanta on Monday for a hearing regarding the Shah suit.
</P>
<P>
   Life for Faye Yager, even in the mountains, is anything but
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
