<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MUST STILL PROVE THEY'RE WORTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After bad football _ actually, it was disgraceful football _
life is still good if you're the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday night, at a charity Christmas auction in Arlington,
a Chan Gailey autographed football sold for the top bid of the
evening _ $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours earlier in New Orleans, Gailey's team had given a
performance best described as clueless, gutless and heartless.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys actually had beaten what was supposed to be an
inferior foe, then what would have been the bid in Arlington?
</P>
<P>
   Four days after the New Orleans crash, Jerry Jones was appearing
before the Irving City Council. He was also dealing. For a mere $15
million, five-year contract, Jerry offered to cut in Irving on his
corporate sponsorship package.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Irving tax dollars built Texas Stadium. Jones
holds the lease, but nowhere in the fine print does the city have
any advertising rights. Unless, of course, Irving meets a certain
price. And apparently, Irving will.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jerry threw in a discount after the Bourbon Street
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the Cowboys absolutely can't sell is another
mindless effort like the last one. There is no lower form of jock
life than a team that simply mails in a game, and with postage due.
This was, however, the Cowboys last week.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, this was also the Cowboys all of last December. They
quit.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact it happened on the Gailey watch was both shocking
and disturbing. What had been a good overall season, particularly
when you factor in a multitude of injuries, suddenly has a large
cloud hovering over Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Do these people even care enough to care anymore?
</P>
<P>
   There won't be a long wait for the answer. Keep a close watch on
today in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Cowboys don't have to win this game to prove anything.
Instead, their criteria is very elementary, and also something that
by now should be totally unnecessary. Is this a team that will show
up in the proper frame of mind? In other words, just be prepared to
play hard, OK?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like our season came to an end because we had one bad
game on offense,'' said Gailey at midweek.
</P>
<P>
   But Chan, is that all it was? Merely one bad game on offense?
There seemed to be more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that New Orleans was anything beyond what Chan
said,'' noted Jones on Friday. ``I didn't see a lack of effort or
heart. I really didn't. What I saw was a frustration level that
kept building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did underestimate some things last week _ like the extent
of hostility the Saints would bring. I'm as guilty as anyone of
that. I didn't think we'd see what we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Gailey's halftime message, with the Cowboys down,
19-3, was ``let's go out, start running the football, that will
open up everything else, and we can win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it took us like seven minutes to get the ball back (to
open the third quarter),'' said Jones. ``When we did nothing, what
continued was a loss of confidence. We had come to expect this
offense to put up points. As we struggled to do that, our
confidence level dropped out from under us.''
</P>
<P>
   Did it remind Jones of last December, maybe the worst month in
Cowboys' history?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``Last December happened mainly because
we had no playoff hopes. This team can get it turned around in
Kansas City, and we will be right back on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. It all comes right back to today in Kansas City. The
Cowboys have not played a bigger game this season. In fact, nothing
else has been close, at least from the standpoint of
re-establishing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect us to play well, and as far as hostility goes, this
situation, in that stadium, will be about as hostile as it gets,''
said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I like the approach of the coaches and the players this
week. I do expect us to shake off New Orleans and regain what we
lost down there. Take it one first down at a time. Get one, then
get another, and let the confidence level build from there.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, like an autographed football, the Cowboys were
still a top sell after New Orleans. But on the field, this is now a
team trying to get back to market value. The Cowboys' worth in that
area will be established today.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
