<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH TRADING SAN DIEGO'S UNCERTAIN CLIMATE FOR HAWAII 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know the situation with the Chargers is bad when June Jones
would rather coach at the University of Hawaii _ where the team was
0-12 _ than at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii may be nice this time of year _ all right, it is nice
every day of the year _ but a pro coach demoting himself?
</P>
<P>
   The story of Jones, the interim head coach of the Chargers who
would have very likely been promoted to permanent head coach at the
end of the season, is one of the stranger ones in the National
Football League this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who replaced Kevin Gilbride as the Chargers' coach on
Oct. 13, said part of his decision had to do with lifestyle issues
because he wanted to spend more time with his wife. Also, the lure
of Hawaii was too strong to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you've lived in Hawaii, unless you know the people
there, it's different than anything else,'' Jones said. ``It's just
a passion that I've had, and that's what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to this story, according to several Chargers
assistant coaches and league executives.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Chargers' organization is hinging its future on
quarterback Ryan Leaf, and Jones is not convinced that Leaf has the
maturity to be a top NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf has spent much of the second half of the season on the
bench because of poor play and several off-the-field incidents,
including cursing at a reporter and being accused of throwing beer
on several Washington State students when he visited his alma
mater.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Jones has told friends he thinks General Manager Bobby
Beathard may be in jeopardy of losing his job. The Chargers, 3-4
under Jones and 5-8 overall, will be looking for their fourth head
coach in four years, and much of the blame for the turnover is
falling on Beathard.
</P>
<P>
   Factions apparently are developing among the San Diego owners,
with some wanting to dismiss Beathard and hire Green Bay Coach Mike
Holmgren to run the organization and coach the team. Others want
Beathard to stay because they believe he gives the Chargers the
best chance to get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear who wants to keep Beathard and who does not, but
coaches and league officials said Jones felt his future was cloudy
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the Chargers said they planned to wait until after the
season to decide if Jones would be made the permanent head coach.
But Jones was apparently told by the Chargers that the interim tag
would most likely be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely unstable,'' linebacker Junior Seau said.
``Until we find a way to win, things like this are going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Beathard wants to hire an offensive coach to tutor Leaf. Coaches
who might receive consideration are the Packers' offensive
coordinator, Sherman Lewis, and the Vikings' offensive coordinator,
Brian Billick, a former assistant at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   I Spy Super Bowl Contenders
</P>
<P>
   Are the Denver Broncos and the Minnesota Vikings watching one
another from afar as they try to make their way to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe said he occasionally catches
highlights from Vikings games and was impressed by their talent,
particularly rookie wide receiver Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings quarterback Randall Cunningham has friends on the
Broncos and is pulling for them to go undefeated _ unless Denver
plays Minnesota in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But neither head coach said he was thinking beyond next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are where they were last year, so we still have a lot to
learn,'' Minnesota Coach Dennis Green said. ``I'm not looking at
Denver just yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how entertaining a Broncos-Vikings game would be.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Mike Shanahan, the Broncos' coach, are two of the
smartest coaches in football, which means much of the game would be
a chess match.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the game would not be is a defensive struggle. Denver
has scored at least 30 points in 10 of 13 games this season, and
the Vikings have scored a league-high 442 points, an average of 34
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Bluffing or Packing?
</P>
<P>
   There continues to be speculation among a small group of owners
that Bob Kraft, the owner of the New England Patriots, is mounting
one of the most impressive bluffs in football history.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners think Kraft is too image-conscious to move the
Patriots from the Boston area to Hartford, and several Patriots
officials said in interviews this week that they still had not made
plans to move because they did not believe Kraft would relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that Kraft is going through all of these elaborate
talks with the state of Connecticut in order to get the city of
Boston to come up with a better stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft is bluffing, it is a great bluff, and is contrary to
what most of the league owners and executives believe. Most feel
Kraft's bags will be packed and ready to move for the 2001 season,
when the Patriots are expected to play in a new 68,000-seat stadium
that will cost taxpayers $350 million to build.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kraft met with Connecticut legislators, and though
there were a few protesters, Kraft mostly received a warm welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating an Issue
</P>
<P>
   The competition committee will speak in a conference call on
Tuesday to discuss instant replay for the playoffs. But while
instant replay may be voted back in during the owner's meetings in
March, it probably will not be for the playoffs because owners and
executives think there has not been enough time to study the many
different ideas. ... After the Carolina Panthers lost to the San
Francisco 49ers in overtime last week, Coach Dom Capers gave the
team Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday off to ``do some
soul-searching.'' But some players were asking themselves: Why the
introspection now? The Panthers are 2-11. ... Several NFL Players
Association officials said that more than 25 percent of the
league's players do not participate in the 401(k) retirement plan,
which worries some union officials. ... Oakland Coach Jon Gruden
may need to add some spice to his offense. Last week in the 27-17
loss to the Miami Dolphins, the Raiders threw two interceptions
that were turned into touchdowns, suffered eight sacks and lost one
fumble. Dolphins players said they looked at the Raiders'
formations and matched them exactly to game film, meaning Oakland
did very little to try to fool the Miami defense. ... The Terrell
Davis Migraine Foundation will honor 10 adolescent migraine
sufferers from New York and New Jersey during a ceremony after the
Giants-Broncos game at Giants Stadium on Sunday. Davis has suffered
from migraines most of his life, but takes medication to control
the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
