<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SEEK WIN VS. NON-DIVISION FOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As Emmitt Smith sees it, the Cowboys don't have
enough passion.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have much more talent than their 8-5 record
indicates, but they lacked pure emotion in upset losses against New
Orleans, Chicago and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to fight,'' Smith said. ``When we throw a blow,
we've got to throw a serious blow and mean it. We need to be a
little more emotional and enthusiastic about what we are doing. If
we add that element to our game, maybe you will see a different
type of ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the businesslike Cowboys face the Kansas City Chiefs
(5-8) at blustery Arrowhead Stadium. The NFC East title and a home
playoff game is theirs with a victory. The Cowboys are favored, but
they must be wondering how good they really are. They are
undefeated in six division games and have outscored their opponents
by an average of 31-10. But outside the division they are 2-5 _
which includes the current two-game losing streak _ and they have
been outscored by an average of 25-20.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere does the disparity show more than on defense. The
Cowboys allow 71 more yards and 15 more points per game in the
seven games they've played outside the division.
</P>
<P>
   This statistic has a lot to do with quality of competition in
the NFC East. Outside the Cowboys, no division team ranks in the
top 15 of total offense; New York and Philadelphia are ranked 29th
and 30th. There is no Top 15 passer, no Top 15 rusher, and only one
Top 15 receiver.
</P>
<P>
   This competition certainly has not prepared the Cowboys for
what's outside the division. In blowout losses to Denver and
Minnesota, the Cowboys have been unable to handle the quarterback
with the highest passer rating (Randall Cunningham), the league's
leading rusher (Terrell Davis), and the league's leader in
receiving yards (Randy Moss).
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs do not have one of the top offenses in the league,
but wide receivers Andre Rison and Derrick Alexander are
gamebreakers. Mobile quarterback Rich Gannon makes few mistakes;
his 1.3-percent interception ratio is one of the lowest in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret our division is down right now,'' Cowboys
strong safety Darren Woodson said. ``One of our goals was to win
the NFC East, and then take care of everything else. We have not
taken care of everything else. Maybe it's confidence. Guys have
been injured, and we've got to have trust in the guys that are out
there. The bottom line is we need to come up with something this
week to change the tide.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting George Teague at free safety for the second consecutive
week has been the only major lineup change on defense. The
cornerback situation is still unsettled. Even if Kevin Smith and
Deion Sanders play despite their injuries, they'll be limited, at
best. To help offset the hurting secondary, defensive coordinator
Dave Campo said the club needs a better pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have only five sacks in the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams who get a real good pass rush are at an advantage,''
Campo said. ``We're not that bad, but there are other teams who are
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense may have failed the Cowboys against Minnesota and
Denver, but the offense had its problems in losses against Oakland,
Chicago and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   With Jason Garrett subbing for an injured Troy Aikman, the
Cowboys were held to 12 points against Oakland and Chicago. The
loss against the Bears saw the Cowboys total a season-low 128 yards
passing. In New Orleans, the running game suffered a complete
meltdown, totaling a franchise-low eight yards.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Cowboys score 10 fewer points and rush for 48 fewer
yards per game outside the division. The Cowboys have faced only
two teams all season with a higher rating than the Chiefs'
12th-ranked defense.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said outsiders can draw their own
conclusions about whether his club can matchup outside the
division. ``They can think what they want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he realizes the importance of his team playing well as it
heads into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith does, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a little more committed, quit relying on
someone else to make a play and make the play ourselves,'' Smith
said. ``I'm confident we'll get things turned around. If it takes
something like New Orleans to get us back refocused, fine. I'm all
for it. But we have to learn from that and get better real quick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
