r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CHIEFS-ED     12-12 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CHIEFS-EDGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO HAS THE EDGE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Edge
Cowboys Run Offense vs. Chiefs Run Defense Edge: Cowboys The Chiefs
have had problems against the run all season, ranking 21st in the
league. Even though they will copy the strategy used by the Saints
to shut down the Cowboys running game, don't count on them having
the same success. Their linebackers aren't as fast and the Cowboys
won't be fooled again.
Cowboys Run Defense vs. Chiefs Run Offense Edge: Cowboys This
should be a slam dunk for the Cowboys. The Chiefs don't have a
running game. The run defense has been the only consistent facet of
the Cowboys defense all season. The hope for the Chiefs is to get
some scrambles from quarterback Rich Gannon.
Cowboys Pass Offense vs. Chiefs Pass Defense Edge: Cowboys The
Chiefs are solid against the pass statistically, however, they have
been giving up big chunks of yardage lately because they have
overcompensated to stop the run. The Cowboys pass offense is as
good as any in the league and should be back on track after last
week's debacle against the Saints.
Cowboys Pass Defense vs. Chiefs Pass Offense Edge: Chiefs The
problems the Cowboys have in the secondary have been the story for
some time now. Their problems getting a consistent pass rush has
been the story all season. Don't look for the Chiefs, who have one
the league's hottest passing attacks of late, to have any sympathy.
Special Teams Edge: Cowboys Chiefs returner Tamarick Vanover is as
dangerous as any in the league. However, the Cowboys coverage teams
are among the league's best, as are punter Toby Gowin and kicker
Richie Cunningham. The Chiefs have problems in special teams
coverage.
Coaching Chan Gailey (8-5) Marty Schottenheimer (143-84-1) Edge:
Even Schottenheimer certainly has the edge in experience, however,
it seems that he is no longer getting through to his players. The
Chiefs are the most undisciplined team in the league and are on the
verge of quitting. The matchup, however, could also reveal a lot
about Gailey and how his team responds from a shocking loss.
Ones to Stop Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman Considering the
much-publicized problems of the Cowboys defense, the Cowboys know
they must score big to win games. And that puts the onus on
quarterback Troy Aikman, who has led the Cowboys to at least 30
points in five games of the seven games he's started and finished
this season. When he gets time to throw the ball, the Cowboys
offense is virtually unstoppable. He didn't get time last week and
the Cowboys offense was shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs quarterback Rich Gannon Gannon is playing as well as any
quarterback in the league over the past three weeks, completing 68
of 104 passes for 775 yards with seven touchdowns and two
interceptions over his last three starts. That comes with a
sizzling quarterback rating of 102.1. As a result, the Chiefs has
scored at least 30 points in each of the past three games _ a first
in ten years under coach Marty Schottenheimer and a first for the
franchise since 1967.
Story Lines Cowboys (8-5)
</P>
<P>
   Can the Cowboys get a pass rush?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to talk about the problems the Cowboys have had in the
secondary. However, already-struggling defensive backfield is
getting no help from the Cowboys front seven. None of the defensive
linemen have gotten to the quarterback with any consistency. And
when they have gotten pressure, they have been unable to complete
the play because the quarterback has usually danced away and made a
play on the outside. A defensive backfield is only as good as the
line in front of it. And if the Cowboys don't get to Rich Gannon,
it will be another long day in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   How will the Chiefs game affect the Cowboys playoff chances?
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the Chiefs game will probably have little impact
on the Cowboys playoff chances. Barring the unthinkable, the
Cowboys are virtually assured of winning the NFC East and hosting a
wild card game. There is no way they can catch Atlanta for the
second-best record to possibly host two playoff games. That being
said, the Cowboys don't want to back into the playoffs on a losing
note if they plan on doing something when they get there.
Considering that the last two games are against the woeful Eagles
and Redskins, the Chiefs game could tell a lot about what type of
team the Cowboys have. A loss would certainly reinforce the view
that the Cowboys just benefited from being in a weak division and
are not a legitimate contender.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs (5-8)
</P>
<P>
   Did the Chiefs fire their last shot against the Broncos?
</P>
<P>
   Key for the Chiefs is how they will respond following last
Sunday's loss to the Broncos. The Chiefs' season has been over for
some time, but they put a lot of energy into trying to get some
redemption and knock off the Broncos. They didn't get it done.
Considering the many disappointments and embarrassments they've had
in 1998, the question now is have they mentally closed shop for the
season. They need to come out strong because if they get behind, no
one is sure if they will fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Chiefs muster a running game?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Rich Gannon is throwing the ball well. However, the Chiefs
still want a solid running game to help balance the offense. Right
now, there is no need to respect the Chiefs ground attack, which
has topped 100 yards only once in the past eight games and has
averaged less than three yards a carry in three of the past four
games. They will be hard-pressed to find running room against the
Cowboys defense, however, they will try to ram former Texas Tech
star Bam Morris in the middle to soften the Cowboys for the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys analysis Mike Fisher NFL beat writer
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys came away from the Superdome in New Orleans last
week believing that it's one of the toughest places to play in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   They ain't seen nothin' yet.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Chiefs are about out of fight. They began the season
boasting about their prospects for going 16-0, and in recent weeks,
they turned a loss against Denver into a bar brawl. Then came a
loss against the woeful Chargers, followed by a hard-fought loss at
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   I've always known the Chiefs don't possess the big-play weapons
on offense that can hurt an opponent. Now I wonder if the Cowboys
do.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs 17, Cowboys 16
Clarence E. Hill Jr. Cowboys beat writer
</P>
<P>
   Let me see. The Cowboys are 6-0 against the NFC East. And 2-5
against everybody else. Sounds like a trend to me. Let's look
again. Of seven non-division games, the are Cowboys 2-1 against
teams no longer in the playoff chase _ wins against Carolina and
Seattle and a loss to Chicago. Is that a trend? Or how about the
fact that the Cowboys are 0-3 against teams above .500 and 8-2
against teams below .500. So where does the matchup against the
Chiefs (5-8), who have nothing to play for, fall. Who cares? As my
grandma said a long time ago, statistics are like a lamp post, some
use it for illumination, a wino uses it for support.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys 28, Chiefs 21
Kevin Lyons beat writer
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs are a talented team with nothing to lose. Out of the
playoff race, the Chiefs would like nothing more than to slow the
Cowboys' momentum toward the postseason. The Cowboys have more
talent, but today's game will be about more than that. Grit.
Determination. Confidence. The Cowboys will need all of these
things to win at noisy Arrowhead Stadium. They have not played with
much confidence lately, and should they get behind early, it could
be a long afternoon for the 'Boys. But this game should bring out
the championship mettle in the Cowboys as well as coach Chan
Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys 28, Chiefs 27
</P>
</TEXT>
