<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-BLUEFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 A BLUEFISH BLITZ IS SURFCASTING HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN C. SAUTNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDY HOOK, N.J. _ Here, along the Eastern shoreline in autumn,
few things cause pandemonium among fishers _ particularly
surfcasters _ quite like a school of bluefish blitzing the beach.
Utterly satisfying like a home run in baseball, a true blitz, or
feeding frenzy, offers one of those rare moments when the angler,
having caught his or her fill, may actually walk away with fish
still biting.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case during a recent trip to this westernmost point
of Lower New York Bay, and gateway to New York Harbor. Cooler
temperatures had begun flushing baitfish out of the estuaries
sending them migrating along beach fronts. The bluefish schools, in
turn, were in hot pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   I had just pulled into the parking lot, when several anglers
trudged past, carrying buckets full of 2-pound bluefish. ``They're
still hitting,'' one of them told me, looking wild-eyed but
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The next five minutes I spent yanking on my waders, grabbing
lures, then racing for the beach. Almost immediately, I spotted a
large flock of laughing gulls and terns wheeling above the surf.
Ocean fishermen keep a perpetual vigil for ``working'' seabirds,
knowing that they often follow schools of bait fish, swooping down
when predators drive them to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I saw a picket fence of perhaps 50 anglers. More than half
clutched doubled-over fishing rods. As I walked closer, freshly
caught bluefish could be seen flopping all over the beach. Beyond
them in the surf, shoals of coppery rainfish _ so tightly packed
they made each wave look almost red _ weaved and undulated as they
tried to evade the hungry blues.
</P>
<P>
   Even though striped bass, weakfish and other surf-caught game
fish periodically swarm in dense schools while chasing prey, for
sheer carnage nothing matches a pack of hungry bluefish. In 1874,
the United States' first fish commissioner, Spencer Baird, said it
best when he described them as ``animated chopping machines.'' My
friend Richard Kress, a former lifeguard and avid surf angler,
remembers having to whistle swimmers out of the water one summer
because the blues were in so thick.
</P>
<P>
   I chose a spot and cast a silver popper beyond the breakers. I
turned the reel once and right away a fish boiled behind the lure.
A second turn produced a slashing strike. Minutes later, a wave
deposited a prime fall-run bluefish at my feet, a gift from the
fishing gods.
</P>
<P>
   The scene continued on _ a fury of blues, birds and fishermen.
In five casts, I caught five bluefish. A rolling wave picked up a
particularly dense school of bait then collapsed on the beach,
scattering rainfish on the sand like confetti.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen chased the bluefish schools on foot as they swept down
the surf line. Old men with custom rods stood side by side with
tourists using push-button reels. All caught fish. Kids too young
to cast gathered the bluefish in buckets for their parents. One
angler that seemed a little too well-dressed, as if he had sneaked
out on his lunch break, wore a beeper, which proceeded to go off
just as he landed a fish. He read the message, then, looking
obviously dismayed, gathered his gear and left.
</P>
<P>
   I finally stopped casting, having released so many fish I lost
count. Instead, I sat in the sand and watched the schools pass on
their long migration to southern waters. By Thanksgiving, they
would be off Cape Hatteras; by Christmas, Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, anglers began filing off the beach, weighed down
with limits of bluefish which they dragged on rope stringers, or
carried off in coolers and buckets. Some fishermen were dripping
wet and laughing, others wore a thin layer of wet sand. Meanwhile,
behind them in the surf, the bluefish kept blitzing, apparently
having worn out even those who pursue them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1STLE     12-12 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLEDGES TO ``WALK WITH ISRAEL'' BUT NUDGES ITS LEADER
 &HT;    EDS: New top and writethru after Clinton's arrival ceremony.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Casting his three day Middle East visit as a solemn
mission to ''put the peace process on track,'' President Clinton
pledged early Sunday that ''the United States will walk this road
with Israel every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a precursor to tough talks ahead, Clinton served notice
on Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu that Israel must move forward
with currently suspended West Bank withdrawals, as Netanyahu
protested that Palestinians have failed to live up to their own
promises to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the last few weeks, our partners have not kept their
commitments,'' Netanyahu said, a reference to increased street
protests against Israelis by Palestinians in Israeli-occupied
territories. ''We must, therefore, seek compliance without let
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Their comments came at a ceremony to welcome Clinton on the
tarmac of Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion International Airport, named for
Israel's first prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers in America witnessed an odd juxtaposition of
split-screen images. As House Judiciary Committee members were
shown heatedly debating articles of impeachment, Clinton was seen
receiving a statesman's greeting a half world away.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., one of more than a dozen lawmakers
who accompanied Clinton aboard Air Force One, said the president
``seemed very fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there's going to be a lot on his mind and a lot of
churning inside him,'' Wellstone told reporters. ``But he seems
very focused on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Netanyahu is in deep political trouble. He
narrowly survived a no confidence vote this past week and may soon
face another one.
</P>
<P>
   In a possible opening on other fronts, Netanyahu said he hoped
to reinvigorate long-stalled peace talks with two of Israel's other
regional foes: Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ''We extend our hands to the Syrians and the Lebanese to revive
the process,'' Netanyahu said. ''And we extend our hands to our
Palestinian neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu, whose relations with Clinton have rarely risen
above frosty, salted his welcome with some hard-edged talk.
</P>
<P>
   In a thinly-veiled jab at White House diplomacy, Netanyahu
chided Clinton at one point. ``Peace agreements in themselves do
not necessarily bring about peace,'' he said, adding that Israel
seeks ''a peace that will endure for decades _ and not just for the
next newscast.''
</P>
<P>
   Capping a dramatic day in which the House Judiciary Committee
passed its fourth article of impeachment against Clinton, the
president, accompanied by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
their daughter Chelsea, arrived at Ben Gurion shortly before
midnight local time. After a ceremonial reception and arrival
remarks, Clinton flew by helicopter to his hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to meet Sunday with Netanyahu for what promises to be
contentious talks over what can be done to keep the imperiled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Clinton is to meet in Palestinian-controlled Gaza with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to discuss Palestinian commitments
made under the peace accord Clinton brokered in October between
Arafat and Netanyahu at the Wye River Plantation in rural Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking shortly after midnight, Clinton said he had come ''to
reaffirm America's unbreakable ties to Israel, (and) to reaffirm
our unshakable commitment to Israeli security.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is asking Congress for an additional $1.2 billion in aid
to Israel for next year, on top of the $3 billion already planned.
</P>
<P>
   Also meeting the Clintons at Ben Gurion was Israeli President
Ezer Weizman. An Israeli military band played the national anthems
of both countries _ the Star Spangled Banner and Hatikva, which
translates roughly into ''hope.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton walked through a ceremonial review of the troops on
the tarmac, Netanyahu chatted easily with Mrs. Clinton, who smiled
and appeared engaged and animated after the ten-hour flight from
Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Netanyahu's tough talk, Weizman said Israelis welcomed
Clinton's visit his fourth to Israel as president and his efforts
to get the peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hour is late, but it is the hour of truth,'' said Weizman.
''The people of Israel yearn for peace and security.''
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over impeachment raged Saturday on Capitol Hill,
there was relative calm in and around Israel after two weeks of
sometimes bloody clashes between police and Palestinian protestors.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, about a half dozen protestors were injured in
Bethlehem in the West Bank before Palestinian police quelled the
violence. The crackdown was seen as a sign that Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat will not allow demonstrations to mar Clinton's
scheduled visit to Bethlehem on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The protestors were not angry about Clinton's pending visit.
Rather, they were demonstrating against Israel's refusal to release
hundreds of Palestinians jailed for anti-Israel activities.
</P>
<P>
   Before the brief violence in Bethlehem on Saturday, workers
unfurled 40-foot-long U.S. and Palestinian flags side-by-side on
the wall of the 1,600-year-old stone Church of the Nativity, the
site of Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the Jewish Sabbath and most stores and offices in
Israel were closed.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Netanyahu was coming off a bad week in which his
government was almost toppled, in part by former allies who oppose
the Wye River peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the violence in Bethlehem Saturday, there were only a
couple incidents of the isolated rioting that has occurred almost
daily for two weeks. In the West Bank, funerals were held for two
of the four Palestinians killed by Israeli soldiers in the recent
riots. In the Arab section of east Jerusalem, Israeli riot police
with M-16 rifles were out in unusually large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say they are rioting because Israel is not
releasing enough prisoners from Israeli jails releases prompted by
the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get our prisoners and our rights. If they don't let
them out we'll have an Intifada (uprising) with Clinton here,''
said Mahmoud Ismail, a 15-year-old in Bethlehem near where youths
had been throwing rocks at Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ismail said he would join his neighbors in trying to see
Clinton when he visits the town on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
