<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-BIBLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER SUSPENDED AFTER BRINGING BIBLES TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx elementary school teacher has been suspended
on charges that he distributed religious books and promoted
Christianity in his classroom. The teacher, Simpson Gray, says he
is being unfairly singled out for his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, a fifth-grade teacher at Public School 5, was removed from
his classroom last week after a school board investigation of one
parent's complaint that he supplied the school's library and his
students with six copies of the Bible and four religious books that
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   His suspension marks the second time this year that a Bronx
teacher has been embroiled in a controversy about religion in the
classroom. Mildred Rosario, a substitute teacher at Intermediate
School 74, was dismissed after she asked children in her class if
they accepted Jesus as their Savior.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, 57, said he did take the materials into the school in
October 1997, but not for religious reasons. Instead, Gray said, he
was trying to broaden the selection of reading materials and to
show children that at least one of their teachers was also an
author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the law,'' said Gray, a former lawyer who has taught at
the school for seven years. ``What it says is that you can't
preach, you can't pray and you can't teach the Bible in school.
Nowhere does it say it is illegal for a teacher to bring a Bible
into an elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education officials have a different view, and say that
Gray may be guilty of much more. ``There is quite an array of
allegations concerning this particular teacher,'' said Chiara
Coletti, chief spokeswoman for the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are allegations that he may have said or written things
that were adverse toward other religious faiths, that he advocated
religion in his classroom and there are some corporal punishment
charges,'' she said, declining to be specific. ``All these things
have to be sorted out; there is always the possibility they are not
valid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said the allegations stemmed from an incident with one
parent who accused him of calling her child dumb and teaching
religion to the students. The parent demanded that her child be
removed from his class.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who said he was being aided by his union, denied the
parent's accusations and said board investigators never found proof
that he called the student dumb. He declined to identify the
parent.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he had filed a $400 million lawsuit against the Board
of Education charging religious discrimination and defamation of
character. He said he selected his books because they illustrate
``that any one can change their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he turned his life over to God after he was convicted
in October 1985 of stealing $18,000 to $22,000 from his law
clients. He was on probation for five years and performed 2,000
hours of community service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an inner city school where students are facing all sorts of
challenges to their academic development,'' he said, ``it's
essential that they have role models, that they have a chance to
relate to someone who made a mistake but is now living right. They
need as much motivation as they can get. ''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on Gray's lawsuit is scheduled for Friday in Bronx
Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
