<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-1     12-12 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL REJECTS CENSURE, APPROVES 4TH IMPEACHMENT ARTICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: INSERTS 5TH graf to describe committee votes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee on Saturday approved
a fourth article of impeachment against President Clinton and
rejected Democratic-led efforts to substitute a softer censure
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's final action sets the stage for the historic
vote by the full House later this week on four articles of
impeachment against the president, marking only the second time in
U.S. history that a president has faced such a constitutional
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   If a majority of the House approves one or more articles of
impeachment, the Senate would then conduct a trial and vote whether
to convict the president. A conviction, which requires a two-thirds
vote of the 100 senators, would automatically expel Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the censure alternative brings maximum pressure
on House members who believe Clinton should be punished to vote for
the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The committee votes approving the fourth article of impeachment
and rejecting the censure alternative were largely along party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the senior Democrat on the committee
and a steadfast defender of the president, said he hoped outgoing
House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia or Speaker-elect Bob
Livingston of Louisiana would allow the full House to take up the
censure option.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that the Republican leadership will allow us to
fashion a way out of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, Livingston told reporters, ``Frankly we haven't
decided yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting the move to censure Clinton, Republicans on the
Judiciary Committee argued that the Constitution did not allow such
a step. They also argued that a censure would not adequately punish
Clinton for his alleged wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure is a constitutional cop-out,'' said Rep. Bob Barr,
R-Ga., a leader in the impeachment drive. Rep. Bob Goodlatte,
R-Va., said the president would immediately begin undermining a
censure by ``sending out his spindoctors'' to attack it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what the president wants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marty Meehan, D-Mass., rejected the idea that the president
would ``laugh off'' a censure, saying it would be a ``scarlet
letter'' on the legacy of Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``No American history textbook will fail to mention what the
president did and what we thought of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also contended that opinion polls show that a majority
of the American people favor censure over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers said the American public only now is becoming aware that
Clinton is close to being impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a lot of Americans are finding out that the
Republican move to remove the president is not only wrong but
real,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated censure resolution accused Clinton of violating the
trust of the American people; failing to uphold his presidential
oath; making ``false statements concerning his reprehensible
conduct'' with a subordinate; and ``wrongly'' delaying the
discovery of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The censure resolution also would have required the president to
sign it to ``acknowledge the censure and condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who invited Congress to censure him on Friday, was on a
journey to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the committee voted 21-16 to approve a
fourth article of impeachment that accused the president of abuse
of power in connection with written answers he recently submitted
to Congress in response to 81 written questions about his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Before approving the article, members of the committee narrowed
it by removing language condemning the president for asserting
executive privilege in trying to prevent testimony sought by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and for lying to the American
people and his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was simply uttering a privilege that is accorded him,''
said Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., who proposed making the changes to
the article. ``We ought to give the benefit of the doubt to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democratic committee members approved the narrowing,
although they continued to oppose the remaining allegation that
Clinton lied to Congress when he answered the 81 questions
submitted by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, both inside and outside the committee, have
voiced anger over Clinton's answers to those questions, claiming
they showed that the president was continuing to cover up his
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois called Clinton's
evasive answers to the questions ``an assault on the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said even the limited
accusation of abuse of power was ``absolutely indefensible'' and
that the 81 questions were written to ``trap'' Clinton into
admitting he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., praised the committee for limiting
the charge. He said Congress ``could go down the list of every
president from George Washington to the present and impeach
everyone of them'' if lying were an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, special counsel Gregory Craig, who defended
the president before the committee on Thursday, attacked the
committee, claiming its results would ``divide the country,
gridlock the government and defy the will of the people.'' He added
that ``nothing about this process has been fair.''
</P>
<P>
   All four impeachment articles arise from Clinton's relationship
with Lewinsky and his effort to cover it up, drawing from material
that Starr submitted to Congress in September.
</P>
<P>
   The first three articles approved Friday alleged that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton provided ``perjurious, false and misleading
testimony'' to Starr's grand jury last August about his
relationship with the former White House intern and other matters;
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton provided ``perjurious, false and misleading
testimony'' in a sworn deposition as part of the Paula Jones civil
suit against the president alleging sexual harassment;
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton obstructed justice in an effort to impede Starr's
investigation by encouraging Lewinsky to testify falsely; by
coaching presidential secretary Betty Currie in her own testimony,
to hide the truth about gifts the president received from Lewinsky
and other matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
