<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RIVALS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons-Saints a feud undiminished
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly 20 years later, former Falcons linebacker Dewey
McClain still relates the tale with enough hint of embellishment to
suggest his narrative of woe is even deeper than the nap of the
Superdome carpet where he claimed to have almost expired.
</P>
<P>
   The play on which McClain purported to be within a breath of
suffocation occurred in the 1979 season opener between the Falcons
and Saints, a game much more infamous in the Big Easy because of
the incredible gaffe by New Orleans punter Russell Erxleben that
led to Atlanta's 40-34 overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   On a blitz, McClain raised his arms to deflect an Archie Manning
pass and was violently sucker-punched in the gut by New Orleans
guard Conrad Dobler, the notorious cheap-shot practitioner who had
invented nearly every dirty trick in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy `double-barreled' me,'' McClain recalled last week.
``Hey, I didn't even know you could get away with something like
that. But there I was, face down in the AstroTurf and here comes
(trainer) Jerry Rhea out to me. The first thing trainers always did
back then was put their hand on your head to calm you down. So
here's Jerry with his hand on the back of my helmet and my nose is
deep into that rug. By the time he rolled me over, I'd about had
it, man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons-Saints rivalry, which will be renewed for the 60th
time today (counting a '91 playoff matchup), has been many things
to many people. Even with Atlanta's current seven-game winning
streak, eight of the past 12 meetings were determined by eight or
fewer points and nine were decided in the final seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the fans haven't turned out the way they once did for a game
formerly viewed as the social event of year in both cities _ the
average attendance for the past seven games is just 51,871 and
charter services no longer order extra buses _ the lore of one of
the NFL's most colorful rivalries remains.
</P>
<P>
   As with Dewey McClain, there's no reason yet to call for a
respirator.
</P>
<P>
   There have been ``Big Ben'' plays and brutal blunders. Overtime
and underachieving. A guy dressed like Moses parading through the
stands, and four players impersonating an NFL secondary but parting
like the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's been the ridiculous and the sublime, and
sometimes all of those elements converged in the same contest.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the wins and losses, however, every man who ever lined up
in a Falcons-Saints game has a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one I remember best,'' said all-time great Atlanta center
Jeff Van Note, ``was that year the Saints just laid down like dogs.
We beat them 62-7 at their place (in the 1973 season opener) and
they had quit halfway through the first quarter. A lot of crazy
stuff has taken place in this rivalry, but I'd never seen anything
like that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the trouncing, in fact, Saints coach John North
placed his entire roster on waivers. When he addressed his rag-tag
team the Tuesday after the loss, North let the players know the
disdain with which he regarded every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Former defensive back Tommy Myers remembered the game, in which
Atlanta set 35 franchise records, and the unbelievable aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Recalled Myers: ``Coach North came in and said, `Don't any of
you ever ask to be traded again. I just put the whole bunch of you
on waivers and nobody wanted any of you guys.' From the back of the
room somebody yelled out, `What, even Archie?' And North said,
`Yeah, even Archie.' '' Van Note said several Saints players
related the same story.
</P>
<P>
   Before he died in 1994, Falcons equipment manager Whitey
Zimmerman would sit watching practice and, along with assistant
Horace Daniel, regale his visitors with several tales from what he
called ``the damnedest rivalry that no one outside the South even
knows anything about.'' Mostly Zimmerman would speak of the annual
appearance of his favorite guy named Jack _ Jack Daniels, that is _
among the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, who was at the Georgia Dome last Sunday afternoon to
watch son Peyton play against the Falcons, grew up with the rivalry
and still regards it has a highlight of his career _ even if some
of the memories are painful ones. Manning recalled the game his
rookie season, '71, when the Falcons defense was pounding him into
the mud at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium in the midst of a 28-6
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, I was running for my life and the crowd wanted
blood,'' Manning said. ``Late in the game, Claude Humphrey came
through on a jail break and had me in his sights. And then he just
pulled up and went right by me. I was so relieved, I about cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Such displays of compassion have been rare in a series that, no
matter the records of the teams, characteristically is played with
intensity. The era of free agency has taken away some of the edge,
but Saints coach Mike Ditka allowed last week there are still
enough old-timers around the city of New Orleans to enlighten those
younger players on the significance of the rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you don't like to think you can make or break
your reputation on one play in one game,'' former Saints linebacker
Rickey Jackson said. ``But in Atlanta or in New Orleans, lots of
folks remember you by what you did in the Falcons-Saints games.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, wide receiver Alfred Jackson remains one of the finest
big-play performers in Falcons history, but will be most remembered
for his ``Big Ben'' catch he hauled in from Steve Bartkowski to
rally Atlanta to a 20-17 victory in 1978. ``A signature play,''
said Jackson recently.
</P>
<P>
   At home in Dallas, former punter Russell Erxleben still is
haunted by the snap that sailed over his head in the '79 game where
McClain was slugged by Dobler. After chasing down the errant snap,
Erxleben attempted an ill-advised pass that was intercepted by
Atlanta's James Mayberry and returned for the game-winning
touchdown, one of only two he scored in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, I knew it was a stupid play,'' Erxleben said. ``And if I
didn't, there always someone who calls when the Falcons play the
Saints and reminds me of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
