<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Games encore unclear
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Even after a few red-white-and-booed U.S. hockey
players turned a Nagano, Japan dormitory into Animal House, even
after the NHL's grand marketing venture accomplished little outside
of Kladno, it appeared to be a lock that the league would supply
players to the Winter Olympics at least one more time.
</P>
<P>
   NHL commissioner Gary Bettman's constant focus is to increase
the NHL's exposure, make it hip, sell T-shirts. There is no bigger
stage than the Olympics, especially with the next Games being held
on U.S. soil/ice, in Salt Lake City in 2002. And didn't the U.S.
win hockey gold medals in Squaw Valley (1960) and Lake Placid
(1980)? How great a boost would hockey, on levels from grassroots
to Gretzky, be given if Americans win gold in Salt Lake City?
</P>
<P>
   For the aforementioned potential, the NHL's participation in the
next Games remains probable. But a lock? No. Consider the major
factors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Television: Bettman was upset about the hockey competition
being buried by CBS in Nagano and wants assurances that NBC won't
do the same. But women's figure skating and skiing generally take
precedent in primetime network coverage. Bettman and network
officials have had conversations, but NBC spokesman Ed Markey said,
``We're not close to making any programming decisions for Salt Lake
City. We're still working on Sydney (2000 Summer Olympics).''
Bottom line: The NHL will have to make its decision without the
benefit of a programming guide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Management: Some general managers were not thrilled with the
17-day break in the schedule last season and are not warm to doing
it again (although it would be only 12 days this time). The
Colorado Avalance was 29-13-16 before the intermission, sent a
league-high nine players to Nagano, then went 10-13-1 after the
break. If the Olympics were this year and you're the Phoenix
Coyotes, who lead the Western Conference, would you embrace a break
in the schedule right now?
</P>
<P>
   _ Players: Like GMs, the players wonder if the Games are more
trouble than they're worth. Prior to committing to Nagano, the NHL
Players Association asked for a ``reopener'' clause to be taken out
of the collective bargaining agreement. As a result, the collective
bargaining agreement runs through 2004. NHLPA executive director
Bob Goodenow, who convinced his constituents to keep quiet on the
identity of the three U.S. room trashers, has remained quiet on
these Games. But one American, Phoenix's Jeremy Roenick, said this
week, ``If they say no NHL players in the Olympics, I won't lose
one wink of sleep over it. We have a goal in the NHL and that's to
win the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the thrill of Olympic rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said a decision will come in ``60 to 90 days,'' so the
world's respective hockey federations can make alternative plans if
the NHL backs out. But the issue may be clarified when the Board of
Governors meet next month during the All-Star break in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the potential of another Czech-Russia final, Thrashers
and Turner Sports president Harvey Schiller said he would support
any decision that improves the NHL's visibility. But that
visibility is linked to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix center Keith Tkachuk, who also was in Nagano, said,
``Why send NHL players if you're not going to show the games?
What's the sense of doing it?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
