<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holy Toledo, the UCLA coach may be headed to NFL
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite the season-ending loss to Butch Davis and
Miami, the hot name among college coaches who will be considered
for NFL vacancies is UCLA's Bob Toledo. In an intriguing twist, two
teams that might vie for Toledo are the reborn Cleveland Browns and
their predecessors, the Baltimore Ravens. While Denver offensive
coordinator Gary Kubiak is likely to get a strong recommendation
for the Cleveland post from boss Mike Shanahan, team president
Carmen Policy will interview several candidates and Toledo probably
will be one of them. Meanwhile, Ravens owner Art Modell is telling
confidantes he feels Toledo might be a ``great'' NFL coach. Toledo
also will draw interest from San Diego GM Bobby Beathard, who wants
to replace June Jones with an offense-minded coach who can develop
Ryan Leaf. The Chargers' primary target, however, is Florida coach
Steve Spurrier. If Beathard can't lure Spurrier to the West Coast,
he'll consider Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham, Toledo and others.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett comeback
</P>
<P>
   The success in '98 of 30-something sackmasters like Reggie White
(Green Bay), Kevin Greene (Carolina), Chris Doleman (San Francisco)
and Trace Armstrong (Miami) almost certainly means former standout
defensive end Tony Bennett will be back in the league in 1999.
Surgery on his left knee limited Bennett to six games with
Indianapolis last season, and the Colts released the eight-year pro
this summer when president Bill Polian didn't feel his rehab was
far enough along. Bennett recently had the left knee repaired by
leading orthopedist Richard Steadman, got some loose bodies removed
from his right knee, and feels better than he has in years. Several
teams, including the Falcons, have phoned agent Pat Dye Jr. about
Bennett, a speed-rusher who has 64 1/2 career sacks and won't turn
32 until next July.
</P>
<P>
   Goin' from Kansas City
</P>
<P>
   Among the teams interested in Bennett is Kansas City, where
players and management have tired of linebacker Derrick Thomas.
Since pillaging Oakland tackle Pat Harlow for six sacks in the
season opener, Thomas has only three sacks. When team president
Carl Peterson sits down with coach Marty Schottenheimer at year's
end to evaluate players, Thomas' name will be first on the list.
There's also a chance Schottenheimer, who will not be fired, could
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle vacancy
</P>
<P>
   The erroneous call by head linesman Earnie Frantz last week,
which cost Seattle a win when he ruled Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde had crossed the goal line, left coach Dennis Erickson in
tears in his locker room. With the Seahawks all but eliminated from
the playoffs for a fourth straight year, the coach realizes he may
soon be eliminated as well. Two names of interest to owner Paul
Allen and club president Bob Whitsitt are former 49ers coach George
Seifert and Pittsburgh defensive coordinator Jim Haslett. But if
Schottenheimer left the Chiefs, he'd probably move to the top of
the Seattle wish-list.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback update
</P>
<P>
   Three more quarterbacks, all in the AFC, will be added to the
starter's role call today _ Jeff Blake (Cincinnati), Jamie Martin
(Jacksonville) and Wade Wilson (Oakland). That will raise to 58 the
number of quarterbacks who started at least one game in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle tailback Ricky Watters needs 21 yards to become the
first player in league history to gain 1,000 rushing yards with
three different teams. Kevin GilbrideSkip Holtz... Buffalo's Doug
FlutieMarshall Faulk
</P>
</TEXT>
