<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves, Ditka: This is personal
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ It might lack the panache of the pro wrestling,
but it would be similarly entertaining if old buddies Dan Reeves
and Mike Ditka were televised while competing against each other in
golf, racquetball, poker, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   They're fiercely competitive, and Ditka, of course, gets
downright ferocious. Imagine ``Iron Mike'' losing a hand at the
poker table only to pick up his chair and throw it so that all four
legs stuck in a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves nor Ditka has confirmed or denied this, but enough people
who count the men as friends have told the story that it has become
legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if I'm surprised by Mike, but that's just
Mike,'' said Reeves who met Ditka in 1969 when they were teammates
with the Dallas Cowboys (and later assistant coaches). ``There's
nothing phony about him. He's just intense, and he hates to lose at
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves' Atlanta Falcons (11-2) play Ditka's New Orleans
Saints (6-7) today, it figures to be like an extension of their
personal rivalry _ heated.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, both teams have something on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who have won 17 of 21 dating to last season, are
trying to hold off the San Francisco 49ers (10-3) to win just the
second NFC West title in the 33-year history of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   This game is huge for Atlanta, which has overcome slow starts
three games in a row to beat the Bears, Rams and Colts in a
six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Saints would be the Falcons' second in the
division this season, and the 49ers have just one. In essence,
Atlanta would fall out of first place, even with the same overall
record as the 49ers, as long as San Francisco wins Monday night at
home against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have beaten the Saints seven in a row, including
three consecutive wins here, but New Orleans is in a fight of its
own, tied with Arizona and Tampa Bay in a race for the third and
final wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints are 4-2 at home, and have allowed just one field goal
in each of their past three games in the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   As Ditka promised after a 30-10 loss at Miami two weeks ago, New
Orleans used a much more aggressive defense in a 22-3 win over the
Dallas Cowboys, surrendering just eight rushing yards on 18
carries.
</P>
<P>
   In a 31-23 Falcons win over the Saints on Oct. 18 in the Georgia
Dome, running back Jamal Anderson rushed 25 times for 132 yards and
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is like one of the racquetball games between
Ditka and Reeves _ ``That didn't hit the wall ... Yes it did; one
inch up .. . No, it short-hopped the wall. I'm telling you, that's
my point.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, one guy is saying ``We're going to run'' and the other
``No, you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them will be proven wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you coach football for, to get into the types of
games we're in here,'' Reeves said. ``That's what Mike thrives on.
That's the reason he's so competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
