<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Bucs pass agai
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ For much of his five-year tenure, quarterback
Trent Dilfer has been the convenient whipping boy, a once-anointed
savior whose erratic performances stymied the progress of the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   But with three weeks remaining in the season, and the suddenly
resurgent Bucs poised to claim the final NFC wild-card berth,
Dilfer could go from scatter-arm to golden arm.
</P>
<P>
   Since an embarrassing 9-3 defeat at New Orleans on Oct. 25, the
former first-rounder ('94) has been at the forefront of Tampa Bay's
offensive revival. In a six-week stretch, Dilfer has thrown 13
touchdown passes, tying Randall Cunningham for the most in that
period. His passer rating, just 70.6 in the first seven games, is
85.5 in the last six. And an offense that averaged only 264 yards
and 13.4 points the first two months of this season has rung up
349.3 yards and 25.5 points since the collapse against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately they've been the guys bailing us out,'' defensive
tackle Warren Sapp said of the Bucs' offense. ``It's hard to play
(defense) when you know you have to hold the other guy under 20
points to have a chance. But when our offense gets on the
scoreboard early ... oh, my goodness, we can do all sorts of damage
on our side of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That the offense is most responsible for resurrecting a season
gone bad is, indeed, a surprising twist in this NFL precinct. In
the first seven games, Tampa Bay scored more than 20 points on just
one occasion. Although the last six games have produced just a 3-3
record, the Bucs haven't been under 22 points in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In the three defeats, the usually stingy defense surrendered an
average of 29.3 points and twice allowed game-winning drives after
the Bucs had taken late leads.
</P>
<P>
   While coach Tony Dungy still is waiting for his club to dominate
an opponent for 60 minutes, the Monday night victory over Green Bay
was a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer threw the ball efficiently and the two wide receivers the
Bucs acquired specifically to help them beat the Packers, veteran
Bert Emanuel and second-rounder Jacquez Green, both turned short
passes into long touchdowns. The duo of Mike Alstott and Warrick
Dunn ran hard. The defense, struggling to overcome several
injuries, exerted consistent pressure on Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   It is enough to at least suggest that the Bucs, beginning with
today's game against the Pittsburgh Steelers, could win out, finish
a respectable 9-7 and still cause some trouble in the playoffs.
That wasn't the scenario many envisioned when the Bucs began the
season as the chic pick to represent the NFC in the Super Bowl, but
it is more than could have been expected when the club was 3-4 on
Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current standings, a Tampa Bay-Dallas matchup in the
first round of the playoffs is a strong likelihood. And with the
Cowboys in a funk _ their secondary is in tatters and Dallas is
only 2-5 in games outside its division _ anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a chance for us to salvage something,''
Dilfer said. ``We still feel our best game hasn't been played
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact the Bucs are even contemplating a playoff
run is a reflection of how unbalanced the NFC has become. Not since
1990 has the conference included a wild-card team with less than a
winning record, but it's a distinct possibility this season in the
NFC.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs, New Orleans Saints and Arizona Cardinals all begin
today with 6-7 marks and the chance to sneak into the No. 3
wild-card spot. After years of being treated like an outcast, maybe
it's apropos Dilfer be the one to help the Bucs crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
