<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCNOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys limping defense leaves team open
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLATNA _ Although the Cowboys will meet the lowest-seeded
wild-card team in the opening round of the playoffs, Dallas might
be the division champion most vulnerable to a premature exit. The
multiple-set offense installed by rookie coach Chan Gailey is fine,
but Dallas' secondary woes could severely hamper coordinator Dave
Campo's defense. Both corners, Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith, are
out with injuries. Free safety Omar Stoutmire is a liability
against the pass and young ends Kavika Pittman and Greg Ellis
aren't getting a lot of pressure. Some defensive players were
stunned that owner Jerry Jones couldn't come up with a better
stop-gap corner than Larry Brown. ``We are pretty exploitable right
now,'' agreed strong safety Darren Woodson. In their last two games
without Sanders, the Cowboys have surrendered six TD passes (five
of 50-plus yards) and 598 passing yards. If Kansas City's Rich
Gannon throws the ball today as well as he did a week ago, Dallas
could post a third straight loss. Dallas is 6-0 in the division but
just 2-5 outside the ``NFC Least.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions roar
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue has deferred the $50,000 fine levied
against Lions owner William Clay Ford for criticism of referee Phil
Luckett's crew in the Thanksgiving Day victory over Pittsburgh, and
the penalty likely will be altogether rescinded. Still some Lions
officials remain angry that Tagliabue faxed Ford, one of the NFL's
most respected owners, notification of the fine instead of phoning
him. And in the fax to Ford, he also attached a copy of a letter
sent earlier this year to Colts president Jim Irsay. In that
letter, Tagliabue lauded Irsay and coach Jim Mora for the
``professionalism'' and ``class'' demonstrated in the wake of a
loss at San Francisco in which the officials crew headed by Walt
Coleman made two erroneous calls which cost the Colts an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel fizzling
</P>
<P>
   Very quietly last week, Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi
served unofficial notice that coach Jim Fassel will be on the hot
seat in '99. Accorsi acknowledged owners Bob Tisch and Wellington
Mara were disappointed in the team's performance, noted that the
front office has confidence in Fassel but asid he will get no
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the low Rhodes
</P>
<P>
   Embattled coach Ray Rhodes, certain to lose his job at season's
end, doesn't figure to leave the Eagles quietly. Rhodes took a
couple shots at director of football operations Tom Modrak last
week, claiming two recently released players, safety Matt Stevens
and receiver Russell Copeland, would be valuable pickups for other
teams. His words might have stung a little more had Rhodes been
using either player. Owner Jeff Lurie and vice president Joe Banner
have started looking at replacements for Rhodes, who is 9-20-1 in
the last 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   Replay redux
</P>
<P>
   The league's competititon committee will meet by conference call
Tuesday to discuss the possibility of instant replay for the
playoffs. Both co-chairmen, Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren and Tampa
Bay GM Rich McKay, concede the committee is split and the concept
probably won't even come before the entire league membership.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of derogatory remarks by defensive tackle Joe
Phillips, Rams officials are rethinking the future of coach Dick
Vermeil and staff. Phillips sounded off about Vermeil's 3 1/2-hour
practices and president John Shaw fears the Rams will have problems
landing veteran free agents. Former Falcons center Roman Fortin
turned down more money in St. Louis, and signed with San Diego,
because of Vermeil's practices. ... The 49ers are trying to extend
the contract of wideout Terrell Owens before the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
