<SLUG> BC-FBN-ODDS-ENDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-minutes with 49ers tailback Garrison Hearst
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: San Francisco 49ers tailback Garrison Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: Long-distance scoring plays.
</P>
<P>
   Background: A first-round pick by Arizona in 1993, Hearst, a
former University of Georgia star, is in his sixth season and with
his third team. Through 13 games, Hearst already has a career-best
1,224 rushing yards, his third 1,000-yard season in the last four.
Hearst has added the big play to his repertoire this year. He has
four touchdowns _ three runs and one reception _ of 70-plus yards.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You started the year with a 96-yard touchdown run in overtime
of the opener. What do you remember about that play?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nearly suffocating to death with all those people piled on
top of me. Even after watching tapes, it's hard to believe. I'd run
10 yards, break a tackle then run 10 more yards. I thought I'd die
when I hit the 20 (yard line).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is straight-line speed the primary component to long
touchdown plays?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, I think you have to be more slow, in a patient
sense, than fast. You don't see many guys just sprint 70 yards
untouched. You have to set up your blocks well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But there are times, like on last week's 71-yard run at
Carolina, when everything is blocked perfectly, you break clean
into the secondary, and it's all over.
</P>
<P>
   A: You get those mostly in short yardage, when (the defense) is
bunched at the line of scrimmage. Those are the ones you dream
about.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON . . .
</P>
<P>
   Veteran: In his first two seasons, Bills wideout Eric Moulds
totaled 49 catches, 573 yards and two touchdowns. His numbers for
1998 project to 67 receptions, 1,362 yards and 10 scores. He faces
aggressive coverage today from Oakland's Charles Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie: Pittsburgh's playoff hopes and running game are on
life-support. Unless rookie guard Alan Faneca can handle Tampa Bay
tackles Warren Sapp and Brad Culpepper today, the Steelers are
doomed. A tough in-line blocker, Faneca struggles against
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent: In three seasons, quarterback Jamie Martin has
thrown only 68 passes. He gets his first career start today in
place of Jacksonville's injured Mark Brunell. The running game, led
by Fred Taylor, is peaking, but Martin has to hold things together.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Two weeks ago it looked as if the Cardinals were headed
to the playoffs for the first time since 1982. Having faltered
against an easy schedule, however, Vince Tobin could be in trouble
with owner Bill Bidwill. Tobin needs a victory against lame duck
Ray Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   TIP SHEET
</P>
<P>
   With the Detroit Lions having taken a step backward in Bobby
Ross' second season, tailback Barry Sanders is distressed enough to
have started looking down the road to retirement for the first
time. ... The NFL pulled a classic end run on vice president George
Young and director of officiating Jerry Seeman last week, leaving
them in the dark about its attempts to resurrect instant replay in
the postseason. Young and Seeman met with commissioner Paul
Tagliabue all day Monday, but were not apprised of plans to float a
replay trial balloon later that night. ... San Diego president Dean
Spanos wants to get a contract extension with general manager Bobby
Beathard, who has just one year remaining on his current deal. ...
Carolina owner Jerry Richardson wanted another shot at luring Joe
Gibbs out of retirement. That became a moot point when the former
Washington coach teamed up with Phoenix businessman Sam Grossman on
a bid for the Redskins. ... It's still a good bet Tim Couch will be
in the draft, but the Kentucky quarterback recently called the NFL
Players Association for Peyton Manning's telephone number so that
he could discuss the decision with him.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   Coaches like Mike Holmgren of Green Bay and Tampa Bay's Tony
Dungy spoke out against the league's trial balloon of restoring
instant replay for the postseason. ``If you're a guy like Dennis
Erickson in Seattle, and you lost a game (to poor officiating), it
wouldn't seem fair,'' Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   A day after Cincinnati punter Lee Johnson suggested the Bengals
would improve only when the team's front office was upgraded, owner
Mike Brown released the 14-year vet and fined him one game check _
$20,588 _ for conduct detrimental to the team. Given the Bengals'
eight-game losing streak, Johnson must have plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   THE LIST
</P>
<P>
