<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collins finding Saints redeeming
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kerry Collins says he's not looking for redemption,
but he's having a hard time outrunning his checkered past.
</P>
<P>
   The story is old news: Several players said he quit on the
Carolina Panthers two months ago by walking into the office of
coach Dom Capers a couple days after a 51-23 loss in Atlanta and
saying his heart wasn't in it. Collins insists he didn't quit. He
said he told Capers that he should be benched ``If I'm the reason
this (0-4 start) is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was waived early the following week, and his agent
arranged for Collins to plead his case on national television. He
looked foolish, and his image continued to take a pounding. It got
worse in the wee hours of the morning after the Saints' Nov. 1 game
at Carolina, when Collins was arrested in Charlotte on suspicions
of drunken driving. None of it helped a man who reportedly had
alcohol-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   But as Collins gets ready to make his fifth start for the
Saints, who claimed him off waivers Oct. 14, he says he doesn't
care about history. It will be his fourth appearance, three as a
starter, against the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely am aware (of the image),'' Collins said. ``But
I'm worried about the guys on this team and getting ready to play
three tough ball games. That will take care of itself. I've always
been a guy who has played hard and played every game to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After not playing for four games in New Orleans, Collins hasn't
been spectacular. In fact, his four-game statistics are inferior to
those of Billy Joe Tolliver, his backup; Collins has completed 60
of 122 passes for 827 yards and three touchdowns and has thrown six
interceptions and been sacked 14 times. But he led New Orleans to a
resounding victory against Dallas on Sunday, and the
quarterback-starved city thinks it has found its man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing he's not, and you can talk to our players to
a man _ he's not a quitter,'' Ditka said. ``He may get flustered at
times and make a mistake or two, but he's not a quitter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints are interested in signing Collins to a new contract
after the season. ``Kerry is a guy who can be very good in this
league if he dedicates himself to it,'' Ditka said. ``We're
interested, but . . . that will come down to him and his agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Collins still sees a psychologist, as mandated by the
league. And he'd prefer his on-field performance speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish,'' he said, ``that things . . . in my private life
would stay private.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Collins
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback
</P>
<P>
   Age: 25
</P>
<P>
   Height, weight: 6-5, 240 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: West Lawn, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   College: Penn State. He was All-American and a Heisman Trophy
finalist in 1994, leading the Nittany Lions to a 12-0 record and a
38-20 victory over Oregon in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Single. Was selected by the Detroit Tigers as a
pitcher in the 26th round of the 1990 draft and in the 58th round
by Toronto in '94.
</P>
<P>
   Professional: Collins was the fifth overall selection of the
1995 draft, selected by Carolina with a pick acquired from
Cincinnati. He began the season with a career passer rating of
65.3. His best season was in '96, when he had a 79.4 passer rating,
completing 204 of 381 passes (53.5 percent) for 2,454 yards, 14
touchdowns and nine interceptions. He started 14 games and helped
lead the Panthers to the NFC West title and the NFC Championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
