</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers use caution, careful consideration in picking goalie
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ THRASHERS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   If goaltending makes or breaks any hockey team, it follows that
Thrashers general manager Don Waddell will draw on several
resources before drafting a goalie in the expansion or amateur
drafts next June. But he will not rely merely on his team's
scouting staff. Waddell plans to hire a goaltending consultant for
six months, and is on the verge of signing the recently retired
Andy Moog. If signed, Moog would be the highest-profile hire by the
Thrashers to date. He played on three Stanley Cup winners with the
Edmonton Oilers and competed for four teams before retiring in June
after 18 seasons. Moog, who also played for the 1988 Canadian
Olympic team, went 372-209-88 with a 3.13 goals-against average in
713 games with Edmonton, Boston, Dallas and Montreal. He also
played in four All-Star Games. If hired, Moog would scout NHL
goalies who might be left unprotected by their teams, as well as
the top four or five amateurs. ... Reporters asked Waddell at last
week's league meetings in Arizona if he was going to hire Marc
Crawford as his coach. ``I told them what I've been saying all
along _ I'm not going to begin that process for a couple of
months,'' he said. Crawford, who left Colorado in a dispute after
last season, has expressed interest in the Thrashers job. ...
Waddell and assistant general manager Les Jackson were in Orlando
last week to explore the possibility of setting up training camp
there next year and having the IHL's Solar Bears as the Thrashers'
minor-league affiliate. ... The Thrashers plan to bring in some
season-ticket holders to get a gauge on the team's recent marketing
efforts and visibility. ... Greg Stathis, who coaches Georgia
Tech's club hockey team, conducted the team's skating clinic
Saturday at the ``Coke on Ice'' rink adjacent to Underground. The
clinics are held Saturday mornings in conjunction with the Boys &AMP;
Girls Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE CREASE: DOMINIK HASEK
</P>
<P>
   Pos., team: Goalie, Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Pardubice, Czech Republic
</P>
<P>
   Update: In four straight starts against Florida, Philadelphia,
Nashville and St. Louis, he went 3-0-1, allowing only four goals on
139 shots for a saves percentage of .971. He leads the league at
.942 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   On using his head to make a save: ``I'm not afraid to stop the
puck with my head. I try to do it sometimes even in practice. I say
to me teammates, 'Shoot me in my head.' Maybe other people think of
a different way to make a save.''
</P>
<P>
   On whether NHL players should go back to the Olympics: ``I think
so. It's the only competition in the world where all the best
players can meet and play for their country, and it's only every
four years.''
</P>
<P>
   On whether two extra feet between the net and end boards has
helped forwards: ``I think it helps the goalies and the defense.
Before the puck hit the board and (bounced) right away in front of
the net. I think, to be honest, the NHL made a mistake moving the
goal line.''
</P>
<P>
   FIT TO BE TIED
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has been studying ways to minimize tie games in the
regular season, and here's why. The percentage of games that remain
tied after overtime is on the rise in the last three years.
Following is a 10-year breakdown of total games played, overtime
games, completed ties and percentage of ties to overtimes.
</P>
