</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Valley of the Funds on the West side
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Things like this don't happen by coincidence. The NHL
held its Board of Governors meetings in the Phoenix area last week
and commissioner Gary Bettman used the stage to help the Coyotes
pressure local governments for a new arena, dangling the
possibility of landing the All-Star Game in return. No question,
this is prime time to ask for a new building. The Coyotes were a
league-best 16-3-3 going into their game at Ottawa Saturday night,
leaving the Dallas Stars in the unfamiliar position of second
place. But Bettman and ownership had better tiptoe through this
arena subject. Jerry Colangelo _ owner of the Arizona Diamondbacks,
Phoenix Suns, America West Arena and BankOne Ballpark _ is not at
the height of popularity these days after helping orchestrate $253
million in public money to build a new baseball stadium. There is
nothing wrong with America West Arena, except that it was built for
basketball, not hockey. Consequently, 4,300 upper-level seats have
an obstructed view of the ice. The Coyotes have lost $4 million a
year since moving from Winnipeg three years ago. The plan is to
build an arena adjacent to an old mall in Scottsdale. Ironically,
the Coyotes plan to move out of an arena owned by Colangelo, who
helped Bettman lure the team. The Coyotes are in the third year of
a five-year lease agreement. ``The Suns and America West are both
successful,'' Bettman said. ``The bottom line is the Coyotes need a
place to play of their own. Long-term, in its present
configuration, America West has a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado climate warms The heat is temporarily off Colorado
general manager Pierre Lacroix and coach Bob Hartley _ one for
expediting the departure of Marc Crawford, the other for replacing
him. The Avalanche, which started the year 0-4-1, was on a 9-3-1
streak going into New Jersey Saturday, including a five-game
winning streak. ``It was with hard work that we came out of that
torture,'' Hartley said. ... When Nashville third-string goalie
Tomas Vokoun, recalled from the minors because of injuries, stopped
34 of 35 shots against San Jose in a 2-1 win, it was the first time
in seven games the Predators won a game without Mike Dunham in
goal. ... Los Angeles president Tim Leiweke, concerned about a
dwindling season-ticket base as the Kings flounder the year before
moving into a new arena, sent a ``we still believe in this team''
letter to ticketholders. Asked what kind of reaction he got to the
letters, Leiweke responded, ``Some said, `Class act.' Others said,
``If you don't make the playoffs, it will be our last year.' '' ...
No, Vancouver hasn't traded Pavel Bure yet. The Rangers remain at
the center of rumors, but, then again, they're at the center of
every trade rumor. ... Glen SatherFelix PotvinBob Essensa Tony
Amonte
</P>
</TEXT>
