<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cancellation raises hard questions
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the sake of argument, let's pretend officials
canceled the 1998-99 NBA season today. Now let's ask some hard
questions about the game:
</P>
<P>
   Before the league can begin play again, it must decide the draft
rotation. Would the Clippers get the first pick again?
</P>
<P>
   When will the players and union rejoin negotiations? And when
would the league begin play? Before another season can start, the
league and the union still must come to an agreement. There were no
negotiations last summer because the players filed an
unfair-labor-practices complaint that was withdrawn on the eve of a
ruling. Then they filed for lost wages and were beaten again,
delaying negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   When will they start talking? Next September? When will they
start playing? Next December?
</P>
<P>
   And with new arenas opening in Atlanta, Los Angeles,
Indianapolis and Toronto, what happens to season-ticket sales and
pre-paid suites?
</P>
<P>
   Other important questions: What happens to this season's
contracts? Are they wiped out? What happens to the next group of
free agents, including Allen Iverson, Stephon Marbury, Ray Allen,
Kobe Bryant, Antoine Walker, Toni Kukoc, Zydrunas Ilgauskas, Steve
Nash, Mitch Richmond, Vin Baker, Jeff Hornacek and John Stockton?
Can Shaquille O'Neal, Penny Hardaway and Grant Hill invoke escape
clauses?
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern defers any answers. ``You want to take
all of our lawyers' fun away,'' Stern said. ``There are probably a
thousand different questions that are now being compiled at
considerable hourly expense, as we contemplate a first in
professional sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Threat to cancel a ploy?
</P>
<P>
   Too much pessimism? OK. Suppose they reach agreement. Union
members remain skeptical about the league's resolve to cancel.
Union chief Billy Hunter underscored that sentiment when he assured
80 agents, many of them quite angry, that there will be a season.
</P>
<P>
   The union leader says the league is following the example set by
the NHL during the 1994-95 season. The NHL All-Star Game was
canceled the second week of December and there were no negotiations
until Jan. 7, when a around-the-clock negotiations resulted in a
48-game season. Some think the NBA could push back its championship
to accommodate more games.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy commissioner Russ Granik says there have been no formal
discussions with NBC. ``I think that we may be able to get an extra
week or 10 days or so, but that's about it,'' he said. ``I don't
think that it makes any sense to us or to them to put the Finals on
into July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Households using television drops so dramatically as you
approach the July 4th weekend, that I don't think that is a
realistic possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 14 start not viable
</P>
<P>
   Can the league start as late as All-Star weekend, Feb. 14, and
still have a viable season?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I don't think so,'' Stern said. ``I am going to leave that
to the board of governors. But my personal view is, no, not at all.
And I don't think we would ever do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Demise of the NBA possible
</P>
<P>
   And here's the commissioner's icy view of the future: ``If we
and our players, who are ultimately going to have to work together
to rebuild this sport, can't make this deal, I don't think there is
that much hope for the sport itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe the hype
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a few players have protested the lockout. But now
the strident Charles Oakley weighs in with his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Losing out on a $10 million balloon payment, the Atlanta
resident, who was traded from New York to Toronto, speaks for all
the have-nots: ``I always see where they put the microphones when
they come out of these meetings, only with the franchise players.
They don't let the little man speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they ought to put the microphones next to the guy who's
making $350,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley says the status quo exists ``because you have all these
so-called franchise players who aren't leaders, who don't make
anybody better and don't even make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league has become all about fake superstars, about
hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners hold all the cards
</P>
<P>
   And here's the view of agent Harold MacDonald, so at odds with
David Falk and Arn Tellem that client Derrick Coleman, a '94 Dream
Team member, was not invited to play next weekend in Atlantic City,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald assails union leadership, saying: ``I don't think they
ever recognized how strong and organized the owners are. The owners
were never going to back off of a hard cap. But the union
leadership called the owners' bluff and got the players to fall on
the sword for a soft cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is almost impossible to make a deal without the players
having to say it's a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there back in 1994 in Minneapolis when David Stern
signed his (new) contract with the league. He told the owners then,
'Don't hire me if you are not willing to back me all the way on
getting a hard cap.'''
</P>
<P>
   Layups
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley is hurting. Additional problems were discovered
when Barkley underwent surgery for a hernia. He's still
recuperating. ...
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Rick Majerus isn't being kind when he says about Kobe
Bryant: ``He's heading more in the direction of Dominique Wilkins
than Michael Jordan.'' Wilkins' No. 21 will be retired by the
Hawks, if he ever leaves the game. At age 38, he wants at least one
more NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
