<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH13-COX     12-12 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich bows out to tribute
 &HT;    By Clint Williams and Duane Stanford
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COBB COUNTY, Ga. _ More than 600 people put holiday preparations
on hold Saturday and packed a Cobb County high school auditorium to
pay tribute to House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is leaving Congress in January after resigning amid
criticism that he failed to engineer Republican gains in the
November elections. He gave the overflow crowd at his final town
hall meeting a long look at his agenda for the future, but made
only brief mention of the current impeachment debate in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American should read the report of the Judiciary
Committee next week,'' Gingrich said. ``Every American should take
the future of their country seriously. Every American should decide
what the rule of law and the Constitution require. And every
American should make up their own mind as a matter of conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said there was no need to add to the public debate
``because the calmer we are, the more factual we are and the more
we look at the big picture and the future of our children's country
... the clearer it will be to every American what the appropriate
outcome is.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, and in a letter to constituents distributed at
the meeting, Gingrich said that he went to Congress 20 years ago
with the goals of cutting taxes, balancing the federal budget,
reforming welfare, defeating the Soviet empire and establishing a
Republican majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1998, we had accomplished every major goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who won re-election to his Sixth District seat by a
landslide, told the crowd he decided not to run again for speaker
because criticism focusing on him was diverting attention from
additional goals he wanted to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I was speaker, I was the excuse,'' Gingrich said.
``The fact is that I was the excuse for Clinton. The fact is that I
was the excuse for the Republicans who didn't want to learn how to
be the majority. The fact is that I was the excuse for the news
media that doesn't want to think about the issues and just wants to
cover stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he decided not to run for speaker, resigning from Congress
was the next logical step, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can have two head coaches on a team,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich announced he would not run for another term as speaker
shortly after being re-elected to Sixth District congressional
seat. His decision to resign from Congress came days later.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation is effective at noon Jan. 3. A special election
to fill the seat is expected in February.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich said he and his wife aren't going from Capitol Hill
to the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving public office, but we're not leaving public
life,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will speak out for Social Security reform and
redefining America's role in the world. And he will work to shorten
the time it takes for state-of-the-art medical research to become
standard practice in the typical doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said changing the Social Security system is his top
priority. He proposed allowing people to put 3 percent of their
income into a private retirement account instead of into the Social
Security system. The current federal budget surplus could be used
to make up the difference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his remarks, Carol Hughes, chairwoman of Gingrich's
disabilities task force, presented him with a book, ``Dinosaur
Hunters,'' in recognition of his fossil-collecting hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, whose son uses a wheelchair, praised Gingrich as a
compassionate champion for the disabled and triggered a sustained
standing ovation when she said, ``There is not another leader in
the world today of his caliber.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people lined up in the aisles of the Walton High
School auditorium to speak to Gingrich, and to a person they
offered thanks and praise. A few in the crowd held up signs of
support, but many more cradled camcorders to record the speaker's
last town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Widow Diane Davis grew emotional has she thanked Gingrich for
his support of the ``innocent spouse'' law, which protects spouses
from being forced to pay the delinquent tax bills of their late, or
former, husbands or wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the day when I can vote for you for
president of the United States of America,'' said Davis, who was
released from an IRS lein for taxes her husband owed.
</P>
<P>
   Though the meeting went far beyond its scheduled time, some of
Gingrich's supporters wished he had said more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had mentioned education in the state of Georgia,''
said Dan Buyers, a 27-year-old commercial Realtor from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers, who filled out ``A Farewell Note to Newt'' on a form
passed around by the speaker's staff, said he would like to see
Gingrich focus his expertise as an educator locally. Buyers
believes Gingrich can use his leadership talents to make Georgia a
testing ground for improving public education. If successful,
Buyers said, Gingrich could take the formula to the nation in a
year 2000 presidential election bid.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Eidell, 50, a Roswell sales manager in the funeral
industry, wanted Gingrich to say more about tax reform. However,
Eidell was pleased that Gingrich had discussed overhauling the
Social Security program by giving individuals more control of the
fund. Eidell, a volunteer with Citizens for an Alternative Tax
System, said giving ``control back to the people'' is fundamental
to both reform movements.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
