<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      12-12 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL APPROVES FOURTH IMPEACHMENT CHARGE, REJECTS CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee, nearly united in
disdain for President Clinton's misconduct but irreparably split
over the appropriate sanction, approved a fourth impeachment charge
Saturday against the president and rejected a resolution to censure
him.
</P>
<P>
   In the last public act of the committee's historic drama, the
Republican-controlled panel voted along party lines, 21-16, to
recommend Clinton's impeachment for allegedly abusing the power of
his office by lying to Congress about his extramarital affair with
a former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic censure alternative lost several hours later,
22-14, as Representative Robert C. Scott, a Virginia Democrat,
joined every Republican in opposing the option. Scott and
Representative Maxine Waters of California, who voted present,
complained that Clinton has been treated unjustly in the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Amid high solemnity tinged with raw political posturing, the
climactic votes unfolded as members of both parties jockeyed
fiercely to sway a critical bloc of undecided lawmakers who are
expected to decide Clinton's fate when the impeachment saga reaches
the House floor on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the struggle for the hearts and souls of the
undecideds will escalate in the final days before the showdown, as
the White House, Republican leaders, and advocacy groups on both
sides of the issue wage campaigns to seize the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The decibel level had risen since the panel approved three
articles of impeachment the day before: two counts of perjury and
one count of obstructing justice, all arising from Clinton's
alleged attempt to coverup his sexual liaisons with Lewinsky in the
Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the committee's action in the face of what polls say
is overwhelming public support for a censure and opposition to
impeachment, the panel's chairman, Representative Henry J. Hyde,
said the multiple allegations of perjury and obstruction against
Clinton warrant the only constitutional remedy available to
Congress: his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Censure, Hyde said, ``is similar to yelling at a teenager. It
purges you of your emotional feelings, but I don't know what it
accomplishes.''
</P>
<P>
   A prime sponsor of the censure resolution, Representative
William D. Delahunt of Quincy, cited the public preference for the
alternative sanction, which was first proposed by a Republican,
former President Gerald R. Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution is not a suicide pact,'' Delahunt said. ``It
does not compel us to detonate a nuclear explosion when light
artillery will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had appealed the day earlier for a censure to
resolve his impeachment crisis, was flying to the Middle East
Saturday when the committee snubbed his plea.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, special counsel Gregory Craig warned that
the enduring impeachment process could have dire consequences for
the country _ and possibly the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the goal of the partisan majority on the committee is to
impeach the president and remove him from office, the certain
result would be to divide the country, gridlock the government, and
defy the will of the people,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, hinting at a possible backlash against the Republican
majority, added: ``In the end, the American people will make the
final judgment about whether the impeachment of the president is in
the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending a fractious, two-month inquiry, committee Republicans
Saturday abruptly dropped three of the four proposed sections of
the abuse-of-power charge. The move was approved, 29-5, with three
Democrats voting present on the premise that the amended article is
no less offensive than the original measure.
</P>
<P>
   Under the changes, Clinton no longer is at risk of losing his
office for misleading the American people by denying he had sexual
relations with Lewinsky. He also will not face charges that he
``willfully made false and misleading statements'' to his Cabinet
and top aides.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the scope of the fourth article was narrowed, at
the urging of Representative George W. Gekas, a Pennsylvania
Republican, by removing a reference to Clinton's assertion of
executive privilege to try to limit testimony that was sought by
investigators in the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the fourth impeachment article charges Clinton with
making ``perjurious, false, and misleading statements'' in his
responses to 81 questions from the committee asking him to admit to
aspects of the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde called Clinton's responses ``an assault on the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats said the 81 questions were an unfair ploy to
force Clinton to admit guilt despite his constitutional right to be
presumed innocent. They also chided Republicans for recommending
removing Clinton from office over responses to questions about
intimate details of his private, consensual sex life, and about
gifts that he and Lewinsky exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   One perjury charge in the article alleges that Clinton abused
the power of his office in answering a question about gifts he
bought at the Black Dog on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not there were additional gifts from the Black Dog
cannot possibly be grounds for removal of the president of the
United States,'' said Representative Zoe Lofgren, a California
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In defeat, the censure plan's future remains highly uncertain,
though it looms as a potentially decisive factor in whether Clinton
will be allowed to serve the remainder of his term with the taint
of a congressional rebuke or will suffer the grave indignity of a
Senate trial that could force him to forfeit the presidency in
shame.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in both parties believe a censure vote in the full
House would prevail because it would permit undecided moderate
Republicans to express their outrage at Clinton's misdeeds without
endorsing the step of ousting a president without an election.
</P>
<P>
   But House Republican leaders have steadfastly refused to
sanction a censure vote. And several Democrats said they might only
be swayed by public pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be a censure resolution on the House floor,''
Delahunt said, ``unless the American people become engaged in the
process and stand up and demand it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that bordered at times on the surreal, the Judiciary
Committee executed what many members described as their most
serious duty other than declaring war as the rest of official
Washington was shuttered for the weekend and much of the public was
congregating at Christmas tree lots and holiday shopping spots.
</P>
<P>
   The censure resolution also was pushed by the committee's other
two Massachusetts Democrats: Representatives Barney Frank of Newton
and Martin T. Meehan of Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said lawmakers should not think ``the president will just
laugh at a censure resolution and there will be champagne toasts at
the White House.'' To support his assertion, he cited Frank's
comments last week about the effect of his reprimand by the House
for an ethics violation stemming from his relationship with a male
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell you that having been reprimanded by this House of
Representatives, where I'm so proud to serve, was no triviality,''
Frank said. ``It is not something that is a matter of pride. I wish
I could go back and undo it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
