<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 12/12/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- NY-MEXICANS-GUADALUPE, 12-12
-- Mexican runners with lighted torches Saturday before the start
of a marathon outside the Church of Our Lady of Guadalupe in
Manhattan. With impassioned prayers, adoring serenades, candles and
wave upon wave of red roses, thousands of Mexican immigrants across
New York rejoiced in the Feast of Our Lady of Guadalupe,
celebrating the Virgin they revere as their patron in Masses.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- Dec. 12, 1998 --
CASINOS-POKER-PAYCUT, 12-12 -- Okham Rathpakey dealing poker at the
national championships at the Taj Mahal. Ms. Rathpakeys says she
took a waitress job for a time, to make up for a recent drop in
tips. ``When the players' luck is bad a lot of them blame the
dealer,'' she says. ``They swear at you or throw their cards. But
when they win, what do they do? Most of them throw you a dollar.''
(Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-12 -- During
the House Judiciary Committee vote on articles of impeachment
Saturday, above, from left, Reps. Bill McCollum, Republican of
Florida; F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., Republican of Wisconsin; a
counsel to the majority; Henry Hyde, Republican of Illinois. Below,
Reps. Sheila Jackson-Lee, Democrat of Texas; Maxine Waters,
Democrat of California; Martin Meehan, Democrat of Massachusetts.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) RAMALLAH, West Bank -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- PALESTINE-STATE,
12-12 -- Palestinians are enjoying many new symbols of sovereignty,
among them a national flag, which this unemployed man uses for his
midday prayers. The Palestinians, with a relatively sizable
intellectual elite, international help and the model of Israel,
have moved more quickly and closer toward developing democratic
institutions than any of their Arab neighbors, experts say. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) TARRYTOWN, N.Y. -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- IMPEACH-REACT-2,
12-12 -- Paul Janos, 43, a candidate for mayor of Tarrytown says
that he does not think the president should be exempt from laws.
``I know that a lot of people are tired of it, myself included, but
what's right is right, what's wrong is wrong,'' he says of Clinton.
But he wonders, ``Is it worth the turmoil?'' ``I'm afraid of what
the market reaction will be.'' (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TARRYTOWN, N.Y. -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- IMPEACH-REACT-1,
12-12 -- As the House Judiciary Committee approves articles of
impeachment against President Clinton, the seriousness of the
situation began to sink in around the historic village of
Tarrytown, N.Y. Still, others have been shutting out the issue.
Darron Copeland, 32, a tax accountant from Stamford, Conn., with
Stacy Belkind, 44, of Tarrytown. ``I would rather watch the History
Channel than 30 seconds of political commentary these days,'' says
Copeland. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BIRNEY, Mont. -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- MONTANA-RAIL-2, 12-12
-- Irv Alderson, a 68-year-old rancher, and his daughter Jeanie,
owners of the Bones Brothers Ranch, are opposed to a $385 million
railroad link that would bisect the Montana's Tongue River Valley.
The cost to the valley, they say, will be unbearable. ``It's
already split the community,'' says Alderson. ``There's people who
don't speak to each other anymore.'' (Jim Robbins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BIRNEY, Mont. -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- MONTANA-RAIL-1, 12-12
-- Montana's Tongue River Valley, may seem peaceful, but a proposal
to build a $385 million rail link to haul coal from the isolated
area has divided residents, some of whom see a bonanza and others a
disaster waiting to happen. The proposed rail line would bring
startling change to an area where stillness is broken only by
cattle lowing or an occasional tractor-trailer hauling livestock.
(Jim Robbins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Dec. 12, 1998 -- HOG-FARMER-WOES, 12-12 -- Rex
Hoppes feeding his pigs on his 160-acre farm near Indianola, Iowa.
The near-collapse of the market for hogs -- his now sell for far
less than last year -- has forced him to take money out of a
retirement account to keep going and has led him to question his
lifelong dream of being a hog farmer. (Rodney White/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
