<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6764 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-BOS &LR;      12-12 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ARRIVES IN MIDDLE EAST FOR THREE-DAY VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Far from the bitter impeachment hearings threatening
to engulf his office, President Clinton arrived Saturday to carry
out a historic and personal commitment to overcome the mistrust
between Israelis and Palestinians that has blocked a path to peace.
</P>
<P>
   At an airport ceremony last night that began a challenging
three-day mission, including the first visit by a US president to
Palestinian territory, Clinton urged both sides to live up to the
commitments in the troubled land-for-security deal they signed in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that for two peoples who are fated to share this
land, peace is not simply an option,'' Clinton said, ``but the only
choice that can avert still more years of bloodshed, apprehension,
and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it was the right thing to do,'' Clinton said of the
deal concluded after nine days of dogged diplomacy at the Wye River
Plantation in Maryland. ``I believe it now. But both sides must now
face the challenge of implementing Wye.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton concluded the remarks by saying: ``It is good to be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a stange twist of fate that Clinton's journey back into
the lion's den of Mideast conflict seems to offer him political
shelter from the storm of controversy he left behind in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But this trip will be anything but easy.
</P>
<P>
   New Israeli ultimatums and bloody West Bank street clashes,
which continued Saturday, have stalled the Wye agreement. The
visit, planned in October to celebrate the success of Wye, now has
become a mission to salvage it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began immediately trying to sell the benefits of moving
forward on peace to embittered Israelis and Palestinians, an effort
their own leaders have failed to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his trip, the fourth to Israel in his presidency,
was to honor a promise he made at Wye ``to speak with the people of
Israel and the Palestinians about the benefits of peace, and to
stand by you as you take risks for a just, lasting, and secure
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Many security analysts indicated Clinton may be taking his own
risks as violence and threats of violence have been heightened by
extremists intent on destroying the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 Israeli military and police were on duty last
night to ensure Clinton's safety as Air Force One touched down in
Tel Aviv and the president, Mrs. Clinton, and their daughter,
Chelsea, were shuttled by helicopter to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the arrival, violent clashes continued in the
West Bank town of Bethlehem, where Clinton is to light a Christmas
tree on Monday. Saturday, near the birthplace of Jesus, tear gas
and acrid black smoke from street clashes enveloped a banner that
read ``Bill Clinton: Welcome to Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian protesters have taken to the street in angry protest
because they say Israel has not met a commitment to release
hundreds of Palestinians jailed for anti-Israel activities.
</P>
<P>
   In a verbal agreement at Wye, Israel agreed to release some 750
Palestinian prisoners. In the first phase last month, Israel
released 250 prisoners, but most of them were common criminals,
many of whom had only a short time left on their sentences. The
Palestinians claim the agreement was to free what they call
``political prisoners,'' those involved in the political and armed
struggle against Israel. But Netanyahu insists he will release none
with ``blood on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said Saturday the release of
more ``political prisoners'' would be ``a real indication Israel is
implementing'' the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the prisoners, Clinton will face deep challenges in
confronting other issues that threaten the Wye agreement. The
agreement spelled out specific steps that the Palestinians must
take to step up its fight against terrorism aimed at Israel in
exchange for Israeli troop withdrawls from 13 percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel last week issued an ultimatum, saying that it would
not cede any more West Bank land to Palestinians in the aftermath
of violent street clashes that Israel claims were provoked by
Palestinian leaders. Chilling videotape of an attack by Palestinian
stone throwers on an Israeli citizen and a soldier put intense
domestic pressure on Netanyahu to act.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the violence in his ultimatum, Netanyahu said Israel
would cede no more West Bank land until Arafat clearly retracted
repeated statements that he would unilaterally declare a
Palestinian state in May, the expiration of the five-year peace
process that began in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   This left both sides claiming that the other has violated the
Wye agreement. It will be a difficult task, analysts said, for
Clinton to re-establish trust between the two sides in time for the
next scheduled phase of Israeli troop redeployments set for the end
of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism looms large in this presidential visit. Israelis worry
that Clinton's visit to the Palestinian areas may put a kind of
unofficial blessing on a future Palestinian state. The Palestinian
leaders are thrilled with that impression.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's senior aide David Bar-Illan said, ``We are concerned
that this trip will turn into an endorsement of a state, because it
has the trappings of a state visit. It concerns us because it
encourages the Palestinians to believe that they can indeed discard
the Oslo process by unilaterally declaring a state. We are looking
for a clear message from the president that this is not
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   At the red-carpet arrival for Clinton last night, an Israeli
military band played an old Zionist song from before the founding
of the state of Israel in 1948. Titled ``Tomorrow,'' The main
stanza was an ironic reminder of just how enduring are the
Israelis' hopes for peace in a secure state, and how Israel's
founders knew that would take a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The song says, ``All this will come tomorrow, if not today, and
if not tomorrow then the next day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
