<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGSMAIN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    L.A. signs Brown for $105M
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ A pitcher with just one 20-win season to his
credit and who has not won a Cy Young Award buzzed baseball's
salary structure Saturday. Kevin Brown is the game's first $100
million man.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers outlasted Baltimore and Colorado in a
fierce bidding war to lock Brown into a seven-year $105 million
deal that spun the winter meetings with its largesse. The agreement
includes no deferred payments and allows for twice-monthly charter
jet flights from his Macon home to L.A. at the club's expense
during the season to allow Brown's wife Candace and the couple's
young sons to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a (financial) position we did not want to exceed,''
said Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone. ``We pushed it as far as
we could. We went as far as we thought we'd have to go. We could
not go any further.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal ended Randy Johnson's reign as the game's highest paid
player at just two weeks. Brown will average $15 million a year
compared to Johnson's $13.1 million via his five-year $65.1 million
deal with Arizona. Pedro Martinez, whose $76 million deal with
Boston was finalized a year ago Saturday, earns $12.5 million year.
Atlanta's Greg Maddux could be a bargain with a $10 million average
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about an hour ago, I got a lot smarter,'' said incoming
Dodger manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   If Major League Baseball had any reservations about allowing
communications magnate Rupert Murdoch to buy the Dodgers this year,
those thoughts were being revisited even before the L.A. management
evacuated the podium. The Dodgers payroll at the end of the season
stood at $60.7 million and has now jumped to $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there's reason for surprise but there is reason
for disappointment,'' said Sandy Alderson, executive vice president
for baseball operations for MLB. ``As a former GM (with Oakland),
I'm alarmed by the contract. As a member of the commissioner's
office, I'm alarmed by the contract. And as a fan, I'm alarmed by
the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final stages, St. Louis and San Diego were eliminated for
being unwilling to add a seventh year to the deal and though both
the Rockies and Orioles expressed willingness to up the bid,
according to Malone, agent Scott Boras ended the process then.
Brown, the former Georgia Tech star, heads up a rotation that
includes Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort, Carlos Perez and Ismael
Valdes while throwing Dave Mlicki's fate into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it,'' Johnson said. ``There's going
to be a lot of swagger there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who did not attend the announcement, will be 41 when the
contract expires in 2006. Only four pitchers have ever recorded
20-win seasons at age 40 (Phil Niekro, Warren Spahn, Grover
Cleveland Alexander and Cy Young) and only Young won 20 at 41. The
Dodgers countered that Brown's durability is excellent (only Maddux
matches his 1,400 innings over the last seven years) and would not
apologize about the terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do, what the Dodgers do, what the major market teams
do, we can't really change,'' said Malone, former GM with
cash-strapped Montreal. ``The smaller markets have limitations. I
do not see how we can change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
