<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HISTORY-BOS &LR;      12-12 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FRAMERS, PROCESS WAS ALL ABOUT POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's all politics.
</P>
<P>
   That's the dour conclusion many Americans, especially President
Clinton's staunch defenders, will probably reach as they consider
the House Judiciary Committee's mostly party-line votes for four
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But, to a degree, that's exactly what the framers of the
Constitution intended. Impeachment is, by design, a politician's
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on politics also explains why the House might vote
this week mostly along party lines to impeach Clinton, and it sheds
light on why the Senate could be likely to acquit Clinton in a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the talk last week about whether Clinton committed
perjury, the fact is there is no requirement that any member of
Congress determine the president broke a specific law. This is not
a case in which a defense attorney, such as Johnnie L. Cochran Jr.
in the O.J. Simpson trial, can point to a piece of exculpatory
evidence and say, ``You must acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this is a case in which many Republicans and Democrats
agree on the most important fact _ that Clinton lied about his
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky _ but have come to different
conclusions whether that is an impeachable offense. It is a
political choice.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, the first
Democrat to come to the Senate floor earlier this year and strongly
condemn Clinton's actions, said he could conclude Clinton committed
perjury and still vote to acquit him in a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite possible that a given member of Congress could
conclude that a president committed a crime, but it was not
sufficiently grave to overrule the result of an election,''
Lieberman said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of argument sends many Republicans into a rage. They
note the Constitution states a president can be impeached for
``treason, bribery and other high crimes and misdemeanors.''
Although the Constitution does not mention perjury, obstruction of
justice or abuse of power, Republicans said they fit into the
``other'' category.
</P>
<P>
   But even House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, in
arguing for impeachment, acknowledged there is no simple way to
define it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment is like beauty,'' Hyde of Illinois said. ``It is
in the eye of the beholder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution is always subject to interpretation, as
emphasized by the murky standard for such a momentous decision as
impeachment. But the clues to understanding what will happen in the
House this week, and possibly in the Senate next year, were written
long ago in the Federalist Papers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Alexander Hamilton foresaw the kind of partisan split
engulfing the Congress today on impeachment. The impeachment of a
president, Hamilton wrote in the Federalist Papers on March 7,
1778, ``will seldom fail to agitate the passions of the whole
community, and to divide it into parties more or less friendly or
inimical to the accused. In many cases it will connect itself with
the pre-existing factions ... in such cases, there will always be
the greatest danger that the decision will be regulated by the
comparative strength of the parties, than by real demonstrations of
innocence or guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Baron, who served in 1988 and 1989 as the Senate counsel in
the last two impeachment trials of federal judges, said those
outcomes demonstrate how the constitutional language is so
``amorphous.'' Former US District Judge Walter Nixon had already
been convicted on charges of lying to a grand jury when his case
came before the Senate, and he was impeached and convicted. But
former US District Judge Alcee Hastings, who had been acquitted in
a criminal trial on bribery and conspiracy charges, also was
convicted by the Senate. Hastings is now a Florida congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really highlights that it is conduct, not whether they were
convicted of a crime,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Baron, who worked as a Democratic counsel on
Capitol Hill, does not think impeachment is warranted in Clinton's
case. He said that just as the impeachment of President Andrew
Johnson in 1868 is now seen as a regrettable and excessive
political sanction, so would the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   The framers of the Constitution could have avoided many
political aspects of impeachment by having the cases heard by the
Supreme Court. But the framers decided instead to make it a
political act that, in most cases, couldn't be controlled by one
party. Thus, the framers made it relatively easy for a political
party to impeach a president with a majority vote in the House, but
difficult to convict him, with a two-thirds vote needed in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   No less an authority than Supreme Court Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, who would preside over the possible Clinton trial in the
Senate, has written that the impeachment system has worked well
because politicians have been able to make the right decision in
the end. In the single instance when the Senate conducted an
impeachment trial of a president, Rehnquist wrote in his 1992 book,
``Grand Inquests,'' the Senate rightly decided by a single vote to
acquit President Andrew Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said the impeachments of Johnson and federal Judge
Samuel Chase had been overly political. ``The importance of these
two acquittals in our constitutional history can hardly be
overstated,'' he wrote. Rehnquist applauded the way the framers of
the Constitution ``left considerable room for `play in the
joints''' for determining to impeach and convict a president.
</P>
<P>
   To Clinton's relief, there is much more ``play in the joints''
in the Senate, which is controlled 55-45 by Republicans, than in
the House. If all senators are present, it would take 67 votes to
convict him, meaning a defection of at least 12 Democrats. In other
words, while the Republican control of the House might lead to
Clinton's impeachment, the framers' insistence upon a two-thirds
vote in the Senate probably will save him.
</P>
<P>
   When the House votes this week on impeachment, the members are
bound to argue that their vote is based on how they interpret the
Constitution. If Hamilton were alive today, he might commiserate
with Clinton. Fourteen years after Hamilton wrote about impeachment
in the Federalist Papers, the treasury secretary was confronted
with allegations he had conducted corrupt stock transactions with a
man named James Reynolds. No, Hamilton responded, he was paying off
Reynolds because he had an affair with Reynolds's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton complained that the ``malicious intrigues to stab me in
the dark ... distract me to a point, which (makes) my situation
scarcely tolerable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
