<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' DEFENSE FINALLY REINFORCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been plenty of ink used to chronicle the resurgence of
Bruins right wing Dmitri Khristich, the heady finesse of center
Jason Allison and the flashy moves of left wing Sergei Samsonov.
Goalie Byron Dafoe is on his way to a potential career year and a
new contract, and his role in the club's recent run has been duly
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that hasn't been recognized as much as it should is
the substantial contribution of the defensive corps. Quick, when
was the last time the Bruins had six or even seven reliable
defensemen? Can't remember? Try 1989-90, the last year the club
went to the Stanley Cup finals. Ray Bourque, Don Sweeney, Garry
Galley, Glen Wesley, Al Pederson, and Bob Beers manned the blue
line.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque and Sweeney remain from that group, and they're now
complemented by Kyle McLaren, Hal Gill, Darren Van Impe, Grant
Ledyard, and Dave Ellett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only remember back 48 months, any more it's a problem,''
said Bourque with a laugh, when the question was posed to him. ``We
kind of had a revolving door there for a while. We had a good,
solid three or four guys, but the fifth and sixth guy were
constantly being changed and not used very much. It's good when you
are able to use people and have confidence in all six guys. Last
year, we lost Donny and we lost Kyle for a while. Van Impe really
came on in the last part of last year and got off to a good start
this year. I think he knows what it's all about now. (The coaches)
feel like they can use everybody. It helps me, and it helps
everybody. I know I'll be out there against the top lines and on
the power play and penalty killing. But if I can't go, someone else
is going to pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he vividly remembers the 1989-90 season because it
was the first time in his career he played the majority of his year
in the NHL. He had split his first pro year the season before in
Maine and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not slighting anybody, but the depth we had with Garry
and Al Pederson then,'' said Sweeney. ``I was in the same situation
Hal and (the younger guys) were in. It's been a few years (since)
we had that kind of overall depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Having more options has resulted in less pressure on Bourque, a
luxury he hasn't had for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good and bad scenario for him,'' said Sweeney, who was
mentored by Bourque early in his career. ``He's a teacher in that
he's helping and can bail guys out every once in a while in
situations. But it's hard on him because he's playing against the
top guys each and every night and at the same time, you've got a
younger guy you're trying to help teach. I say that because I was
in the situation with him. Maybe you're spending more time in your
own end whereas if you were playing with a guy of equal caliber you
wouldn't be. Not that many are equal to him. But it does make it
more difficult, though you wouldn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bourque has never been one to revel in his accomplishments. To
him, that's something he will do long after his playing days are
over (unless of course, as some predict, he will just play
forever). However, as much as he prefers to put off discussing his
achievements, one milestone does stand out _ his approach of
 &UR; Gordie Howe's  &LR; 1,049 assists. Bourque went into last night needing
two assists to tie Howe for third all-time. Next up is  &UR; Paul
Coffey's  &LR; 1,090.  &UR; Wayne Gretzky  &LR; is first with 1,932 and counting.
Bourque said just the stature of Howe makes the mark special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Gordie Howe,'' said Bourque, ``just that name. Knowing
you're going to go by him, it's something. He's Mr. Hockey. It just
tells you that things have gone pretty well for yourself. But no
matter ... you enjoy it, you know things have gone well but you
wake up the next morning and you've got to keep doing it. You've
got to keep going out and playing well and playing hard. Whatever
I've achieved, I've enjoyed. I've had fun doing it. I've enjoyed my
success but knowing that, you've always got to prove it again the
next day. That's how I've taken things all along. Like I said, once
it's all over and you sit down and see where you stand among other
guys, I think that's where you're going to say it's been good. But
I've still got time to play and I still have to go out and do the
job. I can't stop, I've got to keep going. I've got to keep putting
up numbers and you've got to keep playing hard, winning games, and
that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest beneficiary (only?) of goalie  &UR; Felix Potvin  &LR; walking
away from the Maple Leafs while he awaits a trade has been  &UR; Glenn
Healy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who finished his three-month exile in the International
Hockey League with Chicago last week and is now back with Toronto.
``You can sit on pins and needles all the time or go out and live
your life fully, and that's the way I approached it,'' said Healy.
``It was refreshing. You learn a lot about yourself and you learn
that a lot of guys are in this game for pure fun, not the money.''
Healy feels for Potvin. ``I care a lot for that guy,'' he said.
``He's a tremendous human being and he was a great partner. I'm
sure at the end of the day it will all work out for everyone.'' ...
Say what you will about the big guns on the Coyotes roster but two
impressive contributors to Phoenix's success are bruising forwards
 &UR; Shane Doan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 22, and  &UR; Brad Isbister &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 21. The two competed
against each other in junior hockey with Isbister playing for
Portland and Doan for Kamloops. ``I fought him once in junior,''
Isbister said. Being the good teammate, Isbister wouldn't say who
won ... The Sharks had been interested in acquiring Calgary star
 &UR; Theo Fleury &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but that has dwindled. They don't want to give up
defense prospect  &UR; Brad Stuart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and it's not as if the Sharks are
one player away from the Stanley Cup. ``It doesn't make sense,''
said San Jose coach  &UR; Darryl Sutter &LR; . ``(Stuart) was our best player
at training camp. You can't trade a Brad Stuart. When you've got to
give up a player like that, that's wrong. It would be different if
they wanted someone else. If they wanted someone else, go for it. I
will drive him up there myself. Until somebody takes the Stanley
Cup away from Detroit, there is nobody else. They have the best
team in the league by 10 miles. I mean, is there any other team in
the league that can play four lines and have their starting
goaltender ( &UR; Chris Osgood &LR; ) out for a period of time (six games
because of a hip injury) and it doesn't bother them at all?'' ...
Young forward  &UR; Harry York  &LR; changed teams again last week when he
was picked up off waivers by Vancouver. York began his career with
the Blues, was traded to the Rangers last season, went to
Pittsburgh a few weeks ago, and ended up with the Canucks last
Tuesday. York, who grew up outside Edmonton, said he dreamed of
playing on the Oilers' dynasty teams of the 1980s. So far, he has
played with goalie  &UR; Grant Fuhr  &LR; in St. Louis,  &UR; Wayne Gretzky  &LR; in
New York, and now he's on the same team as  &UR; Mark Messier &LR; . ``As I
make my rounds around the league, I'm getting to play with all the
old Oilers,'' said the 24-year-old. ``But in my original dream we
were all together in Edmonton.'' York was 14 when those three
players led the Oilers to the Cup in 1988 ... The nightmarish
situation continues in Tampa. As rumors persist that Potvin will be
traded there, the franchise continues to struggle. The most recent
controversy revolved around former Bruin goalie  &UR; Bill Ranford  &LR; and
the seriousness of his groin injury. Last week, he met with general
manager/coach  &UR; Jacques Demers  &LR; to clear the air about the situation
in which there were behind-the-scenes grumblings that Ranford
wasn't hurt that badly. Even when he was playing, his numbers were
brutal (1-7-1 record and .866 save percentage), though he wasn't
helped by the shoddy defense. Former Rangers goalie  &UR; John
Davidson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now a Rangers broadcaster, thinks Ranford will have to
change his style. ``What I see him doing is playing goal
feet-first,'' said Davidson. ``Goalies now, the majority of them
anyway, use all of their body to make the saves. Billy can change,
lots of goalies have done it. The guy's always done well under
pressure. Mentally I think he's still there. I just don't think you
can play goal now acrobatically.'' ... All right, we give. On the
notes given out before Thursday night's Bruins-Hurricanes game, it
lists Carolina's No. 13 as left wing  &UR; Bates Battaglia &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a name we
actually love. At the end of the game, however, the final
scoresheet listed the same left wing as ``Jon'' Battaglia. So? As
Carolina media relations manager  &UR; Jerry Peters  &LR; explained, Jon is
his given name, Bates is the name he prefers.
</P>
</TEXT>
