<SLUG> BC-FBN-TUPA-PATSPUNTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID FOOTWORK ASIDE, TUPA'S A HANDY MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH _ Watch closely, very closely, when Adam Vinatieri
attempts a field goal or extra point this afternoon in St. Louis.
But don't only peer at Vinatieri's foot; also notice the fingers of
the holder, Tom Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up with the idea a couple of years ago,'' Vinatieri
said of what the sharp-eyed should see. ``Tom figured it could only
help me with my kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, if not all, holders of field goal and extra point attempts
hold the football for the kicker with one finger, their index
finger at the top of the ball. Tupa, though, uses two fingers, his
index finger and his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just at practice one day and I decided to give it a
try,'' said Tupa. ``I feel like I have a better feel for the ball
that way and I can turn the ball faster.''
</P>
<P>
   So important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have to kick the laces,'' said Vinatieri. ``Every
time, all the time, Tom has them turned.''
</P>
<P>
   So typical of Tupa, the ultimate thinking person's football
player. Spinning the ball is a job requirement of every holder,
spinning the laces forward is so key to a good kick, so kickers
don't kick the laces; but holders have taken hundreds of thousands
of snaps in football for eons after eons, all doing the job the way
it always has been done. Virtually all spin the ball with one hand
while holding the point with the index finger of the other.
</P>
<P>
   One holder, though, decided to try a new and creative way. Two
fingers, instead of one. Tom Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't put them on the point of the ball,'' said Tupa.
``I put them on the sides of the point. I feel I can spin the ball
faster using two fingers and I can have more control of the ball so
Adam won't see the laces, won't see them forward (to Vinatieri). It
works so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   No coincidence, either, that Tupa's kicker _ Vinatieri _ is one
of the more dependable kickers in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is unique in what he does with two fingers,'' said Dante
Scarnecchia, the Patriots' special teams coach. ``As far as I know,
he's the only one who does it that way. Tom has such good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is prelude. Tupa is much more than a holder for extra
points and field goals and his true value to the Patriots is as a
punter, not to mention fill-in quarterback. And, in the middle of
the third quarter of last Sunday's game in Pittsburgh, as the game
_ and their lead _ seemingly was about to slip from the Patriots'
grasp, Tupa stood at the back line of the end zone, ready to punt.
</P>
<P>
   New England had a fourth-and-27. Three Rivers Stadium was loud
and raucous, the Steelers' fans willing their team to make the play
that might turn the game. Mike Bartrum snapped the ball back to
Tupa, a Steeler slipped through the Patriot line and seemed ready
to block the punt.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa stopped his leg, seemingly in mid-punt. Tupa seemed ready
to take a safety, rather than risk a blocked punt and a possible
recovery in the end zone for a Pittsburgh TD.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for football intelligence is so great that it was
presumed that Tupa through all the myriad possibilities in that
split-second that he saw the Steeler upon him and sensed the punt
was about to be blocked. It all seemed so apropos for Tupa's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said Tupa with a small laugh, ``I thought I heard
a whistle. I sort of heard a whistle, and I thought it was off to
my right. So I just held the ball because I saw (the Steeler)
coming free at me. I didn't want to take a chance on a block there
and give them a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   True and not true. The play actually was dead, but the actual
reason why was unknown to Tupa. The Patriots had let the time clock
run out and there was no play. The whistle had come from the stands
behind Tupa. But his instincts had been so perfectly on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided, just in case there had been a whistle,'' said
Tupa, ``that I should hold onto the ball and not punt it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tupa was given a second chance. And that second chance was
fatal to the Steelers because this time, again pushed back to the
endline of the end zone, Tupa took the snap from Bartum and boomed
what the Patriots most needed at the moment _ a 63-yard punt. It
was amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole mindset (before the second punt) was not to take a
block and just to get the ball out of there,'' said Tupa. This is
the mindset of all punters in such situations _ just get the ball
out, even if only to the 40- or 45-yard line. But Tupa did so much
more than just ``get it out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it sit pretty well on my foot and it just went,'' said
Tupa, modestly. ``I just happened to get it out of there. Dante and
I have been working a lot on field situations, the last five or six
weeks, what to do in a situation like that. And it just happened to
come in handy just then.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa is very consistent and it seems difficult to remember many
poor punts (``Oh, I can remember them,'' he says), but he feels
back in the groove as the December pressure games are played,
because ``I started out the season well and then I was kicking the
ball kind of average during the middle of the season. Now I'm
feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Tupa has delivered crucial punts in the most
crucial of situations. Tupa did it in the last-second victory over
Buffalo, just as he did in the last-second victory over Miami, just
as he has done through his entire career in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Good-natured ribbing
</P>
<P>
   Tupa's locker is near the lockers of quarterbacks Drew Bledsoe
and Scott Zolak. Tupa no sooner had gotten a word or two out of his
mouth to a media member when Zolak began the needling. ``How come
you are talking to him? How about that for sweet potatoes, somebody
talking to the punter?''
</P>
<P>
   Because he is one of the most valuable members of the team,
Zolak was told.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' needled Tupa back to Zolak. ``Silence ... you think I'm
surprised by that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Bledsoe came by and his needle toward Tupa
was even longer than Zolak's as Tupa tried to speak. ``On that
ball, I took the snap from center and I punted it,'' joshed
Bledsoe, impersonating a Tupa interview. ```That's what I did on
that play. Then, on that other play, I took the snap and I stood it
up on its tip and Adam kicked it. Then ...'''
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' said Tupa again. ``I don't get respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from it. Tupa kicks in a (sometimes) cold weather climate,
the wind and swirls of November and December hindering his punts.
Yet, year after year, Tupa is one of the top punters in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care for statistics except for one,'' said
Tupa. ``And that's my (net) average compared to what the punter on
the other team has done, punting the same day and under the same
conditions as I do. And the last few years, I've done pretty well
on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XXX, Tupa may have been the one Patriot who played
up to his potential. Time and again, Tupa not only boomed long
punts, but they all were angled toward the sideline _ both long and
perfectly placed _ so that Green Bay return threat Desmond Howard
had little room to maneuver. Tupa certainly contained Howard, even
if New England's kickoff team did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the game I'm most proud of,'' said Tupa. ``In the
biggest situation, under the most pressure, with everybody
watching, that's when you want to do your best. That Super Bowl, I
feel, was my best game.''
</P>
<P>
   He's earned their respect
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on three teams and Tom's the best punter I've ever
played with,'' said Bartrum. ``Not only that, but he's the best
punter I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And Vinatieri, singing the praises of his holder, said he's not
surprised by anything Tupa does in an athletic contest. The Super
Bowl? And those perfectly angled punts? ``You give Tom six days or
a week to work something specific,'' said Vinatieri, ``and Tom
always comes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri and Tupa, of course, spend endless hours during camp
together, as do kickers and punters on all NFL teams. And they talk
and talk (``He does talk about Ohio a lot''), but from time to
time, ``I'll say to him, `Tom, I want you to stay here as much as
anybody. I want you to be my holder forever.' That's because I
never have to worry about a hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Bartrum said he never has to worry about a snap. (``Tom
has such good hands that no matter where I put the ball, he just
snags it.'') Indeed, the needed confidence between snapper and
punter, snapper, holder and placekicker, Bartum, Tupa, and
Vinatieri is almost tangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike almost never gives me a bad snap,'' said Tupa. ``And
Adam, if you get the ball down, he puts it through the uprights.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Vinatieri, and not Tupa, who will spill the word that Tupa
is a scratch golfer, a very good basketball player (``He's the best
basketball player on the team'') and a man who could be successful
in virtually any sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just enjoying my job,'' said the punter. ``I think I have
the best job in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe one of the better wits on the team. Tupa, who has also
played for the Colts, Cardinals, and Browns, delivered the line of
the year on the day news broke the Patriots would be moving to
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``All four teams I've been on have moved their franchise at one
time or another,'' said Tupa. ``All I can say is that if there is
any owner out there who might be thinking of moving his team, just
sign me. I'll be his guarantee he'll move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
