u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-INSTANTR     12-12 2482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-INSTANTREPLAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD CALL: NO INSTANT REVERSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Thankfully, instant replay is going to come back slowly in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   After an instant of panic, it appears NFL owners have decided,
upon further review, that efforts to rush a system into this year's
playoffs have proven inconclusive, so the way they play will stand
until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There may yet be a straw vote of the owners by phone, but the
early returns hint strongly that commissioner Paul Tagliabue's
suggestion that some form of replay be instituted in the playoffs
because of the recent spate of obvious errors has met with
surprising resistance, although for the best of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks last winter several highly respected NFL coaches and
front office leaders _ like Packers coach Mike Holmgren and
Redskins GM Charley Casserly _ worked diligently to come up with a
system that would win approval at the winter meetings. For the
seventh time, their efforts failed, and so the decision was made to
play this season with replay available to everyone involved in an
NFL game but the people who need it _ the officials.
</P>
<P>
   The wise heads in the NFL now are saying so be it, and they are
right.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL needs instant replay. It always has. It just doesn't
need it to show up like a blindside blitz, because the only thing
worse than continuing to vote down the reinstitution of replay next
winter would be ramming some form of it through now, because
decisions made in haste and panic invariably cause more problems
than they solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should change the rules in the middle of the
stream,'' said one NFC executive who has always supported replay.
``We've (made) proposals in the past. Charley Casserly will again
this winter. Personally, I think it's a slamdunk this time. Even
some of the naysayers of the past like Buffalo and Rich McKay in
Tampa are saying they're considering voting for it next time, and
you already know Cleveland will.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not sure we'd even vote for a playoff system this
year. We adopted a set of rules. Stick with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, that is what will happen. The call for replay began,
in truth, not from a blown call but from a hearing problem when
referee Phil Luckett couldn't make heads or tails out of Jerome
Bettis trying to say heads or tails. That error on a simple
overtime coin flip on Thanksgiving Day is what has really fueled
support for replay, even though it would have done nothing to
reverse that situation.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment of it, however, when coupled with recent blown
calls in the Patriots-Bills game and last week in the Seahawks-Jets
game have the suits in New York petrified that one of these days,
one of their half-competent officiating crews will cost somebody
the Super Bowl, when even Heidi in Hanover watching at home could
see that they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   That could happen, but generally the best crews work the
playoffs and that reduces the odds. Still, not even that is reason
enough to add a replay system no one is yet fully satisfied with on
a moment's notice, and a lot of wise NFL owners like the Chiefs'
Lamar Hunt know it and have counseled their brethren about the
folly of such a rapid-fire decision.
</P>
<P>
   When respected owners like Hunt and recently burned coaches like
Pittsburgh's Bill Cowher, as well as a pro-replay advocate like
Holmgren, all counsel against a postseason form of replay coming
in, the idea is doomed. Fortunately.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, why should a playoff game be any different from the
rest of the games? If the league thinks they're more important they
should talk to Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson, who may well be
fired because of Vinny Testaverde's phantom touchdown run last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Panic is never the best way to find a solution to a recurring
problem. Common sense is. This time it appears that both may
prevail in the NFL when they should _ at next March's owners'
meetings in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It is being taken as a given that Minnesota wide receiver  &UR; Randy
Moss  &LR; is a shoo-in for rookie of the year and that thinking is
probably right. But is it accurate?
</P>
<P>
   Moss has been nothing short of unstoppable in Minnesota, where
he's scored 14 touchdowns and so terrorized defenses that his
mentor and close friend,  &UR; Cris Carter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said earlier this season,
``Do you understand that this kid could be  &UR; Michael Jordan &LR; ? That
we're on the ground floor of something huge?''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Moss leads the league in touchdown catches (14)
and receiving yards (1,120), it's an easy case to make for him,
especially when you consider 19 teams passed on drafting him
(including the Bengals twice, which figures). Then point out that
Moss has already broken the rookie record for touchdown catches
(13) set by old Green Bay Packer receiver  &UR; Billy Howton  &LR; in 1952
and tied by  &UR; John Jefferson  &LR; in 1979, and there seems little room
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you happen to live in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   If you do, you can build a powerful case for Forgotten  &UR; Fred
Taylor &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is the first Jaguar runner to ever rush for 1,000
yards and he still has three games left.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor gained 183 yards last weekend against the Lions to lift
his total to 1,005, only 115 fewer than Moss has produced. If you
add Taylor's additional 343 receiving yards, he's ahead of Moss in
yardage production and, surprise, Taylor has also scored 14
touchdowns, many of them the hard way. By running over people.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a better argument to make for Taylor. He has
produced his numbers on a team that has nowhere near the ancillary
talents Moss finds around him, and he's done it despite missing all
or most of four games with a shoulder injury after barely playing
in the season's first two games while head coach  &UR; Tom Coughlin &LR;  was
trying to bring him along slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach  &UR; Jeff Fisher  &LR; was studying ways to try and stop
Taylor this week and couldn't find many.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a 6-foot, 225-pound guy who runs like
he's 180,'' Fisher said. ``He's got quickness and strength to the
hole and what really is impressive is what he does after initial
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that explosiveness or those numbers may be enough to
derail the train Moss is riding toward NFL Rookie of the Year
honors, but failing that, the train should at least stop in
Jacksonville and pick Taylor up for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jets wide receiver  &UR; Keyshawn Johnson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; during a conference call
this week with the national media, explained perfectly the problem
coaches have with instant replay. It giveth but it also taketh
away. When asked if he would vote for or against it, Johnson said,
``Well, you know, different situations come up every other game and
some games you say, no, I wouldn't vote (for it). Some games you
say, yes, I would vote. What happened to us in Detroit last year, I
would vote for instant replay. What happened to us this year, no, I
wouldn't vote for instant replay.'' In other words, when it gets
you a win great and when it doesn't, forget about it ... Sometimes
being lucky is far better than being smart. Two years ago, the
49ers offered restricted free agent running back  &UR; Rodney Hampton  &LR; a
six-year, $16.45 million offer sheet. When the Giants matched it,
San Francisco was forced to go find someone else and settled on
oft-injured  &UR; Garrison Hearst &LR; .  &UR; today &LR; , Hampton is out of football
and Hearst has become the first 49er running back since 1988-89 to
rush for more than 1,000 yards in back-to-back seasons. Asked about
his good fortune, Hearst said, ``I knew the (cloudy) running back
situation (in San Francisco) and I was hoping I could be the runner
that changed things.'' That he has been, somehow avoiding the
debilitating injuries that ruined him in Arizona ... You think the
Patriots have injury problems? How about the Packers? Green Bay
listed a club-record 17 players on their injured list on Wednesday
and they already had eight players on injured reserve. In Monday
night's loss to the Buccaneers, eight players left the game with
various injuries. The most costly may be to wide receiver  &UR; Robert
Brooks &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has yet to play a full game this season. Once the
featured deep threat, Brooks is now a shadow of himself after knee
and finger injuries, back surgery, and a hamstring pull, and
defenses know it. They now rotate coverages to double  &UR; Antonio
Freeman  &LR; in the belief Brooks can no longer hurt them deep, and now
he may not even have the chance, because he may be out for the
season with the hamstring problems. And now Freeman is expected to
play Sunday with a broken jaw. Although his jaw is still wired,
Freeman had some of the wires cut shorter last week and was fitted
with a special mouthpiece ... Only a team run the way the Bengals
are would try something like this. On Monday, Cincinnati cut
14-year veteran punter  &UR; Lee Johnson  &LR; for publicly criticizing
management. On Tuesday they tried to fine him $20,588, which is a
week's pay. Good luck trying to collect. The NFLPA immediately said
they would fight the fine because you can't discipline someone
after you fire them. The union won a similar case a year ago
against Carolina when the Panthers tried to collect a summer's
worth of fines from  &UR; Kevin Greene  &LR; after releasing him for holding
out with a valid contract. An arbitrator ruled in Greene's favor.
Bengals president  &UR; Mike Brown  &LR; insists he'll go after the money.
Like most everyone else associated with the Bengals of late, he'll
come up empty ... The Broncos may be sailing along toward an
undefeated season, but running back  &UR; Terrell Davis's  &LR; quest to
break  &UR; Eric Dickerson's  &LR; single-season rushing record has slowed.
Davis still leads the NFL with 1,654 yards rushing, but he's been
held under 100 the past two games and has significantly fallen off
the pace to match Dickerson's 2,105. Davis now must average 151
yards a game the next three weeks to break the record. But whether
he makes it to 2,000 or not, someone already has in the NFL.
Referee  &UR; Dick Hantak &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the flag-throwingest man since  &UR; Abbie
Hoffman &LR; , leads a crew that has called 259 penalties in 13 games
for 2,090 yards ... Here's one good reason Denver is so tough to
beat. It not only has the most balanced attack in the league, but
is averaging 6.5 yards a play on first down, which results in third
and short an alarming amount of the time if you're an opposing
defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; seems to be almost a weekly topic in the NFL.
This week, in addition to his phony flap with Sports Illustrated
about having been promised he wouldn't be on the cover of the
magazine, Johnson explained why he likes playing for his often
bombastic coach. ``I think I have a coach who wants me to succeed
on all levels and he's putting me in a position to succeed,''
Johnson said of what many are viewing as his breakthrough season.
``No. 1 picks go to poor organizations and they don't know what to
do with you. They don't know how to use you. They just know how to
pick you. For me, I thank God that I got Bill Parcells in my second
year because my first year was devastating.'' ... Parcells, by the
way, has told friends he's hoping Testaverde &UR;  &LR; can turn into the
 &UR; Jim Plunkett  &LR; of the 1990s. Plunkett was the Heisman Trophy winner
and former No. 1 draft choice in New England who appeared to be
washed up when he arrived in Oakland in 1978, but two years later
led the Raiders to the first of his two Super Bowl triumphs. When
Testaverde arrived with the Jets, he, too, looked like a
broken-down former Heisman winner at the end of his career. Now
he's been reborn, although he acknowledges he had reservations when
Parcells first talked to him about signing on. ``After what I saw
last year with ( &UR; Neil &LR; )  &UR; O'Donnell  &LR; and ( &UR; Glenn &LR; )  &UR; Foley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; you
know, I was a little skeptical about coming here,'' Testaverde said
recently. ``I didn't want it to be kind of a circus with the
quarterbacks in and out every week. I expressed that feeling to
him. He's the head coach. He's going to run the team like he wants
to do it. As players, you just go each week and do what he tells
you. So far, things have been great, we've gotten along great. I
don't expect it to be any different. He's very demanding of his
players but yet he takes care of them when he needs to. He's a
little bit different, but I felt like if I wanted a chance to win a
championship, it was going to be with a coach like Bill Parcells.''
The Jets hold an option on Testaverde for next season but are close
to a long-term deal that could see him through to the end of his
career, at least as a starter ... Much-maligned and seldom-seen
49ers free agent acquisition  &UR; Gabe Wilkins  &LR; got a chance to pay
back some of the $20 million contract he signed in the offseason
last Sunday when he came off the bench to be part of a three-man
rotation coach  &UR; Steve Mariucci  &LR; must use down the stretch to try
and replace All-Pro defensive tackle  &UR; Bryant Young &LR; . Young was lost
for the season with a badly broken leg sustained when he was hit by
teammate  &UR; Ken Norton's  &LR; helmet two weeks ago. Wilkins was brought
in at a defensive end from the Packers but will now rotate inside
after spending all but the last month on the inactive list ... The
Carolina Panthers rushed for 203 yards against the Niners last
Sunday, and they're ranked 29th in the NFL in rushing. Now they
have  &UR; Barry Sanders  &LR; to contend with Monday night. That should be
interesting ... The Saints' decision to release former second-round
pick  &UR; Ray Zellars  &LR; last week wasn't because the powerful fullback
can't run. It was because he wouldn't block. Just a year ago,  &UR; Mike
Ditka  &LR; was so high on Zellars he made him a starter, and he led the
team in rushing with 552 yards. But apparently he began to think he
was now a runner not a blocker. The result has been that in three
of his four starts, quarterback  &UR; Kerry Collins  &LR; has led the team in
rushing, and Zellars was finally replaced by fifth-round pick
 &UR; Wilmont Perry &LR; . &UR;  &LR; Zellars was not active for the last two games and
reportedly learned he wouldn't play against the Dolphins when he
got to the stadium and found there was no uniform in his locker ...
Meanwhile, Saints pass rusher  &UR; Joe Johnson &LR;  should be tougher than
ever to keep away from quarterbacks the next three weeks. Johnson
stands to earn a $1 million bonus if he can produce three more
sacks ... Although he'll be trying hard to beat him Sunday, Raiders
coach  &UR; Jon Gruden &LR;  is a big fan of Bills quarterback  &UR; Doug Flutie &LR; .
When Gruden was an undersized quarterback at the University of
Dayton, Flutie was an undersized quarterback winning the Heisman
Trophy at Boston College. ``He was my idol when I was a player,''
Gruden said. ``He gave all us 5-foot-9-inch quarterbacks hope.''
Sunday, however, Gruden's Raiders could lose all hope of reaching
the playoffs if Flutie continues his magic.
</P>
</TEXT>
