<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-PROGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RURAL PUERTO RICO, SIGNS OF CORPORATE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODR I GUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOIZA, Puerto Rico _ Nestled among sand dunes with towering palm
trees, plywood shacks line the main road to Loiza, a coastal town
where the descendants of African slaves still carve masks from
coconut shells.
</P>
<P>
   As Mazdas and Toyotas whisked by, Antonio Perez Montalvo, 22,
waited under a canopy sign that read, ``Coco frio,'' cold coconut.
Finally, a customer arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's calloused hands clenched a machete as he eyed the
coconut on the counter before him. Whack! Perez struck, chopping
off the tip, before poking a straw into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Un peso,'' one dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in one of the poorest pueblos in Puerto Rico, this is
commerce. Deeper in town, open-air restaurants and bodegas abound,
but not much more. It's a different world from San Juan, 30 miles
west, where yuppies live in high-rise condominiums, eat bagels for
breakfast, carry cell phones, and go to nightclubs that spin Janet
Jackson and Green Day.
</P>
<P>
   But already there are signs of changes to come in Loiza. A
Burger King stands on a corner, offering ``los mejores,'' the best,
hamburgers. At least the sign is in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100 years since the United States took possession of this
Caribbean island, it has been evolving, becoming more Americanized
every day. Most Puerto Ricans welcome the corporate-driven way of
life: fast food, drive-through service, designer clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, they say, the island already resembles the rest of
the United States, and, like it or not, they predict, the island
will one day become the 51st state. The only question is when.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 80 percent of registerd voters among Puerto
Rico's 3.9 million residents are expected to head to the polls,
essentially shutting down the island, in a daylong plebiscite that
will be celebrated with fiestas, flag waving, homemade food, and
dancing in parks.
</P>
<P>
   The plebiscite offers voters five choices, including statehood,
which is expected to win. Statehood supporters hope the results of
the nonbinding referendum will persuade Congress to begin the
process of adding another star to the US flag. That would only
ratify what has become a reality in the island's urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course we should become a state,'' said Lucy Hernandez
Rios, 30, an interpreter, as she walked through the cobblestone
streets of Old San Juan. ``We're practically American.''
</P>
<P>
   Old San Juan is one of the oldest cities in the Western
Hemisphere, established in 1521, long before Pilgrims even thought
about sailing to America. It sits near a harbor of luminescent blue
waters. Above the harbor rise Spanish colonial buildings with
protruding balconies in the colors of sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   Old San Juan clings to its culture, an area where jewelry and
clothing stores are owned by locals. Restaurants display menus of
carne asada and sopa de pollo, stewed beef and chicken soup. But
around every corner there are surprises: Pizza Hut, McDonald's,
Payless Shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like everything that is American,'' said Gregorio Gonzalez
Rios, 72, standing in a brick-paved plaza under the sweeping
branches of a ficus tree. ``I like the blues, Frank Sinatra.''
</P>
<P>
   Four men sitting at a table playing dominoes echoed that
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   While adults debate the future of Puerto Rico _ those in
Americanized cities like San Juan generally siding with statehood
and those in small towns favoring the status quo or independence _
the younger generation wants a permanent relationship with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the Planet Hollywood in Old San Juan, rock music blares, and
a video of ``The Wedding Singer'' plays overhead, as Kenitza
Salgado Vega folds T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Salgado, 24, of Bayamon, a city southwest of San Juan, is like
most young people here: She watches MTV, VH1, and loves American
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Everclear, Natalie Imbruglia, Alanis Morrissette, Puff
Daddy,'' she said. ``Tourists are surprised when they hear me
speak. They're like, `You speak English so well and without an
accent.' But of course. This isn't a Third World country.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Puerto Rico is nothing like its Caribbean neighbors, the
Dominican Republic, Haiti, Cuba. Its standard of living is
exponentially greater, due mostly to its status as a US
commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   In the 50 years since ``Operation Bootstrap'' lured American
textile factories here by offering corporate tax breaks, the Puerto
Rican economy has changed in waves. First it was factories like
Jansen and Maidenform offering low-wage jobs, but it was still a
step above the long days of toiling in sugar cane and coffee
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Oil refineries moved in but then shut down after the oil crisis
a few years later in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical companies that replaced them now produce 20
percent of the pharmaceuticals sold in America, according to Carlos
Vivoni, secretary of the Department of Economic Development and
Commerce in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Vivoni said, Governor Pedro Rossello wants to gear Puerto
Rico toward high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an economic policy that hinged on (US) tax breaks,''
Vivoni said. ``We needed to get away from that kind of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes sense, especially now that Congress has repealed a
law that gave corporate tax breaks to American companies on the
island, ending them in 2002. This week, as the heads of 34 Latin
American countries meet in Miami to discuss creating a market of
the Americas, like the European Union, Vivoni hopes Puerto Rico
will be able to serve as a bridge between Latin America and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the states, people regard Puerto Ricans as Latin Americans,
but in Latin America, they consider us Americans,'' Vivoni said.
``That doesnt give us an identity crisis; instead, a very unique
identity. We feel as comfortable in Chile as we do in New York
City.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Rosello's staff, Vivoni is a member of the New
Progressive Party, which advocates statehood. He sees the
Americanization of Puerto Rico as a trend toward a globalized
culture in Puerto Rico, where the best is mixed, just as it is in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Tokyo once, and people were upset because the
Japanese were eating more hamburgers than sushi.'' Vivoni said.
``Is that good or bad? I don't think it's bad. Open markets give
people choices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
