u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-LOCKOUT-     12-12 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-LOCKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK RUNNING OUT ON SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hanukkah starts Monday. There's a new moon on Friday. In between
these two events, there's a chance we may finally learn if we're
going to see NBA basketball this season.
</P>
<P>
   The signs are not encouraging. There is no agreement on how to
divide the $2 billion in revenues. There is no agreement on
regulating the salaries of the high-end earners. There is no
agreement on how the much-discussed escrow system would work. There
is no agreement on conduct or the drug program.
</P>
<P>
   And those are the issues that need to be settled now simply to
play a shortened, made-for-NBC season. What if there is no season?
What happens to the draft, to players whose contracts expire, to
rookies drafted but never signed? What happens to the sport itself?
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern joked, ``you want to take all of our
lawyers' fun away.'' Then, he added, ``it is sad to say that we are
looking into that and a lot of other issues.'' We asked Stern's
consigliore, Jeff Mishkin, about the Great Unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of horrendous issues,'' Mishkin said,
``that we have not yet even contemplated.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple math tells us that this week is crucial. A miraculous
agreement by, say, Friday, would mean we might see basketball in
mid-January. But there's a history of mistrust and distrust here
when it comes to putting verbal agreements into writing. Stern
isn't about to open the floodgates until he sees what he wants in
print. That leaves 4 1/2 months to cram in however many games are
deemed necessary and, possibly, a playoff system that may not look
a lot like the one we're used to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   So let's use Jan. 24 as the mythical starting date. The Celtics'
schedule has them with 43 games left. Cramming in games here and
there and adding another week might stretch the season to 50 games.
Is that enough? It was in 1947-48; the season that year was 48
games as the league cut games (there had been 60 the year before)
to reduce travel. ``Unfortunately,'' the NBA Encyclopedia notes,
``with so few games, teams could barely generate sufficient income
to cover basic expenses.'' The league went back to 60 games the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   So there is precedent, however flimsy. But all of this
speculation/wishful thinking is contingent on an agreement getting
done in a week or so and that seems improbable given neither side
has shown much inclination to get it done. The players say they
have already made enough compromises. The owners say the
compromises mean little until the main issue of dividing revenue is
settled.
</P>
<P>
   The players this past week demonstrated all the public relations
aplomb of major tobacco or the baby seal bashers. Alonzo Mourning,
whose lust for the extra dollar forced Charlotte to trade him, was
calling the owners greedy. Ron Mercer never bothered to tell his
public relations firm that his teammates were inclined to skip ``an
intense workout'' at Brandeis.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this proposed ``All-Star Game'' this weekend in
Atlantic City. Why can't these guys stage a game or rally in a
place where there aren't blackjack tables or slot machines? We can
just hear Claude Rains coming out and saying how shocked he is to
learn that there is gambling going on. Do you think the Delta
Center was booked?
</P>
<P>
   The casinos are indifferent to the event. Don't expect a traffic
jam on the Atlantic City Expressway, either. Public relations has
not been the players' strong suit and they'd be better off pulling
the plug on this silly thing and figuring out a way to survive, as
Patrick Ewing likes to say, under the Draconian system being
offered by their employers that will pay the average player around
$5 million when the deal is up. We should all be so subjugated.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One of the so-called ``third rail'' issues from the union's
standpoint is the ``timing rule.'' The owners want to prevent a
team from using its cap room to sign a free agent and then turning
around and re-signing its own players using the  &UR; Larry Bird
 &LR; exception. Under this scenario, a free agent such as  &UR; Scottie
Pippen &LR; , &UR; Charles Barkley  &LR; or  &UR; Damon Stoudamire  &LR; would have trouble
signing with a Phoenix or a Houston because the Suns or Rockets
couldn't then turn around and re-sign their own people. (Similarly,
if the Celtics used their cap room to sign  &UR; Matt Geiger &LR; , &UR;  &LR; they
couldn't then turn around and re-sign  &UR; Popeye Jones &LR; .) The union
thinks such a system would inhibit free agent movement. It would.
But there's a catch. The league would likely allow a team to do
both if the union accepted its proposal for a pay scale for Bird
free agents. The union has been loathe to do that, preferring
instead a tax that would kick in at a level few players could
expect to reach ... Old friend  &UR; Ed Pinckney  &LR; had his Villanova
uniform retired Saturday. Pinckney said most people remember him
for, as he called it, ``that game.'' That would be the 1985 NCAA
final, the Villanova upset of mighty Georgetown and future  &UR; Joe
Hill  &LR; clone Ewing. (Pinckney was the MVP of the tournament.) But
Easy Ed also says his professional ID is strictly Boston, even
though he also toiled for the Suns, Kings, Bucks, Raptors, and
Heat. He spent 5 1/2 seasons with the Celtics, arriving with  &UR; Joe
Kleine  &LR; in February 1989 and leaving in June 1994 in a draft day
deal for  &UR; Derek Strong  &LR; and  &UR; Blue Edwards &LR; . ``For my family and
myself, it was the best,'' he said of Boston. ``The atmosphere in
Boston, sportswise, is difficult to simulate anywhere else. People
mean it when they say they live and die with the Red Sox, Celtics,
Bruins, and Patriots. It's a religion. It really is.'' Pinckney
didn't want to talk about the lockout; technically, he's an
employee of the Heat because he scouts for them in addition to
broadcasting their games. He's also doing college games for ESPN;
``I don't have anything else to do,'' he said. He said he was
surprised by Villanova's decision to retire No. 54, mainly because
he has been out of college for 13 years and out of the NBA for a
year. ``My son ( &UR; Shea &LR; ) is playing for his eighth grade team and he
thinks I'm an old fogey,'' Pinckney said. ``It's nice to be
recognized.'' ... The rosters were announced this week for the
European League All-Star Game, Dec. 29 in Berlin.  &UR; Dino Radja  &LR; will
be there, representing Panathinaikos on the East team. Among the
other familiar and soon-to-be-more-familiar participants include
 &UR; Radoslav Nesterovic  &LR; and  &UR; Zeljko Rebraca &LR; , &UR;  &LR; both big men whose
rights are owned by  &UR; Kevin McHale's  &LR; Timberwolves, and former US
collegians  &UR; David Rivers &LR; , &UR; Wendell Alexis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Conrad McRae &LR; .
Another participant is  &UR; Dragan Tarlac &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Bulls' second-round
pick in 1995 who may be Chicago's starting center (he's 6 feet 10
inches).  &UR; Zan Tabak &LR; , &UR;  &LR; alas, did not make the squad ... Mercer may
have been unable to make it to Brandeis this past week, but his
coach,  &UR; Rick Pitino &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and the Celtics' staff promises to be there
this afternoon for the Massachusetts High School Coaches
Association clinic. Also scheduled to attend are WNBA players
 &UR; Cindy Blodgett  &LR; and  &UR; Nykesha Sales &LR; . Maybe Sales could demonstrate
how to make a layup wearing a cast ... Speaking of Mercer, he has
dumped  &UR; David Falk  &LR; and signed on with  &UR; Master P &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the rapper and
former college hoopster who otherwise goes by the name of  &UR; Percy
Miller &LR; . ``My main thing is that I like to have a closeknit
relationship with the guy that I deal with,'' Mercer said. ``I want
to be able to talk to him three or four times a week. I couldn't do
that with (Falk).'' He said he met Master P while working out in
Los Angeles and liked what he heard. He said he and former Kentucky
teammate  &UR; Derek Anderson  &LR; signed with the man the same day.
</P>
</TEXT>
