<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-KEVINBROW     12-12 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-KEVINBROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BREAK BANK TO LAND ACE BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ It took one year to the day he signed with the Red
Sox for Pedro Martinez to look like a bargain, and just 2 1/2 weeks
for Mo Vaughn to lose his distinction as baseball's highest-paid
player.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Los Angeles Dodgers broke the $100 million salary
level by signing pitcher Kevin Brown to a seven-year, $105 million
deal in which Brown, who has won 20 games in a season only once,
hasn't won a game in the World Series, or won a Cy Young Award,
will collect $15 million a year until he turns 41. He received a $5
million signing bonus, a $10 million salary next season, and $15
million a year for the last six years of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also agreed to provide Brown a private plane to fly
his family to Los Angeles from his home in Macon, Ga., 12 times a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't do it, and that doesn't justify it, but somebody
else was going to do it,'' said Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone, who said two clubs _ believed to be the Orioles and Rockies
_ were prepared to pay Brown even more. ``He's been to the World
Series in each of the last two years. The Dodgers haven't been to
the World Series since 1988. That's why we've made the seven-year
commitment we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Only nine pitchers in major league history have won 15 or more
games at age 40. That number drops to five at age 41, which means
Brown, who went to the World Series with the Florida Marlins in
1997 and the San Diego Padres in 1998, will be paid $1 million a
win if he can join that group.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who last year signed a then-record, six-year, $75
million deal, will not reach the $15 million plateau until 2003,
the last year of his deal with the Sox. He will turn 32 at the end
of that season, and has a chance to be paid $17.5 million if the
club picks up his option in 2004. By then, Martinez may be no more
than a middle-of-the-road wage earner in the exploding economics of
Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you cross the $100 million barrier, you have what makes
us tantamount to the NBA,'' said Sandy Alderson, executive vice
president of baseball operations for Major League Baseball,
``especially when you start extending that level of money to a
player who is going to be in his late 30s or early 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred million (dollar) contracts are why the NBA is
locked out today. This is not a good baseball decision. This was
not a decision made by a baseball person.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, whose first GM job was with the threadbare Montreal
Expos, said he was sensitive to how Brown's contract, which
eclipses the average annual value of $13.333 million in Vaughn's
contract with the Angels as baseball's richest deal, will further
exacerbate the disparity between the haves and have-nots in the
game. But he said it's unfair to cast stones at the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a society that has a lower class, a middle class,
and an upper class,'' Malone said. ``We try to help those who are
less fortunate, but to criticize us because we're the Dodgers, we
have the stadium we have, we draw 3-4 million fans a year ... I
feel very blessed that we have the revenues that we can make this
kind of commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are owned by Rupert Murdoch's Fox media
conglomerate, which is fulfilling predictions that it would quickly
become among the game's biggest spenders. Brown's signing raises
the Dodgers' payroll to around $80 million for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of event was not unforeseen,'' Alderson said of
Fox's record-setting deal.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to an outrageously expensive blueprint,
Randy Johnson of the Arizona Diamondbacks will face Brown on
Opening Day in Dodger Stadium next April, a matchup of pitchers
whose combined 1999 earnings ($28 million) will be higher than the
total payrolls of eight teams last season: Tampa Bay, Detroit,
Minnesota, Cincinnati, Florida, Oakland, Pittsburgh, and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the enormous difference in payrolls between the elite
teams and their lesser brethren, Alderson said that realistically
only 12 to 15 teams have a chance to advance to the playoffs next
season. That means at least half of the teams will begin play
knowing they have no chance of competing.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Alderson was asked whether some clubs
should market themselves not as being in competition, but as
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some clubs are going to have to continue doing that,'' he
said. ``Many have a place that is no longer an arena, it's that
place you go for entertainment. It's the House of David.'' That
being a reference to the barnstorming team of bearded players that
used to play exhibitions around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez contract, of course, shows the Red Sox have not
been innocents in this salary escalation, or in pitchers getting
seven-year deals. Sox GM Dan Duquette, who was due to arrive here
Saturday, afternoon, has said he had interest in Brown, but was
unwilling to give him a six-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers justified giving him seven years by noting he and
Greg Maddux of the Braves are the only pitchers to have thrown
1,400 innings in the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, the new Dodgers manager, was asked if he
considered Brown the best pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly do,'' he said. ``He's my Opening Day pitcher. I
don't usually announce it this early. Yes, I'd have to say we're
favorites to win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone is known to be interested in trying to move outfielder
Gary Sheffield, who has a $10 million-a-year contract, and the Sox
are known to like Dodgers outfielder Raul Mondesi. But Malone said
Saturday he has had no discussions with Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
