<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UMASSWOMEN-DEFECT     12-12 2206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UMASSWOMEN-DEFECTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TIME TURMOIL AT UMASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; AMHERST _ They arrived here in the fall of 1997, three women
from vastly different backgrounds and athletic programs. Nicky
Vallieres, Tory Grant, and Kara Trent were united in their love for
basketball and their desire to play it for the University of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a big-time program. The Minutewomen play in the
Atlantic 10 Conference. They travel the country; their practices
routinely run three hours or more. It's a serious commitment, but
the allure was understandable for three promising recruits eager to
play college hoops. The reality under coach Joanie O'Brien, they
say, proved to be quite different.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, none of the three is playing for UMass, a
development all attribute to O'Brien, now in her eighth year at
UMass and last season's conference Coach of the Year. Vallieres has
transferred to Division 2 American International, Grant has been
kicked off the team, and Trent has quit; due, in part, she said, to
what happened to the other two.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the individuals and many of their friends and
relatives describe O'Brien as a knowledgeable coach with an
unpredictable temper who insults and demeans some players while
unfairly favoring others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her language on the court was like none I had ever heard from
a coach before,'' Vallieres said. ``I understand getting frustrated
and blowing off steam in that way, but I thought most of her
language was unnecessary and could be taken for verbal abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent's family has hired a lawyer, who has been in negotiations
with the university about the charges. Grant, too, said she is
seeking legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   There are others who share the concerns of the three former
teammates. Many of the players on the team reportedly are in
counseling. The parents of a player still on the squad were so
concerned about O'Brien's behavior they had a relative attend a
game for the sole purpose of videotaping the coach in action.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth player, former Globe All-Scholastic Rekiya Penton, also
just left the team, citing ``personal reasons.'' Penton, who played
at Jeremiah Burke in Dorchester, had played only six minutes all
season, none during a Nov. 16 game at Boston College, disappointing
a contingent of around 25, many from Burke, who attended the game.
Efforts to reach Penton were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, O'Brien dismisses the criticism as a matter of
style. ``Am I an aggressive coach? Yeah. Am I intense? Absolutely.
If that's the way it comes across to them, that's their opinion of
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it. You just do what you feel like you have to do.
It's whatever's best. I don't see where that's coming from, as far
as being able to make a statement like that.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Bob Marcum, the athletic director at UMass,
said he has been impressed ``that Joanie operates her program in a
way that I think she has a great concern for the young people. Is
she an intense coach? Yes, she is. In all honesty, I don't see
where Joanie O'Brien is much different from a lot of the college
coaches I've seen. I'm not saying all their behavior is excellent
or all of it is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Carroll, UMass's sixth leading all-time scorer who
played for O'Brien for four years, said she had no problems with
the coach in her time there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken with other kids who've gone through Division 1
programs and it's a mirror image of what I went through with
Joanie,'' said Carroll, an assistant coach/athletic director at
Emmanuel College in Boston. ``She's also had two players who have
gone back there for a fifth year. If I could, I'd have stayed there
for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever side is correct, the turmoil at UMass reflects a new
reality for women athletes. Being taken seriously means being
subjected to the same pressures _ and flaws _ that plague men's
college sports. It's the flip side of Title IX. There's more
exposure, more pressure to win, more pressure to find that certain
someone to carry the program.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it wasn't a game. It wasn't fun,'' Vallieres said.
``It was like going to work every day, having a job. Everything
here (at AIC) is so less stressful. It's a game again. This is more
like high school, where you have fun doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven to tears
</P>
<P>
   In her one year at Massachusetts, Vallieres kept a journal that
described a coach selective in her punishment, profane in her
language and abusive in her interactions with her players. ``I
never knew I would feel like I want to kill myself every day,''
Vallieres wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Roberta Cernik, recalled long, tearful telephone
conversations with her daughter. ``Am I bitter? I'm furious,''
Cernik said. ``This did not have to happen. And Nicky isn't the
only one. I feel sorry for all the girls there. I thank God my
daughter is out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallieres wanted desperately to play for Massachusetts. Her
uncle, Warren Anton, played on the freshman team with Julius Erving
and wore No. 44, the same number Vallieres chose as a freshman last
fall. But her excitement quickly ended when confronted with the
demands of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hard. I was on an emotional roller coaster every
day,'' she said. ``It was so tough. It wasn't normal, the way I was
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And while she was aware of O'Brien's reputation as a screamer,
she was unprepared for the real thing. During practice, she said
O'Brien would grab a player's arm ``very forcefully'' if the player
was out of position and ``sometimes even almost throw us in the
right direction.'' During games, Vallieres said, ``she would slap
our butts when we were subbing in.'' She recalled a teammate who
still had a welt on her behind two hours after a game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she ever grabbed players, O'Brien said, ``I guess it
would depend. Do we get after it in practice? Yeah. Am I involved?
As far as that type of stuff goes, not a lot. I'm not always the
one in there. But I'm a coach. I'm out there trying to show them
some things. `Get 'em here. Get 'em there. Do this. Do this. Watch
this.' Those types of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallieres may have been overmatched at UMass. She noticed
immediately that her teammates were faster, stronger, more
polished. O'Brien said the 5-foot-8-inch guard didn't deliver as
expected and, as a result, played only 66 minutes all season and
did not appear in one third of the 30 games. Vallieres told O'Brien
in January she wanted to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't deal with it anymore,'' Vallieres said. ``I was
used to getting a lot of playing time and here I am, sitting on the
bench. And the way she talked to me, I wasn't going to get too much
playing time in the future. I wanted to play ball. I wanted to have
fun. I wasn't doing either. So, I figured, why should I stay?''
</P>
<P>
   American International may be down a level, but it also meant
she wouldn't have to sit out the season. She couldn't wear No. 44 _
it was taken _ so she chose No. 21, the number she wore in high
school. Now, instead of spacious gyms with cushioned seats, she
plays in places like the Fieldhouse at Franklin Pierce College,
with wooden bleachers on one side and aluminum bleachers on the
other. The sound system wasn't working on a recent night, but no
one seemed to care, least of all the starting shooting guard for
AIC, Nicky Vallieres.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat performance
</P>
<P>
   When the UMass women gathered for the start of the 1998-99
season in mid-October, no one was more eager than the 5-11 Grant.
She was finally going to get a chance to play. She had played
sparingly as a freshman at Seton Hall and not at all last year
because of transfer regulations and surgery on both shins.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had practices begun, she said, than O'Brien was on
her in much the same way she said the coach had been on Vallieres
and Trent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember last year telling Trent and Nicky to `suck it up,
don't pay attention to what she says. Don't let it affect your
game,''' she said. ``They would tell me how hard it was with her
constantly on them every second. Then, when I started practicing,
it was me she was on all the time. She grabs people. She grabbed me
all the time and I didn't like it. Every time I stepped on the
court, it was (expletive) this and (expletive) that. The things she
says to you, well, no one should talk to anyone like that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien acknowledged that she ``probably'' was often profane
with her team. ``I don't know. Everyone has their own way of doing
things. But to say that I ever called anybody a name is an absolute
fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   On Halloween, O'Brien called Grant into her office. A teammate
had told the coach about a rules violation, one substantially more
severe than missing practice or being late for the team bus.
Neither Grant nor the university, however, has elaborated on the
violation. This was, however, Grant's second offense. She had done
the same thing the previous spring and, O'Brien said, had been told
that any future violation would lead to a dismissal from the team.
Grant said there had been no such warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that had been the case, I would have lied just to stay on
the team,'' Grant said. ``There was no proof. But I figured if I
just told the truth, Joanie would get mad and I'd get punished and
things would go from there. But I never expected her to kick me off
the team. I had no clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Grant understood the situation the second time around,
O'Brien said, ``yes, she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said she wasn't the only violator, however. She said
another player, a starter, was involved in both incidents. That
player remained on the team. Grant said she told O'Brien about the
individual the day after Halloween. O'Brien said she had received
no such information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who they're talking about,'' O'Brien said. ``If
she (the other individual) did it, no one ever said it. And she
never admitted it. I can't accuse her.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Grant, ``I understand I did something wrong, but why does
this rule apply to me and not to anyone else? The other players
know. If it had been the other way around, I would have asked why
she got kicked off and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant waited a few days to tell her parents. She talked to the
school's athletic psychologist, who, Grant said, cautioned her
against ``going to the newspapers.'' When she finally did call
home, her parents came up from New Jersey the next day, hoping to
see Marcum. They never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left a number for me to call,'' Marcum said. ``That's
where they said they would be. I left a message saying to call
back, that I'd be happy to meet with them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a month ago. There still has been no contact between
the Grants and either Marcum or O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you kick someone off the team, you could at least have the
decency to talk to their parents,'' Grant said. ``My parents don't
like what's going on at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dropout
</P>
<P>
   The Trents had better luck than the Grants. Having already
scheduled a meeting with Marcum, they drove to UMass and met with
the athletic director for an hour. Mark Trent has a long history in
Massachusetts women's prep basketball, running the Massachusetts
Magic program and coaching many of the region's top college stars,
including BC's Brianne Stepherson and BU's Alison Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   The family spelled out their concerns, and then Kara Trent
walked down the hall to O'Brien's office and said she was through.
</P>
<P>
   ``She walked in here, sat in this office, and said that I wasn't
letting her be the person she wanted to be,'' O'Brien said of
Trent, who also told her coach ``I don't agree with how you dealt
with Tory and I don't want to play for you anymore.'' That was the
gist of what she said.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it certainly looked as if Trent had adjusted
quite well to UMass. She had been a two-time Globe All-Scholastic
selection while playing at Sandwich High School and had been the
subject of a flattering story in the Cape Cod Times after she moved
into the starting lineup late last year. She later confided to
friends that ``I made a nightmare into a fairy tale'' while talking
to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, she dreaded the prospect of a second season under
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joanie was always on Trent last year,'' Grant said. ``And
Trent couldn't handle it. She couldn't handle the way Joanie talked
to her and it completely changed her game.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent participated in the first two weeks of practice this fall.
Then, after Grant was kicked off the team, Trent called home the
next night and told her parents she planned to quit.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutewomen lost five of their first six games this season
and, for the second straight year, also lost starter Kelly Van
Huisen to a torn anterior cruciate ligament. They are 4-7 after
Friday's 72-70 loss to Dartmouth. According to O'Brien, ``There's a
lot going on this year.'' Are the allegations a distraction?
``Yeah,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the season, O'Brien said she had the deepest and
most talented team in her eight years at Amherst. For a number of
reasons, that is no longer the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
