<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY DEMOCRACY HIJACKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people have spoken, and many of them say Congress has
ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not doing what Americans want,'' said Ann Fricke, the
liberal postmaster of small-town Burlington, Ill. A ``witch hunt,''
she called it.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cullen, an Atlanta salesman who twice voted against
Clinton, said, ``What Clinton did was despicable, but what they're
doing is totally deplorable.'' He called it ``politics masquerading
as jurisprudence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Bollman, a nuclear reactor operator for the US Air Force
from Napa, Calif., said he considers the impeachment hearings a
sham and subversion of the people's will. Bollman doesn't like
President Clinton, either his dalliance with a White House intern
or his refusal to fess up afterward, but he said it was ``time to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on long enough,'' Bollman said. ``People just
want it to go away already.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite poll after poll showing that the American people do not
want Clinton removed from office by impeachment, despite November
election results sending the same message, the House Judiciary
Committee voted on party lines to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The charges: perjury and obstruction of justice. The message,
said scores of voters from New York to Florida to Washington state
in interviews Saturday: Democracy has been hijacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We elect Congress; they're supposed to listen to us,'' said
Mike Owens, a Clinton supporter who works in the shipping and
receiving department of a Seattle company. ``If we say, `Hey, don't
pursue it,' then they shouldn't pursue it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Frank Tiano, vice president of a Philadelphia
pharmaceutical company, who did not vote for Clinton either time,
``There are things that Congress should be doing. I don't know if
impeachment of the president is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Tiano favors impeachment, although he dislikes the
partisanship displayed in Washington ever since Clinton's sexual
relationship with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky became public in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed that Clinton needs to be punished, if only
censured by Congress as the White House wants. But those
declarations also tended to break down along party lines, with
Republican voters wishing to see the president ousted and Democrats
wanting to see him left alone to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment ``is what should take place under the balance of
powers,'' said Brian Radachy, a Queens, N.Y., auto parts
distributor who voted for Clinton in 1992 and against him in 1996.
``The executive has committed a crime, now the legislature must
act. ... Though, surprisingly, he seems to have the support of the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spezzano, however, simply doesn't believe the polls
indicating that Clinton is as popular as ever, if not more so. As
the owner of a lawn-care service in Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., Spezzano
said he speaks with 100 or more clients a week. Most are against
Clinton and for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the silent majority is in favor of impeachment, but
they won't speak up,'' said Spezzano, who voted for Bob Dole in the
last election. ``The majority of the public'' agreed with
congressmen pushing for impeachment, he said. ``Secretly, they're
saying, `That's right.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Peggy Cozart, an Atlanta photographer and registered
independent who did not vote for Clinton, what the people want is
of little concern anyway. What matters, she said, is that in her
eyes Clinton broke the law. He lied to the American public and,
worse, in a court of law during his testimony in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person who supports the Constitution of the United
States, I believe we have to go with the rule of law, despite the
will of the people,'' Cozart said. ``In the South, segregation was
once the will of the people. The law doesn't have to do with what
people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Still the $40 million investigation by independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr has never gripped the rest of the country as it
has Washington. With the only charges at issue related to furtive
sex in the White House, many voters said they had no interest in
listening to the House Judiciary Committee hearings on radio or
television. Unlike the Watergate hearings, voters clearly were not
riveted.
</P>
<P>
   As Dano Weisbord, program director for the Family and Wilderness
Foundation in Plymouth, Vt., put it, ``I'm not indifferent or
angry; I'm fascinated but also bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Added her breakfast companion, Rob Schultz, the foundation's
executive director and also a Democrat: ``How could this be
anything but partisan? I'm disgusted with the Republicans, but also
with the Democrats for coming to Clinton's defense so thoroughly.
He's a bonehead, missing a few important standards. It's disgusting
partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the people who oppose impeachment, the phrase, ``witch
hunt,'' arose again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Holden, a high school history teacher in Atlanta, called
the impreachment effort a vendetta by Republicans intent on evening
the score for the forced resignation of President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Crenshaw, an environmental writer and consultant from
Birmingham, Ala., called the impeachment hearings a ``ruse to
attack and possibly destroy Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to imply, however, that the people who continue to
support Clinton or to oppose impeachment were willing to condone
his behavior. While many again said the fallout from the
president's extramarital relations should be between him and the
first lady, they also said they found his behavior distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   But few thought that lying about such an affair was what the
founding fathers had in mind when they penned the phrase, ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.'' Instead, time and again, they said that
Congress had wrongly made the personal political.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are out of their minds,'' said Jack Halsbond,
a Republican and freelance publicist in New York who said he
reluctantly voted for Clinton because he could not stand Dole.
``They're following a political agenda. ... How do you have
representation without paying attention to public opinion?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jim McGeough, a computer consultant who lives in
Washington, D.C.: ``I think they are very isolated from reality,
those Republicans on the committee. It's only recently that the
American public could gain instant access to such proceedings, and
I think the politicians are underestimating the feelings of the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rosie Colter, a Realtor from Charleston, S.C.: ``They say
that the American people want to know, but I want to know who these
American people are. Everybody I talk to wants to know why they're
doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome of the impeachment proceedings, many
voters predicted a backlash in the next election. While some fear
that voters will stay away from the polls, convinced by the
hearings that their representatives do not heed their wishes,
others said they will at least be heard at the voting place.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to lose their seats,'' said Craig
Levesh, a printer and registered independent from Branford, Conn.,
who voted for Clinton. ``Or a lot less people will be voting
because they'll say, `Why should I? They're not listening to me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
