u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-HNS &LR;      12-12 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
VIOLENCE OVERSHADOWS CLINTON'S FIRST VISIT TO PALESTINIAN-RULED
SOIL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By DEBORAH HORAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QALQILYA, West Bank _ Palestinians buried the latest two victims
of West Bank violence on Saturday with angry chants and shouts of
``God is great'' just hours before President Clinton arrived in
Israel to try to salvage an ailing peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At Israeli checkpoints outside Ramallah and Bethlehem,
Palestinian youths and Israeli soldiers clashed, while Palestinian
police tried in vain to stop the youths from throwing stones. In
Hebron, Palestinian demonstrators threw a homemade firebomb in the
central market.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Palestinians were injured by soldiers who fired
tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse the crowds. Two Israelis,
one border guard and a civilian, were also injured outside
Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   In Qalqilya, just before noon, pallbearers carried the body of
Kamal Adwan, 21, wrapped in a white Muslim burial shroud and a
Palestinian flag, as thousands of mourners slowly walked through
narrow streets to the town cemetery. At the same time, another
group of mourners gathered in the West Bank village of Qbeibeh to
bury Mohammed Suleiman, 18.
</P>
<P>
   The two young men had been among hundreds who fought with
Israeli soldiers Friday evening in an open field on Qalqilya's
western border with Israel. It was the deadliest incident in a week
of violent protests against the detention of hundreds of
Palestinians in Israelis jails. Adwan and Suleiman were the third
and fourth victims shot and killed during the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The violence has overshadowed Clinton's first visit to
Palestinian-ruled soil, a trip meant to add momentum to the Wye
peace accord, signed on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton is scheduled to address a meeting of the
Palestine National Council in Gaza City. The council is to remove
clauses of the Palestinian charter that call for Israel's
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's three-day visit will include trips to Gaza,
Palestinian-ruled Bethlehem on the West Bank and Masada, a hilltop
fortress that is symbolic of ancient Jewish resistance to the
Romans, in the Negev Desert.
</P>
<P>
   The week leading up to Clinton's visit has been marred by
violence and disputes between Israel and the Palestinians over the
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat accused Israel of
trying to ``raise tensions'' before Clinton's visit by allowing
troops to quell riots with live bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Israeli officials accused Arafat of instigating
problems by timing the demonstrations to coincide with Clinton's
visit as a way to pressure Israel to release more Palestinian
prisoners incarcerated for their involvement in the struggle
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, Palestinian prisoners and their families
have staged a hunger strike that they say will continue until the
last prisoner is released.
</P>
<P>
   Other Palestinians have gathered at hunger-strike tents set up
in most major West Bank and Gaza towns. Daily clashes between
Palestinian youths and Israeli soldiers have left hundreds injured.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Palestinian activists plan to call a general strike
in solidarity with the prisoners. And on Tuesday, they plan to have
the children of prisoners hold a candlelight vigil in Bethlehem to
coincide with Clinton's visit to that West Bank city to light a
Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   In Qalqilya on Saturday, Palestinians closed closing shops,
restaurants and schools in honor of the two dead, but Israeli army
checkpoints at the entrances to the city, the scenes of violent
rioting on Friday, remained quiet.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral, mourners vented anger at Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, who last month freed mostly common criminals in
a prisoner release deal negotiated in October at the Wye River
conference center. The crowd yelled, ``Netanyahu, you coward,
release all the prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only way to get the prisoners released,'' said
Nasser Mansour, head of the Palestinian Prisoners' Club in
Qalqilya, referring to the bloody clashes with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high price to pay,'' said Mansour. ``But there is no
other way. There is no peace as long as any prisoner is still in
Israeli prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu promised at the Wye negotiations to release 750
Palestinian prisoners. He angered Palestinians by mixing 150 common
criminals in with the first group of 250 that were released last
month. The action sparked riots that Palestinians have dubbed the
``prisoners' intifada,'' a reference to the seven-year uprising
against Israeli rule that ended with a peace agreement five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of brewing trouble, Israelis and Palestinians
spent last week in dispute over the purpose of Monday's meeting of
the Palestinian National Council in Gaza. Israel insists that the
700-member body conduct a formal vote to remove the clauses from
the Palestinian Liberation Organization charter calling for
Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wye agreement does not specifically call for a vote, and
the Palestinians say a vote is neither needed nor planned.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, U.S. officials were still trying to set up a
three-way meeting between Arafat, Netanyahu and Clinton, which the
Palestinian leader has already agreed to attend. Netanyahu has said
the meeting will take place only if the Palestinian National
Council votes to annul the controversial clauses of the charter on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Qalqiliya, Palestinians said they hoped Clinton's visit would
finally put the issue of the charter to rest and would push Israel
to release more prisoners. ``If he helps to free the prisoners
without conditions, then he will definitely help the situation
here,'' said Ghassan Jasser, an English teacher who taught
Suleiman, one of the two Palestinians killed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Gaza City, the militant Hamas organization
ridiculed the Palestinian Authority's anticipation of Clinton's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian Authority claims that Clinton's visit
reinforces Palestinian sovereignty, but this is a mere illusion,''
the leaflet said.
</P>
<P>
   (Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
