<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TIJERINA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPEVINE MAKES HUGE STATEMENT IN TEXAS 4A TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD TIJERINA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The hug between Grapevine football coach Mike Sneed and
Carroll coach Tom Rapp occurred at midfield, right on Texas
Stadium's big blue star. The words were from Sneed, and they were
oh so sweet for him to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't win district,'' Sneed told his District 11-4A
rival, ``but we won state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We won state''. The words sound strange _ not so much because
it is Grapevine High School we are talking about. The Mustangs
have, after all, now won two Class 4A Division I championships in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the way they did it that makes them such an incredible
story.
</P>
<P>
   These were not the Mustangs of old, that 1996 Grapevine team
that rampaged through Class 4A with an unblemished record. This was
a scrappy, sometimes ignored, often underestimated bunch.
</P>
<P>
   There are big games and big-game teams. Then there is Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's 22-0 victory against Bay City was an exclamation
point for so many, a perfect ending to a storybook season.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, junior linebacker Matt France laid in bed for
nearly three hours, unable to sleep, alone with his thoughts,
anxieties and hopes. He said he knew the Mustangs would dominate.
He was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best Christmas present I think I'll ever get in my
life,'' said France, who was the game's leading tackler. ``Nobody
expected us to do it, but now we're state champions.''
</P>
<P>
   State champions. There's that phrase again. How did these
Mustangs pull it off? How did Grapevine transform from a team that
had to defeat Colleyville Heritage and Keller in its final two
regular-season games simply to get into the playoffs into one that
now sits on top of the Class 4A mountain?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. All they did was manage to win the games that counted
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to think that to win a state title, you had to
have better players than anybody else, like we did in 1996,'' Sneed
said. ``This has been done in a whole different way. If your kids
want to win, you have a chance. For every team in Texas, this is
the ultimate goal. We're no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sneed wasn't given the credit he deserved for
leading Grapevine to a state title. Overshadowed by Lewisville's
championship the same year in Class 5A, Sneed was given the
sleight. Anyone could have taken a team that included Jack Brewer
and Tellis Redmon and won it all, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody will be saying that this year,'' Sneed
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, seniors can wear their state-title rings with pride.
Though they received rings then by being little-used junior-varsity
players called up for the playoffs, they don't wear them.
</P>
<P>
   Now they can. They did in 1998 what they felt they did not do in
1996: earn their rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the last game of my life and we won a state
championship,'' linebacker Jared Brown said. ``What more could you
ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Mustangs asked for much. They asked to find a way
to get into the playoffs and they did it. They asked to survive a
three-overtime gut-check against Greenville and they did it. They
asked to squeak past Plainview last week and they did that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, they asked for the magic one more time. France was
asking for his bedtime thoughts to be true. Sneed was asking for
his Mustangs to find a way. Quarterback Jordan Wilson was wanting a
new ring he could wear with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, they got all those things and more.
</P>
<P>
   They got their magic, their answered prayers, their vindication.
They earned their rings and their title. And they proved that the
rest of us who gave them up for dead more than a month ago were
instead dead wrong ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know the Mustangs never were dead.
</P>
<P>
   They were only getting started.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Tijerina writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 685-3871. E-mail:
tijerina(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's high
school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
