<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6831 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS &LR;      12-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH IMPEACHMENT CLOUD OVER HIS HEAD, CLINTON TRIES TO SALVAGE
MIDEAST PEACE ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Clinton, his mission to salvage a troubled
peace accord overshadowed by impeachment proceedings at home,
Saturday urged Palestinians and Israelis to keep their commitments
to the troubled Wye River agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But a tough-talking Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
his own right-wing coalition government near collapse, accused
Palestinians of breaching the peace and inciting violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
daughter Chelsea, was greeted at Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion
International Airport by Netanyahu and Israeli President Ezer
Weizman. But several of Netanyahu's conservative Cabinet members
boycotted the arrival, adding to the air of uncertainty about the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth time I have come here as president to
reaffirm America's unbreakable ties to Israel, to reaffirm our
unshakable commitment to Israel's security; and this time to
fulfill the pledge I made at the Wye talks to speak with the people
of Israel and the Palestinians about the benefits of peace,''
Clinton said. ``The United States will walk this road with Israel
every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, breaking from English for an unexpected passage in
Hebrew, denounced Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat's
quest for Palestinian statehood. The Palestinians have embraced
Clinton's visits to the Gaza Strip and the West Bank as a step
toward acknowledging an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli leader, whose decision to sign the Wye River
Memorandum in October angered members of his coalition and may
bring down his government in two weeks, said the accord ``means
that our partners must honor the agreements with deeds and not only
with promises that all too often prove empty; with implementation,
not with signatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This also means that our partners must totally and permanently
discard incitement, violence and terrorism. Above all, our partners
must realize that genuine peace can only be achieved through
negotiations, not through unilateral attempts to decide issues
which can only be settled by mutual consent,'' he said, referring
to statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here as part of an agreement in October at the Wye
Plantation in Maryland that he would address both Israelis and
Palestinians. The Wye River agreement called for further Israeli
troop withdrawals from the West Bank in return for security
guarantees for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   However, the accord appears troubled as Palestinians protest
Israel's refusal to release political prisoners. Israelis, in turn,
have postponed further troop withdrawals from the West Bank and the
situation seems again at a standstill. Violence repeatedly has
flared in the West Bank in recent days. Arafat also angered some
Israelis by announcing he would declare a Palestinian state in May.
</P>
<P>
   Many right-wing Israelis object to Clinton's visit here and to
the Palestinian territories. Some posters portray Clinton in a
black and white kaffiyeh similar to the headdress worn by Arafat.
But in Palestinian controlled areas, the president's visit is being
hailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Palestine,'' said many posters in Bethlehem. Police
tore down signs around Clinton's hotel referring to his affair with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will address Israeli youth tonight (Sunday) here. On
Monday, he will speak to the Palestinian National Council in Gaza
City as it affirms removal of passages in its charter calling for
Israel's destruction. On Tuesday, Clinton will tour Holy Land sites
before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that for two peoples who are fated to share this
land, peace is not simply an option among many, but the only choice
that can avert still more years of bloodshed, apprehension and
sorrow,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   His visit to the troubled region sparked a remarkable display of
security as Israel put 10,000 police onto its streets. Soldiers
with automatic weapons slung casually over their shoulders
patrolled the streets around Clinton's hotel, even though Hamas,
the Palestinian terrorist group, pledged to give Clinton safe
passage.
</P>
<P>
   The oddly timed trip came as not only Netanyahu was fighting for
his political life but Clinton's fate also was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   As Air Force One landed in Tel Aviv, the House Judiciary
Committee in Washington was debating a resolution to censure the
president for lying about a sexual affair with a White House
intern. The resolution later failed, but the committee already had
approved four articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on board Air Force One with Clinton were Rep. Rick
Lazio, R-N.Y., and Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa. If the dramatic issue
of impeachment was weighing on Clinton's mind it wasn't showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's wonderful. He's fine. He's in apparent good spirits,''
said Specter, who prefers having Clinton prosecuted after leaving
office instead of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also said it was important that Clinton be seen as
still in charge and that foreign policy was not being crippled by
the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, one of about two dozen undecided Republican moderates,
said he had not discussed the issue with Clinton. Lazio said it was
``up to him to raise the issue if he wants to speak to me. I'm not
looking for it (an impeachment conversation) and I'm not going to
ask for it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
