<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      12-12 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TWO PARTIES PLOT STRATEGY TO INFLUENCE PUBLIC, UNDECIDED LAWMAKERS
IN IMPEACHMENT BATTLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BENNETT ROTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle Washington Bureau &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a high-stakes impeachment showdown headed for
the House floor this week, Republicans have begun playing down the
impact of the historic vote, as Democrats escalated warnings of the
dire consequences of ousting the president.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing strategies, which were in evidence during the
Judiciary Committee's final deliberations Saturday, were aimed at
convincing undecided lawmakers and influencing a public that has
grown weary of the scandal and for the most part opposes the
president's removal.
</P>
<P>
   The full House consideration of impeachment, scheduled to begin
Thursday, will be decided by a handful of Republican moderates who
represent districts Clinton captured in his presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Judiciary Committee approved the fourth and final
article of impeachment, the panel's Republicans tried to reassure
those undecided lawmakers who may be nervous about upsetting the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that a House approval of impeachment only meant the
matter was being sent to the Senate for a trial. It takes a
two-thirds vote to remove the president, which is considered
unlikely in Clinton's case.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R- Ill., bristled at Democrats'
suggestion that the House impeachment vote meant that the moving
vans would be arriving at the White House any day now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you imply we are kicking him out of office you go too
far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., even suggested that if the Senate
convicted Clinton, it might decide to let him remain in office.
Such action is prohibited by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats, seeking to arouse voters opposed to
impeachment but who appear to be more focused on Christmas shopping
than the president's fate, stepped up their warnings that House
Republicans are on the verge of doing something drastic and harmful
to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not sending the Senate a questionnaire,'' said Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass., ``We are beginning the process of throwing
the president out of office. We are beginning the process of
undoing the last election.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats continued to insist that the only way out of the mess
was for the House to approve a censure resolution, a course that
polls show is favored by the majority of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee Republicans rejected such a resolution,
arguing that it was not tough enough punishment for a president who
they claimed repeatedly committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The debate and vote on censure broke down along the same
partisan lines as the other actions of a committee that has been
bitterly polarized since the day it commenced the impeachment
probe.
</P>
<P>
   And while many politicians predicted that for impeachment to be
accepted by voters it had to eventually win bipartisan backing, it
appears that the upcoming House debate and vote will be as divisive
and partisan as the committee deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believed that with Republican losses in the
midterm election and polls as recently as Saturday showing that as
many as 60 percent of Americans oppose impeachment that the GOP
would back off.
</P>
<P>
   However, spurred on by its most conservative members, the House
GOP has pressed forward with its impeachment drive. Political
observers say the national polls do not accurately reflect the
lawmakers' sentiment in part because they represent heavily
Republican districts which are supportive of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, many Republicans are scared that a vote against
impeachment will open them up to primary challenges. When one GOP
lawmaker, Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., said last week that he would
vote against impeachment, a conservative in his district
immediately announced he would challenge him.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including a number of prominent Republicans outside
of Washington, have argued that the impeachment pursuit has hurt
the GOP because it is increasingly alienating voters.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki, a leader among the moderate
Republicans, recently announced he supported censure over
impeachment, arguing ``I really want to see Congress focus on
issues that affect people's lives as opposed to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats believe that their only hope for stopping
impeachment is if a ground swell of public opposition materializes
in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   While the impeachment hearings have riveted the nation's
capital, they have failed to stir Americans in the way the
Watergate hearings did almost a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The three major networks largely ignored the proceedings last
week, with network executives citing public indifference and the
belief that the Senate would not convict the president.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Watergate, which sparked passionate demonstrations in
front of the White House, the current impeachment procedure has
produced only scattered protests.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday only a handful of demonstrators advocating Clinton's
impeachment marched in front of the White House. But they were
largely ignored by the tourists roaming the lawns and having their
pictures taken in front of the historic home of the president.
</P>
<P>
   David Rizzo, visiting from Tampa, said he wasn't terribly
interested in the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to listen to us,'' he said. Rizzo added that
while the impeachment didn't affect him personally, he feared that
kicking the president out could ``really throw a monkey wrench into
a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Cheryl Smith, also of Tampa, said she believed the
inquiry was a ``waste of taxpayer money.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she didn't believe the president should be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be different if he was doing a lousy job,'' she said.
``But the economy is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
