<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL WEARS SALARY CAP RIGHT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aside from insurance salesmen who dress up as referees every
weekend, aside from widening commercial breaks that destroy the
flow of the game, the NFL has it right.
</P>
<P>
   And aside from the natural evolution of talent, it is the only
major professional league that is better today than in the previous
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that a hard salary cap is the only way to save sports.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Sunday, three teams in the NFC are vying for the last
wild card entry. In the AFC, nine teams are above .500, with four
of six playoff slots up for grabs. For all the mediocrity, the
drama of competition still lives. Merely the reason you watch
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, baseball is spiraling out of control. The NBA is
getting sucked into the same vortex. And while the NHL might be on
solid ice, there's no doubt it has lost some of its roots.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Rupert Murdoch one-upped the rest of the fat cat
frat, purchasing the most expensive toy in the neighborhood. His
Los Angeles Dollars produced the first $100 million player, the
exclamation point on a league fast becoming a joke.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago when small markets had a chance in
baseball. The Minnesota Twins won two championships. The Kansas
City Royals won a World Series and lost a World Series. Even the
Milwaukee Brewers reached the pinnacle, losing to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   For a glorious while, in nearly every locale, the rite of spring
training flourished. The giddy belief that your team was going to
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, everything is neatly ordained. In 1998, if you didn't have
a payroll over $47 million, you didn't make the playoffs. With the
exception of the Blue Jays, you had to spend more than $46 million
just to break .500, which 15 teams did not.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 20 cities, or 67 percent of the league, knows their
teams have no chance entering next season. Hideous facts that
qualify as a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is at the same crossroads. Currently, small-market teams
such as Utah and Indiana still are in the mix. But if there is no
cap on high-end salaries soon, the league will have the same
division of classes.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors that the lockout might end by Christmas, and
hopefully, the players union is beginning to represent its masses.
Nearly 20 percent of the league is making the NBA minimum. And
they're all fighting for Stephon Marbury's right to make $100
million, so David Falk's commission doesn't take a hit.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is ridiculous, aptly described by a Chicago
columnist as two limousines fighting for one parking spot. But if
the current system prevails, the financial heavyweights will
eventually gobble up the best players. The middle class will
disappear. The small markets will get by at the cost of
competition. The NBA will become baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the owners must win this fight.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's problem is more about feel, the melody and not the
lyrics. It is about the declining Canadian influence, a country
that treats hockey with a respect and passion that most Americans
can never comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, eight of 21 teams belonged to Canada, at least one in
each division. While the NHL has expanded by six teams, it has lost
two Canadian cities. And now, four of six divisions are
all-American.
</P>
<P>
   So while the league is thriving as a whole, it has lost some of
its fervor, its clash of borders and cultures. All of the
mysteries, traditions and codes of chivalry that somehow weave
together the undeniable allure of hockey were born in Canada. But
now, their teams just can't compete economically. Not like they
used to.
</P>
<P>
   Three more U.S. teams will join the league in the next two
years, and the Canadian influence will shrink from 39 percent to 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, if we can't beat you, we'll buy you out. So thank you
for the players. And sorry about the corporate takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't that America?
</P>
<P>
   So be thankful this weekend that for all its warts and blown
calls, the NFL has a hard cap that every team can afford. And not
coincidentally, a system that still works. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
