<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
ASTRONAUTS' FINAL SPACEWALK PAVES WAY FOR MAY'S MISSION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By MARK CARREAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Spacewalking Endeavour astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman floated
outside the first components of the new international space station
on Saturday, preparing the towering spacecraft for the shuttle's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   The tasks took the two men 76 feet above Endeavour's cargo bay,
where the first two modules of the station jutted eight stories
into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' exclaimed Ross at one point, as he gazed at the sun
rising over Russia. ``Fantastic blues on the horizon, man.''
</P>
<P>
   During the near seven-hour excursion, the two men freed a jammed
guidance antenna, stowed construction tools and snapped photographs
documenting last week's assembly work. The walk was the third for
the duo since the shuttle crew linked the new station's American
Unity and Russian Zarya modules on Dec. 6. It was the mission's
final spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The Endeavour crew was prepared to undock from the first modules
of the new station today, leaving the 75-foot-long, 70,000-pound
orbital complex unstaffed in Earth orbit. The shuttle's 12-day
station-assembly flight is scheduled to end Tuesday night with a
landing at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's spacewalk was considered the lowest priority of the
mission's three excursions, conducted primarily to lighten the
workload for a pair of spacewalkers on the next shuttle-station
assembly flight in May.
</P>
<P>
   The spacewalk's most dramatic moments occurred as the two
astronauts scaled the modules to install a hand rail near the
summit of the towering structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the snow on the mountains below,'' said Ross as they
flew 248 miles over China. ``Not very often you get to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Working cherry-picker style from the tip of the shuttle's long
robot arm earlier in the excursion, Ross used a 10-foot-long
boat-hook tool to free a 4-foot-long guidance-system antenna on the
Russian module. Newman performed a similar task during Wednesday's
spacewalk. Both antennas had failed to deploy after Zarya's Nov. 20
launch from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Ross poked at the antenna, which was coiled like a tape measure,
more than a dozen times with the boat hook before it sprung free.
</P>
<P>
   The two men began their final spacewalk at 2:33 p.m., CST, by
lugging an ice-chest-size bag with nearly two dozen wrenches,
ratchets, foot restraints and power-tool attachments to the docking
assembly separating the two modules. Ross lashed the tool bag in
place, staging the implements for use by the May shuttle crew.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Newman were to complete the excursion late Saturday
with brief test flights of the back-mounted jet packs worn as a
rescue device.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the spacewalking astronauts are double-tethered to the
structure of the station or the tip of the robot arm as they work.
The jet packs would provide a sort of ``parachute,'' a means for
spacewalkers to steer themselves back to the station if both safety
lines were to snap.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's test flight was to be conducted with the two men
tethered in the shuttle's payload bay. During a similar test in
1997, a valve that allows the nitrogen gas fuel to reach the
thrusters on the jet pack failed to open.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
