<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6847 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-EAGLES-AZR &LR;      12-12 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-EAGLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SHOW SIGNALS CHANGE  
 PLUMMER'S DEBUT PUT CARDS IN HIS CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Fourteen months ago, Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer ran into his first NFL regular-season huddle and
immediately took charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `No more (expletive) around,' '' center Mike Devlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Who did this pencil-neck rookie think he was, thought some of
the veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, he announces, `We're going to take this down and score,'
'' Devlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were 98 yards from the Philadelphia Eagles' end
zone, hadn't scored a touchdown through three quarters and had
gained only 96 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer made good on his prediction, one of the most dramatic
debuts in the franchise's 100-year history. The Cardinals return to
Philadelphia today to play the Eagles, Plummer's opening act still
fresh on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The more the veterans thought about Plummer's remarks in the
huddle, the more they liked it. ``We needed something,'' offensive
tackle Lomas Brown said. ``We were at the point of being desperate.
We needed any spark.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Rob Moore listened and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the huddle jacked up and was yelling a whole
bunch of stuff,'' Moore said. ``He believed he could take it down
and score, and we needed that (attitude).''
</P>
<P>
   There was 10:26 left in the fourth quarter when Coach Vince
Tobin sent Plummer into the Oct. 19, 1997 game to replace Stoney
Case, who made his first start.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin told Plummer while the defense was on the field that he
was going to put him in the game on the next offensive series. &QL; 
Here, go 98 yards
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made the decision to put Jake in, I didn't envision it
would be at the 2-yard line,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer wasn't nervous about his pro debut. But he, too, didn't
expect to start with such poor field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of amazing I was actually getting a shot,'' he
said. ``It didn't really sink in until afterwards. But I just had
to go out and play. We were down to our third (quarterback) and no
one was really expecting much from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 2-yard line, the best-case scenario would be to drive
for a touchdown. The next best thing would be to get a little
yardage for the punter.
</P>
<P>
   Facing his first third-down situation, Plummer ran around right
end for five yards and a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he was cool as a cucumber,'' fullback Larry Centers
said. ``Then he scrambles for that first down, and I said, `You're
bad. You're a bad dude.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `I am, ain't I?' I thought, `That cocky rookie.' As
long as he was making first downs, I didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer missed his first three passes before hitting Moore for a
34-yard gain to the Eagles 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling that our future had come a little early,''
Moore said. ``I was just happy to be along for the ride.'' &QL; 
Sack, sack, touchdown
</P>
<P>
   Plummer got sacked on the next play. In fact, the Eagles were
blitzing him almost every passing down. But then he completed a
16-yard pass to Centers to the Eagles' 30.
</P>
<P>
   He got sacked again, and after an eight-yard completion to wide
receiver Frank Sanders, the Cardinals faced third and 11 at the
Eagles 31.
</P>
<P>
   The play-call in the huddle was a slant pattern by wide receiver
Kevin Williams, who caught Plummer's pass about the 25 and outraced
two defenders to the end zone for a 31-yard score. Joe Nedney's
extra point gave the Cardinals a 10-7 lead with 3:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your first touchdown pass is something obviously you're real
proud of, especially where I'd come from and everything,'' Plummer
said. ``It was a big moment for me and a big moment for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer had driven the Cardinals 98 yards in 14 plays, using
more than seven minutes of the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd actually do it,'' Brown said of Plummer
making good on his prediction. ``A young guy being put in a
situation like that in such hostile territory, it was so gutsy.''
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't have been surprised had they done their homework
on Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore at Boise Capital High School, he drove the team
to a 96-yard score on his first possession.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he made his first appearance at Arizona State as a
freshman against Utah at Sun Devil Stadium. His first pass went for
a 78-yard score. &QL; 
Some kind of rookie
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see (Plummer's 98-yard drive against the Eagles), but
I remember hearing about it,'' said free safety Pat Tillman, who
was a senior at ASU at the time. ``I know rookies don't normally do
that, but Jake's an exceptional guy. Some people have it; some
don't. He has it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Rose Bowl year, we knew if we needed points, he was going
to get them. If we had any chance in hell, he'd get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president/player personnel of the Cardinals,
had preached in meetings before the 1997 draft that Plummer had a
chance to be a special player because of his intangibles, including
comeback ability. He remembers talking about Plummer in one meeting
for 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Plummer became the first NFL quarterback to take his
team more than 66 yards for a score on his opening possession,
Ferguson got emotional in the press box at Philadelphia's Veterans
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited because that was the kind of thing we hoped he
could do on a regular basis,'' Ferguson said. ``It was storybook,
but the ending can be storybook, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there were some questions about this kid (physically).
But everybody said a horse (Seattle Slew) was too short. But all he
did was win the Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense couldn't hold on in regulation and allowed
Philadelphia to go 59 yards in 11 plays to tie the score on Chris
Boniol's 38-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, the Cardinals won the toss, and Plummer went right
to work. On first down, he ran for 18 yards to the Eagles 40. But
then a questionable intentional grounding call forced the Cardinals
into a second-and-27 situation.
</P>
<P>
   On third and 18, Plummer had Moore wide open. ``We still should
have won the game,'' Plummer said. ``People forget that I missed
Rob on a hook route and threw it short.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Cardinals punted, the Eagles needed only six plays to
go 73 yards for a game-winning field goal. It was the Cardinals'
fifth loss in a row, but Plummer's performance overshadowed
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   The following Tuesday, he was named the starter and has been in
every game since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he'll have 98 more of those before it's over,''
Ferguson said of Plummer's debut.
</P>
<P>
   Devlin said there has been some revisionist history in
discussing the 98-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legend has grown such that some think he (Plummer) really
wasn't actually there,'' Devlin said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
