<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     12-12 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA HUSTLES PAST UNLV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The game began with aerial acrobatics and
exhilarating alley-oops, as these December duels often do. But it
ended quite differently _ on the floor, with a slap, a scoop and a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA freshman forward JaRon Rush knew it, too. He knew the easy
baskets would disappear, the large lead would diminish and the
decisive plays would come at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   So he waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that the hustle points were going to matter,'' Rush
said after UCLA's 72-67 victory over Nevada-Las Vegas on Saturday
before 9,855 at Pauley Pavilion. ``My jumper wasn't falling, and
when that happens I try to go to the basket, get offensive
rebounds, get points that way. That's how you win games, with the
hustle points.''
</P>
<P>
   With 40 seconds remaining and the Bruins leading 68-67, Rush
slapped the ball from UNLV's Kevin Simmons as Simmons charged into
the heart of UCLA's defense. Baron Davis grabbed the loose ball,
was fouled, and made two free throws for a three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rush wasn't done. With 10 seconds left and UCLA leading 70-67,
he beat two Rebels to a loose ball, scooped it up and scored from
under the basket to secure the victory. Simple as that _ a slap, a
scoop and a smile, jumpers and dunks need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   The victory improved UCLA's record to 5-2 and moved the Bruins
one win closer to the 18 or 19 they'll need for an NCAA Tournament
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to recent seasons, when veteran UCLA teams could
count on 12 to 14 conference wins to pad the total, this year holds
no guarantees _ what with the most competitive Pac-10 in memory and
a lineup of freshmen and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will be heavily favored in their remaining December
games (Cal State Northridge, American, Loyola Marymount) and should
enter Pac-10 play with an 8-2 mark. What happens after that is
anyone's guess _ they could win 12 Pac-10 games or they could win
eight, such are the inconsistencies of youth. But each victory this
month increases their margin for error down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get satisfied,'' sophomore forward Travis Reed said.
``That's what happened (Saturday). We got that big lead and we got
satisfied. We got ahead early and thought we'd roll over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush's play typified UCLA. He started with a burst as the Bruins
built a 20-6 lead, then lapsed into a prolonged funk of fatigue and
frustration. Despite the double-digit deficit, UNLV never wavered
from its zone defense, and it slowly smothered the hard-charging
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels dominated the middle 20 minutes, outscoring UCLA
38-12 and building a 13-point lead with 13 minutes remaining.
UCLA's athleticism and energy gave way to its inexperience with
sloppy ballhandling, ill-timed shots and lethargic defense.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rush _ and the Bruins _ snapped out of it, using their best
defense of the season to hold UNLV without a field goal for 10
minutes. The frenzy on defense became efficiency on offense. Earl
Watson atoned for sloppy ballhandling with two 3-point shots during
UCLA's game-changing charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins tied it with five minutes left on Davis' dunk and
took their first lead of the second half with 1:57 remaining on Dan
Gadzuric's free throw. The rest was left to Rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a way of making it interesting,'' Bruins
coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rush's hustle points aside, the other lasting impression was
Davis _ or, rather, Davis' influence on Watson. When he's on the
bench and Watson must run the offense, the Bruins stagnate. When
Davis takes charge and Watson moves to the wing, where he can roam
and create without ballhandling responsibilities, the Bruins are at
their best.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise, then, that Watson's crucial 3-pointers came
from the left wing, on feeds from Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something Earl didn't look to do last year, but he's a
good offensive player,'' Davis said. ``We need him to be aggressive
for us to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
