r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      12-12 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTIVE SERVICE OR FICKLE FLOP?  
 DESPITE CRITICS, BCS BRINGS SANITY TO BOWLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Its family tree can be traced to 1991, when
something called the Bowl Coalition was formed. That begat the Bowl
Alliance in 1994, which has produced the Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your point of view, the BCS, which debuted this
season, is either a brilliant idea produced by great thinkers or
the ugly byproduct of an antiquated system.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, the bowls and conference officials have
tried to devise a system that would ensure the health of the bowl
system while pacifying those who have cried for a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   It's debatable whether their latest invention is working.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents point to this season's Fiesta Bowl, where No. 1
Tennessee will play No. 2 Florida State on Jan. 4, as proof that
the system works. The winner of that game surely will be the
consensus national champion, and the last few weeks of the season
have never been more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents point out that there easily could be have been three
undefeated teams this year, meaning one would have been left out of
a so-called title game. And, they say, there are at least six other
teams in the Top 10 that deserve a shot at the national title at
least as much as the once-beaten Seminoles do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things worked out for us; we were lucky,'' Florida State Coach
Bobby Bowden said. ``And yet, there are several other teams who
probably deserve to be in there as much as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year of the Bowl Championship Series, which
was formed when the Rose Bowl joined the system, assuring that the
Pac-10 and Big Ten champions would be available to play in a
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS agreement involves four bowls _ the Fiesta, Sugar,
Orange and Rose _ and guarantees berths to six conferences _ the
Atlantic Coast, the Big East, Big 12, Southeastern, Big Ten and
Pac-10 _ and, in some cases, Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS agreement is for four years, with an option for three
more.
</P>
<P>
   A formula comprised of the two polls, strength of schedule,
record and the average of three computer polls was devised to
determine the top two teams that would meet at one of the bowls on
a rotating basis.
</P>
<P>
   When the formula was announced, officials cautioned that its
only intent was to identify the top two teams in the country. The
other three bowls were still free to make their own match-ups after
conference tie-ins were honored.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations of the system grew during the first season. As
perceived flaws were detected, the cry for a playoff system became
louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't designed to do all the things we thought it would
do,'' said Jim Livengood, Arizona's athletic director. ``We thought
it would be able to make coffee and straighten up furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   What it wasn't able to do was overcome the inherent unfairness
of bowl games, which have always existed to provide intriguing
match-ups, sell tickets and bring tourists to town. The bowls'
mission hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the national title game, the main goal of the other
games is to fill seats and provide an entertaining game. It's not
about matching up the No. 3 and No. 4 teams in the country, or
making sure No. 5 team (this year, Arizona) is assured of a spot in
a major bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar and Orange bowls were free to take two at-large teams,
Ohio State and Florida, even though both were ranked behind No. 3
Kansas State. And even though Florida has two losses, one more than
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   There was no joy in Manhattan, Kan., when the Wildcats were left
out of BCS bowls, which pay each team about $13 million, and ended
up in the Alamo Bowl, which pays about $1 million to each team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I would start thinking more of a championship format of an
eight-team playoff than I would have, say, one week ago,'' Kansas
State President Jon Wefald told reporters Monday. ``Based on the
numbers of calls I've had (from the media), I think people feel
that we got hosed. When something like that happens, sometimes
reform gets in the air, so we'll have to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, there was no expression of outrage from the Wildcats last
year, when the Fiesta Bowl passed over UCLA and North Carolina to
take Kansas State, which was ranked lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process that helped Kansas State last year maybe hurt them
this year,'' said John Junker, the executive director of the Fiesta
Bowl. ``I tend to look at our business over a period of years. No
matter what we say about the system, the greatest rewards go to
those who win the most and the latest.''
</P>
<P>
   That, critics maintain, is one reason why there should be a
playoff. Why should Florida State, beaten by North Carolina State
in September, have a shot at a national title when Kansas State,
which lost in double overtime in the Big 12 title game, does not?
</P>
<P>
   ``An early loss is less troublesome to people, and I don't think
that will ever change, no matter what the format,'' Junker said.
``That's just human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, like Bowden and Livengood, thinks the BCS system
has brought college football closer to a playoff. But that doesn't
mean a playoff is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much sentiment among college presidents for
extending the season, said Pac-10 Commissioner Tom Hansen, even
though it's done at other levels of NCAA football.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA studied the playoff issue a few years ago but rejected
it. One big factor is that the players on the study committee, Rob
Zatechka of Nebraska and Derrick Brooks of Florida State, said
athletes would want to share in the money the venture was sure to
make.
</P>
<P>
   ``That drove people away from it,'' Hansen said. ``If you were
only paying players who participated, how do you stop the horrible
inequity for the teams that get in every year? It would take the
first coach about a tenth of a second to say, `We're going to pay a
lot more money than the other team you're considering because we're
going to be in the eight-team playoff.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If you spread the money throughout Division I-A college
football, that might cause problems among a school's athletes, some
of whom were getting paid and some who weren't, Livengood said.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS formula and selection process is likely to undergo a
lengthy review process in the off-season. Some officials think the
automatic berths for conference champions should be reviewed. It's
unfair, they say, that this year's Big East champion, 18th-ranked
Syracuse, is playing in a BCS bowl when Kansas State and Arizona
are not.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS formula itself also will be examined. For example, some
people think the three computer rankings carry too much weight. But
it likely will be only a tuneup. Love or hate it, the BCS won't be
going away any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's a system that, whether or not we say it's perfect,
all the parties have agreed will be followed,'' Junker said. ``That
allows for a little sanity in the process that was missing 10 years
ago. It is a better system than has been employed in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
