<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFLCOL13-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFC EAST, PLAYOFFS GET NEW LOOK WITH DO-OVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upon further review, these plays don't stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vaulting''  &UR; Vinny Testaverde, who apparently has learned to
crawl after he runs, is down at the 1-yard line, preserving the
Seahawks' victory over the New York Jets last week.
</P>
<P>
   New England wide receiver  &UR; Shawn Jefferson's fourth-down catch
on the sideline against Buffalo two weeks ago is out of bounds,
allowing the Bills to hold on for the win and saving team owner
 &UR; Ralph Wilson $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh is awarded the ball in overtime when running back
 &UR; Jerome Bettis calls ``tails.'' The Steelers score on their first
drive and beat the Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   So these corrections in the NFL standings should be made: Miami
and Buffalo now lead the AFC East with 9-4 records. The Jets are
8-5 and New England is 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh improves to 8-5, putting the Steelers in the AFC
playoffs if the season were to end today.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're doing do-overs, here are some other wrongs that can
be corrected this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas drafts Marshall wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss instead of
North Carolina defensive end  &UR; Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than cutting him, Carolina tells quarterback  &UR; Kerry
Collins to stand in the corner until he grows up.
</P>
<P>
   Referee  &UR; Phil Luckett is sent to NFL Europe, formerly known as
the World League, until he masters the coin toss and learns that a
player doesn't score until he crosses the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has another vote for its nickname and choose any name
except Titans. &QL; 
Don't you dare &QL; 
Don't even suggest to Tampa Bay Coach  &UR; Tony Dungy that that league
bring back instant replay for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He is opposed to changing the rules ``in midstream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can change intentional grounding,'' Dungy said,
sarcastically. ``Maybe we can play with 12 men instead of 11. If
they put it in for the playoffs, I'd throw a fit if I was Seattle.
I'd say, `Why didn't you put replay in the week before our Jets
game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be retroactive. Why wait for the playoffs. Everybody
knew the ramifications of no replay when they voted that way. You
can't say there's been too much pass interference, so we're going
to change the rules for the playoffs.'' &QL; 
Clouded vision &QL; 
The headlines in the New York papers after Testaverde's phantom
touchdown were classic. The back page of the ``New York Post''
tabloid said, ``GOD'S A JET FAN.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``New York Daily News'' said, ``CLOSE ENOUGH.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Newsday,'' sympathizing with the Seahawks, said, ``They Wuz
Robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, not all of the Jets players agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver  &UR; Keyshawn Johnson thinks Testaverde actually
scored. ``Television can do a lot of different things,'' he said.
``I think the referee actually saw Vinny's right hand go over the
goal line with the ball in it. Then when the players pushing guys
back in the pile, you can't get a true feeling right there.
Television cameras, for some reason, didn't see exactly what we
saw. We saw a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde still thinks he scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the angle of the slow-motion replay, you would think that
I was down just short of the goal line,'' he said. ``But if they
had a camera on the goal line looking from one flat to the other,
and I'm taking the word of some of my teammates, you'd see a
different view of where the ball was.'' &QL; 
Superstitious &QL; 
Jets Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells, whose team plays at Miami today, might
be the most superstitious NFL coach of all time.
</P>
<P>
   He had dentist appointments on three consecutive Tuesday
mornings earlier this season, each preceding a victory. So on the
fourth straight Tuesday, he went to the dentist again ``even though
I didn't need anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had his teeth cleaned, and the Jets went on to win
their fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat there _ same chair, same time,'' Parcells said.
``But then the Colts beat us so I didn't have to go anymore.'' &QL; 
Overworked? &QL; 
Defensive lineman  &UR; Joe Phillips is the latest member of the St.
Louis Rams to complain about the grueling practices of Coach  &UR; Dick
Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said last week that Vermeil's training camp was
``abusive,'' joining former teammates  &UR; Leslie O'Neal and  &UR; Craig
Heyward in criticizing the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil doesn't think his practices are abusive but acknowledges
that they're ``very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   No team practices longer than the Rams' three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are responding,'' one Rams player said. ``The response is
we're 3-10.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Rams player recently asked of the team, ``How are
things at the slave factory?'' &QL; 
Beer bath &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Steelers fan was so upset with quarterback  &UR; Kordell Stewart
last week that he dumped beer on Stewart's head as he ran off the
field last Sunday at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was enraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's agitating walking off the field and people throwing beer
on you and saying this, that and other,'' Stewart said. ``I've
never had that happen to me in my life.'' &QL; 
Short people &QL; 
When Buffalo Bills quarterback  &UR; Doug Flutie was at a recent
autograph show, a woman came up to him and presented him with
Flutie's original NFL scouting report.
</P>
<P>
   The first two words on the report were ``extremely small.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it went into all the superlatives after that,'' Flutie
said. ``I'm thinking, `If you have all these superlatives, then why
is being too small an issue.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known the game from my perspective all my life. I've
never played the game at 6-2. I don't know what it's like to be
6-2. I've been successful at this game in whatever league I've been
in, and I have to do things the way I do them.'' &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL; 
Without  &UR; Deion Sanders, the Cowboys have given up six touchdown
passes and 598 passing yards in losses to Minnesota and New Orleans
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There's hope for the Detroit Lions on Monday night in San
Francisco. They are 1-8 on Sunday afternoon and 4-0 on Thursdays,
Monday nights and Sunday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay quarterback  &UR; Brett Favre's six fumbles at Tampa last
Monday night make him the team's all-time leader with 67.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are 4-2 since their bye week, the third-best record
in the NFC. Only Atlanta (6-0) and Minnesota (5-1) have done
better.
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
