<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURITY FAVORITE DESTROYED AFTER FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Those who claim horse racing produces the highest
highs and lowest lows in sports could call no better witnesses than
Bob Baffert, the nation's leading trainer, and Hal Earnhardt, one
of his veteran owners.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was one of the lows.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's and Earnhardt's 2-year-old colt Premier Property, the
odds-on favorite in the $393,000 Hollywood Futurity, broke down
shortly after finishing third to Tactical Cat and had to be
destroyed as he lay on the Hollywood Park track.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey David Flores, thrown under the inner rail, got to his
feet in a minute and was fit to ride in the next race. But Premier
Property suffered a severe fracture of his left front cannon (shin)
bone, and track veterinarian Dr. Ray Baran quickly decided to
administer a lethal injection, while an equine ambulance shielded
the 9,883 fans from the unpleasant sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hal and I have had some good times and some bad times
together,'' Baffert _ who trained Earnhardt's Indian Charlie to win
the Santa Anita Derby in April _ said with a shake of his head as
he walked from the track Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' Baffert said. ``The consolation is that
David Flores didn't get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Premier Property, a brown son of Out of Place who had won his
first three starts after being purchased for $100,000, led the
five-horse field into the stretch in the 1 1/16-mile Futurity. But
he tired and was passed on the outside by Baffert-trained Prime
Timber and Chris McCarron. Both were then passed by D. Wayne
Lukas-trained Tactical Cat and Laffit Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   Tactical Cat (who paid $15.80) won by half a length, giving
Lukas and the 51-year-old Pincay their fourth Juvenile victories
and their second together.
</P>
<P>
   Their performance was overshadowed by Premier Property's
accident, as were early-afternoon victories by front-running Lazy
Lode and Corey Nakatani in the $500,000 Hollywood Turf Cup and the
filly Love That Jazz and Kent Desormeaux in the $100,000 Vernon O.
Underwood sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tired,'' Baffert, trainer of the past two Kentucky
Derby winners, said of Premier Property, who had set fast
fractions. ``When they get hurt, it's when they get tired. It's
just a bad break. He took a bad step. It's not the track's fault or
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to give it (the lead) up. He kept trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the split second after the Futurity, this was a great day
of racing:
</P>
<P>
   _A $270,000 pick-six carryover produced a big payoff of $151,673
for each of six perfect tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _Nakatani, who would have ridden favorite and runner-up Yagli in
the Turf Cup if not for a new contract binding him to Thoroughbred
Corp.-owned horses, controlled a slow pace aboard Lazy Lode
($13.20) as they became the first wire-to-wire winners in 18
runnings of the 1{-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   _Love That Jazz ($5) rallied along the rail to beat 55-1 Peyrano
by a length to be the third female winner of the 6-furlong
Underwood and give Desormeaux and trainer Neil Drysdale their 21st
stakes victory together this year.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Bob Baffert-trained Excellent Meeting is 4-5 on the
morning line for today's Hollywood Starlet. This is one 2-year-olds
race Baffert hasn't won. D. Wayne Lukas, who trained the past four
Starlet winners, doesn't have a filly in the field of six. . . .
Laffit Pincay, with six wins in the past three days, has 8,672 in
his career, 161 shy of Bill Shoemaker's record. The Hollywood
Futurity was Pincay's first Grade I stakes victory since he and
Tipically Irish won the 1995 Oak Leaf for Lukas. . . . The $15.2
million wagered Saturday was a Hollywood Park fall-season record
for a non-Breeders' Cup day. . . . Apprentice Ariel Smith got a
10-day suspension from the Hollywood Park stewards _ five for each
of back-to-back disqualifications Friday. The ruling effectively
ends the 16-year-old's California career for now: He was already
scheduled to ride in New York after the Hollywood season ends Dec.
21.
</P>
</TEXT>
