<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOUSE COMMITTEE PASSES FOURTH ARTICLE OF IMPEACHMENT AGAINST
CLINTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle Washington Bureau &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee pushed
through a fourth and final article of impeachment against President
Clinton Saturday and rejected a Democratic measure to censure and
rebuke the president.
</P>
<P>
   With the stage already set for a historic vote by the full House
later this week, the Judiciary Committee voted 21-16 to add abuse
of power to other charges already recommended as grounds to
terminate Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The abuse of power article _ which was pared down considerably
by the committee _ accuses Clinton of providing ``perjurious, false
and misleading'' answers to some of the 81 questions from the
committee concerning his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the committee approved three other articles of
impeachment _ two alleging that Clinton lied under oath and another
accusing him of obstructing justice. Each cleared the committee
without a single vote from the panel's Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans showed comparable solidarity against the Democratic
censure resolution, which Clinton embraced a day earlier. The
measure accused Clinton of violating the trust of the American
people and dishonoring the office of president with his
``reprehensible behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was mocked by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who is among
the president's harshest critics. ``This isn't group therapy. This
isn't a feel-good session,'' Barr said. ``This is the Congress of
the United States and we have a solemn duty here ... to uphold the
Constitution. Let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   After voting down the censure resolution, the Republicans by
voice vote _ and no debate _ refused a Democratic request for the
committee to submit the measure as a minority report when the
impeachment issue reaches the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., sent a
letter to incoming House Speaker Bob Livingston, R-La., saying it
would be inappropriate for the full House to consider censure. ``A
resolution or amendment proposing censure of the president in lieu
of impeachment violates the rules of the House, threatens the
separation of powers, and fails to meet constitutional muster,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new speaker responded in a letter concurring with Hyde's
conclusions, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   White House special counsel Gregory Craig denounced the
Judiciary Committee vote and predicted that impeaching the
president will ``divide the country, gridlock the government and
defy the will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   If the full House approves any of the four articles from the
Judiciary Committee, Clinton would become the second president ever
impeached. He would then face a trial in the Senate similar to the
one that ended with President Andrew Johnson's acquittal in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   If two-thirds of the senators were to vote to convict, Clinton
would be removed immediately from office. Vice President Al Gore
would then become president.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after debate began Saturday on Article 4 _ the abuse of
power allegation _ the raw partisanship that has marked the
committee's three-month impeachment inquiry was once again laid
bare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does sometimes, to some people, begin to take on the
appearance of a coup,'' said Michigan Rep. John Conyers, the
committee's top-ranking Democrat. ``It's staggering. It's
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans bridled at Conyers' characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that impeaching a president of the United
States is a momentous act. But this is not a legislative coup
d'etat. This is a constitutional process,'' said Rep. Charles
Canady, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C. disputed charges he and his colleagues
were seeking vengeance in their pursuit of Clinton. ``We are not
being vengeful. We are not a lynch mob over here. I've had knots in
my guts all week,'' Coble said. ``I don't take it lightly. I don't
take it gleefully at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Before approving the abuse of power article, the panel voted
29-5 to remove three allegations of wrongdoing by the president,
leaving only the accusation that Clinton lied in several answers to
the 81 questions.
</P>
<P>
   As originally written, Article 4 had alleged the president
``frivolously'' asserted executive privilege in the investigation
by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. It also had accused Clinton
of making false statements to Cabinet members, aides and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they did not believe the deleted allegations
rose to the ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' standard set by the
Constitution for impeachable offenses. Democrats claimed the
Republicans drafted the article broadly so they could look fair and
bipartisan when they removed portions of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an orchestrated dance to create an illusion of
reasonability that I don't think people should fall for,'' said
Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   All four articles of impeachment _ which are outlined in a
resolution calling for Clinton's removal from office _ grew out of
his sworn statements and subsequent behavior in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit and, later, his testimony before a
federal grand jury used by independent counsel Kenneth Starr to
investigate the president's affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Article 1 alleges Clinton committed perjury during his August
testimony about the Lewinsky affair before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Article 2 alleges perjury during his January deposition in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Article 3 alleges obstruction of justice in seven instances when
Clinton attempted to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal''
evidence related to the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The censure resolution _ written by four of the committee's
Democratic members, including Houston Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee _
used words like reprehensible and despicable to describe Clinton's
behavior. While rebuking him, the resolution would also have left
him vulnerable to criminal and civil prosecution once his term ends
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure (of the president) is right for this nation. It causes
us to rise above the political divide. And it is not
unconstitutional,'' Jackson Lee said shortly before the resolution
was rejected, 22-14. Rep. Bobby Scott, D-Va., voted with the
Republicans and Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif. refused to take sides
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde argued against the censure resolution, comparing it to
``yelling at a teen-ager'' when angry. ``It purges you of your
emotional feelings, but I don't know what it accomplishes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
