<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 SOLID GOALIES PLUS WINNING SEASON EQUALS NO WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In just about any other NHL city, if a backup goalie such as the
Coyotes'  &UR; Jimmy Waite were getting this many starts and playing
this well to boot, headlines no doubt would be screaming, ``Goalie
controversy!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin's status as the club's No. 1 man would be
analyzed and scrutinized. Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld's decision to keep
turning to Waite every third game would be hashed and rehashed.
There would be whispers of discontent, rumors of clashing heads.
</P>
<P>
   But not in sunny Phoenix, where everything, including any form
of potential negativity, seems to get absorbed by the Coyotes'
amazing start this season. When you're winning as much and as often
as this team is _ the Coyotes were undefeated in 17 of their
previous 18 before Saturday's game at Ottawa _ everyone wears a
happy face.
</P>
<P>
   From forward  &UR; Jim Cummins, who hasn't blown up despite being a
healthy scratch for a dozen straight games, to the two goalies,
Khabibulin and Waite, each of whom legitimately could gripe about
wanting more starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so good about that team, besides the great defense
they're playing and the skill of their forwards,'' Ottawa Coach
 &UR; Jacques Martin said, ``is that you could throw either one of those
goalies in there and you'd feel real good about your chances. It's
quite a combination for Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   It has worked better than the  &UR; John Vanbiesbrouck-Ron Hextall
combo in Philadelphia. Or Carolina's pair of  &UR; Arturs Irbe and
 &UR; Trevor Kidd. Or the duo in Edmonton of  &UR; Mikhail Shtalenkov and
 &UR; Bob Essensa. It's better than  &UR; Patrick Roy and  &UR; Craig Billington
in Colorado and the Senators' own twosome of  &UR; Damian Rhodes and
 &UR; Ron Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said Khabibulin (10-3-1 before Saturday) and the
undefeated Waite (6-0-2) deserve credit for making the part-platoon
system work, although it remains clear that Khabibulin is still the
main man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what the people involved allow it to become,'' Schoenfeld
said of a potential goalie rift. ``You could write a great story
about there being this big controversy. Two Number 1's. Who's going
to be the Number 1 guy? Who's going to be the guy in the playoffs?
Or you could write nothing because nothing's there. But it's not
about that. It's how they (Khabibulin and Waite) interpret it, how
they respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an organizational point of view, we're thrilled to have
two goalies playing as well as they are. Both goalies should be
happy, too. Look, this is great for Nik that Jimmy can lessen the
load and Nik can be more effective by playing less games and be
physically, mentally and emotionally sharper when we need him to be
his best in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   There. He said it. Khabibulin is still the No. 1 guy. There's no
controversy. As for Waite, Schoenfeld said he'd like the backup to
make between 20 and 25 starts on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be more or less,'' he said, ``but based on the way
Jimmy's playing, there is no reason he's not going to get at least
that, if not more, if he keeps playing the way he's been
playing.'' &QL; 
Coffey talk
</P>
<P>
   We saw the premature ending of Cam Neely's career. Can  &UR; Paul
Coffey be very far behind? Sadly, it looks that way.
</P>
<P>
   The former perennial Norris Trophy winner has been battling a
series of lower-back and leg injuries all season and although he's
finally worked himself back into a position to play, it probably
won't last. But at least Coffey knows what went wrong with him
after his problems flared up during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   He recently went to the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota to find out why
his right leg kept going numb. According to Coffey, the doctors
told him he suffered nerve damage from the needle of an epidermal
block he took way back in the first week of October. The shot,
administered by the Blackhawks' medical staff, was supposed to ease
his lower back pain, but only exacerbated the problem and
apparently made everything worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I feel so much better,'' he said. ``I've been going
crazy. They hit a nerve. I'm bitter that it happened, but I don't
have any axes to grind. I just wish I would have known sooner so I
wouldn't be tormenting myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks' chief physician,  &UR; Mark Bowen, said Coffey is
mistaken, that the procedure didn't directly lead to his problems.
Tell that to GM  &UR; Bob Murray, who plunked over $2.5 million to pay
Mr. Coffey after his draft-day trade to Chicago. &QL; 
Behind bars
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nelson Slalbania, the man who signed  &UR; Wayne Gretzky to his
first professional hockey contract in 1978, has been sentenced to a
year in jail in Vancouver for the the theft of $100,000. Slalbania,
a player in the real estate game in western Canada, signed Gretzky
to a seven-year deal worth $850,000 when the superstar was only 17,
and he began his pro career with the Indianapolis Racers of the
WHA.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Slalbania sold Gretzky's rights to  &UR; Peter
Pocklington, who had purchased half of the Edmonton Oilers from
Slalbania for a Rolls Royce, a 14-carat diamond ring belonging to
his wife, Eva, and a painting by Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, bad luck _ and bad investments _ finally
caught up to Pocklington as well. The former Oilers' owner owes a
reported $60 million to a Canadian bank, and several of his
personal possessions have been repossessed in recent weeks. &QL; 
Head case
</P>
<P>
   For years, rumors have been circulating through the NHL that
Buffalo goalie  &UR; Dominik Hasek, the NHL's two-time Hart Trophy
winner as Player of the Year, is double jointed in the knees and
therefore enjoys some semblance of unfair advantage over his
puck-stopping peers.
</P>
<P>
   Hogwash. True or false, Hasek doesn't shy away from blocking
shots no matter where the puck hits him. Even if it's in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to stop the puck with my head,'' Hasek said.
``I try to do it sometimes in practice. Not every day, but once in
a while. I say to my teammates, `Shoot me in the head and I'll try
to stop the puck.' I'm not afraid at all of the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice and the bravery have paid off for the Dominator. &QL; 
Fastest draw in West
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have their fair share of faceoff specialists in  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Corkum, Jeremy Roenick, Mike Stapleton and  &UR; Juha Ylonen. But as
good as they are, they all pretty much pale in comparison to Dallas
Stars center  &UR; Joe Nieuwendyk, who had won 209 of 297 total draws
before Friday _ an incredible 70.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During a 3-3 draw with San Jose on Wednesday, Nieuwendyk won 20
of 21 faceoffs, and a couple of his final circle wins directly led
to goals. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
