A7065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBALABOR-HNS &LR;      12-12 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
 LABOR-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Optimism vanishes after short session
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Just one day after talk that a new agreement was on the horizon,
Saturday's talks between the National Basketball Players'
Association and NBA owners broke down after just 30 minutes, again
putting the season in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting nowhere,'' said NBA deputy commissioner Russ
Granik. ``We learned today that basically nothing has changed at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   No new talks have been scheduled _ secret or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern and union executive director Billy
Hunter had reportedly been trying to hammer out things themselves,
hoping to work out many points of contention in the proposals for a
new collective bargaining agreement. But, as has been the case in
almost all other discussions in this acrimonious labor war, once
larger committees got involved, things broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Expect more explosive ups and downs before the lockout, now in
its 166th day, gets settled.
</P>
<P>
   The owners were represented by Stern, Granik and their
attorneys, while Hunter, union president Patrick Ewing, Herb
Williams and lawyers represented the players.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem Saturday was that the union was reportedly
still insisting on 57 percent of basketball-related income (BRI)
and that they were unwilling to consider a maximum salary tied to a
percentage of the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was worth it, we would have stayed,'' said Stern. ``We
have to go back and report to ownership that we're quite far
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik was equally pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has moved on this track from Day 1,'' he said, ``and
despite the passage of time it didn't move today either.''
</P>
<P>
   The players blamed the owners for the stalemate, saying they
dropped a proposal to relax the changes to the league's timing
rules, which would prohibit teams that sign another team's free
agent from exceeding the salary cap to re-sign their own Larry Bird
exception free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Owners had changed their stance on this demand, allowing it to
be phased in over a period of years and including limited
exceptions, but players say those modifications were taken off the
table during recent negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed general issues we thought were pertinent,''
Hunter said. ``They basically said they had nothing more to say and
they thought it was not necessary to continue to meet, and they
basically left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the issues that we raised were extremely
significant and pertinent, but they continue to be intransigent.
We're trying, we'll continue to try, but it's still a situation
where it's necessary for us to fall on the sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being extremely reasonable, but how much is enough?
That's the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The league already is sharpening the swords.
</P>
<P>
   It is rumored that Stern is now making plans to shut down the
league office in New York, which is run on the six percent of gate
revenues it receives from every team in the league. Without games
being played, there are no gate revenues being generated, so Stern
is mulling plans to save money.
</P>
<P>
   This is what it has come to _ a $2 billion industry is now
reduced to counting paper clips.
</P>
<P>
   But the players are holding on to the notion that had their
spirits up Friday _ that an agreement will be reached before
Christmas and that games will begin in late January or early
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explored where we can go, they felt that it wasn't enough
and the meeting ended,'' said Ewing of Saturday's meeting. ``I
think that there will be a season. It's in no one's best interest
to blow the season up. The repercussions of them doing that would
be severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the mood of the players entering Saturday's meeting was
one of optimism _ a sharp contrast to the mood just 30 minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost two weeks since the full committees have been
involved in a session, last meeting on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we didn't have another meeting for
several days,'' said union attorney Jeffrey Kessler. ``But I also
wouldn't be surprised if we get a phone call from them tomorrow.
The problem is that they (the owners) don't think they have to make
any compromises in order to get a deal that will save the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of saving the season, which looked so bright on
Friday, dimmed _ again _ just 24 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still optimistic, Hunter said. ``You still can't convince
me that we're not going to get a deal or a season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
