<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING BOLTS STRIKE THREE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Two weeks before the second and final time he was
killed, Department of Public Safety officer Doug Knutson was ALMOST
killed, attacked and beaten outside his car while his terrified
wife, Sharon, huddled inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family has been through a lot,'' Sharon says. ``And, sure,
maybe I do feel a little picked on. But I don't believe our
experiences speak well of the justice system. Call it whatever you
like _ lightning striking the same place three times. Fate.
Tragedy. Bad luck. Whatever you call it, it wouldn't be justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Knutson died first on Feb. 22, 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He died a second time, for good, on Jan. 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly a year after she lost him, it's the incident between
her husband's two deaths that most haunts Sharon Knutson. She found
out over Thanksgiving weekend that charges against the suspects in
the beating may be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `Oh, no, not again,' '' she says. ``But
it happened. Again.''
</P>
<P>
   In late February 1983, the Knutsons' 6{-year-old son, Ricky, was
walking along 40th Street with an aunt, who pushed a stroller
holding Ricky's sister and a cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Driving by that day was 19-year-old Cole Dean Sorenson, then a
student at Arizona State University. Police would later find a vial
of cocaine on the car seat next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Without warning, Sorenson's Camaro jumped the curb and struck
Ricky, narrowly missing the others.
</P>
<P>
   The boy died.
</P>
<P>
   His mother and father, notified soon afterward, died with him.
As any loving parent would.
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN SLATE &QL; 
Sorenson eventually pleaded guilty to reckless endangerment and
soliciting to possess cocaine. He spent 14 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   A few years after that, Sorenson went before a judge and got his
record expunged, his slate wiped clean. The Knutsons found out
about it in 1990. I spoke with Sharon Knutson at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out that the charges (against Sorenson) had been
dismissed,'' she said, ``it made it seem like everybody was saying
it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   That was eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if that weren't horror enough, it happened again.
</P>
<P>
   Last Jan. 2, while DPS Officer Doug Knutson stood near his
motorcycle, waiting for a tow truck to remove an abandoned car from
a ramp of the Loop 202 freeway, he was struck and killed by a truck
driven by 22-year-old Bret Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the accident, the state Legislature passed a law
making it illegal to cross the white lines called a ``gore point''
on freeway ramps.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the truck that killed Knutson, however, was not
charged with a ny crime. &QL; 
`SENSE OF LOSS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of loss I could never get across to you,'' Sharon
says. ``The shock. The way you say to yourself, `This can't be
happening.' Particularly, since it occurred only a couple of weeks
after Doug had nearly gotten beaten to death.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been the week before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Knutson and Sharon were in his pickup truck, stopped at 24th
Street and Washington. After the light turned green and they
started forward, Sharon remembers a car running the red light and
clipping a vehicle near them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car just kept going, so Doug said, `We have to follow it,'
'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Knutson tailed the hit-and-run driver to a house near 30th
Street and Oak. When the car pulled into a driveway, he pulled in
behind it and got out of his truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as he got to the driver's door,'' Sharon says, ``Doug was
jumped by six or eight men. One of them had a gun and he put it to
Doug's head and just hit him with it. Then Doug was on the ground
and they were punching and kicking him.''
</P>
<P>
   The windows of the truck were tinted. Sharon slouched down where
she couldn't be seen. At one point in the struggle, Knutson
wrestled a semiautomatic handgun from one of the suspects and
tossed it into his truck. When police arrived, two men were taken
into custody and booked for assault. The driver of the car, a
woman, was charged with driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, on Thanksgiving weekend, I was told the county attorney
wanted to drop the charges,'' Sharon says.
</P>
<P>
   The men who beat Knutson claimed self-defense. They said Knutson
didn't immediately identify himself as a police officer, which is
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that,'' Sharon says. ``As if that gives six
or eight men, one with a gun, the right to beat on an unarmed man.
If they thought Doug was the bad guy, why did they all run when the
police arrived? This was an assault, and now that Doug is gone, the
prosecutors want the charges to go awak.''
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE DESERVED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Sharon and her remaining two children, 20-year-old Justin
and 19-year-old Misty, that's not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   And it shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Any reasonable interpretation of the
People-Who-Have-Been-Through-Enough Rule tells us that, for once,
the Knutsons deserve a shot at justice. They deserve something to
show for the two graves they must visit over the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley told me
Friday afternoon that, while one staff prosecutor has suggested the
case be dismissed, a final decision has yet to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case is still under review,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good chance prosecutors could lose in court, and they
know it. Losses lower the big conviction rate percentage they like
to brag about, and for that reason they still may drop the assault
charges without taking a swing at the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   They've gone to the plate for the Knutsons twice before and
stood there while the ball sailed by for called strikes.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the family is concerned, what works for the crooks
should apply to the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Three strikes and you're out. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
