r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-DISLIKED-A     12-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-DISLIKED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE SPENDING BREEDS DISDAIN FOR DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ About a year ago, the Diamondbacks became one of the
most vilified franchises in baseball, which was quite an
achievement considering the club still was months away from playing
its first game.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' controversial signing of shortstop Jay Bell to
a five-year, $34 million contract, in which they basically bid
against themselves, and their often brash statements of contending
in their first season made them an easy target for opposing front
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Their perceived disregard for the game's financial structure,
punctuated when they signed third baseman Matt Williams to a
five-year extension worth $45 million, had many opposing general
managers and owners stewing and steaming.
</P>
<P>
   The general thought among those who disliked the Diamondbacks
centered on thoughts such as, ``Just who do these young punks think
they are?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the resentment from opposing clubs originated from the
small-market clubs, the ones who realize they have virtually no
chance to compete as long as the current economic structure remains
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a sense that they had not suffered enough,''
a prominent American League general manager said. ``It was a case
of a new kid emerging on the block and immediately throwing their
weight around. That ticked off a lot of other clubs who basically
wished they could spend the same kind of money. I think a lot of it
centered around envy.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Diamondbacks remain on the short list of
the most-hated franchises in the majors. Whereas they were fairly
well despised a year ago, the Diamondbacks now find themselves
accepted by one faction, the large-market clubs capable of spending
big-time money.
</P>
<P>
   The small-market clubs, the ones who wanted the Diamondbacks to
follow the path of every previous expansion club, building from
within, still have no love for Arizona or its smooth point man,
Jerry Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not written in any constitution that expansion clubs
cannot sign free agents,'' Atlanta General Manager John Schuerholz
said. ``If they can afford the money, then they should be commended
for spending it on player payroll and not just sticking it in their
pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that hasn't stopped the anti-Diamondbacks faction from
rearing its head. When the Diamondbacks started signing free agents
this off-season, which began with the additions of reliever Greg
Swindell at three years for $5.7 million and Greg Colbrunn at two
years for $1.8 million, several clubs looked on rather
suspiciously, wondering what direction the Diamondbacks were
headed.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came quickly. Starters Todd Stottlemyre and Randy
Johnson joined Arizona's rotation for a combined $84.4 million for
the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Within a matter of days, the Diamondbacks had re-emerged on the
hate list of about 20 clubs, most from small markets. The feelings
about the Diamondbacks appear to be split between the haves and the
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got absolutely no problem with the direction the
Diamondbacks are headed, and I don't think anyone else should
either,'' Cleveland General Manager John Hart said. ``How can
anyone really get on a club when they're just trying to win?''
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly where part of the problem lies with the
perception of the Diamondbacks. Some opposing general managers
resent the Diamondbacks for not building their major league roster
through traditional avenues, meaning the often slow process of
waiting for draft picks to make their way to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   By basically circumventing that process and buying themselves a
contender, it's no wonder the Diamondbacks drew the ire of many
clubs, particularly those who can't afford to go the same route.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the basic response from the club has remained the
same. ``Don't penalize us because we have the means to go about our
business in this manner'' has been the company line given for
months by Colangelo, the club's managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, he seems to have a valid case. Nobody really bats an
eye when the New York Yankees or Los Angeles Dodgers go out and
spend tens of millions of dollars for premier free agents. That's
his primary argument whenever anyone mentions Arizona's spending
spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in this simply for a sip of champagne,'' Colangelo
said. ``We will not tear this thing down if we end up winning in a
short time span.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment is a pointed criticism of former Florida Marlins
owner Wayne Huizenga, who began tearing apart the 1997 World Series
champions that he basically built through free agency, within weeks
of beating Cleveland for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga has taken heat for his dismantling of the Marlins from
the moment it began in November of last year with Moises Alou's
trade to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks plan to fill their roster with proven veterans
now and wait for the fledgling minor league system to spit out
major league players, a process that can take as long as four or
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really go in any direction until you know what
you've got,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said. ``What
every club needs is players coming up from the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Diamondbacks realize they will continue to
feel the wrath of some opposing clubs. The clubs that have a
dislike for Arizona can dictate which league the Diamondbacks are
assigned to for 2000, when a major shuffling of the leagues is
expected to take place.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' fate in the National League will be in the
hands of opposing teams after next season because of the expansion
agreement that the Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay signed when they
became the 29th and 30th major league clubs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
