<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGERED BY CRITICISM, LARUSSA STRIKES BACK AT GANT, BRANTLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE - It didn't take long for St. Louis Manager  &UR; Tony La
Russa to take exception to disparaging remarks made by former
Cardinals  &UR; Ron
 &UR; Gant, who said  &UR; Mark McGwire should have batted fourth instead of
third in order to help the Cardinals lineup, and  &UR; Jeff Brantley,
who said he had a terrible working relationship with pitching coach
 &UR; Dave Duncan. La Russa lashed out at both last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lineup worked for  &UR; Ray Lankford and  &UR; Brian Jordan and
 &UR; Delino
 &UR; DeShields and  &UR; J.D. Drew in his few games in September,'' La Russa
said. ``The only one it didn't work for was Ron Gant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was whiff, whiff, whiff. I really hope he goes to Philly
and whiffs for them like he whiffed for us. And we'll see what
excuse he makes. The last two years, he made these comments to me
about the fans not being behind him. I couldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Ron, in any other city, if you had struck out that
many times, you wouldn't be able to show your face on the street.
These people cheer anything you do that's positive. They don't even
boo you when you get announced.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watched us seven games a week, in five games Ron was a
non-factor, 0 for 4 with two strikeouts. In the other two games,
he'd do something crucial to winning. You'd think, `Man, if he
could do that more often, we're in business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for Brantley, La Russa said, ``Here's a guy who had 14 saves
and eight blown saves. He must have had a memory loss during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a half dozen of those flameouts, it got a little ugly.
Duncan went to bat for him a hundred times. If we pitched him, he
got booed. If we didn't pitch him, people wrote that he deserved a
chance. What Brantley said, he embarrassed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are down on him, so they're not going to believe him.
And Duncan's reputation is unanimous. The other players know that
Dunc is the best. Jeff should have said, `The manager misused me.'
That's a better sell. The manager's not as highly regarded as the
pitching coach.'' &QL; 
Park's avenue &QL; 
Los Angeles right-hander  &UR; Chan Ho Park may be pitching for his
freedom this week when he takes the mound for the South Korean
national team, which is competing in the Asian Games in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who turns 26 next June 30, has received several deferments
for the mandatory two-year military service time every South Korean
male must complete before his 27th birthday. Park has been able to
defer his time because he has hidden behind the status of student
while he takes English courses.
</P>
<P>
   Park's status as a national hero in South Korea has helped him
slide back home. Last week, Park told reporters covering the event
in Bangkok that he has a deal set up with the South Korean
government that might allow him to bypass military service if he
helps lead his team to the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Park could be forced to lose up to two years of big-league
service if his government forces the issue and makes him do his
military time. More important, Park, who was 15-9 with a 3.71 ERA
last season, could easily lose upwards of $10 million if that
becomes the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't care about that now,'' Park said. ``I only care
about winning (in Thailand).''
</P>
<P>
   That's a stark contrast to what he told reporter Ken Daley four
years ago: ``Of course the military duty is a law, and I have to
abide by it. But if the Korean government does give me more time to
stay here and play a little bit more baseball, that would be
greatly appreciated. . . . If I become an important player here,
hopefully they will.'' &QL; 
On thin ice? &QL; 
The Atlanta Braves say they are between $5 and $8 million over
budget for the 1999 season. The Braves are looking at a payroll of
nearly $75 million right now.
</P>
<P>
   The one player who should be most worried about his future with
the club is left fielder  &UR; Ryan Klesko, whose $4.75 million salary
for next season is just about the amount the club wants to cut in
order to meet its 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko should also worry since the club recently signed
outfielders
 &UR; Brian Jordan and  &UR; Otis Nixon, who is the only true leadoff hitter
on the club's 40-man roster. Klesko is fully aware that his name
has been mentioned most often in trade rumors this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Making Klesko's status with Atlanta more tenuous were his 18
home runs last season, his lowest total since his rookie season in
1994. Add his .259 average with just two home runs in the second
half of the season and it's no wonder the Braves are shopping
Klesko. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; You'd think the guy would step up to the $100 tables now:  &UR; Randy
 &UR; Johnson, new ace of the Diamondbacks staff, was spotted playing
blackjack in Las Vegas last week at a $5 table.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; There is joy in Mudville, well, at least Detroit:
 &UR; Ernie Harwell, the Hall of Fame voice behind the Detroit Tigers for
32 years ending in 1991, will return behind the mike in 1999.
Harwell is arguably the most popular sports figure in the Motor
City.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Roy Smalley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here's a sign Arizona should hope it never sees: For the fourth
consecutive year, the Cleveland Indians expect to sell out every
home game before they begin spring training. Of course, that means
no one can ever walk up and buy a ticket to a game this summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Last time he said this he wound up playing one game
 &UR; in the outfield for Boston: Jose Canseco insists he wants to play
the outfield next season for the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, who signed
the one-time Most Valuable Player to a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trivia for the buffs: Hats off to  &UR; Si Johnson, the last man to
strike out  &UR; Babe Ruth. Johnson was a young pitcher for Cincinnati
when he whiffed the mighty Bambino three times in one game on May
29, 1935, one day before Ruth played his final game. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Could there possibly be any higher compliment than the one
delivered by Minnesota Manager  &UR; Tom Kelly last week after  &UR; Paul
Molitor retired? Kelly said, ``Paul Molitor? On the baseball field,
he's a moving clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Only  &UR; Mark McGwire,  &UR; Barry Bonds,  &UR; Sammy Sosa,  &UR; Andres
 &UR; Galarraga,  &UR; Mike Piazza and  &UR; Matt Williams have more 30-homer
seasons in their careers than Philadelphia's new left fielder,  &UR; Ron
Gant.
</P>
<P>
   Of the players on Atlanta's 40-man roster, only 10 have appeared
in a World Series game for the Braves. They are:  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Glavine,  &UR; Andruw Jones,  &UR; Chipper Jones,  &UR; Ryan Klesko,  &UR; Javier
Lopez,  &UR; Greg
 &UR; Maddux,  &UR; Eddie Perez,  &UR; John Smoltz,  &UR; Mark Wohlers and  &UR; Otis Nixon,
who returns to Atlanta next year.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego, which offered then free-agent pitcher
 &UR; Kevin Brown a five-year deal worth $55 million and was willing to
take it up to six years and $70 million, had never negotiated a
contract higher than the three-year, $15 million deal it gave  &UR; Greg
Vaughn last year.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest reason  &UR; B.J. Surhoff turned down Pittsburgh's
four-year offer for $16 million was the franchise's uncertainty of
getting its new stadium built, which, in turn, leads to uncertainty
the Pirates will remain in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds will make subtle changes in their uniforms
for the 1999 season, adding the ever-popular color of black to
their trim. In addition, the club will rid itself of the red-billed
white caps, the ones that made the players look like ice cream
salesmen. More drastic changes are planned for the uniforms when
the club moves into its new digs in 2002. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota General Manager  &UR; Terry Ryan receives several weekly
phone calls about the availability of pitcher  &UR; Brad
 &UR; Radke, turning each one away with ease. However, if Seattle were to
offer, say,  &UR; Ryan Anderson, the Twins might be willing to part with
Radke.
</P>
<P>
   Of Baltimore's top three prospects _ first baseman
 &UR; Calvin Pickering, second baseman  &UR; Jerry Hairston Jr., and third
baseman
 &UR; Ryan Minor _ the Orioles appear willing to part with Minor, the
former All-America basketball player at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Orel Hershiser, just 10 victories shy of reaching 200 for his
career, is talking about signing with either Florida or Tampa Bay,
both of which are a short flight or drive away from his Orlando
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has its eyes on  &UR; Bill Haselman and may make the
free-agent catcher a contract offer within a matter of weeks, if
not days. Part of the reason the Tigers are so interested was a
glowing recommendation from  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre, now with the
Diamondbacks.``'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
