<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BIG DEAL, BUT BAN ON HUNT CONTESTS IS NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You may not want to hear any more about Predator Hunt
Extreme or any predator hunting contests.
</P>
<P>
   It's a frustrating topic. The number of predator hunters is
minuscule. Will the media-generated furor over these contests never
go away?
</P>
<P>
   No, it won't. And that's why we must address it again.
</P>
<P>
   Predator Hunt Extreme was promoted by two Mesa men early this
year. It offered a $10,000 prize for the hunter who killed the most
coyotes, bobcats or foxes.
</P>
<P>
   The media jumped on the story, and public outrage caused the
event to be canceled. Those who sponsored it thought they were
doing a good thing. Reduce predator numbers, they believed, and
deer populations would grow. More hunting opportunities, of course.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking is flawed. You can trap, shoot, poison or run down
coyotes with sight dogs. You might reduce their numbers
temporarily, but they are almost as adaptable as a cockroach.
They'll fill their niche.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I love coyotes. I sat in a boat at Lake
Pleasant last week and forgot fishing as a coyote worked its way
along the shoreline. They are marvelous animals.
</P>
<P>
   I've called coyotes any number of times. I used to shoot them
but now just like to see them approach after being attracted by the
call of a wounded rabbit or the like.
</P>
<P>
   Predator hunts aren't the only contests being staged in Arizona.
In northwest Arizona, prairie dog hunts have some enthusiasts. A
.243 rifle, a good scope and patience pays off when the prairie
dogs come to sit above their burrows.
</P>
<P>
   Even anti-hunting groups will admit that predator hunting
contests have almost no impact on populations. It's calling in a
coyote that matters most, not shooting it. The number of predators
killed during contests is extremely low.
</P>
<P>
   I have a friend who is a good shot and an avid coyote hunter.
Yet he misses more than he hits. I suspect his heart is not in
killing the animals, just calling and seeing them. And I must admit
that seeing a coyote running toward you and jumping over you at the
final moment is pretty thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   But Game and Fish commissioners have another problem here:
public perception. A vast majority of the public doesn't hunt.
Arizona has become an urban state. Most citizens don't mind
hunting, but killing for prizes turns them off.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights people call them body-count contests. That's
roughly true.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter to the general public that the hunts have
little or no biological impact. They don't like the idea of bounty
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish commissioners know the biological impact _
nothing. But they also know that the non-hunting public doesn't
favor these contests.
</P>
<P>
   Know what? At their March meeting in Tucson, commissioners
probably will vote to impose a rule that will eliminate organized
hunting contests. They probably have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   They admitted at a public meeting in Phoenix on Friday that if
they don't impose such a rule, that a vote on an initiative by the
people probably will.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of initiative killed trapping on public land in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   All of this doesn't sit well with some commissioners. Wildlife
management in this state has advanced in leaps and bounds. But
despite that management, the courts have taken over some wildlife.
The public wants to manage others.
</P>
<P>
   That's neither good nor bad. Wildlife belongs to the people.
They may not be able to make biological decisions about it, but
they seem to know what they want.
</P>
<P>
   My gut feeling is that rule making on the proposal should be
ended. Hunting contests are such a small part of Arizona hunting
that they mean nothing. Another restrictive rule probably isn't
just.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm a hunter. My non-hunting friends tell me I'm a monster
for not condemning these contests. I may be a monster but not for
thinking this isn't a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   A letter to ``The Republic'' last week carried the thought that
newly introduced Mexican gray wolves would be hiding in the bushes
waiting to eat schoolchildren. That is a completely uneducated
view. That simply doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   But wildlife is public domain. Educated or not, the public has a
right to have its say in wildlife management, except if it hurts
the resource. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
