<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO SHOWS DRAMATIC IMPROVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ With his family preparing for a funeral, Joe
DiMaggio made yet another remarkable comeback, one that left his
doctor thinking of upgrading his condition from critical to serious
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable improvement,'' Dr. Earl Barron told The
Associated Press. ``He was awake and talking to us. He is back to
where he was on Thanksgiving Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron credited the 84-year-old Hall of Famer's dramatic
improvement to an antibiotic _ Rifampin _ being administered
intravenously rather than orally after doctors realized that the
medicine was not being absorbed into DiMaggio's bloodstream. That
had been suggested by Dr. Nelson Zyde, an infectious-diseases
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this discovery had not been made, we would not be talking
about a live person,'' Barron said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, DiMaggio's longtime friend and attorney, said
DiMaggio's two granddaughters, their husbands and the four
great-grandchildren flew home to California on Friday night,
thinking the situation was hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaughters ``were crying hysterically yesterday, and
they said their goodbyes,'' he said. ``I really said goodbye to
him, too. I thought that was the last time I'd see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg said he even called an airline to make reservations to
the San Francisco area _ the planned site of the funeral. DiMaggio
had awakened from a coma on Friday, but Engelberg went home
thinking the worst.
</P>
<P>
   But DiMaggio's fever went down overnight, and his
white-blood-cell count had improved dramatically, Barron said.
X-rays showed an infected lung was largely clear of fluid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the X-rays today,'' Engelberg said. ``Before, you
couldn't see the lung. Now you can actually see his rib cage,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron daily has given Engelberg a rating of 1 to 10 on
DiMaggio's health, with 10 the best. Saturday, Engelberg said he
gave him a 5, the highest since DiMaggio had his first major
setback on Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sitting in a chair and sees and comprehends things,''
said Joe Nachio, DiMaggio's friend of 56 years. ``Now he's got a
fighting chance _ a 50-50 chance.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Engelberg, Nachio has been trying to lift
DiMaggio's spirits since he arrived on Tuesday from Panama to visit
DiMaggio at Memorial Regional Hospital here, where the former
Yankees center fielder has been since Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a funny guy,'' Engelberg said. ``He said, `Joe, there's
no center-field job open for you up there yet. Remember, you've got
bad knees.'''
</P>
<P>
   After lung cancer surgery on Oct. 14, DiMaggio has been near
death now four times, Barron has acknowledged, and Engelberg has
taken to calling him the Miracle Man.
</P>
<P>
   Nachio suggested Saturday that DiMaggio sign some baseballs
inscribed, ``the Miracle Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' Engelberg said. ``I kid around with `Miracle Man,' but
he'll always be the Yankee Clipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg said DiMaggio squeezed his hand Saturday. He said
DiMaggio was trying to talk, but could not because of his
tracheotomy. ``I said, `Joe, I brought you in here Oct. 12, and I
promised to bring you home,'' he said. ``Now don't you dare let me
down.' He squeezed my hand three or four times.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg said the head nurse treating DiMaggio advised them on
Friday to turn his respirator off, signifying that she felt there
was no hope and meaning he would likely die within a half-hour.
Engelberg, whom DiMaggio empowered to make such a decision, said he
asked Nachio's opinion, and they agreed not to.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg paused, basking for a moment in this latest good news.
``Some people may think it's like we're writing a script here,'' he
said. ``But if you see the hospital records, it's happening. And
it's a miracle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
