<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONTROVERSY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC OFFICIAL SAYS SITE VOTES WERE SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ It was a day of mixed signals and
inflammatory allegations at Olympic headquarters, and by the time
it ended, Marc Hodler, a senior International Olympic Committee
member, had expressed his belief that Salt Lake City was not the
only Olympic city that had tried to buy favors and votes in the
bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, a certain part of the votes always have been
given through corruption,'' said Hodler, an 80-year-old Swiss who
is a former president of the International Ski Federation and a
member of the elite IOC executive board that is meeting here until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of remarkable conversations with reporters, Hodler
said Saturday that at least four individuals he termed ``agents''
have offered blocks of IOC members' votes to cities bidding for the
Games, in exchange for payments ranging from $500,000 to as much as
$5 million in case of victory. Hodler said one of the agents was an
IOC member, although he declined to name him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He promises that he will give enough votes so they can win,''
Hodler said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler, who is responsible for establishing the Olympic Games'
bid procedures, said he believed that ``5 to 7 percent'' of the
IOC's 115 members asked for financial support in exchange for their
votes. Without offering specifics, he also suggested that both
Atlanta and Nagano, Japan, circumvented the rules in their
successful bids to host the 1996 Summer Olympics and 1998 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Nagano's bid, Hodler said, ``Certainly they had to
do things which were not legitimate.'' Asked whether Atlanta had
been clean, he initially answered, ``Certainly not''; later he said
that it was difficult to imagine that ``Atlanta could have been
facing this blackmail'' from agents without ``doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler's comments came the day after Bruce Baird, an Australian
politician formerly in charge of Sydney's bid for the 2000 Summer
Olympics, told The Sydney Morning Herald that he was approached by
someone who told him he could secure African IOC votes in exchange
for bribes. John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic
Committee and a member of the bidding team, confirmed that account
Saturday in Lausanne, and said Sydney had broken no bidding rules
in its attempt to secure the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's hard to believe, but I give them the benefit of
the doubt,'' Hodler said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler wants to strip the right to select Olympic cities from
the general IOC membership and give it to the 11-member executive
board, perhaps in conjunction with members of the small committee
that now evaluates bids on technical merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People we trust; people we know,'' Hodler said in describing
his ideal voting group. ``Don't forget that about 50 IOC members
are not interested in Winter Games and are not familiar with winter
sports. They ask their wives where they want to spend holidays in
the winter.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hodler said IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch had encouraged
him to lobby for electoral change at the next general meeting in
Seoul, South Korea, in June. But Samaranch and the executive board
clearly were not in full accord with Hodler's comments Saturday. In
the late afternoon, the executive board released a statement
disassociating itself from Hodler's allegations ``in connection
with the Olympic bid process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These allegations come as a surprise to us,'' said Francois
Carrard, the IOC director general, who added, ``Hodler is a very
highly respected IOC member who expresses his personal views.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch had to wait for the stage early in the afternoon
inside Olympic headquarters while Hodler continued detailing his
allegations during an impromptu news conference. After belatedly
taking his seat, Samaranch said: ``The spokesmen for the IOC
executive board are Carrard and myself. All the other comments are
personal comments, not official comments.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive board formed a special commission on Friday to
investigate scholarship payments made to relatives of some IOC
members by Salt Lake City officials during their successful bid to
hold the 2002 Winter Games. The Salt Lake Organizing Committee had
said that the payments came from a privately financed $500,000 fund
that was started in 1991, the year it lost the bidding for the 1998
Games to Nagano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
