<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BLASTED FOR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown will make $15 million per season
for the next seven seasons, which means he'll make roughly $500,000
every time he takes the mound to start a game.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-year, $105 million deal Brown agreed to Saturday sent
shockwaves throughout baseball, and not many people outside the
Dodgers organization were happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, the former general manager of the Oakland A's
and now the executive vice president of baseball operations in the
commissioner's office, was one of the most outspoken in his
criticism of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good baseball deal. This is not a decision made
by a baseball man _ I don't believe,'' Alderson said, implying the
deal was ordered by Fox executives.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch's Fox Group purchased the Dodgers last spring
from Peter O'Malley for a record $311 million. Some worried a
Murdoch-owned franchise would wreak havoc on the baseball market,
and now they believe their fears have been realized.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, however, defended the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers do not take payroll disparity and economic
responsibility lightly,'' general manager Kevin Malone said in a
statement. ``We are sensitive to the financial concerns of the
industry. This type of monetary commitment to a player of Kevin
Brown's abilities would enable us to field a championship-caliber
club now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner (Bud Selig) is completely frustrated,''
Alderson said in response to the statement. ``The commissioner held
a meeting last week in Chicago that wasn't even attended by the
people who made the decision. To me, that was an affront to the
commissioner. The media comments you have in the release are an
affront to the commissioner and an affront to baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, who went to the World Series with Brown in
1998, were in the running for the 33-year-old pitcher but simply
couldn't come up with good reason to offer a deal like the
Dodgers'. Padres owner John Moores had lobbied to keep Murdoch from
buying the Dodgers because he believed Murdoch would hurt the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to criticize Kevin Brown, but it's a truly tragic
day for baseball,'' Moores said. ``It's extraordinary. It confirms
my worst fears about what would happen if we let Murdoch buy the
Dodgers, and I think it represents a continuation of a very bad
series of events in baseball after a spectacular season.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Brown, the Padres have lost center fielder Steve
Finley and third baseman Ken Caminiti from last season's National
League champions.
</P>
<P>
   Moores said the Padres' top offer to Brown was six years for $60
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were holding our nose on that because six years for a
pitcher is absurd,'' Moores said. ``But we were going to step up to
it because he's obviously a great pitcher and we wanted to give it
our best shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the system is at the point of absolutely breaking
down. A number of people ought to be held responsible. Not just the
agents, but the players' association and the ownership of major
league baseball. We're on the verge of destroying the
competitiveness of many, many ballclubs. Maybe this will be the
straw that broke the camel's back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians general manager John Hart said the Brown deal
only amplifies what has been taking place this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, the horse is already out of the barn,''
Hart said. ``We are starting to see a separation from those clubs
that are almost going to a supergroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, Brown's agent, said the reaction to the deal is an
overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry behavior will always reflect that the contract of the
moment is the death knell for the society as a whole,'' he said
sarcastically. ``That's the drum that's going to be pounded _
especially close to L.A.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
