u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT &LR;      12-12 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NEGOTIATIONS BREAK OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chances of the National Basketball Association having a
season looked even dimmer Saturday after labor talks in Manhattan
broke off after only 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Though no progress was made, neither the league nor the players
union characterized the private negotiating session as divisive.
But with about a month required to restart the season, the pendulum
is swinging more and more toward losing the entire 1998-99
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``No progress was made,'' said Russ Granik, the NBA deputy
commissioner. ``Nothing's really changed. We're no closer on
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, said: ``We didn't
leave on bad terms. We had indicated to them we had some general
parameters pertaining to certain issues that we would be prepared
to take back to our negotiating committee. When we indicated what
they were, they took the position that it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, we felt we should just end the meeting while it
was still amicable.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether there had been any movement in the
percentages of total revenue demanded by the two sides, a key
issue. The players have proposed receiving 58 percent, while the
owners have said they envision a system in which the players would
receive between 52 percent and 53.5 percent for the first few years
of a new agreement. No further talks have been planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always hopeful,'' Hunter said, regarding whether an
agreement could be signed before the season is lost. ``I don't
believe in `no.' It's not in my vocabulary and it's not conducive
to negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
