<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-1S     12-12 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-1STLDWRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPEAKER TO VOTE FOR IMPEACHMENT, OPPOSE CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Leads with new comments from interview.) 
(rl) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, La. _ Rep. Bob Livingston, the incoming speaker of the
House, said Saturday night that he adamantly supported impeachment
of President Clinton and would fight to prevent a censure
resolution from a vote in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   After the House Judiciary Committee voted Saturday night to barr
a censure resolution offered by Democrats, Livingston said for the
first time that he considered it to be an attack on the rules, and
therefore an attack on the speaker and on the majority party.
</P>
<P>
   ``An attack on the rules is an attack on the chair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in an interview before returning to Washington from New
Orleans, Livingston also said he would vote to impeach the
president on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton had committed perjury and added, ``That's not
acceptable and must be dealt with in the only constitutional
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he opposed censure because it was ``not
envisioned in the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a constitutional responsibility to charge or not
charge, impeach or not impeach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Livingston raised the issue of Watergate to buttress his
argument. He said the president's sex scandal was as
``inconsequential'' as the ``third-rate burglary'' that led to the
Watergate scandal except, he said, that he believed Nixon had not
perjured himself whereas he believed Clinton had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon faced impeachment because he covered up a burglary
committed by others,'' he said. ``He did not perjure himself in
that cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said Clinton, however, had admitted ``certain acts
that he covered up and admits to having covered up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So why was impeachment the remedy for Nixon and not for
Clinton?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was particularly adamant that he would reject a
written request from House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt asking for
censure. Such a penalty, Livingston, ``is outside the rules of the
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Livingston has been deliberately ambiguous about
whether he would allow such a vote. As one who strongly supports
the committee system, Livingston has been at pains to avoid
sounding as if he were interfering with the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks earlier in the day, he suggested that Clinton's
apology to the nation on Friday was not enough to influence his own
vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief talk with reporters before he gave the commencement
address at Southeastern Louisiana University, Livingston, a former
criminal prosecutor, evinced a clear displeasure with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has his own actions to justify,'' he said. ``I
will not seek to give him counsel at this late date. A year has
gone by, and we've concentrated on little other than his actions in
the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that judging by the reaction of his colleagues to the
president's newest expression of regret, ``it doesn't appear that
it's made a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than responding to these questions, Livingston seemed to
revel in his distance from Washington this weekend. He delivered a
commencement speech here Saturday that was void of any reference to
the goings-on. Rather, he painted a self-deprecating portrait of
himself as a kind of knockabout who achieved what he has by having
a lot of luck and a good mother.
</P>
<P>
   He told the students that from today on, they should make the
right choices, ``not sell out for money or betray my friends or my
conscience or my religious convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make the wrong choices, if you do take that short way
out,'' he added, ``you might get by with it, but sooner or later,
the piper's got to be paid and you'll fall in the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure has been building in Washington for Livingston to step
into the breach. He has talked behind the scenes with Democrats,
including Gephardt and John Podesta, Clinton's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some of the 31 Democrats who had voted to
allow the Judiciary Committee to proceed with the impeachment
inquiry wrote a letter urging Livingston to allow a vote on an
alternative to impeachment when the full House took up the matter
next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
