<HEADER>
A7100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MEXICANS-GUADALUPE     12-12 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEXICANS-GUADALUPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS UNITE TO HONOR THEIR SPIRITUAL MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(rl) 
 By DAVID M. HERZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With impassioned prayers, adoring serenades, candles
and wave upon wave of red roses, thousands of Mexican immigrants
across New York rejoiced Saturday in the Feast of Our Lady of
Guadalupe, celebrating the Virgin they revere as their patron in
Masses, at neighborhood fiestas and with an early morning marathon
in which hundreds of the faithful carried flaming torches across
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said the marathon, Antorcha Guadalupana '98, would be
an annual event and was intended to draw attention to the plight of
Mexican workers. Many of of these workers hold the lowest-paying
jobs in service industries _ in kitchens, as cooks and dishwashers;
in groceries, as clerks and stock handlers; behind the counters of
delicatessens and pizza shops; in factories, or among construction
and cleaning crews.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Joel Magallan, a Jesuit who works for the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of New York as its liaison to Mexican immigrants, had
urged workers to attend the festivities even if it meant defying
their employers. ``We don't have any kind of day off for them,''
Magallan said. ``Some are people who are working 70 hours a week.
And they are working seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tepeyac Association, a Mexican cultural group, had predicted
that the holiday observance would amount to a general strike. But
Magallan and dozens of other people interviewed Saturday said few
had jeopardized their jobs by skipping work. Some, interviewed
after they had attended pre-dawn Mass, said they were on their way
to work and would rejoin the festivities later. Others said they
had arranged to take the day off without pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than working, it's important to pay respects,'' said
Ramiro Resendic, 25, a deli worker in midtown Manhattan who took
the day off. He said the celebration was worth losing a day's pay
of about $70. ``All Mexicans are more united because we have a day
to celebrate here,'' he said. ``We are taking this day to tell more
people and more people we want to live in the United States with
all the rights everybody else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high number of illegal immigrants, it is
difficult to measure the Mexican population in New York City, but
estimates by the federal government and scholars put the number
somewhere between 100,000 and 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Resendic was standing in an early morning chill waiting for the
marathon to begin outside the Church of Our Lady of Guadalupe on
West 14th Street. Gathering around him were groups of runners from
dozens of parishes throughout the city and from churches in
Yonkers, White Plains, and Newburgh, N.Y. Many wore white warm-up
jackets with a multicolored drawing of the Virgin on the back.
</P>
<P>
   The feast commemorates the Virgin Mary's appearance to Juan
Diego, an Aztec peasant, in 1531. The vision restored the faith of
Mexican natives who were in danger of losing their land, culture
and traditions after the Spanish conquest. The Virgin filled Juan
Diego's cloak with roses and left an image of herself on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest religious holiday of the year,'' Magallan
said. ``We say that we are more Guadalupanos than Mexicans. We say
that because Our Lady Guadalupe is our symbol, our identity. Our
Lady Guadalupe is stronger in the United States because she is the
mother of the oppressed people, of the people who are being
discriminated against. She is the protector, and so in New York
City when we are feeling we are suffering that kind of situation,
she becomes a stronger symbol to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   As the runners assembled, many waved the flag of Mexico. Chants
erupted from the crowd. Worshippers packed the church for the dawn
Mass to sing mananitas, the traditional songs greeting the Virgin.
Many carried roses, which they kissed and touched to a huge image
of Guadalupe on the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Juvier Mejia of the Bronx said, ``I came to observe the
Virgin and asked her to help me with work and with money and to
help my family.''
</P>
<P>
   David Solano, 24, a vendor on West 14th Street selling churros,
the Mexican fritters, and champurrado, the chocolate and corn meal
drink, said, ``We have faith in her. She's like the mama of all the
Mexicans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
