<DOCNO> NYT19981212.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-12 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 20)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNIVERSAL DONOR &LR;  By Craig Nova. Norton, $13. A Los Angeles
doctor, trying to save his lover after she is bitten by a snake
that she is studying, is forced to track down a psychopathic
criminal who shares her rare blood type. Part love story, part
thriller, this novel explores ``highly emotional conflicts without
resorting to either sentimentality or cliche,'' Scott Bradfield
wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CRYSTAL FRONTIER: A NOVEL IN NINE STORIES &LR;  By Carlos
Fuentes. Translated by Alfred Mac Adam. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$13. In a series of tales centering on a powerful tycoon and his
family, the prolific Mexican author explores the troubled relations
between his native country and the United States. Last year New
York Times reviewer Jay Parini found the stories uneven but said
that at their best they display ``acute observation'' and a fine
``sense of satire.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECCENTRIC NEIGHBORHOODS &LR;  By Rosario Ferr. Plume, $12.95. This
is a sweeping novel about the shifting fortunes of two upper-crust
families in Puerto Rico, one representing the nation's agrarian
past and the other its industrial future. ``The author's voice is
bright and vital,'' Mark Childress wrote earlier this year. ``The
magic in Ferr's fiction arises from the intertwined experiences of
human beings, carrying the story of 20th-century Puerto Rico in the
arc of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MRS. KEPPEL AND HER DAUGHTER &LR;  By Diana Souhami. St. Martin's
Griffin, $14.95. This chronicle of adultery, homosexuality and
intrigue among the British aristocracy focuses on Alice Keppel, the
winsome mistress of Queen Victoria's eldest son, both as prince of
Wales and as King Edward VII, and her daughter, Violet, whose heart
was broken when her affair with the writer Vita Sackville-West hit
the skids. The result is a ``fascinating, richly textured story,''
Kennedy Fraser wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE QUEEN: A BIOGRAPHY OF ELIZABETH II &LR;  By Ben Pimlott. Wiley,
$18.95. A professor of politics and contemporary history at the
University of London argues that the queen's dutiful, passive reign
is in keeping with Britain's sense of itself and its history. In
1997 the New York Times reviewer, Andrew Sullivan, called this a
``superbly judicious biography'' with ``a wry awareness of the
paradox of a populist monarchy being at the center of a
constitutional democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TRUEST PLEASURE &LR;  By Robert Morgan. Algonquin, $11.95. In
this historical novel, set in rural North Carolina early in the
century, a religious woman tells of her difficult marriage to an
industrious, practical-minded man, and their conflicting views of
salvation and devotion. ```The Truest Pleasure' is a quietly
audacious book,'' Richard Bausch wrote in The New York Times Book
Review in 1995. ``It contains characters and situations that aren't
easy to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAN WHO ATE EVERYTHING: AND OTHER GASTRONOMIC FEATS,
DISPUTES, AND PLEASURABLE PURSUITS &LR;  By Jeffrey Steingarten.
Vintage, $14. In these obsessively omnivorous essays, the food
critic for Vogue describes his far-flung gastronomic adventures,
stopping along the way with morsels of culinary advice and medical
and scientific digressions. ``Steingarten writes with marvelous
ease and clarity and humor,'' Alexander Chancellor said last year.
``His facts are fascinating and so are his recipes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLIVES: THE LIFE AND LORE OF A NOBLE FRUIT &LR;  By Mort Rosenblum.
North Point, $15. This is a journalist's freewheeling homage to
Athena's gift to mankind, crammed with history, recipes and health
tips. This is an ``edifying new book,'' Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
wrote in The New York Times in 1996. ``Pit by pit, his savory
details add up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIREWALL: THE IRAN-CONTRA CONSPIRACY AND COVER-UP &LR;  By Lawrence
E. Walsh. Norton, $18. The independent counsel in the Iran-contra
affair answers his many critics, charging that Congress,
conservative judges and, above all, Reagan administration officials
prevented him from meting out justice. ``Walsh's book is a useful
record of the scandal and its aftermath,'' John B. Judis wrote in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUN DANCER &LR;  By David London. University of Nebraska, $14.95.
This first novel is about a bloody confrontation between federal
agents and Indian protesters in the Black Hills of South Dakota.
The result is an ``unflinching look at the conflicts among the
Sioux, and ... the pervasive cynicism and slow-burn despair that
accompany a history of frustrated attempts to set right several
generations of wrongs,'' Scott Martelle said in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOONSHINE: A LIFE IN PURSUIT OF WHITE LIQUOR &LR;  By Alec
Wilkinson. Hungry Mind, $12.95. This profile of a brave and cunning
federal agent named Garland Bunting is also a history of
bootlegging, which these days mostly exploits alcoholics among the
rural poor. In 1985 the reviewer Bob Lancaster found the author's
``reporting style so sharp and economical that the prose fairly
crackles.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF FOUDINI M. CAT &LR;  By Susan Fromberg
Schaeffer. Fawcett, $10.95. A precocious house cat recounts his
life and times, from his abandonment as a kitten to his adoption by
a couple he named Warm and Pest. ``This entertaining cat's-eye view
of life ... can be recommended even to those who are less than
entranced by felines,'' Kimberly B. Marlowe wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2342EST &QL; 
