<HEADLINE>
GRAPEVINE RUNNING BACK GETS HIS CHANCE IN 4A TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID THOMAS and RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Grapevine senior running back Taylor Farden, who wore a
special shoe to protect broken bones in his foot, played in his
first postseason game yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Farden's numbers for the day: nine carries for 34 yards and a
bunch of big smiles in Grapevine's 22-0 Class 4A Division I
state-title game at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' said Farden, who played in only four games
this season because of foot injuries. ``I didn't think I'd get this
chance. They told me they'd get me back in there, and we kept
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Farden carried five times on Grapevine's final drive. His last
carry took the ball to Bay City's 2-yard line. But on the next
play, quarterback Jordan Wilson took a knee to run out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   So how bad did Farden want to score on that last possession?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad. Very bad,'' he said. ``I just couldn't break that last
tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   STOP RIGHT THERE: Bay City ran 11 plays inside Grapevine's 30 in
the first half. But the Black Cats accounted for minus-1 yard on
those plays. Bay City had losses on five plays, gains on four
plays, one incompletion and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   GET OUT THE BLEACH: Grapevine coach Mike Sneed told his team
this week that if it won the Class 4A Division I state
championship, he would bleach his hair.
</P>
<P>
   Sneed is about to go blond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be calling me Old Yeller pretty soon,'' Sneed
said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Sneed's second playoff bet payoff. After defeating
favored Greenville in the third round, Sneed had to come to school
dressed as a woman.
</P>
<P>
   THANKS, OFFENSE: Give an assist to the Grapevine offense for the
Mustangs only shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bay City coach Warren Trahan said Grapevine's big-play offense
was why he chose not to attempt field goals on three trips inside
the Mustangs' 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their high-scoring offense, three points wouldn't do us
any good,'' Trahan said. ``We had to have seven points every time
we got down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Black Cats got no points.
</P>
<P>
   On their first possession, the Black Cats were stopped on
fourth-and-1 at Grapevine's 27. On their next possession, Cliff
Roberts was intercepted in the end zone on a fourth-and-8 halfback
pass from Grapevine's 22.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 10-0, Trahan opted to go for it on fourth-and-5 from
Grapevine's 12 late in the first half. Chad Lee was sacked for an
8-yard loss. Then Grapevine drove 80 yards in seven plays for a
17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY: Grapevine running back Josh Cook's 72-yard run in the
first quarter was 33 yards more than he averaged per game during
the regular season. ... Bay City was shut out in both of its
losses. In Week 8 of the regular season, El Campo blanked the Black
Cats, 20-0. ... Grapevine quarterback Jordan Wilson passed the
3,000-yard mark for the season. His 146 yards extended his
single-season school record to 3,070 for the season. His two
touchdowns gave him 27 for the season. ... Grapevine has won two of
the three Class 4A Division I state championships. La Marque has
won both 4A Division II titles and will play for its third next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
