r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGHSCHOOL-     12-12 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGHSCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPEVINE TAKES 4A DIVISION I TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Believe it again. Somehow.
</P>
<P>
   The Grapevine Mustangs' unforeseen playoff ride exceeded
expectations one more time.
</P>
<P>
   In maybe their finest performance of the season, the Mustangs
were transformed from almost counted out in the regular season to
convincing state champions.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine overwhelmed Bay City, 22-0, in the Class 4A Division I
state championship game yesterday before 11,500 at Texas Stadium.
It was the Mustangs' only shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The title is Grapevine's second in three years and was achieved
in the opposite manner of the Mustangs' undefeated, talent-laden
1996 championship team. The Mustangs, who finished second in
District 11-4A, had to win their final two regular-season games
just to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream,'' said Grapevine coach Mike Sneed, tightly
clutching the title trophy. ``To win a championship, I always
thought you needed better talent. This shows what a bunch of good
players, a good coaching staff and a good system can do.''
</P>
<P>
   A .500 team after eight weeks, the Mustangs (11-4) capped their
season with their best game. Grapevine performed well from the
start, instead of needing another second-half revival that had
marked its playoff run. The Mustangs had this title wrapped up by
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bay City (12-2) was a threat early, penetrating Grapevine's
30-yard line on three of its first four possessions. But those
opportunities equaled nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't pull anything off,'' Bay City coach Warren Trahan
said. ``Everything we tried just seemed like it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything worked offensively for Grapevine. Senior running back
Josh Cook rumbled for 223 yards on 26 carries, surpassing Tellis
Redmon's 219-yard effort in the 1996 state championship game. Cook,
who had his second 200-yard game of the playoffs, ran for 718 yards
in the postseason and finished the season with 1,108 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cook exposed a defense expecting Grapevine to pass. Actually,
the Mustangs did that, too. Quarterback Jordan Wilson threw two
touchdown passes to receiver Jason Schindler and finished with a
respectable 146 yards to surpass the 3,000-yard mark for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Schindler, who had three catches for
57 yards. ``I never could in any way think this was possible. I was
joking around with the guys saying we are so terrible, how did we
do this?''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Grapevine's defense finished off its most
impressive effort of the season. Bay City, which entered the game
averaging 320 yards per game, was held to 6 yards in the second
half. Led by outside linebacker Matt France, who finished with a
team-high eight tackles, Grapevine's defense was everywhere Bay
City fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was domination,'' said France, one of eight junior
defensive starters. ``We didn't expect it, but we got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay City quarterback Chad Lee was sacked five times and his
offense was held to 163 yards _ the third team the Mustangs held
under 200 yards in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best game the Grapevine Mustangs have played all
year long,'' Grapevine junior nose guard J.J. Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   As Grapevine's defense stonewalled the Black Cats' offense, Cook
steadily pounded their defense. He averaged 8.5 yards per carry and
ran for 10 of Grapevine's 20 first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine finished the season one playoff victory from equaling
their regular-season win total. The Mustangs defeated four
consecutive teams with at least 10 victories. Bay City was pummeled
under that roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the kids we've been talking about having our best game
of the year, and we had it today,'' Sneed said.
</P>
<P>
   (Rick Herrin writes about high school sports for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 685-3864. Visit the
Star-Telegram's high school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
