<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-12 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXAS-UTAH-TEX     12-12 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-UTAH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS FIND BANK OPEN LATE IN UPSET OF NO. 25 UTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If there was any doubt that Texas was due a
break, it was erased with just over a minute to play last night in
the Erwin Center when Gabe Muoneke banked in a 3-point shot from
the top of the key.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke's perhaps ill-advised shot with 1:11 to play gave the
Longhorns their biggest lead of the night at 67-61. And despite
some suspect free-throw shooting over the last five minutes, Texas
held on to knock off No. 25 Utah, 73-68.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge win for this team and the program,'' said center Chris
Mihm, who posted a double-double with 16 points and 11 rebounds.
``A big statement game. There was a real feeling of elation in our
locker room tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas (2-5) won for only the second time this season, but has
now won two of three. Utah, which has three starters back from the
team that lost the NCAA championship game to Kentucky, fell to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Texas beat us is because they are a better team,''
Utah coach Rick Majerus said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the first for Texas over a ranked team under new
coach Rick Barnes and the 31st Top 25 win for him in 11 seasons as
a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I've ever had a team that needed it more,''
Barnes said. ``I've kept telling our team if we'll continue to work
hard we'll make things happen, and maybe we'll get some luck along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight that rim was good to us on a few of those free throws,
and then on Gabe's three from the top of the key, we actually set
that up for him to bank it. That was a really big play at the time.
But I knew we would be ready to play, because in the locker room
before the game that was the most emotion we've had as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played 40 minutes tonight, really a team win. Our most
complete game. It was a great day for Texas. Ricky won the Heisman,
and we won this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris Clack's 18 points led the Longhorns, who also got 14 from
Muoneke. Another key was the defensive job Texas did by holding
Utah guard Andre Miller to 12 points. Chico Vazquez led, with help
from Ivan Wagner and William Clay. UT also picked a season-high 11
steals.
</P>
<P>
   Blanked the first half, Miller scored six of his 12 points to
lead the Utes to a 9-2 spurt to open the second half and turn
around Texas' 35-31 halftime lead. Utah went up 49-42 before Clack
ignited a 10-0 run with assists on a Clay trey and Vazquez's
driving layup. Clack then drove for two and nailed a three with
10:35 left to put Texas back up, 52-49.
</P>
<P>
   The lead changed five times before Clack stole the ball and
scored on a breakaway jam at 5:29 for a 59-57 lead that Texas never
lost _ despite hitting only five of 11 free throws over a
three-minute period until Muoneke and Mihm netted the final four
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real confidence builder for us,'' Clack said. ``We've worked
so hard and to come out and get a victory over a good team like
Utah is really good for us. And we've got a chance to get a lot
better if we keep playing as hard as we did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas plays Wisconsin (9-1) on Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
