A7121 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HEISMAN-WILLIAMS-     12-12 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' WILLIAMS IS RUNAWAY HEISMAN WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After winning two prestigious awards, Ricky Williams
spent Thursday night in Orlando, Fla., up until 5:30 a.m. talking
football with some of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got about a half-hour of sleep,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, before the biggest night of his 22-year-old life,
Williams and Kansas State quarterback Michael Bishop were out until
an ``undisclosed time'' exploring the Big Apple's night life.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky, does the term Up All Night mean anything to you?
</P>
<P>
   What better way to celebrate winning college football's most
prestigious award. Williams was named the 64th winner of the
Heisman Trophy during ceremonies last night at the Downtown
Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not tired,'' Williams said of his social calendar that
will get busier. ``I had no problems sleeping when I got in, but I
had a long night. When did I get in? ... No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams treated the Heisman voting like an opposing defense.
Before the announcement was made after 55 minutes of preliminaries,
Williams said that he was nervous and ``my heart was really beating
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no reason to get stressed. Williams was first on 714
of the 920 ballots cast. His winning margin of 1,563 votes was the
fourth-largest in Heisman history. He was the first Heisman winner
since Rashaan Salaam in 1994 to finish first in the voting in all
six regions.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State's Bishop was second, UCLA's Cade McNown was third
and Kentucky's Tim Couch was fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Williams' accomplishments, the landslide was not
surprising. Williams finished with 2,124 yards, leading the
Longhorns to an 8-3 record. In his career, he set 16 NCAA and 44
school records. His most impressive achievement was gaining 6,279
yards in his career, surpassing Tony Dorsett's 22-year-old Division
I-A record of 6,082 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Williams became Texas' second Heisman Trophy winner; Earl
Campbell won the award in 1977. Campbell and Dorsett both attended
last night's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' whirlwind continues tonight when he'll attend a
private dinner with other Heisman winners. Tomorrow, he's scheduled
to ring the starting bell at the New York Stock Exchange, and
tomorrow night, he'll attend a $250-a-plate Heisman banquet.
Tuesday night, he's scheduled as a guest on the ``Late Show with
David Letterman''.
</P>
<P>
   This Heisman triumph started in January when Williams announced
he would stay in Austin for his senior season instead of declaring
himself eligible for the NFL draft. And, for a person whose e-mail
address is heisman &LR; mail.utexas.edu, it was apparent that Williams
dreamed big dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching the awards show when I was a little kid,''
Williams said. ``I always thought it was pretty cool because it
said the winner was the best player for that season.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Heisman Trophy goes to the best player on a
successful team. Williams' statistics proved his worth; he needed
his team to perform much better than last year's 4-7 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the day he said he was staying, we felt the pressure,''
said Texas first-year coach Mack Brown. ``The expectations for the
team were higher. People talked about him gaining 1,800 yards; I
thought that would be impossible because people would be gunning
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so competitive and he always set his goals so high. There
are so many things that were against the odds of him doing
everything he did.''
</P>
<P>
   College football's most prestigious award has been as much about
Hype as Heisman. But Texas' sports information department,
acknowledging Williams' role as the preseason favorite, kept their
campaign subtle. The school's ``campaign'' included three postcards
and a weekly conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that the best thing we could do was to have Ricky
talk to as many people, do as many interviews as he could,'' said
UT sports information director John Bianco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a night like this special,'' Brown said. ``It
wouldn't be special if we had someone representing us who wasn't
classy, who didn't stand up for the right things. When I've talked
about how good he is, people have rolled their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so unselfish and humble, but he's got so much confidence.
He's been a pleasure to be around. He's taught us all a lot of
lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Meet The People campaign worked. While Williams' image has
been skewed by his dreadlocks, tattoos (four) and piercings (four),
his Mr. Nice Guy personality _ plus his overwhelming numbers _ won
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me I'd never win the Heisman because of my hair,
because of the piercings,'' said Williams, a silver stud flashing
in his tongue. ``I always said that if that's why they didn't want
to pick me, then I don't want the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people saw I was a good person. It all worked out for
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-12-98 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
